// ── LEARN ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const LEARN={

"vascular-aneurysm":{src:"NICE NG228 (2022) — verified from PDF",c:[
{q:"What defines a thunderclap headache and why is it significant?",a:"A sudden severe headache peaking within 1–5 minutes. Red-flag symptom for SAH. Other causes (cough, exertion, coitus) do not negate the need to investigate if SAH is suspected.",ref:"NG228 1.1.3",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What other symptoms can accompany SAH besides headache?",a:"Neck pain or stiffness; photophobia; nausea and vomiting; altered consciousness, seizure or focal neurological deficit; limited or painful neck flexion on examination.",ref:"NG228 1.1.3",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"If CT is done within 6 hours and is negative (reported by a radiologist), should LP be performed?",a:"No — do NOT routinely offer LP. Think about alternative diagnoses and seek specialist advice. CT within 6 hours has high diagnostic accuracy.",ref:"NG228 1.1.11",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"If CT is done more than 6 hours after symptom onset and is negative, what then?",a:"Consider a lumbar puncture.",ref:"NG228 1.1.12",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"How long after symptom onset must you wait before performing LP to diagnose SAH?",a:"At least 12 hours — to allow xanthochromia to develop as haemoglobin degrades to bilirubin.",ref:"NG228 1.1.13",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What LP finding confirms the diagnosis of SAH?",a:"Elevated bilirubin (xanthochromia) on spectrophotometry — not visual inspection alone.",ref:"NG228 1.1.14",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"Should a subarachnoid haemorrhage severity score be used to determine timing of transfer to a specialist centre?",a:"No. Do NOT use a severity score in isolation to determine need for or timing of transfer. Risk of rebleeding is highest within 24 hours.",ref:"NG228 1.1.17",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What imaging is offered immediately after confirming SAH on CT?",a:"CT angiography (CTA) of the head without delay to identify the cause and guide treatment.",ref:"NG228 1.1.18",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"When is DSA (digital subtraction angiography) indicated after SAH?",a:"When CTA does not identify the cause but aneurysm is still suspected. MRA can be used if DSA is contraindicated.",ref:"NG228 1.1.21",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What is the preferred route for nimodipine in SAH, and when is IV permitted?",a:"Enteral (oral/NG) nimodipine is preferred. IV nimodipine is only used in a specialist setting when enteral treatment is not suitable.",ref:"NG228 1.2.1–2",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"Which aneurysm treatment is preferred — coiling or clipping?",a:"Endovascular coiling is the preferred option. Neurosurgical clipping is offered only if coiling is not suitable. Both options (plus conservative management) must be documented.",ref:"NG228 1.2.4 & 1.2.6",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"When should treatment of the culprit aneurysm be carried out?",a:"At the earliest opportunity — rebleeding risk is highest within 24 hours of symptom onset.",ref:"NG228 1.2.8",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"Should severity score alone determine treatment suitability for a ruptured aneurysm?",a:"No — do NOT use a severity score in isolation to determine suitability for any management option.",ref:"NG228 1.2.5",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"Should transcranial Doppler be used to guide management in SAH?",a:"No — do NOT use TCD monitoring to guide clinical management except in the context of clinical research.",ref:"NG228 1.3.1",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What is the first investigation for unexplained neurological deterioration after SAH?",a:"Non-contrast CT head scan as the first diagnostic investigation.",ref:"NG228 1.3.2",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"How should acute hydrocephalus causing deterioration be managed after SAH?",a:"Consider drainage or diversion of CSF.",ref:"NG228 1.3.4",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"How should chronic hydrocephalus be managed after SAH?",a:"Consider drainage or permanent diversion of CSF. If uncertain about benefit of permanent diversion, consider a trial of temporary drainage first.",ref:"NG228 1.3.5",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What is the recommended treatment for delayed cerebral ischaemia (DCI) after SAH?",a:"Ensure euvolaemia (normal blood volume) and consider a vasopressor if symptoms persist. Note: hypervolaemia (triple-H) is NOT recommended.",ref:"NG228 1.3.6",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What factors guide evaluation of non-culprit (unruptured) aneurysms?",a:"MDT including interventional neuroradiologist and neurosurgeon. Consider: size and location; lifetime rupture risk; treatment risk; comorbidities; patient preference. Options: coiling, clipping, or conservative monitoring.",ref:"NG228 1.4.5–6",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"Can antiplatelets/anticoagulants be withheld after SAH if the aneurysm has been secured?",a:"No — do NOT withhold antiplatelets or anticoagulants solely on the basis of SAH if the culprit aneurysm has been secured by coiling or clipping.",ref:"NG228 1.4.9",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What is the NICE position on routine screening of relatives after SAH?",a:"Routine testing to check for aneurysms in relatives has NOT been shown to save lives. Testing is usually limited to those with ≥2 first-degree relatives (parent, sibling) who have had SAH.",ref:"NG228 1.4.15",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What headache advice is given to patients after SAH discharge?",a:"Post-SAH headaches are common and generally benign, but may indicate chronic hydrocephalus if accompanied by gait disturbance, incontinence, incoordination, or cognitive impairment.",ref:"NG228 1.4.12–13",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What was the ISUIA study and what was its design?",a:"International Study of Unruptured Intracranial Aneurysms (Wiebers 1998). 2621 patients at 53 centres. Retrospective component: natural history of 1937 unruptured aneurysms in 1449 patients. Prospective component: treatment morbidity/mortality in 1172 patients. Group 1: no prior SAH. Group 2: prior SAH from a different aneurysm.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.1",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What was the annual rupture risk of small (<10mm) unruptured aneurysms in ISUIA?",a:"Group 1 (no prior SAH): <0.05% per year (cumulative 0.4% over 7.5 years). Group 2 (prior SAH from different aneurysm): ~0.5% per year — about 11 times higher. Key implication: small incidental aneurysms in patients without SAH history have very low rupture risk.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.4",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What were the rupture rates for larger aneurysms in ISUIA?",a:"Aneurysms ≥10mm: ~1% per year in both groups. Giant aneurysms (≥25mm) in Group 1: 6% rupture rate in the first year. Size and location were independent predictors of rupture. Relative risk for ≥10mm vs <10mm: 11.6 (P=0.03); for ≥25mm: 59.0 (P<0.001).",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.4",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"Which aneurysm locations had the highest rupture risk in ISUIA?",a:"Basilar tip: relative risk 13.8 (P=0.001). Vertebrobasilar/posterior cerebral: relative risk 13.6 (P=0.007). Posterior communicating: relative risk 8.0 (P=0.02). Posterior circulation aneurysms carry significantly higher rupture risk than anterior circulation.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.4",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What was the surgical morbidity and mortality rate for unruptured aneurysms in ISUIA?",a:"Group 1: 17.5% at 30 days, 15.7% at 1 year. Group 2: 13.6% at 30 days, 13.1% at 1 year. Age independently predicted worse surgical outcome. For Group 1 patients with <10mm aneurysms, surgical risk greatly exceeded the 7.5-year rupture risk.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.1",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What was the key clinical implication of ISUIA for managing small incidental aneurysms?",a:"For patients without prior SAH (Group 1) with aneurysms <10mm, the risk of surgical intervention (17.5% morbidity/mortality) far exceeds the natural history risk (<0.05%/year rupture). This supports conservative management with surveillance for many small incidental aneurysms.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.1",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What was the prevalence of intracranial aneurysms reported in ISUIA?",a:"Autopsy studies: 0.2–9.9% of the general population (mean ~5%), suggesting 10–15 million people in the US have or will have intracranial aneurysms. With SAH incidence of ~10/100,000/year, most aneurysms never rupture.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.1",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What risk factors for aneurysm rupture were identified in ISUIA?",a:"Significant predictors in Group 1: aneurysm size and location (posterior circulation). In Group 2: basilar tip location (RR 5.1) and older age. Other documented risk factors: smoking (60.6% current smokers), hypertension (37%), alcohol use. ~75% of patients were female.",ref:"ISUIA, Wiebers 1998, p.3–4",src_id:"k-isuia-1998",korky:true},
{q:"What was ISAT and what was the study design?",a:"International Subarachnoid Aneurysm Trial (Molyneux 2002/2009, Lancet Neurology). RCT of 2143 patients with ruptured intracranial aneurysms at 43 centres (1994-2002). Randomised to neurosurgical clipping vs endovascular coiling. Mean age 52. Long-term follow-up: mean 9 years (max 14 years).",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.1",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What was the primary outcome of ISAT at 1 year?",a:"Death or dependency at 1 year: coiling 24% (250/1063) vs clipping 31% (326/1055). Relative risk reduction 23.9% (95% CI 12.4-33.9). Absolute risk reduction 7.4% (3.6-11.2, p=0.0001). Coiling was significantly better than clipping for ruptured aneurysms suitable for either treatment.",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.2",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What were the 5-year mortality results of ISAT?",a:"Coiling 11% (112/1046) vs clipping 14% (144/1041). Relative risk of death 0.77 (95% CI 0.61-0.98, p=0.03). The survival advantage of coiling was maintained at 5 years. However, independence among survivors at 5 years was identical: coiling 83% vs clipping 82%.",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.4-5",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What were the rebleeding rates after treatment in ISAT?",a:"After 1 year: 13 rebleeds from treated aneurysm (10 coiling, 3 clipping; p=0.06 ITT). Plus 4 rebleeds from pre-existing aneurysms and 6 from new (de novo) aneurysms. Annual rebleed risk from treated aneurysm was low in both groups. Coil rebleeds occurred within 5 years; clip rebleeds after 5 years.",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What did ISAT show about long-term mortality vs general population?",a:"Standardised mortality ratio (SMR) for patients surviving 1 year after SAH treatment was 1.57 (95% CI 1.32-1.82, p<0.0001) — significantly higher than age/sex-matched general population. Main causes of death after 1 year: cancer and cardiovascular disease. ~20% had multiple aneurysms at presentation.",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.4-5",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key clinical implications of ISAT?",a:"(1) Coiling is the preferred treatment for ruptured aneurysms suitable for both treatments. (2) The survival benefit of coiling is durable at 5+ years. (3) Rebleeding risk from coiled aneurysms is slightly higher than clipped but absolute risk is low. (4) All SAH survivors have increased mortality vs general population — need long-term follow-up. (5) Risk of new aneurysm formation requires surveillance.",ref:"ISAT, Molyneux 2009, p.5",src_id:"k-isat-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What does the PHASES score include for predicting 5-year rupture risk of unruptured intracranial aneurysms?",a:"P = Population (Finnish/Japanese = higher risk vs North American/European); H = Hypertension (treated); A = Age (≥70); S = Size (mm, larger = higher risk); E = Earlier SAH from a different treated aneurysm; S = Site (AcomA/PcomA/vertebrobasilar = highest; MCA = intermediate; ICA = lowest). NOT included in PHASES: aneurysm shape/irregularity, family history, polycystic kidney disease, aspect ratio, smoking — these are separate risk factors. Commonly asked: 'Which is NOT in PHASES?' → family history, aneurysm shape, smoking status.",ref:"PHASES score — Greving 2014, Lancet Neurol",recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 42-year-old presents with sudden severe headache peaking within 2 minutes. CT head performed 4 hours after onset is reported by a radiologist as normal. What is the next step per NICE NG228?",opts:["A. Perform LP immediately","B. Do not routinely offer LP; consider alternative diagnoses and seek specialist advice","C. Discharge with analgesia","D. Perform CTA","E. Repeat CT in 6 hours"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.1.11): CT within 6 hours negative + reported by radiologist = do NOT routinely offer LP. Consider alternatives and seek specialist advice. CT has high accuracy within this window.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.1.11",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"LP is planned for suspected SAH. Headache started 10 hours ago. Is it appropriate to proceed now per NG228?",opts:["A. Yes — 10 hours is sufficient","B. No — wait at least 12 hours after symptom onset","C. No — LP is contraindicated after negative CT","D. Yes — any time after 6 hours is acceptable","E. No — DSA is required first"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.1.13): Allow at least 12 hours after symptom onset before LP. At 10 hours the minimum interval has not been reached. This allows xanthochromia to develop.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.1.13",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"Which LP finding confirms SAH per NICE NG228?",opts:["A. RBCs >1000/mm³ in all bottles","B. Elevated bilirubin (xanthochromia) on spectrophotometry","C. Opening pressure >25 cmH₂O","D. Xanthochromia visible to naked eye","E. Protein >1 g/L"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.1.14): SAH is confirmed by elevated bilirubin on spectrophotometry. Visual inspection is insufficient. Spectrophotometry is required.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.1.14",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"CTA confirms a ruptured intracranial aneurysm in a good-grade patient. What does NICE NG228 recommend as first-line treatment?",opts:["A. Neurosurgical clipping","B. Endovascular coiling, or clipping if coiling not suitable","C. Conservative management until Day 3–10","D. Treatment based solely on SAH severity score","E. DSA before any intervention"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.2.6): Offer endovascular coiling, or clipping if coiling is not suitable. Treat at earliest opportunity — rebleeding risk is highest within 24 hours (1.2.8).",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.2.6 & 1.2.8",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"A patient with SAH develops unexplained neurological deterioration on Day 5. What is the first investigation per NG228?",opts:["A. CTA","B. MRI brain","C. Non-contrast CT head","D. Transcranial Doppler","E. Repeat LP"],ans:2,exp:"NG228 (1.3.2): For unexplained neurological deterioration after SAH, offer non-contrast CT head as the FIRST diagnostic investigation.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.3.2",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"A patient develops symptoms of delayed cerebral ischaemia 8 days post-SAH. What does NG228 recommend?",opts:["A. Triple-H therapy (hypertension, hypervolaemia, haemodilution)","B. Ensure euvolaemia; consider vasopressor if symptoms persist","C. Aggressive hypervolaemia with IV fluids","D. Immediate repeat coiling","E. High-dose IV nimodipine"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.3.6): Ensure euvolaemia and consider a vasopressor if symptoms persist. Triple-H (hypervolaemia) is NOT recommended — euvolaemia is the target.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.3.6",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"After successful coiling of a ruptured aneurysm, the patient is on warfarin for AF. Should it be withheld?",opts:["A. Yes, indefinitely","B. Yes, for 6 months","C. No — do not withhold solely on basis of SAH if aneurysm is secured","D. Only restart if HASBLED <3","E. Refer to haematology and delay"],ans:2,exp:"NG228 (1.4.9): Do not withhold antiplatelets or anticoagulants solely on the basis of SAH if the culprit aneurysm has been secured by coiling or clipping.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.4.9",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"Family screening for intracranial aneurysms after SAH — what does NG228 advise?",opts:["A. Screen all first-degree relatives routinely","B. Screen all relatives with MRA","C. Routine testing not shown to save lives; usually limited to ≥2 first-degree relatives with SAH","D. Screen only siblings","E. Refer all relatives to neurosurgery for DSA"],ans:2,exp:"NG228 (1.4.15): Routine relative screening has not been shown to save lives or prevent SAH. Testing is usually limited to those with ≥2 first-degree relatives (parent, sibling) who have had SAH.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.4.15",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"A 52-year-old woman presents with sudden severe headache and neck stiffness. CT confirms SAH from a ruptured posterior communicating artery aneurysm, successfully coiled on day 2. Which of the following is NOT a recognised complication of ruptured intracranial aneurysm SAH?",opts:["A. Rehemorrhage within the first two weeks","B. Cerebral vasospasm leading to ischaemic stroke","C. Communicating hydrocephalus requiring CSF diversion","D. Spontaneous complete resolution after aneurysm treatment with no further complications","E. Persistent neurological deficit from delayed cerebral ischaemia"],ans:3,exp:"Recognised complications: (1) Rehemorrhage — 20% risk in first 2 weeks without treatment; (2) Vasospasm → delayed cerebral ischaemia (day 4–14), may cause permanent deficit; (3) Hydrocephalus — blood impairs CSF reabsorption, may require shunting; (4) Persistent neurological deficit. Option D is incorrect — even after aneurysm securing, vasospasm, DCI, and hydrocephalus require 14–21 days of intensive monitoring.",ref:"Bank, p.3",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 62-year-old hypertensive Japanese woman with a known 7mm posterior communicating artery aneurysm is referred for rupture risk assessment. She had a treated SAH from a different aneurysm 8 years ago. Which factor is NOT included in the PHASES score?",opts:["A. Her hypertension status","B. Her age (62 years)","C. Her Japanese ethnicity","D. Her family history of intracranial aneurysms","E. Her previous SAH from a different aneurysm"],ans:3,exp:"The PHASES score (Greving 2014) includes: P = Population (Finnish/Japanese = highest risk), H = Hypertension, A = Age (≥70), S = Size (mm), E = Earlier SAH from a different aneurysm, S = Site (AcomA/PComA/vertebrobasilar = highest). Family history is NOT part of PHASES, though it is an independent risk factor. Other factors not in PHASES: aneurysm irregularity, aspect ratio, smoking, polycystic kidney disease.",ref:"PHASES score — Greving 2014, Lancet Neurol",recall:true},
{stem:"The ISAT (International Subarachnoid Aneurysm Trial, Molyneux 2002) randomised 2143 patients with ruptured intracranial aneurysms in good neurological grade to endovascular coiling versus neurosurgical clipping. What was the primary finding at 1 year, and what was the approximate absolute risk reduction for the primary endpoint?",opts:["A. Clipping was superior; coiling had unacceptable procedure-related mortality","B. No significant difference — both treatments were equivalent at 1 year","C. Coiling was superior; death or dependence (mRS >2) at 1 year: 23.7% (coiling) vs 30.6% (clipping); ARR approximately 7.4%","D. Coiling was superior at 1 year but inferior at 5 years; the 1-year ARR was 5.6%","E. Coiling superior at 1 year; long-term rebleed rate with coiling equivalent to clipping"],ans:2,exp:"ISAT (Molyneux 2002, Lancet): 2143 patients, good clinical grade (WFNS 1–2), suitable for both treatments, ruptured intracranial aneurysm. Stopped early after second planned interim analysis. Primary endpoint: death or dependency (mRS >2) at 1 year. Results: coiling 23.7% vs clipping 30.6% — ARR ≈ 7.4% (or 6.9% depending on exact calculation), NNT ≈ 14. RRR 22.6%. Key caveats: (1) Only aneurysms suitable for BOTH treatments were enrolled — selection bias. (2) Aneurysm occlusion rate was lower with coiling. (3) Long-term: Molyneux 2005 (5 years) — benefit persisted but rebleed risk HIGHER with coiling (annual rebleed: 0.21% coiling vs 0.06% clipping). The higher long-term rebleed risk with coiling is the main argument for continued follow-up imaging post-coiling.",ref:"ISAT — Molyneux 2002, Lancet; Molyneux 2005 follow-up",recall:true},
{stem:"The ISUIA (International Study of Unruptured Intracranial Aneurysms, Wiebers 2003) reported 5-year rupture rates by aneurysm size. For an anterior circulation aneurysm <7mm in a patient with NO previous history of SAH, what is the 5-year cumulative rupture risk per ISUIA?",opts:["A. 5–10% at 5 years — all aneurysms carry significant risk","B. 1.5% at 5 years — equivalent to the background rate","C. Essentially 0% at 5 years — this is the key ISUIA finding challenged the 5mm treatment threshold","D. 14.5% at 5 years — anterior location confers high risk","E. 40% at 5 years — any detectable aneurysm carries substantial risk"],ans:2,exp:"ISUIA (Wiebers 2003, Lancet): 4060 unruptured aneurysms, 3998 patients. 5-year cumulative rupture rates — anterior circulation, NO prior SAH: <7mm = 0%; 7–12mm = 2.6%; 13–24mm = 14.5%; ≥25mm = 40%. WITH prior SAH (from a different aneurysm): <7mm = 1.5%; 7–12mm = 2.6%. The near-zero 5-year risk for <7mm anterior aneurysms in patients without prior SAH challenged the previous teaching that all aneurysms >5mm required treatment. Posterior circulation aneurysms carry higher rupture risk at equivalent sizes. Surgical complication rate was 12.6% for patients with prior SAH and 10.9% for those without — suggesting treatment risk may exceed natural history risk for small anterior aneurysms in low-risk patients. ISUIA limitations: selection bias; patients referred for conservative management may be inherently lower risk.",ref:"ISUIA — Wiebers 2003, Lancet",recall:true},
{stem:"An aneurysm morphology assessment is being performed to determine suitability for endovascular coiling. Which aneurysm characteristic makes endovascular coiling MOST technically difficult and carries the highest risk of coil prolapse into the parent artery?",opts:["A. Small saccular aneurysm with a narrow neck (neck:dome ratio 1:4)","B. Wide-necked aneurysm with a neck:dome ratio of 2:1 — the neck is twice as wide as the dome","C. Lobulated aneurysm with multiple blebs","D. Aneurysm on a straight segment of the parent artery","E. Aneurysm measuring 10mm with smooth regular walls"],ans:1,exp:"Wide neck (neck:dome ratio ≥1:2 or absolute neck diameter ≥4mm) is the most significant factor making coiling technically challenging. A neck:dome ratio of 2:1 means the neck is WIDER than the dome — coils cannot be retained within the aneurysm sac and will prolapse into the parent vessel, risking thromboembolism or parent artery occlusion. In contrast, a narrow-neck ratio (1:4 — neck is much smaller than dome) is ideal for coiling. Other characteristics making coiling more challenging: (1) Very small aneurysm <3mm (coil wire diameter relatively large, perforation risk); (2) Fusiform or dissecting aneurysm (no distinct neck); (3) Aneurysm arising at an acute angle from the parent artery. For wide-neck aneurysms, assistive techniques are used: balloon-assisted coiling, stent-assisted coiling, or flow diverter devices. MCA aneurysms are often preferred for clipping due to their wide-neck anatomy and direct surgical access.",ref:"claude — aneurysm coiling suitability / neck:dome ratio",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient develops left hemiparesis 2 hours after endovascular coiling of a right MCA aneurysm. The coiling procedure appeared technically successful with near-complete occlusion. What is the most likely cause of this immediate post-procedure neurological deficit?",opts:["A. Vasospasm — the most common cause of post-coiling deficit in the immediate post-operative period","B. Thromboembolic event — coil thrombosis or micro-emboli from the procedure site causing acute ischaemia","C. Re-rupture of the aneurysm post-coiling","D. Osmotic shifts from contrast medium causing cerebral oedema","E. Hydrocephalus from acute blood clot obstruction"],ans:1,exp:"POST-COILING NEUROLOGICAL DEFICIT: (1) IMMEDIATE (within hours): most likely THROMBOEMBOLIC EVENT — clot formation on newly placed coils, micro-emboli from the catheter or coil mass, or thrombosis of perforating arteries from coil protrusion. Treatment: anticoagulation (heparin), antiplatelet agents (aspirin/clopidogrel), intra-arterial thrombolysis in selected cases. (2) DELAYED (day 4–14): most likely VASOSPASM causing delayed cerebral ischaemia (DCI) — the classic post-SAH complication from blood breakdown products stimulating vasospasm. Treatment: euvolaemia, vasopressors, intraarterial vasodilators (verapamil, papaverine), or angioplasty. In this question, 2 hours post-procedure = immediate period → thromboembolic is the most likely cause, not vasospasm. The timing is the key distinguishing feature.",ref:"claude — post-coiling neurological deficit / thromboembolic vs vasospasm",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 48-year-old woman is admitted after aneurysmal SAH. Her father died from SAH at age 55, and she also has a sister with polycystic kidney disease. After recovery, she asks about the risk to her daughter (who is 25 and healthy). What is the most accurate counselling?",opts:["A. The daughter has no elevated risk — only male first-degree relatives are at risk","B. The daughter has an elevated risk as a first-degree relative of an SAH patient; NICE NG228 advises testing only when ≥2 first-degree relatives have had SAH, but risk factors here (family history + PKD association) warrant genetic counselling","C. All first-degree relatives should undergo immediate MRA screening per NG228","D. The risk is only elevated in siblings, not children","E. PKD confers no increased risk of intracranial aneurysm rupture"],ans:1,exp:"SAH family history counselling: (1) First-degree relatives (parent, sibling, child) of an SAH patient have a 2–5× increased risk compared with the general population. (2) NICE NG228 (1.4.15): routine screening of relatives has NOT been shown to save lives — limit to those with ≥2 affected first-degree relatives. However, additional risk factors modify this advice. (3) Polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD): 10–15% prevalence of intracranial aneurysms — much higher than the general population (~2–3%). ADPKD is an independent strong risk factor. Here: the patient's sister has PKD, and the patient herself had SAH + father died of SAH — the daughter has a first-degree relative with SAH AND may carry PKD risk. Referral for genetic counselling (to assess PKD status) and vascular neurology review is appropriate. The PHASES score incorporates 'Family history' as a modifier for individual aneurysm management, though not a formal PHASES variable.",ref:"NICE NG228 1.4.15 / Standard SAH family history risk",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old right-handed patient has a symptomatic unruptured left MCA bifurcation aneurysm (12mm, wide-neck, incorporating the MCA division) with progressive headaches. She is in good health with no comorbidities. CTA and DSA have been performed. What treatment approach is typically preferred for MCA aneurysms specifically, and why?",opts:["A. Endovascular coiling — MCA aneurysms are ideally suited for coiling due to easy catheter access","B. Conservative management — MCA aneurysms almost never rupture","C. Neurosurgical clipping — MCA aneurysms are often wide-necked with branches incorporated into the aneurysm sac, making clipping technically preferable and more durable","D. Radiosurgery — the standard for all unruptured aneurysms","E. Endovascular flow diverter — the first-line treatment for all MCA aneurysms"],ans:2,exp:"MCA aneurysms (particularly at the MCA bifurcation) are one of the few aneurysm locations where surgical CLIPPING is often PREFERRED over endovascular coiling, for the following reasons: (1) WIDE NECK: MCA bifurcation aneurysms often have a broad neck with MCA branches (M2 divisions) arising directly from the aneurysm fundus — making coil retention difficult and branch occlusion risk high. (2) DIRECT SURGICAL ACCESS: pterional craniotomy provides excellent direct access to the MCA bifurcation; the approach is low risk in experienced hands. (3) BRANCH PRESERVATION: microsurgical clipping allows direct visualisation of perforating arteries and M2 branches, with real-time Doppler confirmation. (4) Complete occlusion: surgical clip occlusion rates exceed coiling for complex MCA aneurysms. Endovascular options (stent-assisted coiling, flow diverters) are increasingly used but remain second-line for complex MCA morphology. Contrast: PCOM aneurysms and posterior circulation aneurysms are often preferentially coiled.",ref:"claude — MCA aneurysm treatment preference / clipping vs coiling",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old woman has a ruptured anterior communicating artery (ACOM) aneurysm that points anteriorly and to the right. Her left A1 anterior cerebral artery is dominant (larger). A left pterional craniotomy is planned. Which principle justifies the LEFT-sided approach for a right-pointing aneurysm?",opts:["A. The approach is always from the right for ACOM aneurysms to avoid the dominant hemisphere","B. The surgical approach to an ACOM aneurysm is chosen from the side of the DOMINANT A1 — this provides optimal proximal control and the best angle on the aneurysm neck, independent of dome direction","C. The approach should always be from the side towards which the dome points to allow direct clip application","D. A bifrontal approach is mandatory for all ACOM aneurysms to allow visualisation of both A1 vessels","E. The choice of side is irrelevant for ACOM aneurysms as the clip is applied from the midline"],ans:1,exp:"ACOM aneurysm approach: the dominant consideration is the side of the DOMINANT A1 anterior cerebral artery — approaching from the dominant A1 side allows: (1) optimal proximal control (temporary clip on dominant A1 before exposing the neck); (2) best surgical angle to the aneurysm neck. Dome direction does not determine approach side. If the left A1 is dominant: left pterional approach is correct even if the dome points rightward. ACOM aneurysm is the most common aneurysm to rupture and also the most common to cause intraventricular haemorrhage (into the frontal horn via the lamina terminalis/anterior commissure) if the dome is directed posterosuperiorly. A1 hypoplasia (absent or very small A1 on one side) is present in ~10% of cases and increases aneurysm formation risk on the contralateral dominant side.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old presents with 4 weeks of right-sided ptosis, painful right sixth nerve palsy, and numbness over the right cheek. CT head is normal with no signs of SAH. What is the most likely diagnosis and investigation of choice?",opts:["A. Right PCOM aneurysm causing CN III palsy — CTA circle of Willis","B. Cavernous sinus syndrome from an intracavernous right ICA aneurysm — MRI with gadolinium and MRA of the skull base","C. Orbital cellulitis — CT orbits with contrast","D. Miller-Fisher syndrome — LP for anti-GQ1b antibodies","E. Tolosa-Hunt syndrome (idiopathic granulomatous cavernous sinus inflammation) — corticosteroids"],ans:1,exp:"Cavernous sinus syndrome: the cavernous sinus contains CN III, IV, V1, V2, and VI alongside the intracavernous ICA. Multiple cranial nerve involvement (CN III + VI + V2 sensory loss = ptosis + lateral gaze palsy + cheek numbness) localises to the cavernous sinus. An intracavernous ICA aneurysm is a major cause — crucially, intracavernous aneurysms DO NOT cause SAH if they rupture (the ICA is extradural here); instead they cause a carotid-cavernous fistula (CCF). CN VI is the most medially placed nerve within the cavernous sinus and therefore most susceptible to compression. PCOM aneurysm causes isolated CN III palsy with pupil dilation — not a multi-nerve syndrome. MRI/MRA characterises the lesion. Tolosa-Hunt is a diagnosis of exclusion and does not cause a mass on imaging.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 52-year-old hypertensive Japanese woman has an incidentally discovered unruptured 8mm PCOM aneurysm. She has no prior history of SAH. You calculate her PHASES score. Which factor is NOT a component of the validated PHASES score?",opts:["A. Country of origin (population)","B. Hypertension (yes/no)","C. Aneurysm size","D. Aneurysm morphology (lobulation, irregularity, or bleb formation)","E. Earlier subarachnoid haemorrhage from a different aneurysm"],ans:3,exp:"PHASES score components (Greving 2014): P — Population/country (Japan = 3, Finland = 5, other = 0); H — Hypertension (yes = 1); A — Age (≥70 = 1); S — Size of aneurysm (<7mm = 0; 7–9.9mm = 3; 10–19.9mm = 6; ≥20mm = 10); E — Earlier SAH from a different aneurysm (yes = 1); S — Site (PCOM/posterior circulation = 2–4; ICA/MCA = 0). MORPHOLOGY (lobulation, irregularity, presence of daughter blebs) is NOT a PHASES component — despite being clinically recognised as increasing rupture risk, it was not included in the validated model. PHASES also excludes smoking, family history, and aneurysm growth rate. For this patient: Japan (3) + hypertension (1) + age <70 (0) + 8mm (3) + no prior SAH (0) + PCOM (2) = 9 points → approximately 6.4% 5-year rupture risk.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Which cerebral artery is most commonly the site of fusiform (dolichoectatic, non-saccular) intracranial aneurysms?",opts:["A. Middle cerebral artery (MCA) bifurcation","B. Anterior communicating artery (ACOM)","C. Vertebrobasilar system — particularly the basilar artery and vertebral arteries","D. Internal carotid artery at the cavernous sinus segment","E. Anterior cerebral artery (ACA) A1 segment"],ans:2,exp:"Fusiform intracranial aneurysms (dolichoectasia): diffuse, spindle-shaped dilatation without a distinct neck — caused by atherosclerotic degeneration, dissection, or connective tissue disorder affecting the full circumference of the arterial wall. Most common location: vertebrobasilar system (basilar and vertebral arteries). Clinically: elderly, hypertensive, atherosclerotic patients; causes brainstem compression (CN VI, VII most frequent), obstructive hydrocephalus, or ischaemic strokes from thrombus. Rarely rupture but can expand. Management: antiplatelet therapy for ischaemia prevention; flow diverters in selected cases (no neck for clipping). Contrast: SACCULAR aneurysms are most common at ACOM (25–30%), followed by PCOM and MCA bifurcation. The ACOM is most commonly ruptured among saccular aneurysms.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 48-year-old is found to have a 14mm aneurysm at the P2/P3 junction of the right posterior cerebral artery. Which cranial nerve is most likely to be compressed by an enlarging aneurysm at this specific location?",opts:["A. CN III (oculomotor) — runs between the PCA and SCA in the interpeduncular cistern at the P1 level","B. CN IV (trochlear) — courses through the ambient cistern alongside the P2 segment of the PCA, around the cerebral peduncle","C. CN VI (abducens) — exits the pontomedullary junction adjacent to the P3 segment","D. CN V (trigeminal) — traverses the ambient cistern at P2","E. CN IX (glossopharyngeal) — lies adjacent to the P2 PCA in the ambient cistern"],ans:1,exp:"PCA segment anatomy: P1 = interpeduncular cistern; P2 = ambient cistern (around the cerebral peduncle); P3 = quadrigeminal cistern; P4 = calcarine/occipital. The AMBIENT CISTERN (P2 segment) contains: P2 PCA, CN IV (trochlear nerve — after decussating dorsal to the midbrain, CN IV winds anterolaterally around the cerebral peduncle through the ambient cistern to reach the tentorial edge), basal vein of Rosenthal, and the lateral surface of the cerebral peduncle. A P2/P3 aneurysm is therefore most likely to compress CN IV. CN III palsy is characteristic of PCOM or P1 aneurysms — CN III crosses between the PCA (above) and SCA (below) at the P1/interpeduncular level. CN VI is at the pontomedullary junction — not in the ambient cistern. This distinction from PCOM aneurysm (CN III) vs P2 aneurysm (CN IV) is a high-yield FRCS discriminator.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 40-year-old man presents 33 days after an uninvestigated sudden severe headache. MRI confirms SAH. CTA shows a 9mm right PCOM aneurysm. He is currently GCS 15 with no neurological deficit. He asks about his risk if he delays treatment. How should he be counselled?",opts:["A. The risk of re-rupture has substantially diminished — most re-bleeding occurs in the first 14 days and the risk is now equivalent to an unruptured aneurysm","B. The acute risks (haemorrhage and vasospasm) have fully resolved by 30 days — conservative management with close follow-up is appropriate","C. The aneurysm carries a significant ongoing re-rupture risk: cumulative re-rupture over the next 6 months is approximately 50% without treatment; definitive aneurysm repair is urgently required","D. A 9mm PCOM aneurysm at this size can be safely monitored with annual MRA using the PHASES score","E. The risk of re-rupture from a previously ruptured aneurysm is equivalent to unruptured aneurysm natural history from this point forward"],ans:2,exp:"A ruptured but untreated aneurysm carries MUCH higher re-rupture risk than an unruptured aneurysm — PHASES is not applicable. After the initial 24–48 hours (when the highest acute re-rupture rate occurs), the rate is approximately 1–3% per day for the first 2 weeks, then approximately 3% per month thereafter. Cumulative 6-month re-rupture risk reaches approximately 50%. Each re-rupture carries 70–80% mortality. By day 33, the vasospasm window (peak day 4–14) has likely passed — but re-rupture risk remains substantially elevated. The patient must be counselled that the aneurysm requires urgent definitive treatment. Vasospasm monitoring beyond day 21 is not routinely needed. NICE NG228 and all major guidelines specify early treatment for ruptured aneurysms — delayed presentation does not reduce urgency.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient on day 8 post-SAH (ruptured basilar tip aneurysm, successfully coiled) develops new left hemiparesis. DCI is suspected. Which investigation is LEAST useful for confirming delayed cerebral ischaemia in this patient?",opts:["A. CT perfusion imaging","B. Transcranial Doppler (TCD) ultrasonography","C. Digital subtraction angiography (DSA)","D. CT angiography (CTA) of cerebral vessels","E. MRI diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) and perfusion"],ans:1,exp:"Transcranial Doppler (TCD) is the LEAST useful investigation for confirming DCI in this specific case: (1) OPERATOR-DEPENDENT with high inter-observer variability; (2) the POSTERIOR CIRCULATION (basilar artery) is poorly accessible to TCD — the temporal bone window for MCA is available in ~90% of patients, but basilar/posterior circulation insonation requires the foramen magnum window and is technically unreliable; (3) TCD measures flow VELOCITY — elevated velocity (>120–140 cm/s MCA) suggests vasospasm, but does not confirm ischaemia or correlate reliably with clinical DCI; (4) a normal TCD does NOT exclude DCI. For CONFIRMING DCI: DSA (gold standard — directly visualises vasospasm and allows treatment via angioplasty/vasodilator infusion); CT perfusion (shows perfusion deficits); CTA (shows arterial calibre); MRI DWI (shows established infarct). TCD is useful for SCREENING and MONITORING trends but is the weakest diagnostic tool for confirming established DCI, especially in the posterior circulation.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true}
]},

"head-injury":{src:"NICE NG232 (2023) — verified from PDF",c:[
{q:"What are the 1-hour CT head criteria for adults ≥16 per NG232?",a:"(1) GCS ≤12 on initial ED assessment; (2) GCS <15 at 2 hours after injury; (3) suspected open or depressed skull fracture; (4) signs of basal skull fracture (haemotympanum, panda eyes, CSF leak ear/nose, Battle's sign); (5) post-traumatic seizure; (6) focal neurological deficit; (7) >1 episode of vomiting.",ref:"NG232 1.5.8",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"In adults ≥16 with LOC or amnesia, what 4 factors trigger CT within 8 hours?",a:"(1) Age ≥65; (2) any current bleeding or clotting disorder; (3) dangerous mechanism — pedestrian/cyclist struck by vehicle, ejected from vehicle, fall >1m or 5 stairs; (4) >30 minutes retrograde amnesia.",ref:"NG232 1.5.9",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What additional CT rule applies to patients on anticoagulants or antiplatelets (excluding aspirin monotherapy) who have no other CT indications?",a:"Consider CT within 8 hours of injury (or within 1 hour if presenting >8 hours after injury). Applies to VKAs, DOACs, heparin/LMWH, and antiplatelet agents other than aspirin monotherapy.",ref:"NG232 1.5.13",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What is the tranexamic acid dose for adults ≥16 with head injury and GCS ≤12?",a:"2g IV bolus, given within 2 hours of injury. Only if no active extracranial bleeding. This is an off-label use.",ref:"NG232 1.3.17",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What is the tranexamic acid dose for children <16?",a:"15–30 mg/kg (up to a maximum of 2g) IV bolus, within 2 hours of injury. Off-label use.",ref:"NG232 1.3.17",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What GCS triggers a pre-alert call to the receiving hospital for a head-injured patient?",a:"GCS score of 8 or less.",ref:"NG232 1.3.10",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"When must a neurosurgeon be involved regardless of imaging?",a:"Persisting coma (GCS ≤8 after resuscitation); unexplained confusion >4 hours; deteriorating GCS especially motor; progressive focal signs; seizure without full recovery; penetrating injury; CSF leak.",ref:"NG232 1.4.16",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What is the primary investigation for suspected clinically important TBI?",a:"CT imaging of the head. Do NOT use MRI as primary investigation. Do NOT use plain skull X-rays.",ref:"NG232 1.5.1 & 1.5.4",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"When should intubation and ventilation occur immediately before transfer?",a:"Coma (GCS ≤8, not obeying/speaking/opening eyes); loss of protective laryngeal reflexes; PaO₂ <13 kPa on oxygen; PaCO₂ >6 kPa; irregular respirations.",ref:"NG232 1.8.8",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"When should intubation occur before the journey starts (even if not in coma)?",a:"Deteriorating conscious level (≥1 point drop on motor score even if not in coma); unstable facial skeleton fractures; copious oral bleeding; seizures.",ref:"NG232 1.8.9",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What are the ventilation targets during transfer of a head-injured patient?",a:"PaO₂ >13 kPa; PaCO₂ 4.5–5.0 kPa (unless raised ICP — then more aggressive hyperventilation). Maintain MAP ≥80 mmHg with fluids and vasopressors.",ref:"NG232 1.8.10",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"Does transfer to a neuroscience unit benefit patients with GCS ≤8 who don't need neurosurgery?",a:"Yes — transfer benefits anyone with GCS ≤8, irrespective of the need for neurosurgery.",ref:"NG232 1.8.1",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What is the single-factor CT head criterion for children <16 that differs from adults?",a:"Suspicion of non-accidental injury (single factor = CT within 1 hour). Also: post-traumatic seizure; GCS <14 (<15 for babies <1yr); GCS <15 at 2h; open/depressed skull fracture or tense fontanelle; basal skull fracture signs; focal deficit; baby <1yr with bruise/swelling/laceration >5cm.",ref:"NG232 1.5.10",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"For children <16 with only ONE of the ≥2-factor criteria, what happens?",a:"Observe for minimum 4 hours. If during observation: GCS <15, further vomiting, or abnormal drowsiness — CT within 1 hour.",ref:"NG232 1.5.12",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What are the ≥2-factor criteria for CT within 1 hour in children <16?",a:"LOC >5 minutes; abnormal drowsiness; ≥3 episodes of vomiting; dangerous mechanism (high-speed RTA, fall >3m, high-speed projectile); amnesia >5 minutes; any bleeding/clotting disorder.",ref:"NG232 1.5.11",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What are the high-risk criteria for CT cervical spine in adults ≥16 within 1 hour?",a:"GCS ≤12; intubated; urgent diagnosis needed for surgery/anaesthesia; blunt polytrauma involving head and chest/abdomen/pelvis in alert stable patient; clinical suspicion of cervical injury PLUS age ≥65 OR dangerous mechanism OR focal peripheral deficit OR paraesthesia in limbs.",ref:"NG232 1.6.2",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"When should pain be managed in the ED for a head-injured patient?",a:"Manage pain effectively as it can lead to a rise in ICP. Provide reassurance, splint limb fractures, and catheterise a full bladder.",ref:"NG232 1.4.11",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What does NG232 say about direct community access to neuroimaging after head injury?",a:"Do NOT refer people for neuroimaging by direct access from the community — they must be assessed in an emergency department.",ref:"NG232 1.3.19",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What is the time target for a provisional radiology report after CT head?",a:"Make a provisional written radiology report available within 1 hour of a CT scan.",ref:"NG232 1.5.14",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{q:"What was the DECRA trial — design and population?",a:"Multicentre RCT, 15 ICUs (Australia, NZ, Saudi Arabia), December 2002–April 2010. 155 adults aged 15–59 with severe diffuse TBI and ICP refractory to first-tier therapies. Randomised: 73 to bifrontotemporoparietal DC + standard care, 82 to standard care alone. Primary outcome: Extended Glasgow Outcome Scale (eGOS) at 6 months.",ref:"DECRA, p.1",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the ICP threshold for randomisation in DECRA?",a:"Spontaneous ICP >20 mmHg for >15 minutes (continuously or intermittently) within a 1-hour period, despite optimised first-tier therapies. First-tier therapies included: sedation, PaCO₂ normalisation, mannitol, hypertonic saline, neuromuscular blockade, and EVD.",ref:"DECRA, p.2",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What surgical procedure was performed in DECRA?",a:"Bifrontotemporoparietal decompressive craniectomy using the Polin technique — large bilateral craniectomy with bilateral dural opening to maximise ICP reduction. The sagittal sinus and falx cerebri were NOT divided. Bone stored at −70°C or subcutaneous abdominal pouch; cranioplasty performed 2–3 months later.",ref:"DECRA, p.2",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What were the ICP and ICU outcomes in DECRA?",a:"DC significantly reduced ICP: mean 14.4 vs 19.1 mmHg (p<0.001); hours with ICP >20 mmHg: 9.2 vs 30.0 (p<0.001). Also reduced: mechanical ventilation days (11 vs 15, p<0.001) and ICU stay (13 vs 18 days, p<0.001). Total hospital stay was not different.",ref:"DECRA, p.7",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the primary outcome result in DECRA?",a:"eGOS at 6 months was WORSE in the DC group: median eGOS 3 vs 4 (OR for worse outcome 1.84, CI 1.05–3.24, p=0.03). Unfavourable outcome (eGOS 1–4): 70% DC vs 51% standard care (OR 2.21, CI 1.14–4.26, p=0.02). Mortality was similar: 19% DC vs 18% standard care.",ref:"DECRA, p.6",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"How did DC affect vegetative state rates in DECRA and what mechanism was proposed?",a:"Vegetative state (eGOS 2) was more common in DC group: 12% vs 2%. DC did not reduce death but shifted survivors from favourable outcomes to vegetative/severe disability. Proposed mechanism: bilateral craniotomy permits brain expansion outside the skull causing axonal stretch injury, which in vitro causes neural injury.",ref:"DECRA, p.8",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What complications were more common after DC in DECRA?",a:"Any complication: 37% DC vs 17% standard care. Hydrocephalus markedly more common: 10% DC vs 1% standard care. Cranioplasty also carried further complications. Wound infection, meningitis, and pulmonary embolus rates were similar between groups.",ref:"DECRA, p.8",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the main baseline imbalance in DECRA and how did it affect interpretation?",a:"More patients in the DC group had unreactive pupils at baseline: 27% vs 12% (p=0.04), suggesting the DC group was more severely injured before randomisation. After post hoc adjustment for pupil reactivity, the eGOS difference was no longer significant (OR 1.53, p=0.15). However, a beneficial effect of DC was excluded in all analyses.",ref:"DECRA, p.7",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What is the key clinical conclusion of DECRA and how should it be contextualised?",a:"In adults with severe diffuse TBI, early DC reduced ICP and ICU stay but was associated with worse functional outcomes. DECRA studied early DC for diffuse injury at ICP threshold >20 mmHg. Later RESCUEicp (Hutchinson 2016) studied late DC as last-tier therapy for refractory ICP >25 mmHg in mixed TBI — showed reduced mortality but increased vegetative survival. The two trials address different clinical scenarios.",ref:"DECRA, p.9",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the BEST:TRIP trial (Chesnut 2012) — design and population?",a:"Multicenter RCT, 6 ICUs in Bolivia and Ecuador (South America), 2008–2011. 324 patients aged ≥13 with severe TBI (GCS 3–8 after resuscitation, or GCS that dropped to this range within 48h). Excluded: GCS 3 + bilateral fixed dilated pupils; unsurviable injuries. Randomised 157 to ICP-monitoring protocol vs 167 to imaging-clinical examination (ICE) protocol. BEST:TRIP = Benchmark Evidence from South American Trials: Treatment of Intracranial Pressure.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.1",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What were the two treatment protocols in BEST:TRIP (Chesnut 2012)?",a:"ICP-monitoring group: intraparenchymal monitor placed ASAP; treat to maintain ICP <20 mmHg per Brain Trauma Foundation guidelines. Imaging-clinical examination (ICE) group: CT at baseline, 48h, and 5-7 days; treat signs of intracranial hypertension with scheduled hyperosmolar therapy, optional hyperventilation (PaCO₂ 30-35 mmHg), and ± barbiturates; no ICP monitor. Both groups received mechanical ventilation, sedation, and analgesia.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.2",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What were the primary outcome results of BEST:TRIP (Chesnut 2012)?",a:"No significant difference in the primary outcome — composite of 21 functional/neuropsychological measures at 6 months: score 56 (ICP-monitoring) vs 53 (ICE), p=0.49. 6-month mortality: 39% vs 41% (p=0.60). ICU length of stay: 12 vs 9 days (p=0.25, NS). No significant difference in GOS-E, disability rating, or any individual neuropsychological measure.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.5",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"How did treatment intensity differ between arms in BEST:TRIP?",a:"ICE group used MORE brain-specific treatments: hypertonic saline (72% vs 58%, p=0.008), hyperventilation (73% vs 60%, p=0.003), longer osmotherapy duration, and higher integrated treatment intensity (p<0.001). ICP-monitoring group used more barbiturates (24% vs 13%, p=0.02) and had more decubitus ulcers (12% vs 5%, p=0.03). Rates of craniotomy and craniectomy were similar. The ICE group was treated more aggressively on a fixed schedule.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.7",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What does BEST:TRIP show and — critically — what does it NOT show?",a:"Shows: a monitoring-based protocol (target ICP <20 mmHg) was not superior to a structured imaging-clinical examination protocol in this setting. Does NOT show: ICP monitoring is useless or harmful. Both arms treated intracranial hypertension. The trial tested a specific interventional algorithm, not ICP monitoring per se. Authors: 'The value of knowing the precise intracranial pressure is not being challenged here.'",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.10",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key limitations of BEST:TRIP (Chesnut 2012)?",a:"(1) Low/middle income setting (Bolivia, Ecuador) — less developed prehospital care; most severely injured may not reach hospital; limited post-discharge rehabilitation. (2) Young population (median age 29) — elderly underrepresented. (3) Intraparenchymal monitor (not EVD) — EVD allows CSF drainage, a separate benefit. (4) ICE protocol was highly structured — not comparable to informal clinical management. (5) High post-discharge mortality (35% of deaths after ICU) suggesting outcomes partly driven by resource limitations, not trial protocols.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.9",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What ICP threshold was used in BEST:TRIP and what proportion of monitored patients exceeded it?",a:"Target: ICP <20 mmHg (Brain Trauma Foundation guideline threshold). In the monitoring group: initial ICP ≥20 mmHg in 37% of patients; at any point during monitoring, 79% had ICP ≥20 mmHg. Median monitoring duration 3.6 days. Mean % of readings ≥20 mmHg was 20% overall.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.7",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What was the study population's injury severity in BEST:TRIP and why does this matter for generalisability?",a:"Very severely injured: 82% AIS head ≥4; mesencephalic cisterns compressed/absent in 83-87%; 44% non-reactive pupils; 43% Marshall class III diffuse. Yet median age only 29 (traffic injuries, young males). In low-income settings, less advanced prehospital care may mean the most severely injured don't survive to hospital. The study population may therefore be less severely injured than comparable ICU populations in high-income countries — limiting generalisation to UK/European practice.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.8",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{q:"What are the clinical signs of a basal skull fracture?",a:"Anterior fossa: CSF rhinorrhoea (cribriform plate fracture); periorbital ecchymosis ('panda eyes'); anosmia. Middle fossa: haemotympanum; CSF otorrhoea; Battle's sign (mastoid ecchymosis, appears 24–48h); CN VII/VIII palsy. These are all 1-hour CT criteria per NG232.",ref:"claude — basal skull fracture signs",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"Should prophylactic antibiotics be given for traumatic CSF leak after basal skull fracture?",a:"NO. NICE NG232 (and Cochrane evidence) do NOT recommend prophylactic antibiotics for CSF rhinorrhoea or otorrhoea. No evidence of benefit; may mask meningitis. Most leaks resolve spontaneously within 7–10 days. Head elevation, avoid nose-blowing; surgical repair only for persistent leak >7–10 days.",ref:"claude — NG232 / traumatic CSF leak management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 70-year-old has a head injury with brief LOC, now GCS 15. No other risk factors. What does NG232 require?",opts:["A. Discharge with advice","B. CT head within 1 hour","C. CT head within 8 hours","D. Observe 4 hours then discharge","E. MRI head"],ans:2,exp:"NG232 (1.5.9): Adults ≥16 with LOC + age ≥65 → CT within 8 hours.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.5.9",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"A 30-year-old has vomited twice after head injury. GCS 15, no LOC. What is the CT timing?",opts:["A. No CT needed","B. CT within 1 hour","C. CT within 8 hours","D. CT within 24 hours","E. MRI within 1 hour"],ans:1,exp:"NG232 (1.5.8): >1 episode of vomiting is a 1-hour CT criterion in adults ≥16.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.5.8",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"An adult head injury patient is on rivaroxaban. No other CT indications. What does NG232 say?",opts:["A. No CT unless other indications present","B. CT within 1 hour as DOAC always mandates immediate scan","C. Consider CT within 8 hours, or within 1 hour if presenting >8 hours post-injury","D. CT only if GCS deteriorates","E. Discuss with haematology first"],ans:2,exp:"NG232 (1.5.13): Patients on anticoagulants (including DOACs) without other CT indications: consider CT within 8 hours of injury, or within 1 hour if presenting >8 hours after injury.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.5.13",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"What TXA dose does NG232 recommend for an adult with GCS 10, no extracranial bleeding?",opts:["A. 1g IV bolus","B. 2g IV bolus within 2 hours","C. 15–30 mg/kg up to 2g","D. 500mg then infusion","E. TXA not recommended in TBI"],ans:1,exp:"NG232 (1.3.17): Adults ≥16 with GCS ≤12, no active extracranial bleeding: 2g IV bolus within 2 hours of injury. Off-label.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.3.17",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"A TBI patient GCS 9 needs transfer. What are the ventilation targets per NG232?",opts:["A. PaO₂ >10 kPa; PaCO₂ 3.5–4.0 kPa","B. PaO₂ >13 kPa; PaCO₂ 4.5–5.0 kPa","C. PaO₂ >8 kPa; PaCO₂ any level","D. PaO₂ >13 kPa; PaCO₂ <3.5 kPa","E. No specific targets"],ans:1,exp:"NG232 (1.8.10): PaO₂ >13 kPa; PaCO₂ 4.5–5.0 kPa (unless raised ICP). MAP ≥80 mmHg.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.8.10",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"Which investigation is recommended for suspected TBI per NG232?",opts:["A. MRI head","B. Plain skull X-ray","C. CT head","D. CT or MRI equally","E. Transcranial Doppler"],ans:2,exp:"NG232 (1.5.1): CT head is the primary investigation. MRI should not be used as primary. Plain skull X-rays should not be used for TBI diagnosis.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.5.1",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"In the DECRA RCT, adults with severe diffuse TBI and refractory ICP >20 mmHg were randomised to early bifrontal DC vs standard care. What was the main finding at 6 months?",opts:["A. DC reduced mortality by 10% and improved functional outcome","B. DC reduced ICP but had no effect on functional outcome","C. DC reduced ICP but was associated with worse functional outcome (unfavourable outcome 70% vs 51%)","D. DC reduced ICP and reduced the rate of vegetative state","E. DC was beneficial only in patients with reactive pupils"],ans:2,exp:"DECRA (Cooper 2011, NEJM): DC significantly reduced ICP and ICU stay but the eGOS at 6 months was worse in the DC group (median 3 vs 4, OR 1.84, p=0.03). Unfavourable outcome: 70% vs 51% (OR 2.21, p=0.02). Vegetative state was MORE common in DC group (12% vs 2%). Mortality was identical (19% vs 18%). A baseline pupil imbalance limits certainty, but a beneficial effect was excluded.",ref:"DECRA, p.6",src_id:"k-decra-2011",korky:true},
{stem:"A colleague cites the BEST:TRIP trial (Chesnut 2012) to argue that ICP monitors are not needed in severe TBI. Which response most accurately reflects what the trial showed?",opts:["A. Correct — the trial proved ICP monitoring provides no useful clinical information","B. Correct — both groups did equally well so monitoring adds no value","C. Incorrect — the trial showed no superiority of a monitoring-based protocol over a structured clinical/imaging protocol in a low-income setting; it did not test whether knowing ICP has value","D. Incorrect — the trial actually showed ICP monitoring improved 6-month mortality by 2%","E. Correct — monitoring caused more complications (decubitus ulcers) so should be avoided"],ans:2,exp:"BEST:TRIP (Chesnut 2012, NEJM): RCT in Bolivia/Ecuador — a monitoring-based protocol (ICP <20 mmHg target) was not superior to a structured imaging-clinical exam protocol (composite score 56 vs 53, p=0.49; 6-month mortality 39% vs 41%, p=0.60). Key caveat: both groups were treated for intracranial hypertension; the ICE group used MORE osmotherapy and hyperventilation. The trial tested a protocol, not ICP measurement value per se. The authors explicitly stated: 'The value of knowing the precise ICP is not being challenged.' Limitations: young low-income population, intraparenchymal (not EVD) monitoring, no post-discharge rehabilitation.",ref:"Chesnut 2012, p.10",src_id:"k-chesnut-2012",korky:true},
{stem:"A child aged 7 lost consciousness for 3 minutes after a fall. GCS now 15, no other risk factors. What does NG232 recommend?",opts:["A. CT within 1 hour — LOC is a single-factor criterion","B. Observe minimum 4 hours; CT if GCS <15, vomiting, or drowsiness develops","C. CT within 8 hours","D. No CT — GCS is 15","E. MRI head"],ans:1,exp:"NG232 (1.5.11–12): LOC >5 minutes is a ≥2-factor criterion for children. LOC of 3 minutes is only 1 factor. With a single such factor, observe ≥4 hours. CT within 1 hour if GCS <15, further vomiting, or abnormal drowsiness occurs during observation.",ref:"NICE NG232, 1.5.11–12",src_id:"nice-ng232"},
{stem:"A 15-year-old boy is struck in the temple by a baseball, briefly loses consciousness, then returns to a lucid state in the ED. GCS is 15/15 and examination is normal. Which statement regarding his management is CORRECT?",opts:["A. CT head should be performed regardless of the current neurological examination","B. If neurological examination is entirely normal, he can be safely discharged home without CT","C. The likely mechanism is tearing of cortical bridging veins (subdural haematoma)","D. If a haematoma expands and causes herniation, the CONTRALATERAL pupil will dilate first","E. CT would show a crescent-shaped (concave) hyperdense collection if a haematoma is present"],ans:0,exp:"Any patient with loss of consciousness after head injury requires CT regardless of subsequent lucid interval — the lucid interval is the hallmark of epidural haematoma (EDH). EDH is almost always arterial (middle meningeal artery), not venous. CT shows a lenticular/biconvex (not crescent-shaped) hyperdense collection bounded by skull sutures. As the haematoma expands, uncal herniation compresses the IPSILATERAL CN III → ipsilateral pupil dilation. Bridging vein tears cause subdural haematomas (SDH), which have a crescent CT appearance.",ref:"Bank, p.13–14",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"Which of the following best describes epidural haematoma (EDH)?",opts:["A. Usually venous in origin from tearing of cortical bridging veins","B. Blood accumulates between the arachnoid and the dura mater","C. Associated with a skull fracture in approximately 90% of adult cases","D. Best diagnosed by CT only after clinical herniation signs appear","E. Produces a crescentic (concave) hyperdense collection on CT head"],ans:2,exp:"EDH: almost always arterial — middle meningeal artery laceration in most cases. Blood accumulates between skull and dura (epidural space), not between arachnoid and dura (subdural). ~90% of adult EDH have a concomitant skull fracture (less common in children <2). CT diagnosis should precede herniation — outcomes worsen dramatically once transtentorial herniation occurs. CT appearance: lenticular/biconvex, bounded by skull sutures. Good prognosis if evacuated before herniation.",ref:"Bank, p.4",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A patient with a basal skull fracture is noted to have clear fluid dripping from one nostril. Which is the most appropriate initial management?",opts:["A. Immediate surgical repair of the cribriform plate","B. Prophylactic amoxicillin to prevent meningitis","C. Observe — most CSF leaks resolve spontaneously; prophylactic antibiotics are not recommended","D. High-dose IV cefotaxime for 7 days","E. Urgent lumbar puncture to confirm CSF"],ans:2,exp:"Most traumatic CSF rhinorrhoea resolves spontaneously within 7–10 days. Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT recommended (NICE NG232; Cochrane review) — no evidence of benefit and they may mask meningitis. Management: head elevation, avoid nose-blowing, observe. Surgical repair (endoscopic cribriform plate) for persistent leak >7–10 days or recurrence. LP is not routinely indicated and may increase infection risk.",ref:"claude — traumatic CSF leak / NG232",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient sustains a frontal head injury. CT shows a frontal sinus fracture with disruption of BOTH the anterior and posterior walls and pneumocephalus. On examination she has clear CSF rhinorrhoea. She is neurologically intact. What is the most appropriate immediate management?",opts:["A. Prescribe prophylactic amoxicillin, give pneumococcal vaccine, and discharge home with outpatient follow-up","B. Start prophylactic IV antibiotics, give pneumococcal vaccine, and admit for observation","C. Do NOT prescribe prophylactic antibiotics; give pneumococcal vaccine; ADMIT for observation and monitoring of CSF leak; surgical repair if leak persists >7–10 days or if intracranial air increases","D. Immediate craniotomy and cranialisaton of the frontal sinus","E. Refer to ENT only — no neurosurgical management required for uncomplicated frontal sinus fracture"],ans:2,exp:"Frontal sinus fracture with POSTERIOR WALL involvement and CSF rhinorrhoea: (1) NO PROPHYLACTIC ANTIBIOTICS — evidence does not support their use; may mask meningitis (same principle as other traumatic CSF leaks). (2) PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINATION — indicated for patients with CSF leak or skull base fracture as pneumococcus is the major cause of post-traumatic meningitis. (3) ADMIT for observation — posterior wall fracture means the frontal sinus communicates with the intracranial compartment (dura breached or at risk); cannot safely discharge. (4) Monitor CSF leak: most resolve within 7–10 days. If persistent >7–10 days or brain herniating into sinus → surgical repair (cranialisaton of the frontal sinus or duraplasty via bifrontal craniotomy). Compare with isolated ANTERIOR wall fracture and no CSF leak — these can often be managed conservatively as outpatients (or with ENT).",ref:"claude — frontal sinus fracture management / NICE NG232",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 30-year-old man sustains a closed head injury resulting in a frontal temporal bone fracture at the anterior skull base. Post-operatively he is noted to have complete left ophthalmoplegia — he cannot move his left eye in any direction. His left pupil is fixed and dilated. Left ptosis is present. Visual acuity in the left eye is normal. Where is the most likely site of injury?",opts:["A. Cavernous sinus — compression causing CN III, IV, and VI palsies","B. Superior orbital fissure — fracture through the SOF compressing CN III, IV, V1, and VI as they pass through it","C. Orbital apex — fracture involving both the superior orbital fissure and the optic canal","D. Optic canal — isolated optic nerve compression","E. Sphenoid wing — causing isolated CN VI palsy"],ans:1,exp:"Superior orbital fissure (SOF) syndrome: complete CN III (ptosis + ophthalmoplegia + dilated pupil) + CN IV + CN VI (total ophthalmoplegia) + CN V1 sensory loss. All motor nerves to the eye pass through the SOF, which is traversed by CN III, IV, V1 (ophthalmic), and VI. Mechanism: fracture through the SOF from anterior skull base injury. Distinguish from ORBITAL APEX syndrome = SOF syndrome PLUS visual loss (CN II/optic canal also involved). Here: visual acuity is NORMAL → optic canal is spared → SOF syndrome (not apex syndrome). The cavernous sinus also contains these nerves but is not typically fractured in anterior skull base trauma. Management: orbital decompression if significant proptosis or optic nerve compression; optic nerve canal decompression if visual loss with evidence of nerve compression.",ref:"claude — superior orbital fissure syndrome / skull base fracture",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"An 11-year-old boy playing rugby was knocked unconscious briefly during a match, then recovered. He went home but vomited twice that evening and developed increasing headache. His mother asks when he can return to play. Concussion management guidelines indicate which of the following?",opts:["A. He can return to contact sport as soon as he is symptom-free the following morning","B. If he has another concussion in the same year, stop for the rest of the season only; otherwise return within 48 hours","C. He must follow a graduated return-to-play protocol; he should NOT return to contact sport until fully symptom-free at rest AND during cognitive activity; if another concussion occurs before full recovery, he must stop for the season","D. He cannot play rugby again as repeated concussion in childhood is always permanently disabling","E. Imaging must be performed before any return to play decision can be made"],ans:2,exp:"Concussion management in children and young people: (1) 'If in doubt, sit them out' — remove from play immediately when concussion is suspected. (2) Graduated return-to-play (GRTP) protocol: 6 steps minimum (return to school first, then light aerobic exercise, then sport-specific, then non-contact drills, then full-contact, then return to competition). Each step minimum 24 hours in adults, at least 48 hours and often longer in children <18. (3) Second impact syndrome (SIS): rare but catastrophic cerebral oedema from a second concussion before recovery from the first — more common in adolescents. This is why return to play before full recovery is strictly contraindicated. (4) Return to sport ONLY when: fully symptom-free at rest, with cognitive activity, and with increasing exertion. Not decided by imaging alone. (5) If further concussion occurs before recovery → remove for the season AND neurology review. This child has classic features of concussion (LOC, amnesia, vomiting) — GRTP must be followed.",ref:"RFU/NICE concussion guidelines / Standard paediatric head injury",recall:true},
{stem:"During an elective L4/5 discectomy under general anaesthesia, the anaesthetist notices that the right pupil, which was equal at induction, is now dilated and poorly reactive. There is no change in end-tidal CO₂ or blood pressure to suggest a different cause. What is the most appropriate immediate management?",opts:["A. Administer mannitol and hyperventilate; complete the discectomy first as it is almost finished","B. Abandon the discectomy immediately — leave the wound open; proceed directly to CT head and emergency craniotomy","C. Wake the patient from anaesthesia as quickly as safely possible; abandon the discectomy; perform urgent CT head; if acute intracranial haematoma confirmed, proceed to emergency craniotomy","D. Continue the discectomy and arrange urgent neurosurgical review post-operatively","E. Place an emergency burr hole in theatre without CT — the blown pupil confirms the side of herniation"],ans:2,exp:"Blown (dilated, poorly reactive) pupil during surgery = acute uncal herniation from an intracranial haematoma until proven otherwise. This is a neurosurgical emergency. Management: (1) SAFELY WAKE the patient as quickly as possible — do not blindly rush extubation if anaesthetic reversal is not safe, but abort the non-emergency procedure. (2) Do NOT continue the discectomy — it is an elective procedure and must be abandoned. Close the wound appropriately if possible. (3) URGENT CT HEAD: confirms the nature and side of the intracranial pathology (most likely acute SDH from intracranial venous tear or extradural haematoma — can occur from positioning or venous pressure changes). (4) Emergency craniotomy for haematoma evacuation if confirmed. Blind burr holes without CT are hazardous (wrong side or missing a different pathology). Mannitol and hyperventilation are temporising measures only.",ref:"claude — intraoperative blown pupil / acute intracranial haematoma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Which of the following risk factors is most strongly associated with late post-traumatic seizures (seizures occurring >7 days after TBI)?",opts:["A. Short-duration LOC (<5 minutes)","B. Epidural haematoma (EDH) alone without cortical injury","C. Penetrating head injury — the strongest single risk factor for late post-traumatic epilepsy","D. Scalp laceration requiring sutures","E. Concussion without any intracranial injury on CT"],ans:2,exp:"Risk factors for POST-TRAUMATIC EPILEPSY (late seizures >7 days post-injury): (1) PENETRATING BRAIN INJURY — the strongest single predictor; seizure rate up to 50% after high-velocity penetrating injuries (gunshot wounds). (2) DEPRESSED SKULL FRACTURE with underlying cortical injury. (3) INTRACEREBRAL HAEMATOMA (contusion/ICH). (4) Intracranial haemorrhage requiring surgery. (5) Early seizure (within 7 days) — predicts late PTS. Risk stratified: high risk (≥10% at 5yr) = penetrating injury, depressed fracture + LOC >24h, haematoma. Isolated EDH (without significant cortical contusion) does NOT significantly predict late PTS once evacuated. Simple concussion without intracranial injury: minimal risk. Prophylactic phenytoin/levetiracetam for 7 days is recommended for high-risk TBI to prevent EARLY seizures — does NOT prevent late epilepsy.",ref:"claude — post-traumatic epilepsy / seizure risk factors",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 75-year-old on warfarin (INR 3.4) presents with a 2-week history of worsening confusion and left hemiparesis. CT head shows a large right-sided chronic subdural haematoma with fresh bleeding (acute-on-chronic SDH). What is the correct immediate management of his anticoagulation?",opts:["A. Continue warfarin and add vitamin K only — INR correction takes too long to matter","B. Stop warfarin and administer IV vitamin K to reverse anticoagulation; proceed to surgical evacuation when INR <1.5 or if neurological deterioration mandates urgent surgery with concurrent reversal","C. Reverse with fresh frozen plasma alone — vitamin K is too slow","D. Tranexamic acid is the reversal agent for warfarin","E. Warfarin reversal is contraindicated in SDH as it risks valve thrombosis"],ans:1,exp:"Warfarin reversal in acute SDH: (1) Stop warfarin immediately. (2) IV vitamin K 5–10 mg (full reversal, takes 6–12 hours). (3) For urgent surgery: 4-factor prothrombin complex concentrate (PCC — e.g. Octaplex/Beriplex) provides rapid reversal (INR correction within 30 minutes). FFP is a second-line option if PCC unavailable. Target INR <1.5 before elective surgery. If patient is actively herniating, proceed to surgery while giving PCC simultaneously — do not delay for INR. Warfarin can be restarted after 48–72 hours post-operatively if absolutely required (e.g. mechanical heart valve) with haematology guidance. TXA has no role in warfarin reversal.",ref:"claude — anticoagulation reversal in SDH",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 22-year-old sustains a head injury and CT shows a compound depressed skull fracture over the right parietal region. Which of the following is the LEAST compelling indication for surgical elevation?",opts:["A. Fracture depressed more than the full thickness of the skull (outer table to inner table)","B. Underlying dural laceration with brain exposure (open depressed fracture with dural breach)","C. Cosmetically disfiguring depression over the forehead","D. A single post-traumatic seizure occurring within 1 hour of injury — prior to any surgical or pharmacological intervention","E. Significant underlying haematoma requiring evacuation"],ans:3,exp:"Indications for surgical elevation of a compound depressed skull fracture include: depression > skull thickness; open fracture with dural laceration; significant cosmetic deformity (especially frontal); underlying haematoma; wound contamination. A single early post-traumatic seizure (within the first hour) is NOT an independent indication for surgical elevation — early seizures can occur from the head injury itself (cortical irritation) without necessarily indicating that the fracture geometry needs to change. The fracture is elevated for the anatomical/mechanical reasons listed above. Prophylactic anticonvulsants are given, but the seizure itself does not change the surgical decision for the fracture.",ref:"claude — compound depressed skull fracture surgical indications",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 4-year-old child presents with a slowly enlarging scalp swelling overlying a parietal skull fracture sustained 6 months ago. MRI shows a leptomeningeal cyst (growing skull fracture). Which statement about growing skull fractures is correct?",opts:["A. They can occur with intact dura — the pulsatile CSF pressure alone remodels the bone","B. Growing skull fractures require a dural tear — without dural breach, leptomeninges cannot herniate through the fracture gap and pulsatile CSF pressure cannot remodel the bone edge","C. They are most common in adults over 50 due to bone softening","D. Treatment is conservative — the fracture will close spontaneously with skull growth","E. Associated hydrocephalus is the primary indication for intervention"],ans:1,exp:"Growing skull fractures (leptomeningeal cysts) require a dural tear as a necessary condition. Without dural breach: the fracture gap closes normally with fibrous healing. With dural tear: leptomeninges herniate through the gap; pulsatile CSF pressure transmitted by the herniated arachnoid/brain causes progressive bone edge resorption and enlarging defect. Most common in children <3 years (thinner dura, faster bone remodelling). Management: surgical dural repair + cranioplasty. If untreated, they enlarge progressively — spontaneous closure does not occur.",ref:"claude — growing skull fracture / leptomeningeal cyst",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient develops bilateral orbital haematoma (raccoon eyes) and CSF rhinorrhoea following a high-energy frontal impact. CT shows an anterior skull base fracture. Which statement about management of the CSF leak is correct?",opts:["A. Prophylactic IV antibiotics should be started immediately to prevent meningitis","B. Pneumococcal vaccination should be given; prophylactic antibiotics are NOT routinely recommended — the CSF leak will resolve spontaneously in >90% of cases within 1 week; surgery is considered for leaks persisting >2 weeks or recurrent leak","C. Immediate surgical repair of the skull base fracture is required within 24 hours","D. Lumbar drain insertion is mandatory to reduce CSF pressure and allow the leak to seal","E. CT cisternography must be performed before any management decision"],ans:1,exp:"Post-traumatic CSF rhinorrhoea management: (1) Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT recommended — RCTs show no reduction in meningitis rate and risk antibiotic resistance (Cochrane). (2) Pneumococcal vaccination IS recommended because encapsulated organisms (especially pneumococcus) cause meningitis in this setting. (3) Conservative management: head elevation, avoid nose-blowing/Valsalva, most leaks (>90%) resolve spontaneously within 7–10 days. (4) Surgical repair (endoscopic or transcranial) considered for: leak persisting >2 weeks; recurrent leak after initial resolution; large dural tear with pneumocephalus; associated sinus fractures needing repair. Lumbar drains are sometimes used as adjuncts but are not mandatory.",ref:"claude — CSF rhinorrhoea management / post-traumatic",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During a posterior fossa exploration, a patient has a temporal bone fracture noted on pre-operative imaging. Which cranial nerve is LEAST commonly injured by a temporal bone fracture?",opts:["A. Facial nerve (CN VII) — courses through the facial canal in the petrous temporal bone; at high risk in transverse fractures","B. Vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) — inner ear and cochlea at risk from petrous fractures","C. Abducens nerve (CN VI) — long intracranial course but NOT within the temporal bone; injured at the petrous apex indirectly by raised ICP or fracture vector, rarely directly","D. Trigeminal nerve (CN V) — branches course in structures adjacent to but not within the temporal bone; rarely directly injured","E. CSF otorrhoea is a sign of temporal bone fracture with dural disruption"],ans:3,exp:"Temporal bone fractures typically injure nerves that run within or immediately adjacent to the petrous temporal bone. Most commonly: CN VII (facial nerve, especially transverse fractures through the facial canal) and CN VIII (hearing loss from cochlear/labyrinth damage, or sensorineural from acoustic nerve disruption). CN V branches do not course through the temporal bone and are rarely directly injured. CN VI has a long intracranial course but its injury in temporal fractures is indirect (through raised ICP or basal skull force vectors — 'false localising sign') rather than direct anatomical involvement. CSF otorrhoea indicates longitudinal temporal bone fracture through the middle ear with dural breach.",ref:"claude — temporal bone fracture / cranial nerve injuries",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Evidence from randomised trials indicates which surgical technique is most effective for chronic subdural haematoma (CSDH) evacuation?",opts:["A. Craniotomy — provides the most complete haematoma removal and lowest recurrence rate","B. Single burr hole without drain — equivalent to two burr holes and avoids drain complications","C. Two burr holes with subdural drain — supported by level 1 evidence (RCT); associated with lower recurrence rates than burr hole alone or craniotomy","D. Twist drill craniostomy — bedside procedure; equivalent outcomes to burr hole with drain","E. MRI-guided aspiration — least invasive; first-line in current guidelines"],ans:2,exp:"The CSDH drainage debate: Multiple RCTs and meta-analyses have examined single vs two burr holes vs subdural drainage. Current evidence (including the CSDH trial and Cochrane reviews) supports two burr holes with subdural drain as the technique with the lowest recurrence rate — the drain maintains a cavity for residual haematoma/fluid to drain over 24–48 hours post-operatively. Single burr hole without drain has higher recurrence. Craniotomy is reserved for recurrent, organised, or septated haematomas. Twist drill has higher failure rates. Current NICE guidance and British Neurosurgical Trainee Research Collaborative (BNTRC) evidence support drain insertion as standard.",ref:"claude — CSDH surgical evidence / burr hole with drain",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"The RESCUEicp trial compared decompressive craniectomy with ongoing medical management for refractory traumatic intracranial hypertension. What was the primary finding at 6 months?",opts:["A. No significant difference in mortality or functional outcome between groups","B. Craniectomy reduced mortality by ~22 percentage points but increased rates of vegetative state and severe disability","C. Craniectomy improved both survival and rates of good recovery equally","D. Medical management was superior for diffuse injury; craniectomy beneficial only for focal mass lesions","E. Craniectomy reduced mortality only in patients under 40 years of age"],ans:1,exp:"RESCUEicp (Hutchinson 2016, NEJM): 408 patients, ICP >25 mmHg for 1–12 h despite stages 1+2. At 6 months: death 26.9% (surgical) vs 48.9% (medical) — a 22 percentage point reduction. However, surgery increased vegetative state (8.5% vs 2.1%) and lower severe disability (21.9% vs 14.4%). Favourable outcome (upper severe disability or better) was 42.8% vs 34.6% (P=0.12, not significant). Good recovery rates were similar. Key message: craniectomy saves lives but more survivors are severely disabled.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.6",src_id:"aberdeen-rescueicp",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with diffuse TBI has ICP of 22 mmHg persisting for 20 minutes despite stage 1 measures. Which trial most closely matches this scenario, and what does the evidence show about craniectomy?",opts:["A. RESCUEicp — craniectomy is preferred as it reduces mortality by 22 percentage points","B. DECRA — early bifrontal craniectomy was associated with worse GOS-E outcomes than standard care","C. DECRA — early craniectomy is beneficial as it definitively reduces ICP","D. Neither — no RCT evidence exists for ICP between 20–25 mmHg after stage 1","E. RESCUEicp — craniectomy should be offered once ICP exceeds 20 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"DECRA (Cooper 2011, NEJM): diffuse TBI only, ICP >20 mmHg for ≥15 min despite first-tier (stage 1) measures — this matches the scenario. Early bifrontal craniectomy was associated with worse GOS-E at 6 months vs standard care (P=0.03); mortality rates were similar (19% vs 18%). RESCUEicp enrolled patients with ICP >25 mmHg for 1–12 h after exhausting stages 1 AND 2 — a last-tier intervention. Key distinctions: DECRA = stage 2 threshold, diffuse TBI only; RESCUEicp = stage 3 (ICP >25, 1–12h), includes haematomas, allows unilateral craniectomy.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.10",src_id:"aberdeen-rescueicp",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"In the medical management arm of the RESCUEicp trial, what proportion of patients received barbiturate infusion, and what proportion ultimately crossed over to decompressive craniectomy?",opts:["A. 25% barbiturates; 10% crossed over to surgery","B. 50% barbiturates; 20% crossed over to surgery","C. 75% barbiturates; 25% crossed over to surgery","D. 87.2% barbiturates; 37.2% crossed over to surgery","E. 100% barbiturates; 15% crossed over to surgery"],ans:3,exp:"In the RESCUEicp medical group, 87.2% received barbiturate infusion (median duration 53 hours) — the primary stage 3 medical option. Despite randomisation to medical management, 37.2% ultimately underwent decompressive craniectomy due to further clinical deterioration. This significant crossover may have diluted the observed treatment effect. In the surgical group, craniectomy was performed in 92.6% (median time to surgery: 2.2 hours).",ref:"Aberdeen, p.7",src_id:"aberdeen-rescueicp",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"neuro-onco-cranial":{src:"NICE NG99 (2018, updated 2021) — verified from PDF",c:[
{q:"What is the standard MRI protocol for suspected glioma per NG99?",a:"Standard structural MRI: T2-weighted, FLAIR, DWI series, and T1 pre- and post-contrast volume. This is the initial diagnostic test unless MRI is contraindicated.",ref:"NG99 1.1.1, p6",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should a patient with a suspected glioma be referred to the specialist MDT?",a:"At first radiological diagnosis — refer without delay for management of their tumour.",ref:"NG99 1.1.2, p6",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should advanced MRI techniques (perfusion, spectroscopy) be used in glioma?",a:"Consider MR perfusion and MR spectroscopy to assess potential high-grade transformation in a tumour appearing low-grade on standard structural MRI.",ref:"NG99 1.1.3, p6",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What 5 molecular markers must be included in glioma histopathological reporting per NG99?",a:"(1) IDH1 and IDH2 mutations; (2) ATRX mutations (identifies IDH-mutant astrocytomas and glioblastomas); (3) 1p/19q codeletion (identifies oligodendrogliomas); (4) histone H3.3 K27M (midline gliomas); (5) BRAF fusion and mutation (pilocytic astrocytoma).",ref:"NG99 1.1.4, p7",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Which molecular test must be done on ALL high-grade glioma specimens per NG99?",a:"MGMT promoter methylation — mandatory for all high-grade specimens to inform prognosis and guide treatment.",ref:"NG99 1.1.5, p7",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should TERT promoter mutations be tested in glioma?",a:"Consider testing IDH-wildtype glioma specimens for TERT promoter mutations to inform prognosis.",ref:"NG99 1.1.6, p7",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What surgical expertise must the MDT have for glioma resection per NG99?",a:"Access to: (1) awake craniotomy with language and other functional monitoring; (2) intraoperative neurophysiological monitoring expertise; (3) neuroradiological support; (4) intraoperative image guidance.",ref:"NG99 1.2.1, p7-8",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What are the two goals of surgical resection in suspected low-grade glioma, and within what timeframe?",a:"(1) Obtain histological and molecular diagnosis; AND (2) remove as much tumour as safely possible. Surgery should be considered within 6 months of radiological diagnosis.",ref:"NG99 1.2.2, p8",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"If surgical resection is not appropriate for a suspected LGG, what should be offered?",a:"Consider biopsy to obtain a histological and molecular diagnosis.",ref:"NG99 1.2.3, p8",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"For which LGG subtypes can active monitoring without histological diagnosis be considered?",a:"Lesions with radiological features typical of very low-grade tumours, for example DNET (dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumour) or optic pathway glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.4, p8",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"If a patient on active monitoring for LGG shows radiological or clinical progression, what should be done?",a:"Discuss at MDT and consider surgical resection, or biopsy if resection is not possible.",ref:"NG99 1.2.5, p8",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What adjuvant treatment is recommended for newly diagnosed IDH-mutated, 1p/19q-codeleted LGG (oligodendroglioma) if age around 40 or over, or residual tumour on post-op MRI?",a:"Offer radiotherapy followed by up to 6 cycles of PCV chemotherapy (procarbazine, CCNU [lomustine], vincristine).",ref:"NG99 1.2.6, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What adjuvant treatment is recommended for newly diagnosed IDH-mutated, 1p/19q non-codeleted LGG (astrocytoma) if age around 40 or over, or residual tumour?",a:"Consider radiotherapy followed by up to 6 cycles of PCV chemotherapy.",ref:"NG99 1.2.7, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What does NG99 recommend for an IDH-mutated LGG patient aged around 40 or under with no residual tumour on post-op MRI?",a:"Consider active monitoring — no immediate adjuvant treatment required.",ref:"NG99 1.2.8, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"An IDH-mutated LGG patient who has not had previous radiotherapy develops progressive disease on imaging follow-up. What does NG99 recommend?",a:"Consider radiotherapy followed by up to 6 cycles of PCV chemotherapy. Same applies if intractable seizures develop.",ref:"NG99 1.2.9, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the maximum RT dose and fractionation for IDH-mutated low-grade glioma per NG99?",a:"Do NOT use a treatment dose of more than 54 Gy at 1.8 Gy per fraction.",ref:"NG99 1.2.10, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Why is IDH-wildtype grade 2 glioma clinically important to identify?",a:"Its prognosis may be similar to glioblastoma if other molecular features are consistent with GBM. This must be taken into account when considering management — do not treat as a standard LGG.",ref:"NG99 1.2.11, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment is recommended for newly diagnosed grade 3 glioma with 1p/19q codeletion (anaplastic oligodendroglioma) in a fit patient?",a:"Offer sequential radiotherapy and 4 to 6 cycles of PCV chemotherapy, for patients with Karnofsky performance status of 70 or more.",ref:"NG99 1.2.13, p10",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Does the order of PCV vs radiotherapy matter for anaplastic oligodendroglioma per NG99?",a:"No clinically important difference in OS or PFS. Agree the order with the patient based on fertility plans, life events, and logistics (PCV first = less initial contact with health system; RT first = more predictable chemotherapy start date).",ref:"NG99 1.2.14, p10",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment is recommended for grade 3 non-codeleted glioma (anaplastic astrocytoma) in a fit patient per NG99?",a:"Offer radiotherapy followed by up to 12 cycles of adjuvant temozolomide, for patients with Karnofsky performance status of 70 or more.",ref:"NG99 1.2.15, p11",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Should nitrosoureas (CCNU/lomustine) be given concurrently with radiotherapy for newly diagnosed grade 3 glioma?",a:"No — do NOT offer nitrosoureas concurrently with radiotherapy for newly diagnosed grade 3 glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.16, p11",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What 6 treatments does NG99 say lack evidence for grade 3 glioma?",a:"Cannabis oil; immunotherapy; ketogenic diets; metformin; statins; valganciclovir. Advise patients these are not evidence-based if asked.",ref:"NG99 1.2.17, p11",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the Stupp protocol for newly diagnosed GBM in patients aged around 70 or under with KPS 70 or more?",a:"Radiotherapy 60 Gy in 30 fractions with concomitant temozolomide, followed by up to 6 cycles of adjuvant temozolomide.",ref:"NG99 1.2.19, p12",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment is recommended for GBM in patients aged around 70 or over, KPS 70 or more, with confirmed MGMT methylation?",a:"Offer radiotherapy 40 Gy in 15 fractions with concomitant and up to 12 cycles of adjuvant temozolomide.",ref:"NG99 1.2.20, p12",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment is recommended for GBM in patients aged around 70 or over, KPS 70 or more, with MGMT unmethylated or status unavailable?",a:"Consider radiotherapy 40 Gy in 15 fractions with concomitant and up to 12 cycles of adjuvant temozolomide.",ref:"NG99 1.2.21, p12-13",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment is recommended for GBM in patients aged around 70 or over with KPS under 70?",a:"Consider best supportive care alone.",ref:"NG99 1.2.22, p13",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Does NG99 recommend bevacizumab for newly diagnosed GBM?",a:"No — do NOT offer bevacizumab as part of management of newly diagnosed grade 4 glioma (glioblastoma).",ref:"NG99 1.2.25, p13",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Does NG99 recommend tumour-treating fields (TTF) for newly diagnosed GBM?",a:"No — do NOT offer TTF as part of management of newly diagnosed grade 4 glioma (glioblastoma).",ref:"NG99 1.2.26, p13",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What 6 treatments does NG99 say lack evidence for newly diagnosed or recurrent GBM?",a:"Cannabis oil; immunotherapy; ketogenic diets; metformin; statins; valganciclovir. Same list applies to both grade 3 and grade 4 glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.27, p13-14",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What 5 factors must be taken into account when deciding treatment for recurrent high-grade glioma per NG99?",a:"(1) Karnofsky performance status; (2) patient preferences; (3) time from last treatment; (4) tumour molecular markers; (5) what their last treatment was.",ref:"NG99 1.2.28, p14",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What chemotherapy alternatives exist for recurrent high-grade glioma per NG99?",a:"Consider PCV or single-agent CCNU (lomustine) as alternatives to temozolomide for recurrent high-grade glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.29, p14",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"For focally recurrent high-grade glioma, what additional local treatment options should the MDT consider?",a:"Further surgery and further radiotherapy — in addition to systemic therapy options.",ref:"NG99 1.2.32, p15",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Which targeted agents are explicitly NOT recommended for recurrent high-grade glioma per NG99?",a:"Do NOT offer bevacizumab, erlotinib, or cediranib (alone or in combination with chemotherapy) for recurrent high-grade glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.33, p15",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Does NG99 recommend tumour-treating fields (TTF) for recurrent high-grade glioma?",a:"No — do NOT offer TTF as part of management of recurrent high-grade glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.2.34, p15",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should 5-ALA (5-aminolevulinic acid) be offered during glioma surgery?",a:"Offer 5-ALA guided resection as an adjunct at initial surgery when: (1) tumour is radiologically enhancing; (2) suspected HGG; AND (3) the MDT thinks complete resection of all enhancing tumour is possible.",ref:"NG99 1.2.36, p16",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What intraoperative imaging adjuncts should be considered during glioma resection per NG99?",a:"Consider intraoperative MRI (low and high-grade); consider intraoperative ultrasound (low and high-grade); consider DTI overlays to minimise damage to functionally important fibre tracts.",ref:"NG99 1.2.37-39, p16",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should awake craniotomy be considered for glioma per NG99?",a:"Consider awake craniotomy for both low-grade and high-grade glioma to help preserve neurological function. Discuss benefits and risks. Only proceed if the person is unlikely to be significantly distressed by it. Involve neuropsychologists and SLT as appropriate.",ref:"NG99 1.2.40-42, p16-17",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should baseline post-operative MRI be performed after glioma resection?",a:"Within 72 hours of surgical resection for all types of glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.3.7, p18",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should baseline MRI be performed after radiotherapy for glioma?",a:"3 months after completion of radiotherapy for all types of glioma.",ref:"NG99 1.3.8, p18",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 follow-up imaging schedule for grade 2 IDH-mutated glioma (1p/19q codeleted or non-codeleted) and grade 3 1p/19q codeleted?",a:"0-2 years: scan at 3 months, then every 6 months. 2-4 years: annually. 5-10 years: every 1-2 years. Beyond 10 years: consider ongoing imaging every 1-2 years.",ref:"NG99 Table 3, p19",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 follow-up imaging schedule for grade 2 IDH-wildtype, grade 3 1p/19q non-codeleted, and grade 4 (GBM)?",a:"0-2 years: every 3-6 months. 2-4 years: every 6-12 months. 5-10 years: annually. Beyond 10 years: consider imaging every 1-2 years.",ref:"NG99 Table 3, p19-20",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What imaging is recommended for suspected meningioma per NG99?",a:"Offer standard structural MRI (T2, FLAIR, DWI, T1 pre/post contrast) as the initial diagnostic test. Consider CT imaging in addition if bone involvement is suspected.",ref:"NG99 1.4.1-2, p20",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 recommended management after complete excision (Simpson grade 1-3) of a grade 1 meningioma?",a:"Offer active monitoring.",ref:"NG99 Table 4, p21",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 recommended management after complete excision (Simpson grade 1-3) of a grade 2 meningioma?",a:"Offer a choice between active monitoring and radiotherapy.",ref:"NG99 Table 4, p21",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 recommended management after complete excision (Simpson grade 1-3) of a grade 3 meningioma?",a:"Offer radiotherapy.",ref:"NG99 Table 4, p21",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What is the NG99 management of an asymptomatic incidental meningioma?",a:"Scan at 12 months; if no change, consider discharge or scan again at 5 years. Note: residual tumour can only be established after the first scan at 3 months if surgery was performed.",ref:"NG99 Table 7, p26-27",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What imaging is recommended for suspected brain metastases per NG99?",a:"Offer standard structural MRI (T2, FLAIR, DWI, T1 pre/post contrast) as the initial diagnostic test.",ref:"NG99 1.6.1, p27",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What additional investigation is required before referral to the neuro-oncology MDT for suspected brain metastases?",a:"Offer extracranial imaging (appropriate to primary tumour type) to establish disease status. Complete all intracranial and extracranial imaging, plus biopsy of extracranial disease if appropriate, before MDT referral.",ref:"NG99 1.6.2-3, p27",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What treatment does NG99 recommend for a single brain metastasis?",a:"Consider maximal local therapy with either surgery, stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS), or stereotactic radiotherapy (SRT).",ref:"NG99 1.7.3, p28",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Should adjuvant whole-brain radiotherapy (WBRT) be offered after a single brain metastasis has been treated with SRS or surgery per NG99?",a:"No — do NOT offer adjuvant WBRT to people with a single brain metastasis treated with SRS, SRT, or surgery.",ref:"NG99 1.7.5, p30",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Who should be considered for stereotactic radiosurgery or radiotherapy for multiple brain metastases per NG99?",a:"People with multiple brain metastases who have controlled or controllable extracranial disease AND Karnofsky performance status of 70 or more. Take into account number and total volume of metastases.",ref:"NG99 1.7.7, p30",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"When should WBRT NOT be offered for NSCLC brain metastases per NG99?",a:"Do NOT offer WBRT to people with NSCLC who have brain metastases not suitable for surgery or SRS/SRT AND a Karnofsky performance status under 70.",ref:"NG99 1.7.8, p30-31",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"How should the decision on WBRT be made for multiple brain metastases not suitable for focal treatment per NG99?",a:"Decide with the patient after a shared discussion of potential benefits and risks. Key points from Table 9: WBRT shows no overall survival benefit; causes short-term QoL deterioration; carries risk of accelerated cognitive loss; requires 5-10 hospital visits.",ref:"NG99 1.7.9, p31",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"Should memantine be offered alongside WBRT for brain metastases per NG99?",a:"No — do NOT offer memantine in addition to WBRT, unless as part of a clinical trial.",ref:"NG99 1.7.10, p31",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"List the late-onset side effects of brain tumour treatment per NG99.",a:"Cataracts; cavernoma; cognitive decline; epilepsy; hearing loss; hypopituitarism; infertility; neuropathy (visual loss, numbness, pain, weakness); radionecrosis; secondary tumours; SMART syndrome (stroke-like migraine attacks after radiotherapy); stroke.",ref:"NG99 1.11.1, p37-38",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What endocrine monitoring is required if a patient has received radiotherapy that may have affected pituitary function?",a:"Consider checking endocrine function regularly after the end of treatment.",ref:"NG99 1.11.6, p38",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What legal obligation regarding driving must be explained to all patients with a brain tumour?",a:"The person has a legal obligation to notify the DVLA, as a brain tumour may have implications for their driving.",ref:"NG99 1.9.7, p35",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{q:"What was the Berger 2008 study and what was its key question?",a:"Retrospective study (Smith/Berger, JCO 2008) of 216 adults with hemispheric low-grade gliomas (LGG) at UCSF. Volumetrically assessed the influence of extent of resection (EOR) on overall survival (OS), progression-free survival (PFS), and malignant progression-free survival (MPFS) using FLAIR-based measurements.",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.1",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What was the key finding of Berger 2008 regarding EOR in low-grade gliomas?",a:"Greater EOR independently predicted better OS and MPFS after adjusting for age, KPS, tumour location, and subtype. Patients with ≥90% EOR had 5-year OS 97% and 8-year OS 91%. Patients with <90% EOR had 5-year OS 76% and 8-year OS 60%. EOR HR for death = 0.972 per 1% increase (P<.001).",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.1, p.3",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"How was tumour volume measured in Berger 2008?",a:"Manual segmentation with region-of-interest analysis on FLAIR axial MRI slices. EOR = (preop volume - postop volume) / preop volume. Median preop volume 36.6 cm³, median postop volume 3.7 cm³, median EOR 88%. LGGs are best delineated on FLAIR (not contrast-enhancing).",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.2",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What were the prognostic factors for overall survival in Berger 2008?",a:"After multivariate adjustment: EOR (HR 0.972, P<.001), log preoperative tumour volume (HR 4.442, P=.004), and postoperative tumour volume (HR 1.010, P=.03). Complete resection of all FLAIR abnormality had significantly longer OS vs any residual (HR 0.094, P=.001).",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.3",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What was the safety profile of aggressive LGG resection in Berger 2008?",a:"Zero operative mortality. New postoperative deficits in 17% (36/216), but all except 4 had complete recovery. No significant association between EOR and risk of new deficit (P=.36). Motor mapping used in 71%, speech mapping in 35% of cases.",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.2, Table 2",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What were the tumour characteristics in Berger 2008?",a:"216 patients: astrocytoma 43%, oligodendroglioma 42%, mixed oligoastrocytoma 15%. 83% presented with seizures. Frontal lobe 52%, insular 26%, temporal 14%, parietal 8%. 58% involved eloquent cortex. 35% achieved complete FLAIR resection, 12% had 90-99% EOR.",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.2-3, Table 1",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What did Berger 2008 show about malignant transformation in LGG?",a:"20% (44/216) underwent malignant progression over median follow-up 4.4 years. Median time to malignant progression: 10.1 years. 95% of malignant progressions showed new contrast enhancement. Greater EOR predicted longer MPFS (HR 0.983, P=.005). Larger preop volume also predicted shorter MPFS.",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.2-3",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"Why is Berger 2008 significant for neurosurgical practice in LGG?",a:"It provided volumetric evidence that maximal safe resection improves survival in LGG — supporting an aggressive surgical philosophy over biopsy-only or watchful waiting. The ≥90% EOR threshold showed dramatically better outcomes (97% vs 76% 5-year OS). This shifted the debate toward early maximal resection for operable LGGs.",ref:"Berger 2008, JCO, p.1",src_id:"k-berger-2008",korky:true},
{q:"What was the Stupp trial and what was the study design?",a:"Phase 3 RCT (EORTC/NCIC, NEJM 2005). 573 patients, 85 centres, 15 countries. Newly diagnosed histologically confirmed GBM (WHO grade IV), age 18-70, WHO performance status ≤2. 84% had debulking surgery. Compared RT alone vs RT + concomitant/adjuvant temozolomide.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.1-2",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What is the exact Stupp protocol radiotherapy regimen?",a:"Fractionated focal irradiation: 60 Gy total, 2 Gy per fraction, once daily, 5 days/week (Mon-Fri), over 6 weeks (30 fractions). Delivered to gross tumour volume + 2-3 cm margin. Conformal RT with linear accelerators ≥6 MV.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.2",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What is the exact Stupp protocol concomitant TMZ regimen?",a:"Temozolomide 75 mg/m²/day, given 7 days per week (including weekends), from day 1 to last day of radiotherapy (up to 49 days). PCP prophylaxis required (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or inhaled pentamidine) because continuous TMZ causes lymphocytopenia.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.2-3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What is the exact Stupp protocol adjuvant TMZ regimen?",a:"After a 4-week break post-RT: TMZ 150 mg/m² days 1-5 of cycle 1, escalated to 200 mg/m² from cycle 2 if no haematologic toxicity. Each cycle is 28 days. Up to 6 cycles. NOT 6 weeks — 6 cycles of 28 days each. 47% of patients completed all 6 cycles.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.2-3, Table 2",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What were the primary results of the Stupp trial?",a:"Median survival: 14.6 months (RT+TMZ) vs 12.1 months (RT alone) — 2.5 month benefit. HR for death: 0.63 (95% CI 0.52-0.75, p<0.001) = 37% relative reduction in risk of death. 2-year survival: 26.5% vs 10.4% — a 2.5-fold improvement.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.6, Table 3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What was the progression-free survival in the Stupp trial?",a:"Median PFS: 6.9 months (RT+TMZ) vs 5.0 months (RT alone). HR for progression or death: 0.54 (95% CI 0.45-0.64, p<0.001). PFS at 12 months: 26.9% vs 9.1%. PFS at 24 months: 10.7% vs 1.5%.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.6, Table 3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What were the main toxicities of the Stupp protocol?",a:"Grade 3/4 haematologic toxicity: 7% during concomitant phase. Concomitant phase: neutropenia 4%, thrombocytopenia 3%. Adjuvant phase: thrombocytopenia 11%, neutropenia 4%. Fatigue most common non-haematologic AE (33%). Severe infections: 3% concomitant, 5% adjuvant.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.6-7",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"Why is PCP prophylaxis required during concomitant Stupp protocol?",a:"Continuous daily temozolomide causes lymphocytopenia (CD4 count drops), increasing the risk of Pneumocystis jirovecii (formerly carinii) pneumonia. Prophylaxis with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or inhaled pentamidine is mandatory during the concomitant (daily) phase.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What is the role of MGMT promoter methylation in the Stupp protocol?",a:"MGMT (O6-methylguanine-DNA methyltransferase) is a DNA repair enzyme. MGMT promoter methylation → gene silencing → reduced DNA repair → enhanced sensitivity to alkylating agents (TMZ). Methylated MGMT is a strong predictive biomarker for benefit from TMZ. Continuous TMZ also depletes MGMT enzyme levels.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.1, p.8",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"Which patient subgroups did NOT benefit from the Stupp protocol?",a:"Two subgroups showed no significant benefit: (1) patients who underwent biopsy only (93 patients, no debulking); (2) patients with poor WHO performance status (70 patients, status 2). All other subgroups (age, sex, extent of resection, steroid use) showed significant benefit.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.6",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What is the common exam trap regarding Stupp protocol dosing?",a:"The adjuvant phase is 6 CYCLES of 28 days each (TMZ days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle), NOT 6 weeks of continuous TMZ. The concomitant phase is daily for ~6 weeks during RT. Recall bank notes: 'dose double after initial chemoradio' — the adjuvant dose (200 mg/m²) is higher than the concomitant dose (75 mg/m²).",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.2-3; recall bank",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"Why was temozolomide given concomitantly with radiotherapy in the Stupp protocol?",a:"Three reasons: (1) continuous daily dosing increases dose intensity ~2x vs standard 5-day schedule without extra toxicity; (2) continuous TMZ depletes MGMT — the DNA repair enzyme that can be induced by RT; (3) in vitro synergy between TMZ and RT. TMZ spontaneously converts to its active metabolite and crosses the BBB.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.8",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{q:"When is 5-ALA (5-aminolevulinic acid) used in glioma surgery and what is its mechanism?",a:"Offered when tumour is radiologically enhancing, suspected HGG, AND complete resection of all enhancing tumour appears possible (NG99 1.2.36, p16). Mechanism: 5-ALA is metabolised to fluorescent protoporphyrin IX (PpIX) preferentially in malignant glioma cells — causes pink-red intraoperative fluorescence under violet-blue light, aiding identification of residual tumour. Improves extent of resection and 6-month progression-free survival.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.36, p16",recall:true},
{q:"What is Foster Kennedy syndrome?",a:"Ipsilateral optic atrophy (direct compression of ipsilateral optic nerve) + contralateral papilloedema (raised ICP transmitted to the other eye). Classic cause: large olfactory groove or sphenoid wing meningioma. Often associated with ipsilateral anosmia. Key distinction from 'pseudo-Foster Kennedy' (sequential ischaemic optic neuropathy): imaging shows a mass lesion.",ref:"claude — neuroanatomy — Foster Kennedy syndrome",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What is the clinical significance of 1p/19q codeletion in glioma?",a:"(1) Diagnostic: together with IDH mutation, defines oligodendroglioma (WHO 2021). (2) Predictive: associated with chemosensitivity — responds to PCV chemotherapy. (3) Prognostic: better overall survival than IDH-mutant astrocytoma without codeletion. Arises from an unbalanced whole-arm translocation. Tested by FISH or SNP array.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.1.4, p7 / WHO CNS 2021",recall:true},
{q:"What molecular features can diagnose GBM (grade 4) in a histologically grade 2/3 IDH-wildtype astrocytic glioma under WHO CNS5?",a:"Any ONE of the following in an IDH-wildtype, H3-wildtype astrocytic glioma is sufficient to classify as GBM regardless of histological grade: (1) TERT promoter mutation (~72% of GBM); (2) EGFR amplification (~35%); (3) concurrent whole chromosome 7 gain and whole chromosome 10 loss (+7/−10). These molecular features carry GBM-equivalent prognosis.",ref:"Greenberg, p.665",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What molecular features distinguish oligodendroglioma from IDH-mutant astrocytoma?",a:"Both are IDH-mutant. Oligodendroglioma: IDH mutation + 1p/19q whole-arm codeletion; ATRX is RETAINED; often also TERT promoter mutation. IDH-mutant astrocytoma: IDH mutation + ATRX loss and/or TP53 mutation; 1p/19q codeletion is ABSENT. Loss of ATRX by IHC is a useful surrogate marker for the astrocytic lineage.",ref:"Greenberg, p.662–664",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What is the concurrent temozolomide dose in the Stupp protocol, and why is PCP prophylaxis mandatory?",a:"Concurrent dose: 75 mg/m²/day, given DAILY (7 days/week including weekends) throughout the entire ~6 weeks of radiotherapy (up to 49 days). PCP prophylaxis is mandatory because continuous daily TMZ causes CD4+ T-cell lymphocytopenia, creating risk of Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia. Use trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or inhaled pentamidine.",ref:"Greenberg, p.672",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What is the prevalence of MGMT promoter methylation in GBM IDH-wildtype, and what is its prognostic impact?",a:"MGMT methylation occurs in approximately 36-45% of GBM IDH-wildtype. Methylated patients: median OS ~21-23 months with Stupp protocol. Unmethylated: ~12-14 months. The benefit of TMZ is substantially greater in methylated patients. In elderly patients (>70), MGMT methylation status is particularly important for treatment decisions.",ref:"Greenberg, p.672–673",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What is the T2-FLAIR mismatch sign and what does it indicate?",a:"A solid tumour that is hyperintense on T2-weighted MRI but shows relative signal suppression (hypointensity) on FLAIR. Highly specific (though not sensitive) for IDH-mutant, 1p/19q non-codeleted astrocytoma (grade 2-3). Useful to distinguish IDH-mutant astrocytoma from oligodendroglioma (no mismatch) and GBM. Mechanism: high free-water content of these tumours causes the T2 signal to be suppressed on FLAIR.",ref:"Greenberg, p.660",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What proportion of low-grade gliomas undergo malignant transformation, and over what timeframe?",a:"Approximately 75% undergo malignant dedifferentiation (transformation to grade 3 or 4) over their natural history. Median time to transformation is approximately 5-10 years. New contrast enhancement on MRI heralds transformation. Greater extent of initial resection is associated with longer time to transformation.",ref:"Greenberg, p.662",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What defines low-risk vs high-risk low-grade glioma for adjuvant treatment decisions?",a:"Low risk: age <40 AND gross total resection (no residual tumour on post-op MRI) — active monitoring is appropriate. High risk: age ≥40 OR incomplete resection (either criterion is sufficient). High-risk patients are offered adjuvant RT ± chemotherapy (PCV preferred for 1p/19q codeleted; TMZ for non-codeleted).",ref:"Greenberg, p.671",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"How is GTR defined for non-enhancing low-grade glioma, and which intraoperative tool is NOT useful?",a:"GTR for LGG = resection of all (or near-all) T2-FLAIR signal abnormality on post-op MRI at 48-72 hours (≤1 cm³ residual or no residual FLAIR signal). Since LGGs do not enhance, contrast enhancement does not guide resection. 5-ALA is NOT useful for LGG (requires enhancing tumour). Awake craniotomy, DTI overlays, and intraoperative ultrasound/MRI maximise safe resection.",ref:"Greenberg, p.669",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the five Simpson grades for meningioma removal and their recurrence rates?",a:"Grade I: Macroscopically complete + excision of dural attachment + abnormal bone (including sinus resection); 9% recurrence. Grade II: Complete + endothermy/coagulation of dural attachment (not excision); 19%. Grade III: Complete without dural resection or coagulation; 29%. Grade IV: Partial removal, tumour left in situ; 44%. Grade V: Simple decompression ±biopsy; N/A.",ref:"Greenberg, p.815",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the histological criteria for WHO grade 2 (atypical) meningioma?",a:"Any ONE of: (1) 4-19 mitotic figures per 10 HPF (≥2.5/mm²); (2) unequivocal brain parenchymal invasion (perivascular spread alone does not qualify); (3) chordoid or clear cell subtype. OR ≥3 of: increased cellularity, small cells with high N:C ratio, prominent nucleoli, sheeting (patternless growth), foci of spontaneous (non-iatrogenic) necrosis. Nuclear atypia alone is insufficient.",ref:"Greenberg, p.806",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the histological criteria for WHO grade 3 (anaplastic) meningioma?",a:"Any ONE of: (1) ≥20 mitotic figures per 10 HPF (≥12.5/mm²); (2) frank anaplasia (sarcoma-, carcinoma-, or melanoma-like appearance); (3) TERT promoter mutation; (4) homozygous deletion of CDKN2A and/or CDKN2B. Comprise 1-3% of meningiomas.",ref:"Greenberg, p.806",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the Ki-67 proliferation index and recurrence rates for each WHO grade of meningioma?",a:"Grade 1: mean Ki-67 0.7%, recurrence 9%. Grade 2 (atypical): mean Ki-67 2.1%, recurrence 29%. Grade 3 (anaplastic): mean Ki-67 11%, recurrence 50%. Note: Ki-67 should NOT be used as the sole grading discriminant due to inter-observer variability.",ref:"Greenberg, p.807",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the post-operative radiotherapy indications for meningioma by WHO grade and Simpson resection grade?",a:"Grade 3 (anaplastic): post-op XRT regardless of extent of resection. Grade 2 + subtotal resection (Simpson IV-V): post-op XRT recommended. Grade 2 + GTR (Simpson I-III): monitor, treat at recurrence. Grade 1: post-op XRT NOT recommended even with subtotal resection, unless progressive growth and repeat surgery is not viable. Fractionated dose for grade 2/3: 55-60 Gy.",ref:"Greenberg, p.814",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the five characteristic CT/MRI imaging features of meningioma?",a:"(1) Broad-based dural attachment. (2) Dural tail (not pathognomonic — also in PXA, Rosai-Dorfman disease, others). (3) Hyperostosis of adjacent bone (better on CT; occurs in 5-44%). (4) Cerebral oedema of adjacent brain (variable; marked in secretory, angiomatous, high-grade subtypes). (5) Dense, uniform contrast enhancement. CT: isodense/slightly hyperdense. MRI: isointense on T1 and T2. Angiography: 'comes early, stays late' — prolonged homogeneous blush.",ref:"Greenberg, p.812",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the presentation, blood supply, and surgical approach for olfactory groove meningioma?",a:"Presentation: asymptomatic until large; Foster Kennedy syndrome (ipsilateral anosmia, ipsilateral optic atrophy, contralateral papilloedema); frontal lobe syndrome (apathy, abulia); urinary incontinence; short-term memory loss (fornix compression). Blood supply: 70-80% from anterior ethmoidal artery (branch of ophthalmic) — NOT embolised (risk of blindness). Approach: bifrontal craniotomy + lumbar drain; early blood supply interrupted at floor of frontal fossa. Post-op risk: CSF leak through ethmoid sinuses.",ref:"Greenberg, p.808",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key facts about cerebellar haemangioblastoma and its management of cystic lesions?",a:"Most common primary intra-axial posterior fossa tumour in adults. 70% sporadic, 30% associated with von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease. Any patient with HGB should be screened for VHL. Erythrocytosis (polycythaemia) from EPO secreted by tumour cells. MRI: 70% of cerebellar HGBs are cystic with enhancing mural nodule. Surgery: remove mural nodule ONLY — cyst wall does not need excision (unless tumour in wall on MRI). All patients require MRI of entire neuraxis (spinal HGBs may occur).",ref:"Greenberg, p.823–824",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"Which molecular combination is required to diagnose oligodendroglioma per NG99?",opts:["A. IDH mutation alone","B. 1p/19q codeletion alone","C. IDH mutation AND 1p/19q codeletion","D. ATRX loss alone","E. H3 K27M mutation"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.1.4, p7): Both IDH mutation AND 1p/19q codeletion are required to identify oligodendroglioma. 1p/19q codeletion alone is insufficient.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.1.4, p7",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"IDH-mutated, 1p/19q-codeleted grade 2 glioma, age 36, complete resection on post-op MRI. What does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. RT + PCV immediately","B. Temozolomide alone","C. Active monitoring","D. RT alone at 54 Gy","E. Best supportive care"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.2.8, p9): IDH-mutated LGG, age around 40 or under, no residual tumour — consider active monitoring. RT + PCV applies to age around 40 or over, or if residual tumour remains.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.8, p9",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"GBM, age 62, KPS 80. What treatment does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. RT 60 Gy/30fr + concomitant TMZ + up to 6 cycles adjuvant TMZ","B. RT 40 Gy/15fr + TMZ","C. TMZ alone","D. Best supportive care","E. RT 54 Gy + bevacizumab"],ans:0,exp:"NG99 (1.2.19, p12): Age around 70 or under, KPS 70 or more — offer Stupp protocol: RT 60 Gy/30fr with concomitant TMZ, then up to 6 cycles adjuvant TMZ. The 40 Gy/15fr protocol is for age around 70 or over.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.19, p12",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"GBM, age 74, KPS 75, MGMT methylated. What does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. Stupp (60 Gy/30fr + TMZ)","B. RT 40 Gy/15fr with concomitant + up to 12 cycles adjuvant TMZ","C. TMZ alone","D. Best supportive care","E. RT 54 Gy + bevacizumab"],ans:1,exp:"NG99 (1.2.20, p12): Age around 70 or over, KPS 70 or more, MGMT methylated — offer RT 40 Gy/15fr with concomitant and up to 12 cycles adjuvant TMZ.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.20, p12",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"GBM, age 76, KPS 55. What does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. Stupp protocol","B. RT 40 Gy/15fr + TMZ","C. TMZ alone if MGMT methylated","D. Consider best supportive care alone","E. Referral for clinical trial only"],ans:3,exp:"NG99 (1.2.22, p13): Age around 70 or over, Karnofsky performance status under 70 — consider best supportive care alone.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.22, p13",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"Grade 3 anaplastic oligodendroglioma, KPS 80, newly diagnosed after resection. What does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. RT alone","B. TMZ alone","C. Sequential RT and 4-6 cycles PCV, order agreed with patient","D. RT + 12 cycles TMZ","E. Best supportive care"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.2.13-14, p10): Grade 3 with 1p/19q codeletion (anaplastic oligodendroglioma), KPS 70 or more — offer sequential RT and 4-6 cycles PCV. Order of PCV vs RT has no OS difference and is agreed with the patient.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.13-14, p10",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"When should 5-ALA be offered during glioma surgery per NG99?",opts:["A. All glioma resections regardless of grade","B. LGG resections only to aid identification","C. Radiologically enhancing suspected HGG where the MDT believes complete resection of all enhancing tumour is possible","D. All GBM biopsies","E. Recurrent GBM only"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.2.36, p16): 5-ALA is offered when the tumour is radiologically enhancing, suspected HGG, AND complete resection of all enhancing tumour appears possible — as an adjunct to maximise resection at initial surgery.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.36, p16",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"After complete excision (Simpson grade 2) of a grade 2 meningioma, what does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. Active monitoring only","B. Immediate radiotherapy","C. Offer a choice between active monitoring and radiotherapy","D. Chemotherapy","E. Discharge with no follow-up"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (Table 4, p21): Grade 2 meningioma, completely excised (Simpson 1-3) — offer a choice between active monitoring and radiotherapy.",ref:"NICE NG99, Table 4, p21",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"In a single brain metastasis treated with SRS, should adjuvant WBRT be offered per NG99?",opts:["A. Yes, always to reduce intracranial recurrence","B. Yes, if NSCLC primary","C. No","D. Only if KPS under 70","E. Only if multiple new metastases develop later"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.7.5, p30): Do NOT offer adjuvant WBRT to people with a single brain metastasis treated with SRS, SRT, or surgery.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.7.5, p30",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"When should baseline post-operative MRI be performed after glioma surgery?",opts:["A. Within 24 hours","B. Within 72 hours","C. 4-6 weeks post-op","D. 3 months post-op","E. At first outpatient visit"],ans:1,exp:"NG99 (1.3.7, p18): Baseline MRI within 72 hours of surgical resection for all types of glioma.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.3.7, p18",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"A patient with newly diagnosed GBM asks about using a ketogenic diet alongside their chemotherapy. What does NG99 advise?",opts:["A. May be beneficial alongside TMZ","B. Consider alongside TMZ if MGMT methylated","C. Evidence does not support its use for treating glioma","D. Refer to dietitian for assessment","E. Only avoid if patient is on high-dose steroids"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.2.27, p13-14): Evidence does not support cannabis oil, immunotherapy, ketogenic diets, metformin, statins, or valganciclovir for newly diagnosed GBM.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.27, p13-14",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"A patient with multiple brain metastases from NSCLC has KPS 60 and metastases not suitable for surgery or SRS. What does NG99 recommend?",opts:["A. WBRT as standard of care","B. WBRT with memantine","C. Do NOT offer WBRT","D. Concurrent systemic therapy with WBRT","E. Stereotactic radiotherapy regardless of KPS"],ans:2,exp:"NG99 (1.7.8, p30-31): Do NOT offer WBRT to people with NSCLC who have brain metastases not suitable for surgery or SRS/SRT AND Karnofsky performance status under 70.",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.7.8, p30-31",src_id:"nice-ng99"},
{stem:"In the Stupp protocol for newly diagnosed GBM, what is the adjuvant temozolomide schedule?",opts:["A. 75 mg/m²/day continuously for 6 weeks","B. 200 mg/m² days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle for 6 cycles","C. 150 mg/m² days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle for 12 cycles","D. 75 mg/m²/day for 5 days every 28 days for 6 cycles","E. 200 mg/m² continuously for 6 months"],ans:1,exp:"Stupp adjuvant phase: TMZ 150 mg/m² days 1-5 cycle 1, escalated to 200 mg/m² from cycle 2. Six 28-day cycles. NOT 6 weeks continuous. NOT 75 mg/m² (that's the concomitant dose). Common exam trap.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.2-3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old with newly diagnosed GBM has MGMT promoter methylation. What does this mean for treatment with the Stupp protocol?",opts:["A. TMZ is contraindicated","B. Enhanced benefit from TMZ — MGMT methylation is a favourable predictive biomarker","C. No effect on treatment response","D. Switch to carmustine instead","E. Omit radiotherapy, use TMZ alone"],ans:1,exp:"MGMT promoter methylation → gene silencing → less DNA repair → greater sensitivity to alkylating agents (TMZ). Stupp companion paper showed striking survival benefit in methylated patients treated with RT+TMZ.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.1, p.8",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"What prophylaxis is mandatory during the concomitant phase of the Stupp protocol?",opts:["A. Antifungal prophylaxis","B. Pneumocystis jirovecii prophylaxis (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole)","C. Herpes simplex prophylaxis (aciclovir)","D. Neutropenic sepsis prophylaxis (G-CSF)","E. Deep vein thrombosis prophylaxis only"],ans:1,exp:"Continuous daily TMZ causes lymphocytopenia → risk of PCP. Prophylaxis with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or inhaled pentamidine is required during concomitant treatment.",ref:"Stupp 2005, NEJM, p.3",src_id:"k-stupp-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old HIV-positive man with CD4 count 40 cells/μL presents with 4 weeks of progressive left hemiparesis and confusion. MRI shows a solitary ring-enhancing periventricular lesion with surrounding oedema. Which diagnosis is MOST likely?",opts:["A. Glioblastoma multiforme","B. Cerebral metastasis from an unknown primary","C. Ependymoma","D. Primary CNS lymphoma","E. Oligodendroglioma"],ans:3,exp:"Primary CNS lymphoma (PCNSL) occurs with greatly increased frequency in immunocompromised patients — especially AIDS (CD4 <100), organ transplant recipients, and those on immunosuppression. MRI: periventricular ring-enhancing or homogeneously enhancing lesions, often crossing the corpus callosum. Key differential: toxoplasma encephalitis (typically multiple lesions; empirical pyrimethamine+sulfadiazine for 2 weeks — improvement confirms diagnosis). GBM is commonest in immunocompetent adults. CSF cytology and EBV PCR support diagnosis; stereotactic biopsy may be required.",ref:"Bank, p.2",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"During craniotomy for a right temporal enhancing mass, 5-ALA was given pre-operatively. Under violet-blue illumination, part of the lesion fluoresces pink-red. What does this indicate?",opts:["A. Necrotic core — avoid this area","B. Normal cortex activated by retraction","C. Areas of maximum tumour vascularity for embolisation","D. Malignant glioma tissue — guides resection to maximise tumour removal","E. Reactive gliosis without malignant transformation"],ans:3,exp:"5-ALA is converted to protoporphyrin IX (PpIX) preferentially in HGG cells. Under violet-blue light (375–440 nm), tumour fluoresces pink-red while normal brain appears blue/non-fluorescent. Used to identify residual tumour at resection margins — improves complete resection and 6-month progression-free survival. Indicated for radiologically enhancing suspected HGG where complete resection of enhancing tumour appears possible (NG99 1.2.36).",ref:"NICE NG99, 1.2.36, p16",recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old presents with progressive visual loss in the right eye and papilloedema in the left eye. CT shows a large frontal mass at the olfactory groove with right optic nerve compression. What is this syndrome?",opts:["A. Parinaud's syndrome — dorsal midbrain compression","B. Foster Kennedy syndrome — ipsilateral optic atrophy, contralateral papilloedema","C. Internuclear ophthalmoplegia — MLF lesion","D. Bitemporal hemianopia — optic chiasm compression","E. Cavernous sinus syndrome — multiple CN palsies"],ans:1,exp:"Foster Kennedy syndrome: a large olfactory groove or sphenoid wing meningioma compresses the ipsilateral optic nerve (→ direct optic atrophy) and raises ICP (→ contralateral papilloedema). Often associated with ipsilateral anosmia from olfactory tract compression. Distinguished from 'pseudo-Foster Kennedy' (sequential AION) by the presence of a mass lesion on imaging.",ref:"claude — Foster Kennedy syndrome / olfactory groove meningioma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"In the Stupp protocol for newly diagnosed GBM, what is the standard adjuvant temozolomide schedule after completion of chemoradiotherapy?",opts:["A. 75 mg/m²/day continuously for 6 weeks","B. 150 mg/m² (cycle 1) escalating to 200 mg/m² (cycles 2-6), days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle","C. 200 mg/m² continuously for 5 days per week for 6 months","D. 100 mg/m² days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle, up to 12 cycles","E. 150 mg/m² days 1-5 of each 28-day cycle, up to 12 cycles"],ans:1,exp:"Adjuvant TMZ: cycle 1 = 150 mg/m² days 1-5 (to assess haematologic tolerance), then escalate to 200 mg/m² for cycles 2-6 if no significant toxicity. Each cycle is 28 days. Maximum 6 cycles. The concurrent phase dose (75 mg/m²/day daily) is different — a frequent exam trap. A 4-week break from radiotherapy precedes the first adjuvant cycle.",ref:"Greenberg, p.672",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Approximately what percentage of IDH-wildtype GBMs have MGMT promoter methylation?",opts:["A. 5-10%","B. 15-20%","C. 36-45%","D. 60-70%","E. 75-80%"],ans:2,exp:"MGMT promoter methylation is present in approximately 36-45% of GBM IDH-wildtype. It silences the MGMT DNA repair gene, impairing repair of TMZ-induced alkylation damage. Methylated GBM: median OS ~21-23 months with Stupp. Unmethylated: ~12-14 months. MGMT status is mandatory to test for all GBM (NG99 1.1.5).",ref:"Greenberg, p.673",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old presents with a non-enhancing frontal lobe lesion. Histology confirms IDH mutation and 1p/19q whole-arm codeletion. Which statement BEST describes the clinical significance?",opts:["A. Confirms GBM — treat with Stupp protocol immediately","B. Defines oligodendroglioma — associated with chemosensitivity and better prognosis than IDH-mutant astrocytoma","C. Confirms IDH-mutant astrocytoma — ATRX must be retained","D. Suggests aggressive transformation — early RT + PCV is mandatory regardless of age","E. No clinical significance — molecular markers do not change management"],ans:1,exp:"IDH mutation + 1p/19q whole-arm codeletion = oligodendroglioma (WHO CNS5 2021). This predicts chemosensitivity (especially to PCV and alkylating agents) and confers better overall survival than IDH-mutant astrocytoma without codeletion. ATRX is RETAINED in oligodendroglioma (ATRX loss = astrocytic lineage). Management in this low-risk patient: active monitoring after GTR.",ref:"Greenberg, p.662–664",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"On MRI, which single feature is MOST reliable for distinguishing low-grade glioma from high-grade glioma (GBM) prior to tissue diagnosis?",opts:["A. Mass effect and midline shift","B. Lesion diameter greater than 4 cm","C. Absence of contrast enhancement and absence of central necrosis","D. Involvement of eloquent cortex","E. T2 hyperintensity crossing the corpus callosum"],ans:2,exp:"LGGs are classically non-enhancing on T1 post-contrast and lack central necrosis. Contrast enhancement and ring necrosis are hallmarks of GBM, reflecting blood-brain barrier breakdown and tumour necrosis. Important caveat: IDH-wildtype grade 2 glioma may also be non-enhancing but carries GBM-equivalent molecular features — check TERT, EGFR, +7/−10. A butterfly appearance crossing the corpus callosum suggests HGG.",ref:"Greenberg, p.657–659",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which single molecular marker is the most important prognostic and predictive factor for GBM patients receiving the Stupp protocol?",opts:["A. IDH1 mutation","B. EGFR amplification","C. MGMT promoter methylation","D. 1p/19q codeletion","E. ATRX loss"],ans:2,exp:"MGMT promoter methylation is the strongest predictive biomarker for benefit from temozolomide in GBM. It silences MGMT DNA repair, preventing repair of TMZ-induced alkylation damage. Methylated GBM: median OS ~21-23 months. Unmethylated: ~12-14 months. IDH1 mutation is absent in nearly all true GBMs (IDH-mutant GBM is rare). 1p/19q codeletion = oligodendroglioma marker.",ref:"Greenberg, p.667–668, 673",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient is scheduled for craniotomy for a right temporal ring-enhancing mass suspected to be GBM. The surgeon plans fluorescence-guided resection with 5-aminolevulinic acid (5-ALA). What is the correct administration?",opts:["A. IV infusion of 5-ALA 10 mg/kg at induction of anaesthesia","B. Oral 20 mg/kg approximately 3 hours before induction of anaesthesia","C. Topical 5-ALA solution applied to the resection cavity intraoperatively","D. Oral 5 mg/kg the night before surgery","E. IV bolus 100 mg at skin incision"],ans:1,exp:"5-ALA (Gliolan) is given orally at 20 mg/kg body weight, approximately 3 hours before induction of anaesthesia (range 2-4 hours). This allows metabolic conversion to fluorescent protoporphyrin IX (PpIX) preferentially in malignant cells. Under violet-blue illumination (375-440 nm), tumour tissue fluoresces pink-red while normal brain is non-fluorescent. Indicated for radiologically enhancing suspected HGG where complete resection appears possible (NG99 1.2.36).",ref:"Greenberg, p.670",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Three months after completing concurrent chemoradiotherapy (Stupp protocol) for GBM, a patient's MRI shows markedly increased enhancement with oedema and mass effect. The patient is neurologically stable with KPS 80. What is the most appropriate next step?",opts:["A. Treat as true progression — switch to bevacizumab immediately","B. Emergency re-resection for presumed tumour recurrence","C. Assume pseudoprogression — continue adjuvant TMZ and repeat MRI in 6-8 weeks","D. Stop all treatment and arrange palliative care","E. Start high-dose dexamethasone and repeat MRI in 6 months"],ans:2,exp:"Pseudoprogression occurs in 15-30% of GBM patients after Stupp protocol, typically within 3 months of RT completion. It represents treatment-induced inflammatory changes, not true recurrence. Management: continue adjuvant TMZ and repeat MRI in 6-8 weeks. iRANO criteria: if within first 6 months post-RT, continue treatment for ≥2 more TMZ cycles before changing therapy (unless unequivocal clinical deterioration). Biopsy/resection reserved for clinical deterioration.",ref:"Greenberg, p.673",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 33-year-old presents with a single seizure. MRI shows a 3.5 cm non-enhancing left frontal T2-hyperintense lesion. Post-operative MRI after craniotomy shows no residual FLAIR signal. Histology: IDH-mutant, 1p/19q codeleted, grade 2 oligodendroglioma. What is the appropriate adjuvant management?",opts:["A. Immediate RT 54 Gy + PCV chemotherapy","B. Immediate RT alone 54 Gy","C. Temozolomide 12 cycles immediately","D. Active monitoring — low-risk patient","E. Bevacizumab for 6 months"],ans:3,exp:"This is a low-risk LGG: age <40 AND gross total resection (no residual tumour on post-op MRI). Per NG99 (1.2.8) and Greenberg management algorithms, low-risk patients are appropriate for active monitoring with serial imaging. Adjuvant treatment (RT ± PCV) is reserved for high-risk patients (age ≥40 OR incomplete resection). RTOG 9802 showed RT + PCV benefit in high-risk LGG — not demonstrated in low-risk.",ref:"Greenberg, p.671",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient undergoes resection of a left parasagittal meningioma. The surgeon achieves macroscopically complete removal with endothermy of the dural attachment (no dural excision). Histology returns grade 3 (anaplastic) with 22 mitotic figures per 10 HPF. What is the Simpson grade and recommended post-operative management?",opts:["A. Simpson grade I; monitor only","B. Simpson grade II; post-op fractionated radiotherapy 55-60 Gy — grade 3 requires XRT regardless of extent of resection","C. Simpson grade III; monitor, treat at recurrence","D. Simpson grade II; stereotactic radiosurgery only","E. Simpson grade IV; best supportive care"],ans:1,exp:"Simpson grade II = macroscopically complete removal with endothermy (coagulation/cautery) of dural attachment but without dural excision. Grade I would require excision of the dural attachment. WHO grade 3 meningioma (≥20 mitoses/10 HPF) requires post-op XRT regardless of extent of resection, including Simpson grade I or II. Dose: 55-60 Gy fractionated.",ref:"Greenberg, p.814–815",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is Simpson grade I meningioma removal and its recurrence rate?",opts:["A. Macroscopically complete with endothermy of dural attachment; 19%","B. Macroscopically complete with excision of dural attachment and abnormal bone; 9%","C. Macroscopically complete without dural coagulation; 29%","D. Partial removal leaving tumour in situ; 44%","E. Simple decompression ±biopsy; N/A"],ans:1,exp:"Simpson grade I: macroscopically complete removal PLUS excision of dural attachment AND removal of abnormal bone (including sinus resection if involved). Recurrence: 9% — the lowest. Grade II (endothermy, not excision): 19%. The critical distinction: grade I removes the dural origin; grade II coagulates it. This is the 'gold standard' for benign meningioma but not always achievable at skull base.",ref:"Greenberg, p.815",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During resection of a parasagittal meningioma at the middle third of the superior sagittal sinus, the sinus appears completely occluded on pre-operative MRV. What is the safest approach to the involved sinus?",opts:["A. Divide the SSS and reconstruct with a Gore-Tex graft","B. Divide the SSS and reconstruct with a venous graft — ~50% thrombosis rate is acceptable","C. Leave residual tumour attached to the sinus; monitor with serial imaging, consider SRS for growth","D. Pre-operatively embolise the SSS then divide","E. Divide the SSS immediately after induction before tumour swelling occurs"],ans:2,exp:"Middle third SSS involvement: attempting complete removal with SSS division carries 8% morbidity and 3% mortality from venous infarction. Reconstruction: venous graft ~50% thrombosis, Gore-Tex ~100% — BOTH unacceptably high. Greenberg's recommendation: leave residual tumour, follow with serial imaging, use SRS for residual/recurrent tumour <2.3-3 cm diameter. Note: anterior to the coronal suture, the SSS may usually be divided safely.",ref:"Greenberg, p.816",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient consents for excision of a right parasagittal meningioma straddling the motor strip at the middle third of the superior sagittal sinus. Which of the following is the MOST important specific risk related to this tumour location?",opts:["A. CSF leak through the ethmoid sinuses","B. Optic nerve injury","C. Venous infarction from SSS injury, with risk of contralateral leg weakness from ACA territory ischaemia","D. Posterior inferior cerebellar artery injury","E. ICA injury within the cavernous sinus"],ans:2,exp:"Parasagittal meningioma at the middle third SSS: key risks are (1) venous infarction if the SSS is damaged — 8% morbidity, 3% mortality; (2) ACA territory ischaemia — the ACA and cortical branches supply the leg area of the motor strip (parasagittal cortex); damage here causes contralateral leg weakness. The SSS must not be divided posterior to the coronal suture (vein of Trolard).",ref:"Greenberg, p.816",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which tumour type represents the most common primary intracranial neoplasm in adults, and what is the female-to-male ratio?",opts:["A. GBM — equal sex distribution","B. Pituitary adenoma — slight female predominance","C. Meningioma — female:male 2.3:1","D. Vestibular schwannoma — equal sex distribution","E. Metastatic tumour — male predominance"],ans:2,exp:"Meningiomas represent 36.4% of all CNS tumours and 54.5% of non-malignant CNS tumours — the most common primary intracranial neoplasm in adults. Female:male ratio 2.3:1. Median age at diagnosis 65 years. Incidence increases with age (1.49/100,000 at age 20-34 → 57.29 at age >85). The only confirmed environmental risk factor is ionising radiation.",ref:"Greenberg, p.810",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 68-year-old develops confusion on post-operative day 3 after resection of a large right frontal convexity meningioma. Bloods: Na 127 mmol/L, K 3.0 mmol/L, Hb 9.0 g/dL. Which is the MOST likely cause of his confusion?",opts:["A. Hypokalaemia (K 3.0 mmol/L)","B. Hyponatraemia (Na 127 mmol/L)","C. Mild anaemia (Hb 9.0 g/dL)","D. Post-operative deep vein thrombosis","E. Normal post-operative physiological response"],ans:1,exp:"Hyponatraemia is the most common electrolyte cause of post-brain-surgery confusion. Na 127 is moderate hyponatraemia — occurs post-craniotomy from SIADH or cerebral salt wasting (CSW). Hypokalaemia (K 3.0) causes muscle weakness and cardiac arrhythmia, but does NOT typically cause confusion at this level. Mild anaemia alone (Hb 9.0) is unlikely to cause confusion in an otherwise stable patient. DVT does not directly cause confusion.",ref:"Recall bank rq38; Greenberg post-op management",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 26-year-old presents with progressive cerebellar ataxia and headache over 6 weeks. FBC shows haematocrit 58%. MRI reveals a cystic posterior fossa lesion with a small enhancing mural nodule. What is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the correct surgical management of the cyst wall?",opts:["A. Pilocytic astrocytoma — excise the entire cyst wall","B. Medulloblastoma — whole craniospinal irradiation","C. Cerebellar haemangioblastoma — remove the mural nodule only; the cyst wall does not need excision","D. Ependymoma — complete surgical resection of cyst and nodule","E. Metastatic renal cell carcinoma — systemic therapy only"],ans:2,exp:"Cerebellar haemangioblastoma: most common primary intra-axial posterior fossa tumour in adults. Classic presentation: young adult, cerebellar syndrome, erythrocytosis (polycythaemia from EPO secretion). 70% are cystic with mural nodule. Surgery: ONLY the mural nodule requires removal — the cyst wall is non-neoplastic compressed cerebellum. 30% are associated with VHL disease — screen all patients. Pilocytic astrocytoma is also cystic/nodular but does NOT cause polycythaemia.",ref:"Greenberg, p.823–824",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old woman presents with progressive right-sided sensorineural hearing loss and tinnitus over 2 years. MRI shows a right cerebellopontine angle (CPA) mass. CT bone windows show widening of the right internal auditory meatus (IAM). Which diagnosis does this favour, and what imaging feature would instead suggest a meningioma at this location?",opts:["A. IAM widening favours meningioma; a broad dural base would suggest schwannoma","B. IAM widening favours vestibular schwannoma; a broad dural base, dural tail, and absence of IAM widening favour meningioma","C. IAM widening is non-specific; both tumours widen the IAM equally","D. IAM widening favours ependymoma; calcification would suggest meningioma","E. CPA tumours cannot be differentiated by imaging — all require biopsy"],ans:1,exp:"CPA tumour differentiation: (1) VESTIBULAR SCHWANNOMA: IAM widening on CT ('ice cream cone' shape extending into canal) — pathognomonic; arises from CN VIII within the IAM. MRI: homogeneous or heterogeneous enhancement, centred on IAM, no dural tail. Accounts for ~80% of CPA tumours. (2) MENINGIOMA (~10% of CPA tumours): broad dural base along the posterior petrous face, NO IAM widening (does not enter the IAM — it arises from the dura); dural tail sign; may calcify; tends to cause multiple cranial nerve deficits earlier. Other CPA tumours: epidermoid cyst (lobulated, DWI restriction, no enhancement — fills the cistern like water filling a crack), arachnoid cyst (no enhancement, no DWI restriction). Key: if the IAM is widened on CT → schwannoma until proven otherwise.",ref:"claude — CPA tumour differentiation / IAM anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 16-year-old boy presents with Parinaud syndrome and polyuria/polydipsia. MRI shows a pineal region mass and a separate suprasellar mass (bifocal). Tumour markers: serum ALP is mildly elevated; serum β-HCG is 4 IU/L (normal <5); serum AFP is 3 ng/mL (normal <10); CSF cytology negative. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Non-germinomatous germ cell tumour — elevated AFP indicates a yolk sac tumour component","B. Non-germinomatous germ cell tumour — elevated β-HCG indicates choriocarcinoma","C. Pure germinoma — ALP may be mildly elevated; β-HCG and AFP are normal; bifocal pineal + suprasellar location is classic","D. Primary CNS lymphoma — bifocal involvement and diabetes insipidus indicate CSF seeding","E. Pineoblastoma — elevated ALP is pathognomonic for this tumour"],ans:2,exp:"Germ cell tumour marker interpretation: (1) PURE GERMINOMA: ALP may be mildly elevated (placental-like ALP from syncytiotrophoblastic giant cells); β-HCG normal or minimally elevated (<50 IU/L); AFP NORMAL (<10 ng/mL). Bifocal presentation (pineal + suprasellar) is almost pathognomonic of germinoma. (2) CHORIOCARCINOMA: markedly elevated β-HCG (>1000). (3) YOLK SAC TUMOUR: markedly elevated AFP (>100). (4) MATURE TERATOMA: markers usually normal. Key rule: any AFP >10 ng/mL OR β-HCG >50 IU/L = NGGCT (not pure germinoma). Diabetes insipidus occurs most commonly with suprasellar germinomas (infiltrating the infundibulum/posterior pituitary). Pure germinomas are exquisitely radiosensitive — 5-year OS >90%. Avoid biopsy of CPA lesions when markers are diagnostic; however, marker-negative lesions require biopsy.",ref:"claude — intracranial germ cell tumour markers",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"MRI of a pineal region mass in a 55-year-old shows a well-circumscribed 1.5 cm homogeneously enhancing lesion with no brainstem infiltration and no spinal metastases. A 5-year-old child has an ill-defined pineal mass with hydrocephalus, brainstem infiltration, and multiple spinal drop metastases on whole-spine MRI. Which pairing of diagnosis to presentation is correct?",opts:["A. Both are pineocytomas — clinical presentation cannot distinguish grade","B. The adult presentation is consistent with pineocytoma (WHO grade 1 — benign, slow-growing, older adults); the child's presentation is consistent with pineoblastoma (WHO grade 4 — aggressive, young children, high metastatic rate)","C. The adult has pineoblastoma; the child has pineocytoma — pineal tumours are more aggressive in adults","D. Both are pineoblastomas — all pineal tumours metastasise via CSF","E. Both are germinomas — germinomas are the most common pineal tumour at all ages"],ans:1,exp:"Pineal parenchymal tumours: (1) PINEOCYTOMA (WHO grade 1): slow-growing, well-demarcated, typically ADULTS (mean age ~38–40 years); no CSF seeding; 'exploded rosette' pattern on histology; good prognosis with surgical resection. (2) PINEOBLASTOMA (WHO grade 4): highly malignant, predominantly YOUNG CHILDREN (<10 years); ill-defined, invasive, high CSF dissemination rate; associated with DICER1 mutations or bilateral retinoblastoma (trilateral retinoblastoma syndrome). Treatment: max safe resection + craniospinal RT + chemotherapy. Poor prognosis. (3) PPTID (pineal parenchymal tumour of intermediate differentiation, WHO grade 2–3): intermediate behaviour. Distinguishing features: age at presentation, well-defined vs infiltrative, presence of spinal metastases. Germinomas are more common than pineocytomas in younger patients but present in adolescence, not infancy.",ref:"claude — pineocytoma vs pineoblastoma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 7-year-old child undergoes gross total resection of a midline vermian medulloblastoma. Post-operative MRI shows no residual tumour; whole-spine MRI shows no metastases (M0). Molecular analysis: WNT-activated subgroup, no MYC amplification. Which statement correctly identifies the prognostic significance of these findings?",opts:["A. WNT-activated + MYC amplification + M0 = best prognosis","B. WNT-activated subgroup + gross total resection + M0 disease confers the most favourable prognosis; 5-year OS approaches 90–95%","C. SHH-activated + age <3 + M0 = best prognosis regardless of molecular subgroup","D. Group 3 + MYC amplification + M0 = best prognosis","E. Desmoplastic/nodular histology determines prognosis independently of molecular subgroup"],ans:1,exp:"Medulloblastoma prognostic factors — FAVOURABLE: (1) WNT-activated molecular subgroup (5-year OS ~90–95% — best of all subgroups); (2) Gross total resection (residual <1.5 cm² on post-op MRI); (3) M0 disease (no CSF/spinal metastases); (4) Age ≥3 years; (5) Desmoplastic/nodular histology. UNFAVOURABLE (high-risk): (1) Group 3 — often MYC amplified, young children, metastatic → worst prognosis; (2) MYC or MYCN amplification; (3) M+ disease; (4) Residual >1.5 cm²; (5) Age <3 years; (6) Large-cell/anaplastic histology. Clinical implication: trials are evaluating RT dose de-escalation in WNT-activated disease given excellent prognosis. Standard treatment: surgery + craniospinal RT (23.4 Gy + boost) + chemotherapy.",ref:"claude — medulloblastoma molecular subgroups and prognosis",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 5-year-old child with neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is found on surveillance MRI to have a 2 cm optic chiasmatic glioma. She has mild left visual loss. Which tumour type is most likely and what is the preferred management if the lesion is slowly progressive?",opts:["A. Diffuse midline glioma (H3 K27-altered) — aggressive RT is required urgently","B. Pilocytic astrocytoma (WHO grade 1) — associated with NF1 in 30–70% of optic pathway gliomas; first-line treatment when needed is chemotherapy (carboplatin + vincristine); RT is avoided in young children with NF1","C. Glioblastoma — immediate radical resection then chemoradiotherapy","D. Ependymoma — transsphenoidal surgical resection","E. Medulloblastoma — craniospinal irradiation plus chemotherapy"],ans:1,exp:"Optic pathway gliomas (OPG): 70% are pilocytic astrocytomas (WHO grade 1). In NF1, 30–70% of OPGs are NF1-associated — these tend to be more indolent than sporadic OPGs. Management: (1) OBSERVATION if no or minimal visual symptoms, stable vision on serial testing — many NF1-associated OPGs plateau. (2) CHEMOTHERAPY when treatment is needed: carboplatin + vincristine (or vinorelbine-based regimens) is first-line — avoids RT toxicity. (3) RT is AVOIDED in children <5 (preferably <10) with NF1 due to: (a) neurocognitive sequelae; (b) accelerated cerebrovascular disease (moyamoya) — particularly dangerous in NF1 where intrinsic vasculopathy already exists. (4) Surgery: rarely curative for chiasmatic lesions; biopsy may be needed for diagnosis in atypical cases. Compare with non-NF1 OPG: may require earlier treatment; can be more aggressive.",ref:"claude — optic pathway glioma / pilocytic astrocytoma / NF1",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old woman with confirmed Von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease is 12 weeks pregnant. She asks about the risk to her unborn child and what specific complications she should be screened for in pregnancy. Which statement is correct?",opts:["A. VHL is X-linked recessive — only male children are at risk; daughters are carriers only","B. VHL is autosomal dominant — her child has a 50% risk of inheriting the mutation; she requires screening for phaeochromocytoma (blood/urine metanephrines) which can cause fatal hypertensive crises in pregnancy","C. VHL is autosomal recessive — the risk to the child is <25% if the partner is unaffected","D. Pregnancy is contraindicated in VHL — termination should be offered","E. No pregnancy screening is required — VHL only causes neurological problems after age 40"],ans:1,exp:"VHL disease: autosomal dominant mutation on chromosome 3p25.3. Each child of an affected parent has a 50% risk of inheriting the mutation, regardless of sex. Main VHL-associated tumours: cerebellar/spinal/retinal haemangioblastomas, clear cell RCC, phaeochromocytoma/paraganglioma, pancreatic cysts/NETs, endolymphatic sac tumours. In pregnancy, the most dangerous VHL manifestation is phaeochromocytoma: uncontrolled catecholamine release causes severe hypertension, hypertensive crises, maternal cardiac arrhythmia, and fetal death — may mimic pre-eclampsia. Screening: 24-hour urine metanephrines and catecholamines (or plasma metanephrines) must be performed before conception or in early pregnancy in all VHL patients. Haemangioblastomas may enlarge in pregnancy. Genetic counselling and offer of prenatal genetic testing or pre-implantation genetic diagnosis for future pregnancies.",ref:"claude — VHL disease in pregnancy / screening",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient undergoes complete excision of a convexity meningioma, achieving Simpson grade I removal. Final histology returns as WHO grade 3 (anaplastic) meningioma. What is the recommended adjuvant treatment?",opts:["A. Whole-brain radiotherapy (WBRT) 30 Gy in 10 fractions — only option for anaplastic meningioma","B. Focal external beam radiotherapy (IMRT/VMAT) to the resection cavity ± margin, followed by surveillance MRI — standard adjuvant for WHO grade 3 meningioma regardless of resection completeness","C. Stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS) alone — sufficient because resection was complete","D. Observation with 3-monthly MRI — grade 3 meningioma may behave well after complete excision","E. Systemic temozolomide — indicated for anaplastic meningioma"],ans:1,exp:"WHO grade 3 (anaplastic) meningioma carries 50–78% recurrence risk at 5 years even after complete excision. Standard adjuvant treatment is focal fractionated radiotherapy (IMRT/VMAT) to the tumour bed + margin (typically 60 Gy in 30 fractions), regardless of resection grade. WBRT is inappropriate — it delivers unnecessary dose without targeting the specific high-risk cavity. SRS alone is insufficient for anaplastic histology. Temozolomide has no established role. Observation is inappropriate given the aggressive biology of grade 3 meningioma.",ref:"claude — WHO grade 3 meningioma adjuvant RT",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During resection of a cerebellar pilocytic astrocytoma in a 10-year-old, a large cyst is found with a small intensely enhancing mural nodule. After complete excision of the nodule, the remaining cyst wall does not enhance on intraoperative assessment. What should the surgeon do with the non-enhancing cyst wall?",opts:["A. Remove the entire cyst wall circumferentially — the non-enhancing wall harbours tumour cells and is the main source of recurrence","B. Leave the non-enhancing cyst wall in situ — the reactive cyst wall does not contain tumour; recurrence risk is determined by completeness of mural nodule removal","C. Fenestrate the cyst wall only — partial removal reduces recurrence without added morbidity","D. Send frozen section of the cyst wall; excise only if tumour-positive","E. Excise the cyst wall only if it is >2 mm thick"],ans:1,exp:"In pilocytic astrocytoma (WHO grade 1), the cyst wall is typically a reactive non-neoplastic lining. The tumour is confined to the enhancing mural nodule. The non-enhancing wall does not need excision — attempting to strip it increases cerebellar morbidity without reducing recurrence. Completeness of mural nodule removal is the key determinant of outcome. Frozen section of the cyst wall is not standard practice; intraoperative enhancement guides resection extent.",ref:"claude — pilocytic astrocytoma surgical principles",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 50-year-old presents with progressive right-sided sensorineural hearing loss and tinnitus. MRI shows a right CPA mass. Which single MRI feature most specifically favours vestibular schwannoma over CPA meningioma?",opts:["A. Presence of calcification within the mass","B. Enhancement with a dural tail extending along the posterior petrous face","C. Widening (erosion/dilation) of the internal auditory canal","D. Heterogeneous signal with cystic areas","E. Absence of surrounding cerebral oedema"],ans:2,exp:"Dilation of the internal auditory canal (IAC) is the hallmark of vestibular schwannoma — the tumour arises within the IAC and expands it as it grows (producing the classic 'ice-cream cone' configuration). CPA meningiomas can extend into the IAC but characteristically do not widen it. Calcification and hyperostosis of the petrous bone favour meningioma. A dural tail is seen in meningioma (not schwannoma). Heterogeneity and cysts can occur in both; oedema is more common with meningioma but is not specific.",ref:"claude — CPA tumour MRI differentiation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old presents with progressive cerebellar ataxia. MRI shows a non-enhancing cerebellar mass with a characteristic striated 'tiger-stripe' T2 pattern. Biopsy confirms dysplastic cerebellar gangliocytoma (Lhermitte-Duclos disease). Which associated syndrome and inheritance pattern should be discussed?",opts:["A. Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) — autosomal dominant, NF1 gene on chromosome 17","B. Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome — autosomal dominant, VHL gene on chromosome 3","C. Cowden syndrome — autosomal dominant, PTEN tumour suppressor mutation; associated with macrocephaly, hamartomas, breast/thyroid/endometrial cancer","D. Li-Fraumeni syndrome — autosomal dominant, TP53 mutation","E. Turcot syndrome — APC or MMR gene mutation; colorectal polyps + CNS tumours"],ans:2,exp:"Lhermitte-Duclos disease (dysplastic cerebellar gangliocytoma) is pathognomonic for Cowden syndrome — an autosomal dominant condition caused by germline PTEN mutations (tumour suppressor, chromosome 10q23). Cowden features: macrocephaly (>95%), mucocutaneous lesions (trichilemmomas, oral papillomas), significantly elevated lifetime cancer risks: breast (85%), thyroid (35%), endometrial (28%). Patients with Lhermitte-Duclos must be referred for genetic counselling and PTEN testing with lifelong oncological surveillance.",ref:"claude — Cowden syndrome / Lhermitte-Duclos",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Imaging of a pineal region mass in a 45-year-old shows a 1.4 cm well-circumscribed lesion with 'exploded' peripheral calcification and homogeneous enhancement. No CSF dissemination. Which diagnosis and WHO grade are most consistent?",opts:["A. Pineoblastoma — WHO grade 4; requires craniospinal irradiation","B. Germinoma — radiosensitive; AFP normal, mild βHCG elevation possible","C. Pineocytoma — WHO grade 1; slow-growing, good prognosis after surgery","D. Pineal parenchymal tumour of intermediate differentiation (PPTID) — WHO grade 2–3; unpredictable behaviour","E. Mature teratoma — AFP elevated; benign, surgery curative"],ans:2,exp:"'Exploded' or peripheral displacement of calcification (calcification pushed outward from the normal central pineal body) on MRI/CT is the classical sign of pineocytoma (WHO grade 1). The lesion is small, well-circumscribed, homogeneously enhancing, and found in adults. Pineoblastoma (WHO grade 4) is a large heterogeneous aggressive tumour in children with CSF dissemination and poor prognosis. PPTID is intermediate in behaviour and grade. Germinoma has normal or 'engulfed' calcification and specific marker profile.",ref:"claude — pineocytoma vs pineoblastoma imaging",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 7-year-old with a posterior fossa medulloblastoma undergoes molecular subgrouping. The tumour is classified as WNT-activated. Which statement about this subgroup is correct?",opts:["A. WNT-activated medulloblastoma has the worst prognosis — it is rarely cured","B. WNT-activated tumours carry MYC amplification in 50% of cases","C. WNT-activated medulloblastoma has the best prognosis of all subgroups — 5-year OS >90%; metastases at presentation are extremely rare","D. WNT-activated subtype is predominantly in infants under 3 years, who require RT-sparing protocols","E. WNT-activated tumours are characterised by i(17q) chromosomal abnormality"],ans:2,exp:"WNT-activated medulloblastoma (CTNNB1 mutation, ~10% of cases) has the best prognosis of all four molecular subgroups — 5-year overall survival exceeds 90% with standard therapy; metastatic presentation is extremely rare. It predominantly affects older children/adolescents, not infants. This excellent prognosis has prompted clinical trials of therapy de-escalation to reduce long-term toxicity. MYC amplification is associated with Group 3 (worst prognosis). i(17q) is characteristic of Groups 3 and 4. SHH-activated (desmoplastic/nodular) has intermediate to good prognosis especially in infants.",ref:"claude — medulloblastoma molecular subgroups",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 6-year-old presents with raised ICP and truncal ataxia. MRI shows a posterior fossa mass centred in the 4th ventricle. Which feature most strongly favours ependymoma over medulloblastoma?",opts:["A. Marked homogeneous contrast enhancement","B. Extension of tumour through the foramen of Magendie and/or foramina of Luschka into the surrounding cisterns ('plastic' tumour)","C. Diffusion restriction throughout the tumour bulk","D. Homogeneous T2 signal with no cystic change","E. Origin from the inferior vermis and superior medullary velum"],ans:1,exp:"Extension through the foramina of Magendie (into the cisterna magna) and/or Luschka (into the CPA cistern) is the hallmark of 4th ventricle ependymoma — often termed the 'toothpaste' or 'plastic' phenomenon. Ependymoma arises from the floor/lateral recesses and is typically heterogeneous (calcification, cysts, haemorrhage). Medulloblastoma originates from the roof/superior medullary velum, is more homogeneous, shows greater diffusion restriction (high cellularity — key differentiator), and does not extrude through the foramina. Staging MRI spine is mandatory for medulloblastoma (CSF seeding).",ref:"claude — ependymoma vs medulloblastoma posterior fossa",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During elective left posterior temporal craniotomy for a convexity meningioma, a large bridging vein running posteriorly from the temporal lobe to the transverse sinus is torn. The bleeding is controlled with sacrifice of the vein. On the dominant side, what is the most feared consequence?",opts:["A. Contralateral hemiparesis — motor strip infarction from SSS venous occlusion","B. Bitemporal hemianopia — posterior temporal vein occlusion affecting the optic radiation","C. Wernicke's aphasia — posterior temporal lobe venous infarction following sacrifice of the vein of Labbé","D. Cerebellar haematoma — sigmoid sinus backpressure","E. CN III palsy — uncal herniation from temporal swelling"],ans:2,exp:"The vein of Labbé (inferior anastomotic vein) runs from the posterior sylvian fissure to the transverse sinus and is at direct risk during posterior temporal craniotomy. On the dominant hemisphere, its sacrifice causes venous infarction of the posterior temporal lobe (Wernicke's area), producing fluent aphasia with severely impaired comprehension (Wernicke's aphasia). The vein of Trolard (superior anastomotic vein) connects to the SSS; the superficial middle cerebral vein connects anteriorly to the cavernous/sphenoparietal sinus. Preservation of the vein of Labbé is a key priority in left posterior temporal surgery.",ref:"claude — vein of Labbé / posterior temporal craniotomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 19-year-old male presents with Parinaud syndrome and diabetes insipidus. MRI shows a pineal region mass with suprasellar extension. Serum AFP <2 ng/mL (normal), serum βHCG 45 IU/L (mildly elevated), PLAP elevated. CSF cytology negative. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Choriocarcinoma — βHCG typically >1000 IU/L; AFP normal; aggressive, poor prognosis","B. Yolk sac tumour — AFP markedly elevated (often >1000 ng/mL); requires aggressive chemotherapy","C. Germinoma — AFP normal, βHCG mildly elevated in ~30% (syncytiotrophoblast elements), PLAP elevated; exquisitely radiosensitive, >90% 5-year survival","D. Mature teratoma — AFP elevated; benign behaviour; surgery alone curative","E. Pineoblastoma — no serum tumour markers; aggressive posterior fossa tumour in children"],ans:2,exp:"Germinoma is the most common intracranial germ cell tumour, presenting in young males with Parinaud syndrome (pineal) ± diabetes insipidus (suprasellar component). Marker profile: AFP is normal; βHCG is mildly elevated in ~30% due to syncytiotrophoblast giant cells (typically <100 IU/L); PLAP is elevated and characteristic. AFP >25 ng/mL or βHCG >1000 IU/L indicates non-germinomatous GCT (yolk sac/choriocarcinoma component). Germinomas are exquisitely radiosensitive — whole-ventricular RT ± chemotherapy achieves >90% 5-year survival. Biopsy confirms histology before treatment.",ref:"claude — intracranial germ cell tumour markers",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 38-year-old HIV-positive patient with CD4 count 32 cells/μL presents with 3-week history of confusion and left hemiparesis. MRI shows a solitary periventricular lesion with homogeneous enhancement and surrounding oedema. Toxoplasma IgG is negative. What is the most likely diagnosis and appropriate next step?",opts:["A. Toxoplasmic encephalitis — start empirical pyrimethamine/sulfadiazine regardless of serology","B. Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) — non-enhancing white matter; biopsy required","C. Primary CNS lymphoma (PCNSL) — EBV-associated diffuse large B-cell lymphoma; proceed to stereotactic biopsy, then HAART plus methotrexate-based chemotherapy","D. Neurosyphilis — LP for VDRL/FTA-ABS is diagnostic; treat with IV penicillin","E. GBM — occurs at normal CD4 counts; biopsy for Stupp protocol"],ans:2,exp:"Primary CNS lymphoma in HIV is almost universally EBV-driven diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, occurring at very low CD4 counts (<50 cells/μL — late AIDS). MRI: periventricular, often solitary or few lesions, homogeneously or ring-enhancing, may involve the corpus callosum/splenium. Negative toxoplasma IgG makes toxoplasmosis less likely (sensitivity ~97%). EBV-PCR in CSF is near-diagnostic. Management: HAART (immune reconstitution is central) + high-dose methotrexate ± rituximab. Prognosis is substantially worse than immunocompetent PCNSL. Lymphoma is an AIDS-defining illness.",ref:"claude — CNS lymphoma in HIV / AIDS",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During a retrosigmoid craniotomy for vestibular schwannoma, the patient suffers an intraoperative event. Post-operatively: ipsilateral facial numbness (CN V), ipsilateral Horner syndrome, hoarseness, dysphagia, and contralateral loss of pain and temperature to the body. Which vessel injury is responsible?",opts:["A. AICA (anterior inferior cerebellar artery) — causes ipsilateral facial numbness + hearing loss + Horner at pontine level; contralateral body sensory loss is unusual","B. PICA (posterior inferior cerebellar artery) — infarction of the lateral medulla causes Wallenberg syndrome: ipsilateral CN V, IX, X, Horner, spinocerebellar + contralateral spinothalamic loss","C. Basilar artery — occlusion causes locked-in syndrome; not specific to retrosigmoid approach","D. Superior cerebellar artery (SCA) — causes ipsilateral cerebellar ataxia and CN IV palsy; no major sensory or autonomic findings","E. Vertebral artery (V4) — injury causes medullary infarction but is not anatomically encountered in retrosigmoid craniotomy"],ans:1,exp:"The syndrome described is lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome: ipsilateral CN V (spinal nucleus in lateral medulla), Horner syndrome (descending sympathetic fibres), CN IX/X (nucleus ambiguus — hoarseness/dysphagia), ipsilateral spinocerebellar tract (limb ataxia), and contralateral spinothalamic loss (body pain/temperature). PICA supplies the lateral medulla and is at risk during retrosigmoid posterior fossa surgery. AICA infarction (supplies lateral pons + inner ear) causes a similar but higher syndrome: ipsilateral facial nerve palsy, hearing loss, Horner, and ipsilateral facial numbness — but contralateral body sensory loss and dysphagia are not typical of AICA.",ref:"claude — lateral medullary syndrome / PICA anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Histology of a cerebellar lesion in a 9-year-old shows biphasic appearance: compact areas with Rosenthal fibres alternating with loose areas containing eosinophilic granular bodies. Which molecular finding most reliably distinguishes this from a diffuse (infiltrative) low-grade glioma?",opts:["A. IDH1 R132H mutation — present in >80% of diffuse LGGs in young adults; absent in pilocytic astrocytoma (IDH-wildtype)","B. ATRX loss — seen in IDH-mutated diffuse gliomas alongside IDH mutation; absent in pilocytic astrocytoma","C. BRAF V600E point mutation — can occur in both pilocytic (non-cerebellar) and diffuse gliomas","D. EGFR amplification — associated with GBM, not LGG or pilocytic astrocytoma","E. 1p/19q co-deletion — confirms oligodendroglioma lineage; cannot occur in pilocytic astrocytoma"],ans:0,exp:"IDH mutation is the key molecular discriminator. Diffuse LGGs (WHO grade 2–3) carry IDH1 (typically R132H) or IDH2 mutations in >80% of young adults. Pilocytic astrocytoma (WHO grade 1) is IDH-wildtype and instead typically harbours a KIAA1549::BRAF fusion (>70%, especially cerebellar location), creating constitutive BRAF-MEK-ERK pathway activation. BRAF V600E (a point mutation distinct from the fusion) occurs in some extracerebellar pilocytic tumours. Under WHO 2021 CNS classification, IDH status is the primary molecular classifier separating diffuse (infiltrative) gliomas from other astrocytic tumours.",ref:"claude — pilocytic astrocytoma molecular biology / IDH classification",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"neuro-onco-spinal":{src:"NICE NG234 (2023) — verified from PDF",c:[
{q:"What cancer history and cord compression symptoms mandate immediate contact with the MSCC coordinator?",a:"Any past or current diagnosis of cancer presenting with: bladder or bowel dysfunction; gait disturbance; limb weakness; neurological signs of cord/cauda equina compression; numbness/paraesthesia; radicular pain. Treat as oncological emergency.",ref:"NG234 1.3.2",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What pain characteristics in a cancer patient trigger contact with MSCC coordinator within 24 hours?",a:"Severe unremitting back pain; progressive back pain; mechanical pain (worse with movement); pain aggravated by straining (cough/sneeze); night-time back pain; localised tenderness; claudication.",ref:"NG234 1.3.3",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What is the required availability of the MSCC coordinator?",a:"24 hours a day, 7 days a week. The role must be covered at all times and is based in an oncology service.",ref:"NG234 1.1.7",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"Within what timeframe must urgent MRI be available for suspected MSCC with neurological signs?",a:"Within 24 hours, including outside normal working hours if needed to start immediate treatment.",ref:"NG234 1.1.19",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"When should immobilisation begin in suspected MSCC?",a:"Without delay — including for transfer to hospital — for people with suspected or confirmed MSCC where decreased movement is likely to worsen injury.",ref:"NG234 1.4.1",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What does NG234 say about radiotherapy access for MSCC?",a:"Radiotherapy and simulator facilities must be available for urgent (within 24 hours) daytime sessions, 7 days a week, so that RT can be given within 24 hours of a decision to treat.",ref:"NG234 1.1.21",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"When should a cancer patient without previous evidence of spinal metastases but with typical spinal mets pain be referred?",a:"Refer for urgent oncology assessment if cancer is suspected. Seek advice through MSCC coordinator within 24 hours.",ref:"NG234 1.3.3 & 1.3.5",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What scoring system assesses spinal instability in metastatic disease to guide surgical decisions?",a:"SINS — Spinal Instability Neoplastic Score. Scores ≥7 suggest instability; ≥13 suggest frank instability. Higher scores favour surgical evaluation.",ref:"claude — referenced in NG234",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"Which multidisciplinary specialties should be represented in an MSCC service?",a:"Acute oncology; haematology; histopathology; oncology; palliative care; physiotherapy; radiology; spinal surgery.",ref:"NG234 1.1.9",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What information must the MSCC coordinator record for each patient?",a:"Clinical presentation; neurological assessment; performance status; frailty assessment; investigations including imaging; oncology assessment and disease staging; individual needs and preferences.",ref:"NG234 1.1.15",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{q:"What was the Patchell 2005 trial and what did it show?",a:"RCT of direct decompressive surgery + RT vs RT alone for MESCC (Lancet 2005). 101 patients, 7 centres. Stopped early by DSMB due to proven superiority of surgery (p=0.001). Surgery + RT was superior to RT alone for the primary endpoint: ability to walk.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What was the primary endpoint and key result of Patchell 2005?",a:"Primary endpoint: ability to walk (at least 2 steps per foot unassisted). Surgery group: 84% (42/50) walked after treatment vs RT alone: 57% (29/51). OR 6.2 (95% CI 2.0-19.8, p=0.001). Surgery group walked for median 122 days vs 13 days for RT (p=0.003).",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1, p.4",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"In Patchell 2005, what happened to patients who were NOT walking at study entry?",a:"32 patients entered unable to walk (16 per group). Surgery group: 62% (10/16) regained walking. RT group: 19% (3/16) regained walking (p=0.012). Non-ambulatory surgical patients walked for median 59 days vs 0 days for RT (p=0.04).",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.4",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"In Patchell 2005, what happened to patients who WERE walking at study entry?",a:"69 patients entered ambulatory (34 surgery, 35 RT). Surgery maintained walking in 94% (32/34) vs RT 74% (26/35) (p=0.024). Median walking time: surgery 153 days vs RT 54 days (p=0.024).",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.4",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What were the secondary endpoints of Patchell 2005?",a:"All favoured surgery: continence maintained 156 vs 17 days (p=0.016); ASIA score maintained 566 vs 72 days (p=0.001); Frankel score maintained 566 vs 72 days (p=0.0006); survival 126 vs 100 days (p=0.033); reduced steroid use (1.6 vs 4.2mg dex, p=0.009); reduced opioid use (0.4 vs 4.8mg morphine eq, p=0.002).",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.4-5, Table 2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What steroid protocol was used in Patchell 2005?",a:"All patients: dexamethasone 100mg IV bolus at diagnosis, then 24mg every 6 hours until start of radiotherapy or surgery. Then tapered during treatment. Both groups received the same steroid regimen pre-randomisation.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What radiotherapy protocol was used in Patchell 2005?",a:"Both groups: 30 Gy in 10 fractions (3 Gy per fraction). RT-alone group: started within 24h of randomisation. Surgery group: RT started within 14 days of surgery. Port encompassed one vertebral body above and below the lesion.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What were the inclusion criteria for Patchell 2005?",a:"Tissue-proven cancer (not CNS/spinal column origin); MRI evidence of true cord displacement by epidural mass; at least one neurological sign/symptom (including pain); not totally paraplegic >48h; single area of compression; fit for surgery; expected survival ≥3 months.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1-2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What were the exclusion criteria for Patchell 2005?",a:"Radiosensitive tumours (lymphoma, leukaemia, myeloma, germ-cell); multiple discrete compressive lesions; brain metastases; prior MESCC or spinal radiation precluding study dose; total paraplegia >48h; cauda equina/root-only compression.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1-2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"Why was previous laminectomy for MESCC no better than RT, but Patchell's surgery was?",a:"Earlier studies used simple laminectomy, which removes posterior elements but does not decompress anteriorly-located tumour (most spinal mets are in the vertebral body, anterior to the cord). Laminectomy can also destabilise the spine. Patchell used direct decompressive surgery — circumferential decompression, usually anterior approach, with stabilisation as needed.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"Why does surgery work better than RT alone for MESCC, according to Patchell?",a:"Two mechanisms of cord damage: (1) direct compression → oedema, venous congestion, demyelination (reversible if short duration); (2) prolonged compression → secondary vascular injury → infarction (irreversible). Surgery provides immediate decompression before irreversible vascular injury. RT takes days to shrink tumour.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.5",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What was the 30-day morbidity and mortality in Patchell 2005?",a:"30-day mortality: surgery 6% vs RT 14% (not significant, p=0.32). 30-day morbidity (ASIA/Frankel deterioration): worse in RT group — surgery maintained/improved ASIA scores in 86% vs 60% (p=0.006), Frankel in 91% vs 61% (p=0.0008). Hospital stay: 10 days both groups. No excess surgical morbidity.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.5",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What happened to the crossover patients in Patchell 2005?",a:"10 RT patients (20%) deteriorated during radiotherapy and crossed over to surgery. At time of crossover surgery, none could walk. Only 30% (3/10) regained walking — compared with 62% of patients who received surgery first-line. Supports surgery as FIRST-LINE treatment, not salvage after failed RT.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.5",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{q:"What are the limitations of applying Patchell 2005 to all MESCC patients?",a:"Results apply only to patients meeting inclusion criteria: single area of compression, not radiosensitive tumour, not >48h total paraplegia, fit for surgery, expected survival ≥3 months. Does NOT justify surgery in: lymphoma/myeloma (radiosensitive), multiple levels, very poor prognosis, or medically unfit patients.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.5-6",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 58-year-old with breast cancer has urinary retention and leg weakness for 3 days. Immediate action per NG234?",opts:["A. MRI spine as outpatient within 48 hours","B. Contact MSCC coordinator immediately — oncological emergency","C. Start dexamethasone and routine oncology review","D. Plain X-ray spine first","E. Physiotherapy referral"],ans:1,exp:"NG234 (1.3.2): Cord compression signs in a cancer patient = contact MSCC coordinator immediately = oncological emergency. Urinary retention = bladder dysfunction = cord compression symptom.",ref:"NICE NG234, 1.3.2",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{stem:"Cancer patient with back pain only, no neurological signs. When should MSCC coordinator be contacted?",opts:["A. Immediately","B. Within 4 hours","C. Within 24 hours","D. Within 1 week","E. Only if MRI confirms metastases"],ans:2,exp:"NG234 (1.3.3): Pain characteristics suggesting spinal metastases but NO cord compression signs → seek advice through MSCC coordinator within 24 hours.",ref:"NICE NG234, 1.3.3",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{stem:"Within what timeframe must urgent MRI be available for suspected MSCC with neurological signs?",opts:["A. 4 hours, Mon–Fri only","B. 12 hours, 7 days a week","C. 24 hours including out of hours","D. 48 hours","E. During working hours only"],ans:2,exp:"NG234 (1.1.19): Urgent MRI must be available within 24 hours including outside normal working hours for suspected MSCC with neurological signs.",ref:"NICE NG234, 1.1.19",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{stem:"Which scoring system guides surgical decision-making in spinal metastatic disease?",opts:["A. ASIA impairment scale","B. SINS (Spinal Instability Neoplastic Score)","C. Karnofsky Performance Status","D. Tokuhashi score","E. Frankel classification"],ans:1,exp:"SINS assesses spinal stability in metastatic disease. Referenced in NG234 for assessing spinal stability and prognosis. SINS ≥7 suggests instability.",ref:"NICE NG234 — spinal stability tools",src_id:"nice-ng234"},
{stem:"A 55-year-old with lung cancer has MESCC at T8 with leg weakness for 2 days. MRI confirms single-level cord compression. Expected survival 6 months. What does Patchell 2005 support as first-line treatment?",opts:["A. Radiotherapy alone (30 Gy in 10 fractions)","B. Direct decompressive surgery followed by radiotherapy","C. Laminectomy followed by radiotherapy","D. Chemotherapy with dexamethasone","E. Dexamethasone and observation"],ans:1,exp:"Patchell 2005: direct decompressive surgery + postoperative RT is superior to RT alone for MESCC. 84% vs 57% walked (p=0.001). Applies to patients with single-level compression, non-radiosensitive tumour, not paraplegic >48h, fit for surgery, expected survival ≥3 months.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"In Patchell 2005, what percentage of non-ambulatory MESCC patients regained walking with surgery vs radiotherapy alone?",opts:["A. Surgery 84% vs RT 57%","B. Surgery 62% vs RT 19%","C. Surgery 94% vs RT 74%","D. Surgery 30% vs RT 19%","E. Surgery 50% vs RT 25%"],ans:1,exp:"Of 32 patients unable to walk at entry (16 per group): surgery 62% (10/16) regained walking vs RT 19% (3/16), p=0.012. The 84% vs 57% figure is for ALL patients; 94% vs 74% is for those already walking at entry.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.4",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"A patient with MESCC from multiple myeloma presents with cord compression. Based on Patchell 2005, should surgery be first-line?",opts:["A. Yes — surgery + RT for all MESCC","B. No — myeloma was excluded as a radiosensitive tumour","C. Yes — but only if paraplegic >48 hours","D. No — only laminectomy is appropriate for myeloma","E. Yes — regardless of tumour type"],ans:1,exp:"Patchell 2005 excluded radiosensitive tumours (lymphoma, leukaemia, multiple myeloma, germ-cell tumours). These respond well to RT alone. Patchell results cannot be applied to myeloma patients.",ref:"Patchell 2005, Lancet, p.1-2",src_id:"k-patchell-2005",korky:true},
{stem:"Which of the following correctly describes spinal tumours by anatomical compartment?",opts:["A. Extradural tumours are usually benign (e.g. meningiomas, schwannomas)","B. Intradural extramedullary tumours typically require surgery plus postoperative radiotherapy","C. Meningiomas are the most common intramedullary spinal tumour","D. Extradural tumours are usually malignant; intradural extramedullary tumours are usually benign and surgically curable; haemangioblastoma is a benign curable intramedullary tumour","E. Haemangioblastoma is a high-grade malignant intramedullary tumour with poor prognosis"],ans:3,exp:"Extradural tumours are predominantly malignant — most commonly vertebral metastases (lung, breast, prostate, kidney, thyroid). Intradural extramedullary tumours (meningiomas, schwannomas, neurofibromas) are typically benign and surgically curable without adjuvant RT. Meningiomas are extramedullary, not intramedullary. Haemangioblastoma is histologically benign, arises within the cord, and is curable if completely excised; associated with Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome. Most common intramedullary tumours: ependymoma (adults), astrocytoma (children).",ref:"Bank, p.4",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"Which parameter is NOT included in the Tokuhashi revised scoring system for predicting survival in patients with vertebral metastases?",opts:["A. Karnofsky performance status (KPS)","B. Number of extra-spinal bone metastases","C. Patient age","D. Primary tumour site and expected prognosis","E. Severity of spinal cord palsy (Frankel grade)"],ans:2,exp:"The Tokuhashi revised scoring system (2005) predicts prognosis in vertebral metastases using 6 parameters, each scored 0–2 (max 15): (1) KPS; (2) number of extra-spinal bone metastases; (3) number of vertebral metastases; (4) metastases to major internal organs (lungs, liver, kidneys, brain); (5) primary tumour site/prognosis; (6) severity of spinal cord palsy (Frankel/Tokuhashi neurological grade). Age is NOT one of the six Tokuhashi parameters. Score ≥9 predicts survival >6 months (consider surgery); score <9 suggests palliative RT may be more appropriate. Contrast with Tomita score (7 factors including age in some versions).",ref:"claude — Tokuhashi scoring system",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old undergoes complete resection of a cervicothoracic intramedullary spinal ependymoma. Three years later, surveillance MRI shows a new enhancing lesion at the craniocervical junction with an additional small lesion in the internal auditory canal. What is the most likely unifying diagnosis?",opts:["A. Drop metastasis from the spinal ependymoma — spinal ependymomas commonly metastasise intracranially","B. New primary GBM — unrelated to the spinal ependymoma","C. Neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2) — NF2 gene on chromosome 22 causes bilateral vestibular schwannomas and multiple spinal/intracranial ependymomas","D. Von Hippel-Lindau disease — causes multiple haemangioblastomas throughout the CNS","E. Li-Fraumeni syndrome — TP53 mutation predisposes to multiple CNS tumours"],ans:2,exp:"Multiple CNS ependymomas (spinal ependymoma + intracranial ependymoma/schwannoma in the IAC) in a young adult strongly suggests Neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2). NF2 is caused by germline mutations in the NF2 gene (chromosome 22q12) encoding merlin/schwannomin. Classic triad: bilateral vestibular schwannomas (pathognomonic), multiple meningiomas, multiple ependymomas (spinal > cerebral). A new IAC lesion post-spinal ependymoma resection = vestibular schwannoma until proven otherwise = NF2. The craniocervical lesion is likely another ependymoma or meningioma. Spinal ependymomas do NOT commonly metastasise intracranially — this presentation indicates a hereditary syndrome.",ref:"claude — NF2 / chromosome 22 / spinal ependymoma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old presents with progressive low back pain and bladder dysfunction. MRI shows a large T1-hyperintense (bright) intradural mass at the conus/cauda equina region. Which statement is most accurate?",opts:["A. T1 hyperintensity indicates haemorrhage — this is a cauda equina haematoma requiring urgent surgical evacuation","B. A T1-bright intradural mass at the conus/filum is most likely a spinal lipoma; lipomas are associated with spinal dysraphism, tethered cord syndrome, and can cause progressive conus/cauda equina dysfunction requiring surgical untethering","C. T1 hyperintensity indicates gadolinium enhancement — this is a highly vascular tumour (haemangioblastoma)","D. Epidermoid cysts are T1-bright; this requires STIR sequences to confirm","E. T1 hyperintensity at the conus is pathognomonic of multiple sclerosis (Dawson fingers)"],ans:1,exp:"T1-hyperintensity (bright on T1, without gadolinium) at the conus/filum terminale in a fat-saturated sequence is characteristic of lipomatous tissue — a spinal lipoma. Spinal lipomas are the most common form of occult spinal dysraphism in adults with late presentation. They cause tethered cord syndrome: progressive leg weakness, sensory changes, bladder/bowel dysfunction from mechanical tethering of the conus medullaris. Treatment: surgical untethering (section of the filum terminale or debulking of the lipoma). Note: fat appears bright on T1 but suppresses on T1 fat-sat/STIR. Haemorrhage can also be T1-bright but would have a different clinical context (acute onset, associated haematoma).",ref:"claude — spinal lipoma / tethered cord / T1 signal",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 50-year-old presents with thoracic myelopathy. MRI shows an anterior intradural extramedullary mass at T4 compressing the cord, isointense to cord on T1, slightly hyperintense on T2, with homogeneous enhancement. No history of cancer. What is the most likely diagnosis and primary management?",opts:["A. Vertebral haemangioma — observe if asymptomatic; embolise if enlarging","B. Spinal meningioma — surgical resection is curative; anterior thoracic meningiomas have higher surgical complexity due to cord displacement","C. Extradural metastasis — staging CT and oncological review before surgery","D. Spinal cord astrocytoma — surgical debulking plus radiotherapy","E. Neurofibroma — associated with NF1; excision typically via posterior laminectomy"],ans:1,exp:"Intradural extramedullary anterior thoracic mass with homogeneous enhancement in a middle-aged patient = spinal meningioma until proven otherwise. Spinal meningiomas are predominantly: intradural extramedullary, thoracic spine (70–80%), anterior or anterolateral to the cord, more common in middle-aged women, and almost always WHO grade 1. Imaging: isointense to cord on T1/T2, homogeneous enhancement, may have dural tail. Treatment: surgical resection — curative if complete (Simpson grade I/II). Anterior thoracic meningiomas present surgical challenges (cord sitting on the tumour, limited working angle through posterior approach — may need posterolateral or lateral approach). Neurofibromas are usually posterolateral (dorsal root origin).",ref:"claude — spinal meningioma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 40-year-old with no known malignancy has a solitary osteolytic L4 vertebral lesion discovered on staging imaging. There is back pain but no neurological deficit. CT thorax/abdomen/pelvis is negative. What is the correct management?",opts:["A. Proceed directly to L4 corpectomy and reconstruction — the lesion is likely metastatic","B. CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy of the L4 lesion to establish histological diagnosis before committing to any treatment — solitary lesion with no known primary requires tissue diagnosis","C. Empirical radiotherapy — most vertebral lesions are radiosensitive","D. Bone scan is sufficient to establish the diagnosis before treatment","E. Vertebroplasty for pain control — biopsy can be performed later if the lesion grows"],ans:1,exp:"A solitary vertebral lesion in a patient with no known malignancy MUST be biopsied before treatment. The differential is broad: metastasis (from an occult primary), primary bone tumour (chordoma, giant cell tumour, lymphoma, plasmacytoma, osteosarcoma), infection (TB spondylitis, brucellosis), or benign lesion (ABC, haemangioma). CT-guided percutaneous core needle biopsy is the standard — diagnostic yield 70–90% for vertebral lesions. Proceeding to corpectomy without tissue diagnosis risks operating on infection/lymphoma (where surgery is wrong treatment) or misidentifying a primary bone tumour requiring different margins. In a patient with known metastatic cancer and multiple vertebral lesions, biopsy may be deferred if the clinical picture is unambiguous.",ref:"claude — vertebral biopsy / solitary lesion workup",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"vascular-ich":{src:"National Stroke Guideline 2023 — guidelines/rcp_stroke_guideline_2023.pdf",c:[
{q:"What is the SBP target in acute intracerebral haemorrhage management?",a:"Rapid lowering to <140 mmHg within 1 hour for presenting SBP 150–220 mmHg, based on INTERACT2 and ATACH-2 evidence. Avoid dropping below 130 mmHg.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{q:"When is surgical evacuation indicated for cerebellar ICH?",a:"Urgent evacuation for cerebellar haematoma >3cm causing brainstem compression or obstructive hydrocephalus. Conscious patients may also be candidates.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{q:"What is the role of haematoma evacuation for supratentorial ICH?",a:"Deep basal ganglia/thalamic haemorrhage — surgery generally not beneficial. Superficial lobar ICH with deterioration may benefit. Evidence base weaker than for cerebellar ICH.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023 / STICH trial",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{q:"What is the STICH trial conclusion regarding surgery for spontaneous supratentorial ICH?",a:"STICH I & II: early surgery did not improve outcomes overall for spontaneous supratentorial ICH compared to initial conservative treatment. No significant benefit for deep haemorrhages. Superficial haemorrhage subgroup may benefit.",ref:"STICH I (2005), STICH II (2013)"},
{q:"What thrombectomy eligibility was expanded in the 2023 stroke guideline?",a:"Thrombectomy (mechanical clot retrieval) is now offered up to 24 hours from symptom onset for selected patients with large vessel occlusion and salvageable tissue on perfusion imaging. Previously 6 hours.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{q:"What is the role of decompressive craniectomy in malignant MCA infarction?",a:"Decompressive hemicraniectomy within 48 hours improves survival and functional outcome in malignant MCA infarction (DECIMAL, DESTINY, HAMLET trials). Should be discussed with patients <60 years especially, but can be offered up to 65 in selected patients.",ref:"DECIMAL/DESTINY/HAMLET trials"},
{q:"What was the DESTINY II trial (Jüttler 2014) — design and population?",a:"DEcompressive Surgery for the Treatment of malignant INfarction of the middle cerebral arterY II. Prospective RCT, 13 German sites, August 2009–March 2012. 112 patients aged ≥61 years (median 70, range 61–82). Malignant MCA infarction: ischaemic infarction ≥2/3 MCA territory including basal ganglia; NIHSS >14 (non-dominant) or >19 (dominant) with reduced consciousness; pre-existing mRS ≤1, Barthel ≥95. Excluded: absent pupillary reflexes, GCS <6. Published NEJM 2014;370:1091–1100.",ref:"DESTINY II, p.1–2",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What was the primary outcome of DESTINY II and what were the 6-month results?",a:"Primary outcome: survival without severe disability (mRS 0–4) at 6 months. Result: 38% hemicraniectomy (20/49) vs 18% control (10/63); OR 2.91 (95% CI 1.06–7.49), p=0.04. This difference was driven entirely by lower mortality: 33% vs 70% death. NO patient in either group achieved mRS 0–2 (functional independence). mRS distribution at 6 months: mRS 3 = 7% vs 3%; mRS 4 = 32% vs 15%; mRS 5 = 28% vs 13%; death = 33% vs 70%.",ref:"DESTINY II, p.3–4",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What were the 12-month outcomes and disability data in DESTINY II?",a:"12-month survival: 57% hemicraniectomy vs 24% control. Among SURVIVING patients only: all secondary outcomes (mRS, NIHSS, Barthel, SF-36, EQ-5D, HDRS) showed NO significant difference between groups — survivors are equally disabled regardless of treatment. 63% hemi vs 53% control survivors gave retrospective consent to treatment. Early deaths in control were predominantly from herniation (72%); hemi group had more infections (longer ICU stay).",ref:"DESTINY II, p.4–6",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
{q:"How do DESTINY II outcomes in patients ≥61 compare to hemicraniectomy trials in younger patients?",a:"Prior pooled analysis (DECIMAL, DESTINY, HAMLET; patients ≤60 years): hemicraniectomy increased 1-year survival from 29% to 78%; 43% of operated patients had good outcome (mRS ≤3). DESTINY II (≥61 years): survival benefit smaller (+33% vs +49% in younger); only 6% achieved mRS 3 at 12 months (vs 43% mRS ≤3 in younger); 32% mRS 4, 19% mRS 5. Surgery reduces death in the elderly but survivors have predominantly moderate-to-severe disability.",ref:"DESTINY II, p.7–8",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key clinical implications of DESTINY II for consent in elderly malignant MCA stroke?",a:"Hemicraniectomy significantly reduces mortality in patients ≥61 (57% vs 24% at 12 months). However: no patient achieved functional independence (mRS 0–2); the alternative to surgery is typically death (70% mortality conservative at 12 months). Quality of life among survivors was comparable to severe TBI/SAH/ICH — impaired but not uniquely dismal. Framing for consent: surgery offers survival at the cost of significant disability (most requiring assistance with most bodily needs). Decision must be individualised and may incorporate advance directives. A majority of survivors gave retrospective consent.",ref:"DESTINY II, p.8–9",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 67-year-old has a 4cm cerebellar haemorrhage with fourth ventricle compression and GCS 12. Priority management?",opts:["A. Conservative management with BP control","B. Urgent surgical evacuation","C. EVD insertion alone","D. Decompressive craniectomy","E. IV mannitol and repeat CT"],ans:1,exp:"Cerebellar haematoma >3cm with brainstem compression/hydrocephalus → urgent surgical evacuation. An EVD alone does not address the mass lesion.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023 — ICH surgery",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{stem:"Acute ICH, initial SBP 190 mmHg. What is the recommended SBP target within 1 hour?",opts:["A. <180 mmHg","B. <160 mmHg","C. <140 mmHg","D. <120 mmHg","E. No specific target"],ans:2,exp:"2023 Stroke Guideline: rapid SBP lowering to <140 mmHg within 1 hour for presenting SBP 150–220 mmHg. Avoid <130 mmHg.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{stem:"What did the STICH trials demonstrate about early surgery for supratentorial spontaneous ICH?",opts:["A. Surgery significantly improves outcomes for all supratentorial ICH","B. Surgery improves outcomes only for deep thalamic haemorrhage","C. Early surgery does not improve outcomes overall compared to initial conservative treatment","D. Surgery should always be performed within 4 hours","E. Stereotactic aspiration is superior to open surgery"],ans:2,exp:"STICH I & II: early surgery vs initial conservative management for spontaneous supratentorial ICH showed no significant overall benefit. Superficial lobar haemorrhage subgroup may benefit. Evidence does not support routine early surgery for deep ICH.",ref:"STICH I (Mendelow 2005), STICH II (Mendelow 2013)"},
{stem:"The DESTINY II trial (Jüttler 2014) compared hemicraniectomy vs conservative ICU treatment in 112 patients aged ≥61 with malignant MCA infarction. Which statement best describes the findings?",opts:["A. Hemicraniectomy produced no significant difference in survival without severe disability","B. Hemicraniectomy significantly improved survival without severe disability (38% vs 18%), but no patient achieved functional independence","C. Hemicraniectomy produced survival benefit equivalent to that seen in patients aged ≤60","D. Conservative treatment was superior in patients with dominant hemisphere infarction","E. Hemicraniectomy reduced mortality but significantly increased very severe disability among survivors"],ans:1,exp:"DESTINY II: primary outcome (mRS 0–4) met — 38% vs 18%, OR 2.91, p=0.04. No patient in either group achieved mRS 0–2 (functional independence). Benefit was entirely driven by reduced mortality (33% vs 70%). Disability was equivalent among survivors of both groups. In younger patients (prior trials), 43% achieved mRS ≤3 — substantially better functional outcomes.",ref:"DESTINY II, p.3–4",src_id:"k-destiny2-2014",korky:true},
{stem:"A 70-year-old hypertensive man presents with sudden-onset left hemiparesis and facial droop. CT head confirms a spontaneous intracerebral haemorrhage. Which statement about hypertensive intracerebral haemorrhage is CORRECT?",opts:["A. The most common site is the cortex, typical of cerebral amyloid angiopathy","B. Hypertensive haemorrhage most commonly occurs in the basal ganglia","C. Cerebellar hypertensive haemorrhage should always be managed conservatively","D. The most common site is the subarachnoid space","E. Pontine haemorrhage accounts for the majority of hypertensive ICH cases"],ans:1,exp:"Hypertensive intracerebral haemorrhage most commonly affects the basal ganglia (~50%), due to rupture of small penetrating vessels (particularly the lenticulostriate perforators to the putamen). Other sites: thalamus, pons, cerebellum, subcortical white matter. Cerebellar hypertensive haemorrhage (~10%) can cause rapid posterior fossa decompensation — surgical evacuation is life-saving when clot ≥3 cm or clinical deterioration occurs. Cortical lobar haemorrhage is the hallmark of cerebral amyloid angiopathy, not hypertension.",ref:"Bank, p.3",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 72-year-old on warfarin (INR 3.5) for a mechanical mitral valve presents with a 3 cm right frontal haemorrhage and GCS 15. What is the most appropriate immediate management of the anticoagulation?",opts:["A. Continue warfarin — stopping risks mechanical valve thrombosis and systemic embolism","B. Stop warfarin; give 4-factor prothrombin complex concentrate (PCC) and vitamin K 10 mg IV for immediate reversal; restart anticoagulation at 48–72 hours with haematology guidance and close valve monitoring","C. Vitamin K alone — PCC is not indicated in an awake patient","D. Fresh frozen plasma — equivalent to PCC and avoids thrombosis risk","E. Warfarin reversal is contraindicated with a mechanical mitral valve"],ans:1,exp:"ICH on warfarin with mechanical valve: (1) STOP warfarin immediately. (2) 4-FACTOR PCC (Octaplex/Beriplex) + vitamin K 10 mg IV provides immediate INR reversal (within 30 minutes) — superior to FFP (slow, volume-dependent, risk of TRALI). Target INR <1.4. (3) Valve thrombosis risk exists but is outweighed by the haematoma expansion risk (up to 50% if INR remains supratherapeutic). (4) Restart anticoagulation: typically 48–72 hours post-ICH minimum — multidisciplinary decision (cardiology/haematology/neurosurgery). Bridging with heparin may be required for high-risk mechanical valves. Surgery (evacuation): not immediately indicated at GCS 15 for a 3 cm frontal haemorrhage — reconsider if GCS falls or haematoma expands.",ref:"claude — anticoagulant-related ICH / mechanical valve",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old woman presents with 10 days of progressive headache, focal left arm jerks, and confusion. MRI shows right parietal cortical signal change with haemorrhagic transformation and adjacent oedema. CT venography confirms cortical vein thrombosis in the right parietal region. What is the correct treatment?",opts:["A. Urgent surgical thrombectomy — remove the thrombus endoscopically","B. Therapeutic anticoagulation with LMWH or heparin — correct treatment for CVST even in the presence of haemorrhagic infarction","C. IV alteplase — standard stroke thrombolysis protocol applies","D. Aspirin and corticosteroids — anticoagulation contraindicated with haemorrhage","E. Decompressive craniectomy as first-line — haemorrhage indicates surgical emergency"],ans:1,exp:"Cerebral venous sinus/cortical vein thrombosis: anticoagulation is the treatment of choice — including when haemorrhagic infarction is present. This is counterintuitive but well-established: the haemorrhage is caused by VENOUS obstruction and increased venous pressure, not arterial rupture; anticoagulation reduces thrombus propagation and lowers venous hypertension, which is the true mechanism of haemorrhage. EFNS and ESO guidelines: LMWH or UFH then warfarin (or DOAC). Decompressive craniectomy is reserved for malignant oedema with herniation. Investigate for procoagulant causes: OCP, dehydration, pregnancy, thrombophilia, malignancy, infection.",ref:"claude — cerebral venous thrombosis / CVST management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"An 80-year-old woman presents with 3 weeks of right temporal headache, jaw claudication, and scalp tenderness. Visual acuity is normal bilaterally. Which test is most important and what immediate action should be taken if clinical suspicion is high?",opts:["A. Temporal artery biopsy — perform urgently and withhold steroids until result is available","B. CT head and MR angiography — exclude an intracranial cause before testing","C. ESR measurement; if elevated or clinical suspicion is high, start prednisolone immediately without waiting for biopsy — vision loss from GCA is irreversible and can occur before biopsy results","D. MRI temporal lobes — to exclude temporal lobe mass","E. Anti-CCP and rheumatoid factor — screening for connective tissue disease"],ans:2,exp:"Giant cell arteritis (temporal arteritis): affects vessels ≥50 years. Classic triad: temporal headache, jaw claudication (pathognomonic — ischaemia of masseters), and temporal artery tenderness/cord-like texture. ESR typically >50 (often >80) mm/hour; CRP also elevated. CRITICAL MANAGEMENT: if clinical suspicion is HIGH and visual symptoms present (amaurosis fugax, diplopia, blurred vision), start high-dose prednisolone IMMEDIATELY (60 mg/day) WITHOUT WAITING for biopsy. Irreversible anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy can occur within hours. Biopsy remains positive for up to 4 weeks after steroid commencement. Biopsy confirms diagnosis but must not delay treatment.",ref:"claude — giant cell arteritis / temporal arteritis",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 68-year-old hypertensive smoker presents acutely with vomiting, vertigo, and inability to swallow. Examination shows: ipsilateral facial numbness (CN V), ipsilateral Horner syndrome, hoarse voice (CN X), and contralateral loss of pain and temperature in the limbs. There is no hemiplegia. Which artery is most commonly responsible, and what is the syndrome?",opts:["A. Left AICA — lateral pontine infarction; ipsilateral facial nerve palsy is the key difference from Wallenberg","B. Left PICA/posterior vertebral artery — lateral medullary infarction (Wallenberg syndrome); characterised by ipsilateral CN V, Horner, CN IX/X and contralateral spinothalamic loss WITHOUT hemiplegia","C. Left basilar artery perforator — medial pontine infarction; ipsilateral CN VI palsy and contralateral hemiplegia","D. Left vertebral artery at V3 — C1–2 root infarction","E. Left anterior spinal artery — medial medullary syndrome; tongue deviation and contralateral hemiplegia"],ans:1,exp:"Wallenberg syndrome (lateral medullary infarction): PICA (posterior inferior cerebellar artery) or vertebral artery branches supply the lateral medulla. IPSILATERAL: facial numbness (descending trigeminal nucleus/tract), Horner syndrome (descending sympathetics), hoarseness/dysphagia (nucleus ambiguus — CN IX/X), cerebellar ataxia (inferior cerebellar peduncle). CONTRALATERAL: loss of pain and temperature to the body (spinothalamic tract). ABSENT: hemiplegia (corticospinal tract runs medially, not affected). Recall: 'all ipsilateral except pain/temperature loss' — which is contralateral. Distinguish from AICA (higher lesion: ipsilateral facial nerve palsy, hearing loss, no dysphagia).",ref:"claude — Wallenberg syndrome / PICA territory",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"carotid":{src:"National Stroke Guideline 2023 + NASCET/ECST trial data",c:[
{q:"What is the NASCET degree of stenosis that mandates carotid endarterectomy after TIA or minor stroke?",a:"≥70% stenosis (NASCET criteria) — CEA is strongly recommended. Moderate benefit for 50–69%. No benefit for <50%. Must be performed within 2 weeks of index event for maximum benefit.",ref:"NASCET / Stroke Guideline 2023"},
{q:"What is the NASCET method of measuring carotid stenosis?",a:"Ratio of the narrowest diameter at the stenosis to the diameter of the normal ICA distal to the stenosis. NASCET % = (1 − [min stenosis diameter / distal normal ICA diameter]) × 100.",ref:"NASCET methodology"},
{q:"Why must CEA be done within 2 weeks of a TIA or minor stroke?",a:"The risk of recurrent stroke is highest immediately after the index event. Delay significantly reduces the absolute benefit of CEA. CARESS and EXPRESS studies showed early intervention reduces stroke risk dramatically.",ref:"Stroke Guideline 2023 / EXPRESS trial",src_id:"stroke-guideline"},
{q:"What is the role of carotid artery stenting (CAS) vs CEA?",a:"CEA is first-line. CAS is an alternative for patients who are medically high-risk for surgery, or where CEA is technically difficult. Higher peri-procedural stroke risk with CAS, especially in older patients.",ref:"ICSS trial / Stroke Guideline 2023"},
{q:"What are the anaesthetic options for CEA?",a:"General or local (regional) anaesthesia — no strong evidence favours either. GALA trial: no significant difference in outcomes. Surgeon and patient preference guide choice.",ref:"GALA trial"},
],q:[
{stem:"A 72-year-old has a TIA 5 days ago. Duplex shows 75% NASCET stenosis on the symptomatic side. Recommended treatment?",opts:["A. CEA within 2 weeks","B. CEA after 3 months of antiplatelets","C. CAS as first-line","D. Medical management only","E. CEA only if second TIA occurs"],ans:0,exp:"Symptomatic carotid stenosis ≥70% (NASCET) → CEA within 2 weeks of the index event. Delay significantly reduces benefit.",ref:"NASCET / Stroke Guideline 2023"},
{stem:"What is the NASCET method of measuring carotid stenosis?",opts:["A. Stenosis diameter / CCA diameter","B. (1 − [stenosis diameter / distal normal ICA diameter]) × 100","C. Plaque length / total vessel length","D. Peak systolic velocity ratio","E. Stenosis diameter / proximal ICA diameter"],ans:1,exp:"NASCET measures stenosis as the ratio of the narrowest point to the distal normal ICA. This differs from ECST which uses the estimated original lumen.",ref:"NASCET methodology"},
]},

"epilepsy-surgery":{src:"NICE NG217 (2022) + standard surgical epilepsy knowledge",c:[
{q:"When should referral for epilepsy surgery assessment be considered?",a:"After failure of 2 appropriate antiepileptic drugs (AEDs) at adequate doses and duration. This constitutes drug-resistant epilepsy. Early referral is recommended — do not wait for failure of multiple further drugs.",ref:"NICE NG217",src_id:"nice-ng217"},
{q:"What is the most common surgically remediable epilepsy syndrome?",a:"Mesial temporal lobe epilepsy with hippocampal sclerosis. MRI shows unilateral hippocampal atrophy and T2/FLAIR signal change. Temporal lobectomy or selective amygdalohippocampectomy gives ~70% seizure-free rates.",ref:"claude — epilepsy surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What pre-surgical evaluation is required before epilepsy surgery?",a:"Video-EEG telemetry to characterise seizures; structural MRI (3T preferred); neuropsychological assessment; functional imaging (FDG-PET, ictal SPECT) if MRI-negative; fMRI or Wada test for language/memory lateralisation.",ref:"claude — pre-surgical evaluation",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the role of VNS (vagus nerve stimulation) in epilepsy?",a:"Adjunctive treatment for drug-resistant epilepsy where resective surgery is not possible or has failed. Reduces seizure frequency by ~50% in ~50% of patients. Rarely achieves seizure freedom.",ref:"NICE NG217",src_id:"nice-ng217"},
{q:"What is corpus callosotomy used for?",a:"Palliative procedure for drop attacks (atonic/tonic seizures) causing injury. Anterior corpus callosotomy interrupts inter-hemispheric spread. Does not cure epilepsy but significantly reduces drop attacks.",ref:"claude — epilepsy surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What does NG217 say about SUDEP (sudden unexpected death in epilepsy)?",a:"Discuss SUDEP risk with patients and carers. Key risk factors include nocturnal seizures, generalised tonic-clonic seizures, and poor seizure control. Optimise seizure control and provide safety advice (bed alarm, supervision during bathing).",ref:"NICE NG217",src_id:"nice-ng217"},
{q:"What are the surgical options for temporal lobe epilepsy?",a:"Standard anterior temporal lobectomy (ATL); selective amygdalohippocampectomy (SAHE — spares more lateral temporal cortex); laser interstitial thermal therapy (LITT) at specialist centres. ATL and SAHE have similar seizure-free rates (~60–70% at 1 year).",ref:"claude — epilepsy surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the ILAE definition of drug-resistant epilepsy?",a:"Failure to achieve sustained seizure freedom after adequate trials of 2 tolerated and appropriately chosen AED schedules (whether as monotherapy or combination).",ref:"ILAE 2010 definition"},
{q:"What was the Hu 2013 meta-analysis on SelAH vs ATL — design and evidence base?",a:"Systematic review and meta-analysis. PubMed/Embase/Cochrane, 1990–2012. 13 studies included (3 prospective, 10 retrospective; no RCTs): 745 SelAH + 766 ATL patients. Quality assessed by Newcastle-Ottawa Scale (≥6 stars = high quality). Published J Neurosurg 119:1089–1097, 2013. Condition: mesial temporal lobe epilepsy (MTLE), mainly hippocampal sclerosis.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.1–2",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What was the headline seizure outcome result of Hu 2013 (SelAH vs ATL)?",a:"11 studies, 686 SelAH + 711 ATL patients. Overall seizure freedom 68% (956/1397). ATL statistically superior: 71% (504/711) vs 66% (452/686) seizure-free. OR 0.65 [95% CI 0.51–0.82], p=0.0005, favouring ATL. No significant heterogeneity (I² = 43%). Sensitivity analysis (high-quality studies ≥6 stars only): OR 0.57 [0.43–0.76], p=0.0001 — result maintained.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.3",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What were the IQ (neuropsychological) outcomes in Hu 2013 (SelAH vs ATL)?",a:"4 studies met IQ inclusion criteria (Wechsler WAIS-R). Right-side resection: VIQ, PIQ, FIQ all tended to improve more after ATL but differences were NOT significant (VIQ p=0.53; PIQ p=0.16; FIQ p=0.19). Left-side resection: similar — no significant difference (VIQ p=0.09; PIQ p=0.14; FIQ p=0.17). Conclusion: SelAH confers no neuropsychological advantage over ATL with respect to IQ scores.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.3–4",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
{q:"Why might SelAH produce worse seizure outcomes than ATL? (Hu 2013 — mechanisms)",a:"(1) Dual pathology: in a series of 73 HS patients, 70 had additional temporal FCD or scar lesions — not resected by SelAH. FCD Type 1b most common. (2) Temporal pole involvement: Chabardès found temporal pole was involved at seizure onset in 48% of MTLE patients — spared by SelAH but removed by ATL. SelAH only removes mesial structures; the difference between the operations is the anterolateral temporal neocortex.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.5",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key limitations of Hu 2013 and what future research is needed?",a:"(1) Low study quality overall — only 3 non-randomised prospective studies, 10 retrospective; no RCT. (2) Older studies may not have distinguished MTLE from neocortical TLE, potentially biasing toward ATL. (3) Memory outcomes could not be pooled (heterogeneous tests across studies). (4) Absolute seizure-free rate difference is small (66% vs 71%) — clinical significance uncertain. Future: well-designed RCTs comparing SelAH and ATL, including seizure, memory, language, and visual field outcomes.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.6",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 28-year-old with left temporal lobe epilepsy has failed levetiracetam and lamotrigine. MRI shows left hippocampal sclerosis. Next step?",opts:["A. Try a third AED first","B. Refer to specialist epilepsy surgical centre for pre-surgical evaluation","C. Offer VNS as first surgical option","D. Corpus callosotomy","E. Try clobazam add-on for 12 months"],ans:1,exp:"NICE NG217: Drug-resistant epilepsy (failure of 2 AEDs) → refer for epilepsy surgery assessment without trialling further drugs. Hippocampal sclerosis + drug resistance = good surgical candidate.",ref:"NICE NG217 — epilepsy surgery referral",src_id:"nice-ng217"},
{stem:"A patient with severe drop attacks fails multiple AEDs and is not a candidate for resective surgery. Most appropriate surgical option?",opts:["A. Temporal lobectomy","B. Hemispherotomy","C. Anterior corpus callosotomy","D. VNS","E. Selective amygdalohippocampectomy"],ans:2,exp:"Anterior corpus callosotomy is the procedure of choice for drug-resistant drop attacks (atonic/tonic seizures). It interrupts inter-hemispheric spread and significantly reduces drop attacks.",ref:"claude — epilepsy surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A meta-analysis (Hu 2013) pooled 13 studies comparing selective amygdalohippocampectomy (SelAH) and anterior temporal lobectomy (ATL) for mesial temporal lobe epilepsy. Which statement best reflects the main finding?",opts:["A. SelAH and ATL produced equivalent seizure freedom rates","B. SelAH produced significantly better IQ outcomes than ATL","C. ATL produced significantly higher seizure freedom rates, with no IQ difference between the two approaches","D. SelAH produced significantly better seizure freedom with fewer neuropsychological complications","E. ATL was superior for both seizure freedom and IQ outcomes"],ans:2,exp:"Hu 2013: ATL superior for seizure freedom — 71% vs 66%, OR 0.65 [0.51–0.82], p=0.0005. However, IQ outcomes (VIQ, PIQ, FIQ) did not differ significantly by approach for either right or left resection. SelAH offers no neuropsychological advantage. The absolute seizure-free rate difference is modest (5%), and clinical significance requires further RCT evidence.",ref:"Hu 2013, p.3–4",src_id:"k-hu-2013",korky:true},
{stem:"Which patient is MOST appropriate for consideration of epilepsy surgery?",opts:["A. A 25-year-old with generalised tonic-clonic seizures well controlled on levetiracetam monotherapy","B. A 16-year-old with juvenile myoclonic epilepsy and seizures controlled on sodium valproate","C. A 35-year-old with complex partial seizures arising within the right primary motor cortex, poorly controlled on two AEDs","D. A 40-year-old with complex partial seizures poorly controlled despite two AEDs, with concordant EEG, MRI, and semiology pointing to a right anterior temporal focus","E. A 30-year-old with multifocal seizures from bilateral frontal and parietal foci on EEG"],ans:3,exp:"Epilepsy surgery requires: (1) pharmacoresistance — failure of at least two appropriately trialled AEDs; (2) a single identifiable epileptogenic focus with concordant localisation from seizure semiology, EEG, and imaging. Option D meets both criteria with a well-localised temporal focus. Option A: well-controlled — surgery not indicated. Option B: JME is generalised, responds to valproate, surgery rarely appropriate. Option C: motor cortex focus — resection risks permanent hemiparesis. Option E: multifocal origins — resective surgery would not achieve seizure freedom.",ref:"Bank, p.8",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A patient with epilepsy following TBI is taking phenytoin. At clinic review, which combination of side effects is MOST characteristic of chronic phenytoin toxicity?",opts:["A. Weight gain, tremor, and raised liver enzymes","B. Gingival hyperplasia, hirsutism, and peripheral neuropathy with prolonged use; coarse facial features; nystagmus and ataxia at toxic levels","C. Pancreatitis, thrombocytopenia, and hyperammonaemia","D. Alopecia, teratogenicity, and raised valproate levels","E. Nephrolithiasis, visual field defects, and cognitive slowing"],ans:1,exp:"Phenytoin chronic toxicity profile: gingival hyperplasia (occurs in ~50% of patients, dose-related), hirsutism, coarsening of facial features, acne, folate deficiency (megaloblastic anaemia), peripheral neuropathy (long-term), osteoporosis (enzyme induction of vitamin D metabolism), Stevens-Johnson syndrome (idiosyncratic, HLA-B*1502 in some Asian populations). Dose-related neurological toxicity: nystagmus (earliest sign), ataxia, diplopia, sedation. Phenytoin is an enzyme-inducer (CYP450) — reduces efficacy of many co-medications. Options C and E describe valproate and topiramate side effects respectively.",ref:"claude — phenytoin side effects",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with a brain tumour requires an antiepileptic drug. The oncologist is concerned about interactions with chemotherapy. Which antiepileptic is the LEAST likely to cause enzyme induction and reduce chemotherapy efficacy?",opts:["A. Phenytoin — potent CYP3A4 inducer; reduces levels of many chemotherapy agents","B. Carbamazepine — potent CYP3A4 inducer; also an autoinducer","C. Phenobarbitone — hepatic enzyme inducer; reduces plasma levels of multiple drugs","D. Levetiracetam — NOT an enzyme inducer; does not affect cytochrome P450 system; preferred in neuro-oncology","E. Primidone — metabolised to phenobarbitone; an enzyme inducer"],ans:3,exp:"Enzyme-INDUCING AEDs (induce CYP3A4, CYP2C9, etc.): phenytoin, carbamazepine, phenobarbitone, primidone, oxcarbazepine, eslicarbazepine. NON-ENZYME-INDUCING (safe in neuro-oncology): levetiracetam, valproate (actually a CYP inhibitor, not inducer), lamotrigine, topiramate (mild). In neuro-oncology patients on chemotherapy (Stupp protocol TMZ, etc.), enzyme-inducing AEDs significantly reduce plasma chemotherapy levels. Levetiracetam and valproate are preferred. Note: valproate inhibits CYP2C9 and glucuronidation — can RAISE levels of some drugs.",ref:"claude — enzyme-inducing vs non-inducing AEDs",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient in status epilepticus is treated with IV lorazepam 4 mg. What is the mechanism of action of lorazepam in terminating seizures?",opts:["A. Sodium channel blockade — prevents sustained repetitive firing of action potentials","B. Positive allosteric modulation of GABA-A receptors — benzodiazepines bind to the α-subunit interface, increasing the frequency of chloride channel opening, causing hyperpolarisation","C. Glutamate NMDA receptor antagonism — reduces excitatory transmission","D. Inhibition of carbonic anhydrase — reduces neuronal excitability by altering pH","E. Direct opening of GABA-A chloride channels without GABA binding"],ans:1,exp:"Benzodiazepines (diazepam, lorazepam, midazolam, clonazepam) act as POSITIVE ALLOSTERIC MODULATORS of GABA-A receptors: they bind to the benzodiazepine site (between the α and γ subunits) and increase the FREQUENCY of chloride channel opening (in the presence of GABA) → hyperpolarisation → reduced neuronal firing. They do NOT open channels independently (that is barbiturates: barbiturates increase the DURATION of chloride channel opening; benzodiazepines increase the FREQUENCY). Status epilepticus protocol: lorazepam IV first-line; if no IV, midazolam IM/buccal/intranasal; second-line: phenytoin/levetiracetam; third-line: propofol/thiopental coma.",ref:"claude — benzodiazepine mechanism / status epilepticus",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 34-year-old undergoes left anterior temporal lobectomy and selective amygdalohippocampectomy for mesial temporal sclerosis. Which is the most likely neurological complication to warn the patient about specifically at this procedure?",opts:["A. Complete hemianopia — resection of the occipital lobe","B. CN VI palsy causing horizontal diplopia — proximity of the abducens nerve","C. Partial inferior quadrantanopia (pie-in-the-sky defect) — damage to Meyer's loop of the optic radiation in the temporal lobe, occurring in approximately 15% of temporal lobectomies","D. Wernicke's aphasia — if the dominant hemisphere resection extends too far posteriorly","E. Cerebellar ataxia — retraction injury to the posterior fossa"],ans:2,exp:"Meyer's loop carries fibres from the inferior retina (representing the superior visual field) through the anterior temporal lobe before looping posteriorly to the calcarine cortex. During left temporal lobectomy + hippocampectomy, Meyer's loop is vulnerable — damage produces a superior homonymous quadrantanopia (loss of upper visual field contralateral to the resection side) — the 'pie in the sky' defect. This occurs in approximately 15% of temporal lobectomies and may be permanent. Wernicke's aphasia is a risk in dominant hemisphere surgery if the posterior superior temporal gyrus is damaged, but the specific risk at this level (anterior temporal) is the visual field. CN VI palsy is not a recognised temporal lobectomy complication.",ref:"claude — temporal lobectomy complications",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"An MRI in a 38-year-old with refractory temporal lobe epilepsy shows hippocampal atrophy with loss of normal hippocampal internal architecture and signal hyperintensity on T2/FLAIR in the right hippocampus. Which is the most likely diagnosis and its significance?",opts:["A. Hippocampal gliosis from encephalitis — not an epileptogenic substrate for surgery","B. Temporal lobe ganglioglioma — associated with hippocampal sclerosis in dual pathology","C. Mesial temporal sclerosis (hippocampal sclerosis) — the most common structural cause of temporal lobe epilepsy; the MRI finding of hippocampal atrophy + T2 signal change is the key substrate for anterior temporal lobectomy with excellent seizure-free rates (60–70% Engel class I)","D. Cavernous malformation of the hippocampus — T2* blooming characteristic","E. Diffuse hemispheric cortical dysplasia — MRI usually normal; found on histology alone"],ans:2,exp:"Mesial temporal sclerosis (MTS/hippocampal sclerosis): pathology = neuronal loss in CA1, CA3, CA4 of the hippocampus + reactive gliosis. MRI: hippocampal atrophy (smaller than contralateral), loss of normal digitations on coronal imaging, T2/FLAIR hyperintensity. This is the most surgically amenable epilepsy syndrome: concordant clinical semiology (aura of déjà vu/rising epigastric sensation, automatisms, post-ictal confusion) + EEG (mesial temporal spikes) + MRI = anterior temporal lobectomy ± selective amygdalohippocampectomy achieves 60–80% seizure freedom. Dual pathology (concurrent cortical dysplasia) reduces surgical outcomes.",ref:"claude — mesial temporal sclerosis / hippocampal sclerosis",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Approximately what proportion of patients respond to the initial AED, and what additional proportion benefit from substitution of a second AED as monotherapy?",opts:["A. 70% initial; 20% with second AED","B. 47% initial; approximately 13% with second AED monotherapy substitution","C. 60% initial; 25% with second AED","D. 35% initial; 35% with second AED","E. 80% initial; 10% with second AED"],ans:1,exp:"Kwan & Brodie (2000, NEJM) data, cited in Stafstrom (2010): approximately 47% of patients achieve seizure freedom with the initial AED. If that fails, substitution of a second AED as monotherapy benefits approximately a further 13%. The probability of benefit from additional monotherapy trials then drops off markedly. The remaining patients are likely to require polytherapy — approximately 1/3 of all patients with epilepsy are pharmacoresistant.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.1",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Lacosamide is described as unique among sodium channel-blocking AEDs. Which statement correctly distinguishes its mechanism from phenytoin and carbamazepine?",opts:["A. Lacosamide blocks sodium channels in their resting (closed) state; phenytoin binds the active (open) state","B. Lacosamide selectively enhances slow inactivation of voltage-gated sodium channels only, with no effect on fast inactivation, GABA receptors, potassium or calcium channels; phenytoin and carbamazepine bind the active state and reduce high-frequency firing by enhancing fast inactivation","C. Lacosamide and carbamazepine share identical mechanisms — both target slow and fast inactivation equally","D. Lacosamide blocks T-type calcium channels in addition to sodium channels — this distinguishes it from phenytoin","E. Lacosamide is not a sodium channel blocker — it opens potassium channels to reduce neuronal excitability"],ans:1,exp:"Phenytoin and carbamazepine: bind the ACTIVE state of the sodium channel → enhance FAST inactivation (millisecond timescale) → reduce high-frequency repetitive firing. Lacosamide: uniquely selectively enhances only SLOW inactivation of sodium channels — a process occurring over seconds to minutes that could ameliorate prolonged neuronal firing as in a seizure. It has no effect on fast inactivation, GABA receptors, potassium or calcium channels. Preliminary evidence also links lacosamide to modulation of CRMP-2 (collapsin-response mediator protein-2), involved in neuronal growth and plasticity. This distinctive mechanism makes lacosamide a potential adjunct to AEDs that enhance fast inactivation.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Which antiepileptic drug binds to the synaptic vesicle protein SV2A, and what is the proposed consequence of this binding?",opts:["A. Gabapentin — binds SV2A to reduce GABA reuptake","B. Levetiracetam — binds SV2A, decreasing calcium influx into the presynaptic terminal and thereby reducing excitatory neurotransmitter release; also impedes kindling, suggesting anti-epileptogenic as well as anticonvulsant properties","C. Vigabatrin — binds SV2A to inhibit GABA transaminase","D. Lacosamide — binds SV2A as well as enhancing slow sodium channel inactivation","E. Stiripentol — binds SV2A to modulate GABA-A receptor subtypes"],ans:1,exp:"Levetiracetam: primary binding target is the synaptic vesicle protein SV2A (Lynch et al. 2004). Binding to SV2A decreases calcium influx into the presynaptic terminal — the exact mechanism by which this suppresses seizures is unclear but appears related to decreased release of excitatory neurotransmitter (glutamate). Additional effects: levetiracetam blocks HVA calcium channels, alters GABA function, and impedes kindling (suggesting a possible anti-epileptogenic role). This novel, multi-target mechanism (different from all other AED classes) is why levetiracetam does not fit neatly into any single mechanism category.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the primary molecular target of gabapentin and pregabalin, and how does binding to this target suppress seizures?",opts:["A. GABA-A receptor — they are positive allosteric modulators that increase chloride channel opening frequency","B. α2δ subunit of voltage-activated calcium channels — binding reduces calcium channel trafficking to the plasma membrane and reduces release of excitatory neurotransmitters, particularly glutamate","C. Sodium channel — they bind the active state and reduce repetitive firing","D. SV2A synaptic vesicle protein — they reduce calcium influx at the presynaptic terminal","E. GABA transaminase — they increase GABA availability by reducing GABA breakdown"],ans:1,exp:"Gabapentin and pregabalin (gabapentinoids): the primary molecular target is the α2δ subunit of voltage-activated calcium channels. Binding to this site reduces calcium channel trafficking to the plasma membrane (gabapentin inhibits trafficking of a specific calcium channel subunit — an effect abolished if that subunit is mutated to prevent gabapentin binding). The consequence is reduced calcium-dependent neurotransmitter release, particularly glutamate at excitatory synapses. Despite their name, they do NOT directly bind GABA receptors or affect GABA-A function — the 'GABA' in gabapentin is a misnomer.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Ethosuximide is the prototypical AED for which seizure type, and what is its principal mechanism of action?",opts:["A. Focal (partial) onset seizures — blocks HVA calcium channels in cortical neurons","B. Generalised tonic-clonic seizures — enhances GABA-A receptor chloride channel opening","C. Absence seizures — blocks T-type calcium channels in thalamic neurons, disrupting the thalamo-cortical 3 Hz spike-and-wave discharge","D. Myoclonic seizures — binds the α2δ subunit of calcium channels","E. Atonic seizures — opens Kv7 potassium channels, reducing neuronal excitability"],ans:2,exp:"Ethosuximide is the prototypical drug for absence epilepsy. Mechanism: blocks T-type (low-voltage activated) calcium channels in thalamic neurons. T-type calcium channels underlie the low-threshold burst firing in the thalamus that drives the 3 Hz spike-and-wave thalamo-cortical oscillations seen in absence seizures. Ethosuximide may also decrease the persistent sodium current. It is ineffective against generalised tonic-clonic or focal seizures — for these, valproate is preferred (which has multiple mechanisms). Valproate + ethosuximide is a clinically recognised synergistic combination for absence seizures.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"How do the GABA-enhancing mechanisms of vigabatrin and tiagabine differ from each other, and how do they differ from barbiturates?",opts:["A. All three increase the frequency of GABA-A chloride channel opening — the mechanism is identical","B. Vigabatrin inhibits GABA transaminase (the enzyme that breaks down GABA); tiagabine blocks the presynaptic and astrocytic GABA transporter; barbiturates increase the open-time (duration) of the GABA-A chloride channel — all three increase GABA but at distinct molecular sites","C. Vigabatrin and tiagabine both block the GABA transporter; barbiturates inhibit GABA transaminase","D. Barbiturates increase the opening frequency of the GABA-A channel (same as benzodiazepines); vigabatrin opens the channel directly","E. Tiagabine binds GABA-A directly as a positive allosteric modulator; vigabatrin and barbiturates both inhibit GABA transaminase"],ans:1,exp:"Three distinct mechanisms for enhancing GABAergic inhibition: (1) Vigabatrin: irreversibly inhibits GABA transaminase (GABA-T) — the enzyme responsible for breaking down GABA. Blocking GABA-T raises synaptic GABA levels. (2) Tiagabine: blocks the presynaptic neuronal and astrocytic GABA transporter (GAT-1) — prevents reuptake of GABA from the synapse. (3) Barbiturates (phenobarbital): bind the GABA-A receptor and increase the DURATION (open time) of the chloride channel. By contrast, benzodiazepines increase the FREQUENCY of chloride channel opening. These distinctions are clinically and pharmacologically important.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A neonatal seizure fails to respond to standard phenobarbital at therapeutic levels. The neurologist explains that neonatal neurons have a reversed chloride gradient and proposes adding bumetanide. What is the mechanism of this unusual feature and how does bumetanide address it?",opts:["A. Neonatal neurons have reduced GABA-A receptor expression; bumetanide upregulates GABA-A subunits to restore inhibitory function","B. In neonatal neurons the Na⁺-K⁺-Cl⁻ transporter NKCC1 maintains high intracellular Cl⁻, so GABA-A opening causes Cl⁻ to exit the cell (depolarisation/excitation); bumetanide inhibits NKCC1, restoring the adult Cl⁻ gradient so GABA-A activation becomes inhibitory — enabling phenobarbital to exert its expected GABA-enhancing effect","C. Bumetanide is a sodium channel blocker used specifically in neonates; it acts independently of the chloride gradient","D. NKCC1 is overexpressed in adult neurons only; in neonates the intracellular Cl⁻ is already low — bumetanide enhances this effect","E. Bumetanide reverses a calcium gradient abnormality in neonatal neurons, reducing excitatory calcium influx"],ans:1,exp:"In mature neurons: intracellular Cl⁻ < extracellular Cl⁻ — so when GABA-A channels open, Cl⁻ enters and the cell hyperpolarises (inhibitory). In neonatal neurons: the NKCC1 (Na⁺-K⁺-Cl⁻ cotransporter 1) actively pumps Cl⁻ INTO the cell, maintaining HIGH intracellular Cl⁻. When GABA-A channels open, Cl⁻ exits down its gradient → depolarisation (EXCITATORY). This is why phenobarbital (which enhances GABA-A opening) may paradoxically worsen or fail to control neonatal seizures. Bumetanide (a loop diuretic, similar to furosemide) inhibits NKCC1 → lowers intracellular Cl⁻ → GABA-A activation becomes inhibitory — the same as in mature neurons. The rational polytherapy combination is bumetanide (restore Cl⁻ gradient) + phenobarbital (enhance GABA-A inhibition).",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Stiripentol is used for Dravet syndrome. Which combination of facts correctly describes Stiripentol's mechanism and Dravet syndrome's genetic basis?",opts:["A. Dravet syndrome is caused by SCN2A mutations (encoding Nav1.2); stiripentol works by inhibiting GABA transaminase","B. Dravet syndrome is caused by mutations in SCN1A (encoding the voltage-gated sodium channel Nav1.1 — mainly expressed in inhibitory interneurons); stiripentol increases GABA release, inhibits GABA uptake, and directly modulates GABA-A receptor subtypes","C. Dravet syndrome arises from KCNQ2 mutations; stiripentol opens M-type potassium channels to compensate","D. Stiripentol is a sodium channel blocker structurally similar to carbamazepine; it is effective in Dravet syndrome because it also activates GABA-A receptors","E. Dravet syndrome is caused by GRIN2A mutations; stiripentol acts by blocking NMDA glutamate receptors"],ans:1,exp:"Dravet syndrome (severe myoclonic epilepsy of infancy): caused by de novo loss-of-function mutations in SCN1A, encoding Nav1.1 — a voltage-gated sodium channel predominantly expressed in inhibitory GABAergic interneurons. Loss of Nav1.1 → failure of interneuron firing → disinhibition of excitatory circuits → severe seizures. Stiripentol mechanism (Stafstrom 2010): increases GABA release, inhibits GABA uptake (like tiagabine), and directly modulates GABA-A receptor subtypes (positive allosteric modulator, especially at subunits containing α3). The mechanism is complementary to SCN1A dysfunction — enhancing inhibitory GABA transmission compensates for failed inhibitory interneuron firing. Conventional sodium channel blockers (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) can WORSEN Dravet syndrome.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Clinical data from a study of 1,617 seizure-free patients identified the most efficacious AED polytherapy combinations. Which statement correctly identifies the synergistic combination most strongly supported by both clinical data and isobolographic preclinical studies?",opts:["A. Carbamazepine + phenytoin — two sodium channel blockers shown to be synergistic in MES model","B. Valproate + lamotrigine — shown synergistic in clinical data and marked as particularly promising in isobolographic animal studies, with antagonistic (favourable) adverse effect interaction","C. Phenobarbital + benzodiazepine — most commonly prescribed and most evidence-based polytherapy","D. Levetiracetam + topiramate — the only combination with RCT evidence of synergy","E. Oxcarbazepine + carbamazepine — two drugs with similar sodium channel mechanism shown most effective"],ans:1,exp:"Stephen & Brodie (2002): in 1,617 seizure-free patients (>1 year), most efficacious combinations were: lamotrigine + valproate, phenytoin + phenobarbital, carbamazepine + gabapentin, and carbamazepine + valproate. Valproate + lamotrigine (VPA+LTG) is also marked as particularly promising in isobolographic preclinical studies — synergistic effectiveness AND antagonistic (i.e. mutually reducing) adverse effects (or no neurotoxicity on behavioural testing). This double benefit (synergistic seizure control + reduced side effects) makes VPA+LTG a rational and clinically useful combination. Note: VPA + LTG requires careful dosing — VPA inhibits lamotrigine glucuronidation, raising lamotrigine levels ~2-fold.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.4–5",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Isobolographic studies suggest that combining lamotrigine with oxcarbazepine or carbamazepine may produce antagonistic (inferior) seizure control. What mechanistic reason best explains this?",opts:["A. Lamotrigine inhibits the metabolism of oxcarbazepine, raising toxic plasma levels","B. Both lamotrigine and oxcarbazepine/carbamazepine principally enhance fast inactivation of voltage-gated sodium channels — combining two drugs with the same cellular mechanism provides no additional benefit and may produce pharmacodynamic antagonism at a shared target, while additive side effects (dizziness, diplopia) are likely","C. Lamotrigine blocks GABA-A receptors, opposing the GABAergic enhancement of carbamazepine","D. Carbamazepine is an enzyme inducer that reduces lamotrigine plasma levels — the clinical antagonism is purely pharmacokinetic","E. Oxcarbazepine opens potassium channels, which is opposed by lamotrigine's calcium channel blockade"],ans:1,exp:"Lamotrigine, oxcarbazepine, and carbamazepine all primarily enhance FAST inactivation of voltage-gated sodium channels — they share essentially the same cellular mechanism. Rational polytherapy aims to combine drugs with DIFFERENT mechanisms (complementary attack on seizure generation). Combining two drugs with the same mechanism offers limited additional benefit and risks pharmacodynamic antagonism at the shared target (both compete for the same inactivated-channel binding site). Additionally, adverse effects (dizziness, diplopia — common to all sodium channel blockers) become additive. The isobolographic data confirm that LTG + OXC yields poorer seizure control than predicted by additivity. Note: there IS also a pharmacokinetic component — carbamazepine induces LTG metabolism (UGT1A4), reducing LTG levels — but the question asks for the mechanistic reason.",ref:"Aberdeen AEDs, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-aeds",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"pituitary":{src:"Society for Endocrinology Pituitary Apoplexy Guideline 2024 — guidelines/endocrinology_pituitary_apoplexy_2024.pdf",c:[
{q:"What is pituitary apoplexy and what are the classic symptoms?",a:"Sudden haemorrhage or infarction of a pituitary adenoma. Classic triad: sudden severe headache + visual disturbance (bitemporal hemianopia or ophthalmoplegia) + hormonal dysfunction (acute hypopituitarism). May also cause altered consciousness and meningism.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What is the most immediately life-threatening complication of pituitary apoplexy?",a:"Acute secondary adrenal insufficiency (hypoadrenalism). If untreated, it causes an adrenal crisis — haemodynamic collapse and death. IV hydrocortisone is the priority intervention.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What is the immediate first-line medical treatment for suspected pituitary apoplexy?",a:"IV hydrocortisone 100mg stat, without waiting for cortisol levels. Then hydrocortisone 50–100mg every 6–8 hours. Do not delay for test results.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What is the Pituitary Apoplexy Score (PAS) and what does it assess?",a:"Grades severity using: level of consciousness (GCS), visual acuity loss, visual field defects, and ophthalmoplegia. Higher scores indicate more severe disease and favour surgical decompression.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"When is emergency transsphenoidal surgery indicated for pituitary apoplexy?",a:"Severe or rapidly worsening visual loss/field defects; deteriorating consciousness level; high Pituitary Apoplexy Score. Surgery should be performed early in these cases. Conservative management is appropriate for mild cases.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What visual field defect is classically associated with pituitary/chiasmal compression?",a:"Bitemporal hemianopia — compression of the crossing nasal fibres of the optic chiasm causes loss of the temporal visual fields in both eyes. Superior bitemporal field loss often occurs first.",ref:"claude — neuro-ophthalmology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What other hormone deficiencies may be found in pituitary apoplexy?",a:"Acute: cortisol deficiency (most dangerous), TSH deficiency, GH deficiency. Diabetes insipidus can occur if posterior pituitary is involved. Check cortisol, T4/TSH, IGF-1, LH/FSH, prolactin (often high in prolactinoma).",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What anticoagulant/antiplatelet precaution should be noted in managing pituitary apoplexy?",a:"If the patient is on anticoagulation that contributed to haemorrhage, reversal should be considered — discuss with haematology. However, hydrocortisone replacement is the immediate priority.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{q:"What was the Jahangiri 2014 study on repeat transsphenoidal surgery — design and population?",a:"Retrospective review, 5 years, UCSF California Center for Pituitary Disorders. 916 patients, 1015 consecutive endonasal pituitary operations (907 initial + 108 repeat). 10% of patients (90/916) required reoperation: 90 second, 11 third, 4 fourth, 3 fifth-to-seventh. Mean age 46; 56% female. Diagnoses: endocrine active (36%), inactive (30%) adenomas, Rathke's cleft cysts (10%), craniopharyngioma (3%). Craniopharyngioma and miscellaneous pathologies were most likely to require reoperation (p<0.05). Published J Neurosurg 121:67–74, 2014.",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.1–2",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What were the key morbidity rates for initial vs repeat transsphenoidal surgery in Jahangiri 2014?",a:"Initial vs repeat (all pathologies): DI 16% vs 26% (p=0.03); CSF leak requiring repair 1% vs 4% (p=0.04); meningitis 0.4% vs 3% (p=0.02); LOS 2.8 vs 4.5 days (p=0.006). Not significantly different: hyponatremia (16% vs 20%, p=0.3); new hypopituitarism (8% vs 6%, p=0.3). No carotid artery injuries; 1 death (in an initial surgery patient).",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.3–4",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What are the 4 patterns of complication increase across successive reoperations in Jahangiri 2014?",a:"(1) No increase at any reoperation: lumbar drain use, new hypopituitarism. (2) Increases at 2nd surgery but not beyond: DI (16%→25%→27%, p=0.04 for 2nd; p=0.3 for 3rd+) and meningitis (0.4%→5%→0%, p=0.02 for 2nd; p=0.9 for 3rd+). (3) Increases progressively with each operation: LOS (2.8→4.3→6.9 days; p<0.001). (4) No increase at 2nd but increases at 3rd+: hyponatremia (14%→14%→50%, p<0.001) and CSF leak (1%→2%→11%, p=0.02).",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.1, p.3–4",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What did multivariate analysis reveal about predictors of complications in repeat TSS (Jahangiri 2014)?",a:"Operation number was the only independent predictor of increased LOS, CSF leak, and meningitis — after adjusting for sex, age, pathology, radiation therapy, lesion size, and suprasellar extension (none significant). For DI: operation number had OR 2.1 (p=0.02) but did not survive Bonferroni correction. Conclusion: the cumulative surgical insult, not patient or tumour characteristics, drives increasing morbidity with each reoperation.",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.4–5",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What were complication rates specifically for pituitary adenomas and Rathke's cleft cysts at reoperation (Jahangiri 2014)?",a:"698 initial vs 34 repeat operations. DI: 13% vs 35% (p=0.001) — significantly increased. CSF leak requiring repair: 0.3% vs 9% (p=0.0009) — significantly increased. LOS: 2.5 vs 2.3 days (p=0.8) — no difference (unlike the overall cohort). Meningitis: 0.3% vs 3% (p=0.1, NS). Hyponatremia: 14% vs 18% (p=0.6, NS). New hypopituitarism: 19% vs 7% (p=0.3, NS). Key implication: DI and CSF leak are the dominant concerns even for the most common benign pathologies.",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.5–6",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 55-year-old has sudden severe headache and right-sided ptosis. CT shows no SAH. MRI reveals haemorrhage into a pituitary mass. Before results, what is the priority?",opts:["A. Urgent transsphenoidal surgery","B. IV dexamethasone","C. IV hydrocortisone 100mg immediately","D. LP to exclude meningitis","E. CTA to exclude aneurysm"],ans:2,exp:"Pituitary apoplexy → acute adrenal insufficiency is immediately life-threatening. IV hydrocortisone 100mg stat is the priority — before any investigation results. Adrenal crisis without hydrocortisone replacement can be fatal.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024 — emergency management",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{stem:"A patient with pituitary apoplexy has mild headache, no visual field defect, no ophthalmoplegia, GCS 15. What does the guideline support?",opts:["A. Emergency transsphenoidal decompression within 24h","B. Conservative management with hormone replacement and monitoring","C. External ventricular drain","D. Radiotherapy within 72h","E. Craniotomy for pituitary adenomectomy"],ans:1,exp:"2024 guideline: mild cases (no significant visual or conscious level deficit) = conservative management with hormone replacement, close neurological monitoring, and serial visual field assessment. Reserve surgery for deteriorating or severe cases.",ref:"Endocrinology Guideline 2024",src_id:"pituitary-apop"},
{stem:"A patient is being counselled for a third transsphenoidal operation for recurrent non-functioning pituitary adenoma. Based on Jahangiri 2014, which statement about reoperation morbidity is most accurate?",opts:["A. Meningitis risk increases progressively with each successive reoperation","B. New hypopituitarism doubles with each successive reoperation","C. Length of stay increases progressively, reaching approximately 6.9 days for the third and subsequent operations","D. CSF leak risk peaks at the second operation and does not increase further","E. Diabetes insipidus continues to rise with every operation beyond the second"],ans:2,exp:"Jahangiri 2014: LOS is the only complication that increases progressively (2.8d → 4.3d → 6.9d; p<0.001). New hypopituitarism does not increase with reoperations (NS). Meningitis increases at 2nd op but not further (5% at 2nd, 0% at 3rd+). CSF leak does not increase at 2nd op but jumps at 3rd+ (2% → 11%). DI increases at 2nd op but plateaus thereafter (25% at 2nd, 27% at 3rd+ — NS difference).",ref:"Jahangiri 2014, p.3–4",src_id:"k-jahangiri-2014",korky:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old presents to A&E with sudden-onset severe headache, bitemporal hemianopia, and confusion. He is found to be hypotensive (BP 80/50) and tachycardic. MRI shows pituitary apoplexy with suprasellar extension compressing the optic chiasm. What is the most critical immediate intervention?",opts:["A. Emergency transsphenoidal surgery within 2 hours to decompress the chiasm","B. IV 0.9% normal saline bolus only — hypotension is from dehydration","C. IM or IV hydrocortisone 100–200 mg immediately — acute pituitary apoplexy causes ACTH deficiency and secondary adrenal insufficiency; untreated adrenal crisis is fatal","D. Lumbar puncture to exclude SAH — must be done before any hormone replacement","E. CT-guided pituitary aspiration — less invasive than formal surgery"],ans:2,exp:"Pituitary apoplexy = haemorrhage/infarction of the pituitary gland. The immediate life-threatening risk is ACUTE ADRENAL INSUFFICIENCY from sudden ACTH deficiency → cortisol deficit → cardiovascular collapse. Hydrocortisone must be given IMMEDIATELY (100–200 mg IV/IM) before any further assessment — do not wait for cortisol levels. After steroid cover: fluid resuscitation, visual assessment, endocrine input. Surgery (emergency TSS) is considered for: rapidly deteriorating vision, severe ophthalmoplegia, or no improvement on conservative management within 24 hours. Some patients with stable vision improve conservatively with steroids alone. Never perform LP before CT in the setting of chiasmal compression.",ref:"claude — pituitary apoplexy management / ACTH deficiency",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old woman with a known macroprolactinoma (prolactin 8000 mIU/L) is 10 weeks pregnant. She is on bromocriptine, which has reduced her prolactin level. She is concerned about continuing the medication in pregnancy. What is the most appropriate advice?",opts:["A. Bromocriptine must be stopped immediately — it is teratogenic and causes fetal limb abnormalities","B. Cabergoline should be substituted — safer than bromocriptine in pregnancy","C. Bromocriptine can be continued in pregnancy; the prolactinoma should be monitored for symptomatic enlargement (headache, visual field change); bromocriptine can be stopped if the tumour is not growing","D. The patient should be advised to terminate the pregnancy — prolactinomas always expand rapidly in pregnancy","E. Breastfeeding is absolutely contraindicated after delivery in patients with prolactinoma"],ans:2,exp:"Prolactinoma in pregnancy: Dopamine agonists (bromocriptine, cabergoline) have extensive safety data in pregnancy — neither is proven teratogenic. Typically: stop the DA when pregnancy is confirmed (as tumour usually does not enlarge significantly in microadenomas during pregnancy). For macroprolactinoma: the tumour can enlarge in 20–30% due to oestrogen-driven growth; DA is often continued if tumour is large or symptoms develop. Monitoring: VF testing each trimester if DA stopped; MRI without gadolinium if symptomatic. Termination is NOT indicated for prolactinoma alone. Breastfeeding is not contraindicated — the lactational prolactin rise does not significantly stimulate tumour growth.",ref:"claude — prolactinoma management in pregnancy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient has a transsphenoidal resection of a GH-secreting pituitary adenoma (acromegaly). Three months post-operatively, the surgeon wants to assess whether the operation has achieved biochemical cure. Which is the best single test for remission?",opts:["A. Random serum GH measurement — if GH <1 µg/L, cure is confirmed","B. Random IGF-1 measurement — the most sensitive marker of long-term GH excess","C. GH nadir after a 75g oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) — nadir GH <1 µg/L (or <0.4 µg/L with sensitive assays) combined with normal IGF-1 defines biochemical remission","D. MRI pituitary 3 months post-op — no residual tumour confirms cure","E. 24-hour urine GH excretion — reflects integrated daily GH secretion"],ans:2,exp:"Biochemical cure criteria in acromegaly post-surgery: (1) GH nadir <1 µg/L (or <0.4 µg/L with new ultrasensitive assays) during a 75g OGTT — GH normally suppresses to very low levels after glucose load; in active acromegaly, GH fails to suppress; (2) Normal age/sex-matched IGF-1 — reflects integrated GH activity over 24 hours. Random GH is unreliable (pulsatile secretion). MRI confirms anatomy but not biochemistry. Cure definition requires BOTH criteria. IGF-1 is the best single outpatient monitoring test. OGTT is the gold standard for remission confirmation at 3 months post-operatively.",ref:"claude — acromegaly biochemical remission criteria",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Regarding Cushing's disease (ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma), which statement is INCORRECT?",opts:["A. The majority of Cushing's disease is caused by a pituitary corticotroph adenoma secreting ACTH","B. Overnight 1 mg dexamethasone suppression test is a useful screening test — failure to suppress cortisol to <50 nmol/L suggests autonomous secretion","C. A normal pituitary MRI reliably excludes a pituitary adenoma as the cause — no further imaging is needed if MRI is normal","D. Bilateral inferior petrosal sinus sampling (IPSS) is used to confirm pituitary-source ACTH and lateralise the adenoma","E. First-line treatment is transsphenoidal adenomectomy — remission rates 70–90% at specialist centres"],ans:2,exp:"A normal pituitary MRI does NOT exclude Cushing's disease. Approximately 40–50% of ACTH-secreting pituitary adenomas are microadenomas (<6 mm) that are not visible on standard MRI. A negative MRI therefore cannot be used to rule out pituitary Cushing's. In this situation, IPSS is performed to confirm the pituitary as the ACTH source (central:peripheral gradient >2 at baseline, >3 after CRH stimulation) and to lateralise the tumour. If IPSS confirms pituitary source with a negative MRI, surgery is still offered based on clinical and biochemical grounds. Dynamic MRI (SPGR with gadolinium) may identify lesions missed on standard sequences.",ref:"claude — Cushing's disease MRI / IPSS",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 50-year-old patient undergoes transsphenoidal surgery. On post-operative day 2 they are confused and lethargic with serum sodium 119 mmol/L. Urine sodium is 55 mmol/L. The patient appears slightly dehydrated (low skin turgor, dry mucous membranes). Urine output has been 20–30 mL/hour. Serum cortisol post-op was normal. What is the diagnosis and treatment?",opts:["A. SIADH — fluid restrict to 500 mL/day and give oral sodium tablets","B. Cerebral salt wasting (CSW) — administer IV 0.9% saline and consider hypertonic saline if severe; avoid fluid restriction","C. Diabetes insipidus — replace free water and administer DDAVP","D. Adrenal insufficiency — urgent hydrocortisone replacement","E. Hypothyroidism — post-operative hypothyroidism causes hyponatraemia; give levothyroxine"],ans:1,exp:"CSW vs SIADH after pituitary surgery: both cause hyponatraemia with high urine sodium. The KEY differentiator is volume status: CSW = hypovolaemia (low skin turgor, dry mouth, reduced urine output, low CVP); SIADH = euvolaemia or mild hypervolaemia. Cortisol normal → not adrenal insufficiency. No polyuria → not DI. This patient is hypovolaemic = CSW. Treatment: IV saline (0.9%) to replace volume deficit; hypertonic saline (3%) if Na <120 with severe symptoms (seizures, coma). Fluid restriction (SIADH treatment) would worsen hypovolaemia in CSW and is contraindicated here — a dangerous error in post-operative neurosurgical patients.",ref:"claude — CSW vs SIADH post-pituitary surgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During transsphenoidal surgery, the surgeon encounters brisk arterial bleeding from the left side of the operative field, which is immediately controlled with Surgicel packing and gentle compression. Post-operatively, the patient is neurologically intact. What is the priority investigation?",opts:["A. CT head to exclude haematoma — do this within 1 hour","B. MRI pituitary with gadolinium — confirms surgical cavity appearance","C. CTA or DSA of the cerebral vasculature — to assess for ICA pseudoaneurysm or carotido-cavernous fistula from intraoperative ICA injury","D. Repeat TSH/cortisol — to identify post-operative endocrine failure","E. No further imaging needed if the patient is neurologically intact"],ans:2,exp:"Intraoperative ICA haemorrhage is the most feared complication of transsphenoidal surgery. Even if controlled with packing, the ICA may develop a pseudoaneurysm (delayed rupture) or carotido-cavernous fistula (CCF — pulsatile exophthalmos, bruit, chemosis). CTA or DSA must be performed urgently to assess ICA integrity. A pseudoaneurysm can rupture fatally hours to weeks later. If CCF or pseudoaneurysm is confirmed, endovascular treatment (coiling, stenting, balloon occlusion) is required. Neurological intactness in the immediate post-operative period does NOT rule out vascular injury — delayed haemorrhage is the danger.",ref:"claude — ICA injury in transsphenoidal surgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"hydrocephalus":{src:"NICE NG228 (SAH complications) + standard neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What are the two types of hydrocephalus and how do they differ?",a:"Obstructive (non-communicating): CSF blocked within the ventricular system (e.g. aqueduct stenosis, posterior fossa tumour). Communicating: CSF flows freely through ventricles but reabsorption is impaired (e.g. post-SAH, post-meningitis, NPH).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is Hakim's triad (normal pressure hydrocephalus)?",a:"Gait disturbance (wide-based, magnetic gait — first and most prominent); urinary incontinence; cognitive impairment/dementia. Imaging: ventriculomegaly disproportionate to sulcal atrophy.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"How does NG228 say to manage acute hydrocephalus causing deterioration after SAH?",a:"Consider drainage or diversion of CSF (typically via external ventricular drain).",ref:"NG228 1.3.4",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"How does NG228 say to manage chronic hydrocephalus after SAH?",a:"Consider drainage or permanent diversion of CSF. If uncertain about benefit of permanent diversion, consider a trial of temporary drainage first.",ref:"NG228 1.3.5",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{q:"What are the types of CSF shunt used in hydrocephalus?",a:"Ventriculoperitoneal (VP) shunt — most common; ventriculoatrial (VA) shunt — used if abdomen unsuitable; ventriculopleural shunt; lumboperitoneal shunt (communicating hydrocephalus). All can be fixed-pressure or programmable (adjustable).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the Dandy-Walker malformation?",a:"Cystic enlargement of the fourth ventricle with hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis and hydrocephalus. Presents in infancy with macrocephaly and developmental delay. Managed with CSF shunting or endoscopic fenestration.",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is endoscopic third ventriculostomy (ETV) used for?",a:"Creates a communication between the third ventricle and the interpeduncular cistern, bypassing aqueduct stenosis. Alternative to VP shunt in obstructive hydrocephalus. Avoids the complications of shunt hardware. Less effective in communicating hydrocephalus.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the classic shunt complications?",a:"Obstruction (most common — typically at proximal catheter); infection (Staph epidermidis most common — first 6 months); over-drainage (slit ventricle syndrome, subdural collections); under-drainage; shunt migration or fracture.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is DESH and which paper coined the term?",a:"DESH = Disproportionately Enlarged Subarachnoid-space Hydrocephalus. Coined by Hashimoto et al. (SINPHONI, 2010). Describes iNPH's characteristic CSF maldistribution: tight high-convexity and medial subarachnoid spaces PLUS enlarged Sylvian fissures and ventriculomegaly. CSF accumulates inferiorly (Sylvian fissures/basal cisterns) while high-convexity spaces are paradoxically tight.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.9",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What are the MRI inclusion criteria for iNPH diagnosis in the SINPHONI study?",a:"(1) Evans' index > 0.3 (ventriculomegaly) AND (2) tight high-convexity AND medial subarachnoid spaces on coronal T1-weighted MRI. Best seen on coronal sections — axial CT is inferior for evaluating the high-convexity region.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.3",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What is Evans' index and what threshold defines ventriculomegaly in iNPH?",a:"Evans' index = maximum width of frontal horns ÷ maximum inner diameter of skull at same level on axial imaging. >0.3 defines ventriculomegaly and is a key inclusion criterion for iNPH. Mean Evans' index in SINPHONI was 35.6 ± 4.0% (range 30–48%), indicating mild to moderate dilation.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.3, p.5",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"How does DESH differ from cerebral atrophy on MRI?",a:"In cerebral atrophy: subarachnoid spaces are enlarged proportionally to ventriculomegaly AND high-convexity spaces are open/wide. In DESH (iNPH): high-convexity and medial subarachnoid spaces are TIGHT/NARROW despite ventriculomegaly, while Sylvian fissures/inferior spaces are enlarged. The DISPROPORTIONATE distribution is the key distinguishing feature — do not misinterpret large Sylvian fissures + tight convexity as atrophy.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.5, p.9",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What were the 1-year outcomes of VP shunt for iNPH in SINPHONI?",a:"Favorable outcome (≥1 level improvement on mRS at 1 year): 69% (95% CI 59.4–77.2%). Shunt responder (≥1 level mRS improvement at ANY point in 1 year): 80% (95% CI 71.0–86.7%). iNPHGS improvement ≥1 point at 1 year: 77%. iNPHGS response at any point: 89%. All secondary measures (iNPHGS, TUG, MMSE) significantly improved.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.5–6",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What type of shunt was used in SINPHONI and what is the pressure-setting scheme?",a:"Codman-Hakim programmable valve (CHPV). Initial pressure set using a height/weight-based standardised scheme accounting for estimated hydrostatic and intra-abdominal pressure. Mean initial valve pressure 15.5 ± 4.3 cmH₂O. Advantage: reduced serious CSF over-drainage compared with fixed low-pressure valves. Pressure readjusted by 1–3 cmH₂O intervals as required.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.4, p.8–9",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What are the CSF inclusion criteria for iNPH diagnosis in SINPHONI?",a:"Normal CSF pressure ≤20 cmH₂O AND normal CSF content: protein ≤50 mg/dl AND cell count ≤3/mm³. All patients had a tap test (30 ml CSF removed via LP) prior to surgery.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.3",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What were the demographics and symptom profile of iNPH patients in SINPHONI?",a:"100 patients, mean age 74.5 years, 58% male. Symptoms (score ≥2 on iNPHGS): gait disturbance 91%, cognitive impairment 80%, urinary symptoms 60%. Classical triad present in only 51% — the full triad is not required for diagnosis.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.5",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What were the shunt-related adverse events in SINPHONI?",a:"Serious (surgery/shunt-related): 3 events — subdural haematoma requiring surgery, bowel perforation requiring repair, shunt tube obstruction requiring revision. Non-serious: asymptomatic subdural effusion (n=13) and postural headache (n=8), all controlled by programmable valve adjustment. Total SAEs: 15, but most (12) unrelated to surgery.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.6, p.8",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What Sylvian fissure finding was seen in SINPHONI and why is it important?",a:"Dilated Sylvian fissures were present in 96% of iNPH patients — they are a near-universal feature of DESH. This supports the concept that CSF redistributes disproportionately to the inferior subarachnoid spaces. Sylvian fissure dilation + tight high convexity = DESH pattern (not atrophy).",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.5, p.9",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What is the ETV Success Score (ETVSS) and what does it predict?",a:"The ETVSS predicts the probability of 6-month ETV success in a child with hydrocephalus. Developed by Kulkarni et al. (2010). Score = Age score + Etiology score + Previous shunt score. Ranges 0–90; the number roughly equals the % chance of ETV success at 6 months. High score = good ETV candidate.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.1",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"How is the ETVSS calculated? Give the scoring table.",a:"AGE: <1 month=0; 1–<6 months=10; 6 months–<1 year=30; 1–<10 years=40; ≥10 years=50. ETIOLOGY: postinfectious=0; myelomeningocele/IVH/non-tectal brain tumour=20; aqueductal stenosis/tectal tumour/other=30. PREVIOUS SHUNT: previous shunt=0; no previous shunt=10. Total = sum of all three components.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.2 (Table 1)",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What are the ETVSS strata and what do they predict for ETV vs shunt outcomes? (Kulkarni 2010)",a:"High (≥80): ETV superior to shunt right from the early phase — 3-year success 72% (ETV) vs 54% (shunt). Moderate (50–70): ETV initially higher failure rate, but by ~3 months ETV risk becomes slightly lower; 3-year success 52% vs 49%. Low (≤40): shunt superior for first ~2 years; 3-year success 37% (ETV) vs 38% (shunt). Across ALL strata, ETV failure rate eventually becomes lower than shunt failure rate with time.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.3–5 (Table 3, Fig. 3)",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"Which patients have an ETVSS ≥80 and what does this mean clinically?",a:"ETVSS ≥80 requires: age ≥1 year (score ≥40) + aqueductal stenosis or tectal tumour (score 30) + no previous shunt (score 10) = minimum 80. These are the classic ETV indications. ETV shows lower failure rate than shunt right from the early postoperative phase — clear early and lasting survival benefit. Represent the strongest ETV candidates.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.5",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What is the 'front-loading vs back-loading' risk concept for ETV vs shunt? (Kulkarni 2010)",a:"ETV 'front-loads' risk: higher early failure rate (steep early failures first 3–6 months), but lower long-term failure rate compared with shunt. Shunt 'back-loads' risk: better early success, but ongoing failure rate over time (revisions, obstruction, infection). For families of low/moderate ETVSS patients this framing helps with shared decision-making — accept early ETV risk for possible long-term benefit.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.5",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"Work through an ETVSS calculation: 8-month-old child with aqueductal stenosis, no previous shunt.",a:"Age 6–<12 months = 30. Etiology aqueductal stenosis = 30. No previous shunt = 10. ETVSS = 30 + 30 + 10 = 70. This means approximately 70% chance of ETV success at 6 months. Falls in the Moderate-ETVSS group (50–70).",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.2",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What patient population and design underpinned Kulkarni 2010?",a:"Multicenter international cohort: 489 ETV-treated + 720 shunt-treated patients (1,209 total), age ≤19 years, newly diagnosed hydrocephalus. ETV cohort: 12 centres (Canada, Israel, UK), 1989–2006. Shunt cohort: from the Shunt Design Trial + Endoscopic Shunt Insertion Trial. Not randomised — confounders addressed via ETVSS stratification.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.2",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What was the Kumpe 2011 study on dural sinus stenting for IIH — design and population?",a:"Retrospective case series, 18 consecutive patients, 19 stenting procedures. University of Colorado, February 1999 – November 2009. All had papilledema and failed medical management. 12 women, 6 men; ages 16–62; 88% overweight/obese. Follow-up 11–136 months (median 30 months).",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.1",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What are the selection criteria for dural sinus stenting in IIH (Kumpe 2011)?",a:"(1) Clinical IIH with papilledema ± visual deterioration; (2) failed medical management; (3) intraluminal filling defect in the transverse-sigmoid junction region on MRV/CTV or arteriography; (4) pressure gradient ≥10 mmHg across the filling defect on selective intracranial venous manometry. Normal torcular-to-jugular gradient = 4–5 mmHg. Pre-stent gradients in this series: 10.5–39 mmHg (median 21.1 mmHg).",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.1",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What is the anatomical basis for dural sinus stenting in IIH (Kumpe 2011)?",a:"A subset of IIH patients have focal intraluminal filling defects at the transverse-sigmoid junction (typically hypertrophied arachnoid granulations) causing a documentable venous pressure gradient and consequent intracranial venous hypertension. These patients are effectively NOT 'idiopathic' — they have a mechanical venous obstruction. Stenting eliminates the gradient. Distinct from external sinus compression by raised ICP (which resolves with CSF diversion).",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.7",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What were the clinical outcomes of dural sinus stenting for IIH in Kumpe 2011?",a:"Papilledema resolved in 15/16 (94%) patients with fundoscopic follow-up; no recurrence. Visual acuity stable or improved in all patients. Headache: persisted in some form in 10/12 female patients, but improved (less frequent/severe) in 8 of those 10; only 2 fully resolved. All 19 stent placements were technically successful — immediate gradient reduction to 0–7 mmHg in every case.",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.5",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What were the stent patency and hemodynamic durability results in Kumpe 2011?",a:"All stents patent on angiographic follow-up (up to 99 months) — zero in-stent restenosis. Continuing hemodynamic success: 80% (12/15 patients had <4 mmHg change from immediate post-stent gradient at last follow-up); 87% with repeat stenting in 1 patient. 3/15 had hemodynamic deterioration due to narrowing of the transverse sinus ABOVE the stent (not within the stent itself), likely representing a different IIH pathophysiology.",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.6",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What antiplatelet regimen is used with dural sinus stenting for IIH (Kumpe 2011)?",a:"Aspirin 325 mg + clopidogrel 75 mg for ≥5 days before the procedure and for 6 months after; then aspirin alone long-term. Implication: follow-up lumbar punctures should not be performed during the 6-month dual antiplatelet period (haemorrhagic risk); Kumpe did not perform post-procedure LPs for this reason.",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.3",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"How does dural sinus stenting compare to ONSF for IIH (Kumpe 2011)?",a:"ONSF has progressive failure rates: functioning at 66% (12 months), 38% (5 years), 16% (6 years). Complication rate up to 40% in some series. In Kumpe's own cohort: 5/7 who had prior ONSF had visual deterioration in the operated eye, 2 became blind. Stenting achieved 94% papilledema resolution with no recurrence and appears more durable. ONSF also fails to treat the underlying cause.",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.9",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"How does dural sinus stenting compare to CSF shunts for IIH (Kumpe 2011)?",a:"CSF shunts have high failure rates: lumboperitoneal 75% cumulative failure at 1 year; 80% require revision within 36 months. Headache recurs in 48% despite a functioning shunt (McGirt series). Stenting, in the appropriate subgroup with focal venous outflow obstruction, is more durable and avoids hardware complications. However, stenting applies only to patients with a documentable gradient — patients without focal obstruction should still be shunted.",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.9",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the DEPSS trial (Delwel 2013) — design and patient population?",a:"Dutch Evaluation Programme Strata Shunt. RCT, 58 NPH patients (Group 1 n=30, Group 2 n=28), 8 Dutch neurosurgical centres, 2003–2006. Published JNNP 2013;84:813–817. Device: PS Medical Strata I valve (Medtronic) — programmable differential pressure valve with integrated antisiphon device, 5 performance levels (PL 0.5–2.5). Question: what is the optimal starting shunt pressure in NPH?",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.1",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What were the two groups in DEPSS (Delwel 2013) and how was titration managed?",a:"Group 1 (n=30, control): started at PL 1.0 (OPV 35–55 mmH₂O supine — low pressure). Group 2 (n=28): started at PL 2.5 (OPV 135–155 mmH₂O supine — high pressure), then titrated DOWN by one PL at each visit when improvement was seen or absent. Group 1 adjusted UP if no improvement. 32.1% of Group 2 achieved improvement at PL 2.5 and required no down-titration at all.",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.2",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What were the clinical improvement outcomes in DEPSS (Delwel 2013) at 9 months?",a:"Overall clinical improvement at 9 months: Group 1 (low start) 73.1% vs Group 2 (high start) 76.9% — p=0.606, not significant. Secondary outcomes: gait improvement >15% (78.3% vs 71.4%, NS); cognitive improvement >15% (17.4% vs 30.0%, NS). Evans' ratio, mRS, 3MS, and continence improved significantly in both groups with no between-group difference. No difference in absolute efficacy.",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.3",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What were the subdural effusion (SDE) and valve adjustment rates in DEPSS (Delwel 2013)?",a:"SDEs significantly more common in Group 1 (low pressure start): at 1 month p=0.022, at 9 months p=0.043. No SDHs in either group. Valve adjustments required: 23.3% (Group 1, low start) vs 67.9% (Group 2, high start), p=0.001 — high-start required far more titration visits. Trade-off: high-start = fewer SDEs but more clinic visits; low-start = fewer visits but more overdrainage complications.",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.3–4",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What is the DEPSS recommendation for shunt starting pressure in NPH (Delwel 2013)?",a:"Start at the highest performance level (PL 2.5, high pressure) and titrate down as needed. Rationale: equivalent clinical improvement at 9 months, but significantly fewer SDEs compared with low-pressure start. No SDHs in either group. Trade-off: more clinic visits required for down-titration in the high-start group. Strategy mirrors a conservative approach — protect against overdrainage first, then optimise CSF drainage.",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.4–5",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What is the management ladder for idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH)?",a:"(1) Weight loss ≥10% body weight (most effective — normalises ICP in obese patients). (2) Acetazolamide — first-line pharmacotherapy (carbonic anhydrase inhibitor, reduces CSF production). (3) Topiramate — alternative/adjunct. (4) Repeated therapeutic LPs — temporising measure. (5) CSF shunting (LP shunt or VP shunt) for refractory disease. (6) Optic nerve sheath fenestration (ONSF) — for acute visual loss. (7) Dural venous sinus stenting if stenosis with gradient ≥10 mmHg across filling defect (Kumpe 2011 criteria).",ref:"claude — IIH management / Kumpe 2011",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What is a colloid cyst and how does it present?",a:"Benign epithelial cyst at the anterosuperior third ventricle (foramen of Monro). Contains viscous colloid. Presentation: (1) intermittent positional headache ± syncope — cyst acts as a ball-valve obstructing the foramen of Monro; (2) acute obstructive hydrocephalus — sudden deterioration, can be fatal; (3) incidental. Memory disturbance. CT: hyperdense midline lesion at the foramen of Monro. Treatment: endoscopic aspiration/fenestration or microsurgical excision.",ref:"claude — colloid cyst of the third ventricle",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 72-year-old has 6-month progressive gait disturbance, urinary incontinence, and cognitive decline. MRI shows ventriculomegaly disproportionate to sulcal atrophy. Most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Alzheimer's disease","B. Parkinson's disease","C. Normal pressure hydrocephalus","D. Multi-infarct dementia","E. Subdural hygroma"],ans:2,exp:"Classic NPH (Hakim's triad): gait disturbance (typically first, most prominent), urinary incontinence, cognitive impairment. Ventriculomegaly disproportionate to sulcal atrophy on MRI. Gait improves most with CSF shunting.",ref:"claude — NPH",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A patient develops acute hydrocephalus and progressive drowsiness after SAH. What does NG228 recommend?",opts:["A. Observe 24 hours first","B. Consider drainage or diversion of CSF","C. Increase osmotic therapy","D. LP","E. Proceed directly to VP shunt"],ans:1,exp:"NG228 (1.3.4): For neurological deterioration caused by acute hydrocephalus, consider drainage or diversion of CSF — typically via EVD acutely.",ref:"NICE NG228, 1.3.4",src_id:"nice-ng228"},
{stem:"MRI of a 76-year-old with gait disorder shows ventriculomegaly with enlarged Sylvian fissures but tight subarachnoid spaces at the high convexity and midline on coronal T1. Evans' index is 0.36. What is this pattern called and what diagnosis does it support?",opts:["A. Communicating hydrocephalus from prior meningitis","B. Cerebral atrophy","C. DESH — supports iNPH diagnosis","D. Aqueduct stenosis","E. Non-communicating hydrocephalus"],ans:2,exp:"DESH (Disproportionately Enlarged Subarachnoid-space Hydrocephalus): enlarged Sylvian fissures + tight high-convexity/medial subarachnoid spaces + ventriculomegaly (Evans' index >0.3). Coined by Hashimoto 2010 (SINPHONI). Distinguishing from atrophy: in atrophy, subarachnoid spaces are proportionally enlarged including high convexity — in DESH, high convexity is paradoxically tight.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010, p.9",src_id:"k-hashimoto-2010",korky:true},
{stem:"A 3-year-old with aqueductal stenosis (no previous shunt) is being considered for ETV. What is their ETVSS and what does it imply?",opts:["A. ETVSS 40 — low, shunt preferred","B. ETVSS 70 — moderate, ETV initially higher risk but becomes favourable at ~3 months","C. ETVSS 80 — high, ETV clearly superior right from early phase","D. ETVSS 60 — moderate, outcomes equivalent to shunt at 3 years","E. ETVSS 90 — maximum score, near-certain ETV success"],ans:2,exp:"Age 1–<10 years = 40. Aqueductal stenosis = 30. No previous shunt = 10. ETVSS = 80. High group (≥80): ETV shows lower failure rate than shunt right from early phase, 3-year survival 72% (ETV) vs 54% (shunt). This child is a strong ETV candidate — classic indication.",ref:"Kulkarni 2010, p.2, p.3, p.5 (Table 1, Table 3)",src_id:"k-kulkarni-2010",korky:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old obese woman with IIH has progressive papilledema despite maximum medical therapy. MRV shows a filling defect at the right transverse-sigmoid junction. Selective venous manometry reveals a gradient of 18 mmHg across the filling defect (normal 4–5 mmHg). What is the most appropriate next step?",opts:["A. Bilateral optic nerve sheath fenestration","B. Lumboperitoneal shunt","C. Unilateral right transverse sinus stenting","D. Ventriculoperitoneal shunt","E. Repeat lumbar puncture and topiramate dose increase"],ans:2,exp:"Per Kumpe 2011, a gradient ≥10 mmHg across a focal intraluminal filling defect in the transverse-sigmoid junction is the criterion for dural sinus stenting. This patient meets all criteria: IIH, papilledema, failed medical therapy, documented focal venous obstruction with a substantial gradient (18 mmHg). Stenting is the initial procedure of choice in this subgroup: 94% papilledema resolution, no in-stent restenosis, and more durable than shunts (75-80% failure at 1yr for LP shunts) or ONSF (failure rate 16% functioning at 6 years; 5/7 in Kumpe's series had visual deterioration after ONSF).",ref:"Kumpe 2011, p.9",src_id:"k-kumpe-2011",korky:true},
{stem:"The DEPSS trial (Delwel 2013) randomised NPH patients to a low-pressure (PL 1.0) vs high-pressure (PL 2.5) start with a programmable Strata valve. Which best summarises the key finding?",opts:["A. High pressure start produced superior clinical improvement at 9 months","B. Low pressure start caused significantly more subdural effusions with no difference in clinical improvement","C. High pressure start caused significantly more subdural haematomas","D. No differences were found in any outcome between the two groups","E. Low pressure start required significantly more valve adjustments"],ans:1,exp:"DEPSS: clinical improvement equivalent at 9 months (73.1% low vs 76.9% high, p=0.606). However, SDEs were significantly more frequent in the low-pressure start group at both 1 month (p=0.022) and 9 months (p=0.043) — no SDHs in either group. High-start required more valve adjustments (67.9% vs 23.3%, p=0.001) and more clinic visits. Recommendation: start at highest PL (2.5) and titrate down — equivalent efficacy, fewer overdrainage complications.",ref:"Delwel 2013, p.3–4",src_id:"k-delwel-2013",korky:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old obese woman with IIH has papilloedema and headaches unresponsive to acetazolamide. Which management step is NOT appropriate?",opts:["A. Encourage ≥10% body weight loss","B. Topiramate as alternative pharmacotherapy","C. Lumboperitoneal shunt for refractory disease","D. Optic nerve sheath fenestration if acute vision loss develops","E. High-dose corticosteroids as first-line treatment"],ans:4,exp:"IIH management: weight loss (most effective), acetazolamide (first-line), topiramate (alternative), repeated LPs, CSF shunting, ONSF for acute visual loss, dural sinus stenting if stenosis with gradient ≥10 mmHg. High-dose corticosteroids are NOT first-line treatment — risk rebound intracranial hypertension on withdrawal and weight gain, worsening IIH.",ref:"claude — IIH management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old has three episodes over six months of sudden severe headache with brief loss of consciousness, each triggered by standing quickly. MRI shows a 15mm hyperdense midline lesion at the foramen of Monro. What is the diagnosis and key risk?",opts:["A. Aqueduct stenosis — risk of chronic progressive hydrocephalus","B. Colloid cyst of the third ventricle — risk of acute obstructive hydrocephalus and sudden death","C. GBM of the third ventricle — risk of direct invasion","D. Ependymoma — risk of CSF seeding","E. Hypothalamic hamartoma — risk of gelastic epilepsy"],ans:1,exp:"Colloid cyst: benign epithelial cyst at the foramen of Monro. Classic presentation: intermittent positional headache/syncope as the cyst intermittently obstructs CSF flow (ball-valve mechanism). Key risk: acute obstructive hydrocephalus → sudden death. CT: hyperdense midline third ventricle lesion. Treatment: endoscopic or microsurgical excision.",ref:"claude — colloid cyst of the third ventricle",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Which of the following MRI features is NOT a characteristic finding in idiopathic normal pressure hydrocephalus (iNPH)?",opts:["A. DESH — disproportionately enlarged Sylvian fissures with tight high-convexity subarachnoid spaces","B. Evans' index >0.3 on axial MRI","C. INCREASED callosal angle (>120°) suggesting lateral ventricular expansion","D. DECREASED callosal angle (<90°) — suggesting lateral expansion squeezing the corpus callosum","E. Aqueductal flow void on T2 MRI indicating increased CSF pulsatility"],ans:2,exp:"In iNPH, the callosal angle is NARROW/DECREASED — typically <90°. The lateral ventricles expand LATERALLY (due to periventricular white matter compliance loss), compressing the corpus callosum downward → the angle narrows. An INCREASED callosal angle (>120°) is NOT a feature of NPH; it is seen in CEREBRAL ATROPHY (hydrocephalus ex vacuo), where parenchymal loss expands the ventricles superiorly, pushing the corpus callosum upward. This distinction is key for differentiating NPH from atrophy. Other characteristic iNPH MRI features: DESH pattern (Hashimoto 2010), Evans' index >0.3, callosal thinning, periventricular signal change, aqueductal flow void.",ref:"Hashimoto 2010 / Standard iNPH imaging criteria",recall:true},
{stem:"A 72-year-old man with Hakim's triad is being investigated for iNPH before considering VP shunting. Which investigation is considered the MOST reliable predictor of shunt response?",opts:["A. Single CSF tap test (30–50 ml LP) with gait assessment","B. 24-hour external lumbar drainage (ELD) with clinical improvement","C. Measurement of CSF outflow resistance (Rout) by infusion test — Rout ≥18 mmHg/mL/min, accounting for rate of injection and baseline pressure, is the most validated predictor","D. Brain FDG-PET showing frontal hypometabolism","E. Response to acetazolamide over 4 weeks"],ans:2,exp:"CSF outflow resistance (Rout) measured by infusion test is the most validated predictor of shunt response in iNPH. Rout ≥18 mmHg/mL/min indicates impaired CSF reabsorption consistent with NPH and predicts shunt benefit in large series (German/Dutch NPH study — r21-53). Critical caveat: a single Rout measurement alone is insufficient — the RATE OF INJECTION and BASELINE PRESSURE must both be accounted for (rq107). Extended external lumbar drainage (ELD) over 3–5 days also has high predictive value but is more invasive. Single tap test: lower sensitivity (~26–58%) — a negative tap does not exclude shunt response. Acetazolamide has no role in NPH diagnosis. PET is a research tool. The infusion test/Rout is the standard investigation at specialist centres.",ref:"Katzman-Hussey infusion test / German NPH study / Hashimoto 2010",recall:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old obese woman with known IIH has been maximally treated with acetazolamide and has undergone multiple lumbar punctures. She presents with left visual acuity now 6/26 (right 6/9) and bilateral papilloedema worse on the left. She is asking for the next step. Which intervention would be LEAST appropriate here?",opts:["A. Left optic nerve sheath fenestration (ONSF) to protect the more severely affected left optic nerve","B. Lumboperitoneal or ventriculoperitoneal shunting","C. Subtemporal decompression (temporal craniotomy)","D. Dural sinus stenting if MRV and manometry confirm significant transverse sinus stenosis with a pressure gradient ≥10 mmHg","E. Weight loss advice as an ongoing measure"],ans:2,exp:"Subtemporal decompression (temporal craniotomy) has NO role in the management of IIH — it is NOT a recognised treatment and is not in any IIH guideline. Interventions for medically refractory IIH: (1) ONSF: protects the optic nerve by decompressing the CSF sheath; most appropriate when primary concern is vision loss (as here — left VA 6/26); does not reliably resolve headache. (2) LP or VP shunting: treats both visual symptoms and headache; higher long-term failure rate. (3) Dural sinus stenting: increasingly evidence-based when focal venous stenosis with pressure gradient ≥10 mmHg confirmed on manometry (Kumpe 2011). (4) Weight loss: most durable long-term intervention — even 5–10% loss reduces ICP significantly. IIH is not treated by craniotomy under any circumstances.",ref:"claude — IIH surgical management / Kumpe 2011",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old presents with 6-month history of intermittent positional headache. MRI shows a 2 cm third ventricular lesion at the foramen of Monro. There is no ventriculomegaly. Diagnosis is a colloid cyst. What is the preferred surgical technique if intervention is chosen, and which structure is the cyst typically attached to within the third ventricle?",opts:["A. Open microsurgical craniotomy — the cyst is attached to the ependyma of the lateral wall of the third ventricle","B. Endoscopic excision (transcortical or transcallosal approach) — the cyst typically arises from and is attached to the tela choroidea (roof) of the third ventricle","C. Stereotactic aspiration via a twist-drill — the cyst is attached to the choroid plexus of the lateral ventricle","D. VP shunting of the third ventricle — the cyst is attached to the floor of the third ventricle","E. Gamma Knife radiosurgery — the cyst is attached to the mamillary bodies"],ans:1,exp:"Colloid cysts arise from the anterior third ventricle, attached to the tela choroidea (the double layer of pia forming the roof of the third ventricle). During endoscopic surgery, the cyst is typically visualised attached to this membranous roof — the velum interpositum/tela choroidea. Preferred surgical approach: ENDOSCOPIC excision (right transcortical or transcallosal). Advantages over open microsurgical craniotomy: lower morbidity, equivalent complete removal rate (~85–90%), quicker recovery. Open transcallosal: reserved for thick-walled or inaccessible cysts. VP shunting does not remove the cyst and carries ongoing risk of acute obstruction. Aspiration alone has high recurrence. Radiosurgery has no role. Management decision: symptomatic + ventriculomegaly → surgery; symptomatic without ventriculomegaly → surgery or surveillance with clear shared decision-making about sudden death risk.",ref:"claude — colloid cyst surgery / r21-6 tela choroidea attachment",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 4-year-old presents with macrocephaly and developmental delay. MRI shows isolated dilation of the right lateral ventricle with normal left lateral ventricle, normal third ventricle, and normal fourth ventricle. MRI confirms stenosis of the right foramen of Monro. What are the two most appropriate surgical treatments?",opts:["A. Bilateral VP shunts — one shunt per lateral ventricle","B. ETV (endoscopic third ventriculostomy) — bypasses the aqueduct","C. Endoscopic right foramen of Monro plasty (foraminoplasty) OR endoscopic septostomy — fenestration of the septum pellucidum to allow communication between the dilated right and normal left ventricle","D. Open transcallosal craniotomy and microsurgical foraminoplasty — endoscopic approaches are not feasible at this age","E. Right VP shunt + contralateral ETV as a staged procedure"],ans:2,exp:"Unilateral lateral ventricular hydrocephalus from foramen of Monro stenosis: two endoscopic options exist. (1) FORAMEN OF MONRO PLASTY (endoscopic foraminoplasty): dilation of the stenotic foramen to restore normal CSF flow into the third ventricle. Technically feasible if stenosis is not complete/fibrotic. (2) SEPTOSTOMY: endoscopic fenestration of the septum pellucidum to create communication between the dilated right lateral ventricle and the normal left lateral ventricle — CSF equilibrates across the septum, equalising pressures and treating the hydrocephalus without restoring the foramen of Monro itself. Both approaches avoid long-term shunt dependence. VP shunt to the right ventricle alone would work but commits to shunt dependency. Bilateral shunts are unnecessary as only one ventricle is dilated. ETV addresses aqueductal/posterior third ventricular obstruction — not foramen of Monro stenosis.",ref:"claude — unilateral hydrocephalus / endoscopic septostomy / foraminoplasty",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During endoscopic third ventriculostomy (ETV), the surgeon perforates the floor of the third ventricle. Which anatomical structure, when seen through the perforation, confirms the stoma has been made in the correct location and CSF can communicate freely with the subarachnoid space?",opts:["A. Planum sphenoidale — the flat bony roof of the sphenoid sinus, confirming anterior perforations","B. The mammillary bodies — posterior third ventricle structures confirm the perforation is too posterior","C. The basilar artery pulsating in the interpeduncular cistern — confirms communication with the prepontine subarachnoid space; the ipsilateral oculomotor nerve (CN III) is also visible confirming correct midline posterior position","D. The pituitary stalk — confirms the perforation is in the floor anterior to the infundibular recess","E. The optic chiasm — confirms the perforation is anterior to the desired site"],ans:2,exp:"During ETV, the floor of the third ventricle is perforated between the infundibular recess and the mammillary bodies (the 'safe zone'). Correct perforation is confirmed by direct visualisation of the basilar artery pulsating in the interpeduncular cistern through the stoma, and the oculomotor nerve (CN III) is typically visible bilaterally. This confirms the subarachnoid space has been entered and CSF will bypass the obstructed aqueduct. The planum sphenoidale is anterior and not a relevant landmark. The mammillary bodies mark the posterior limit of the safe zone — perforation posterior to them risks midbrain injury.",ref:"claude — ETV anatomy and technique",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old businessman presents with 6-month history of intermittent severe headaches. He describes the headache as positional — worse when bending forward and relieved by lying flat or changing position. MRI shows a 2 cm colloid cyst at the foramen of Monro with mild ventriculomegaly. What is the most appropriate management?",opts:["A. Surveillance MRI in 6 months — small colloid cysts rarely cause symptoms","B. Lumbar puncture for opening pressure measurement — needed before surgical planning","C. Endoscopic or transcallosal/transcortical surgical excision — the combination of positional headache and ventriculomegaly indicates symptomatic obstruction requiring intervention","D. Ventriculoperitoneal shunt — relieves the hydrocephalus without the risks of direct tumour surgery","E. Stereotactic aspiration — first-line minimally invasive treatment for colloid cysts"],ans:2,exp:"Colloid cysts produce a characteristic positional/intermittent headache due to their ball-valve effect at the foramen of Monro — obstructing CSF flow intermittently with head position changes. This is a red-flag presentation. Ventriculomegaly confirms intermittent/chronic obstruction. Surgical excision (endoscopic or open transcortical/transcallosal) is indicated in symptomatic patients with ventriculomegaly. Endoscopic excision is preferred (lower morbidity) but complete excision is technically challenging if the cyst is adherent. VP shunting does not address the direct risk of sudden death from acute obstruction. Surveillance alone is appropriate only for incidental, asymptomatic cysts without ventriculomegaly.",ref:"claude — colloid cyst management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old woman with known idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) has undergone lumboperitoneal shunting 3 months ago. She now presents with persistent headache. The shunt is draining appropriately and CT head is normal. There are no signs of infection. What is the most important assessment?",opts:["A. Repeat lumbar puncture to confirm the opening pressure is controlled","B. Formal ophthalmological assessment including visual acuity, visual fields, and fundoscopy — to exclude ongoing or progressive papilloedema and visual deterioration","C. MRI brain with gadolinium to exclude intracranial pathology","D. Shunt revision — persistent headache implies shunt malfunction","E. Acetazolamide recommencement — headache reflects inadequate CSF pressure reduction"],ans:1,exp:"In IIH follow-up, visual function is the primary endpoint — not headache control. Headache can persist even when ICP is adequately controlled. The critical risk of IIH is permanent visual loss from chronic papilloedema. A shunted patient with persistent headache requires formal ophthalmological review: visual acuity, automated visual fields (Humphrey), and fundoscopy to grade papilloedema. Normal CT and functioning shunt make structural pathology unlikely. Opening pressure measurement is useful if optic disc changes are present. Shunt revision is premature without evidence of failure.",ref:"claude — IIH follow-up and visual monitoring",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old obese woman with IIH presents with acute visual loss: right eye VA 6/9, left eye VA 6/60. She has severe bilateral papilloedema. LP opening pressure is 42 cmH2O. She has failed maximum-dose acetazolamide and topiramate. Which management option is LEAST appropriate?",opts:["A. Urgent CSF diversion (VP shunt or lumboperitoneal shunt)","B. Optic nerve sheath fenestration — directly decompresses the optic nerve sheath, protecting vision","C. Subtemporal decompression — indicated for severe refractory IIH with imminent visual loss","D. Serial therapeutic lumbar punctures as the primary ongoing management","E. Emergency low-molecular-weight heparin anticoagulation and MR venography to exclude cerebral venous sinus thrombosis"],ans:3,exp:"Serial LPs are inappropriate as primary management in a patient with severe acute visual loss (6/60) — they provide temporary relief only, do not address the progressive optic nerve injury, and cannot be sustained as the only strategy. Surgical intervention is urgently needed. Options include: (1) VP shunt (definitive CSF pressure reduction); (2) Optic nerve sheath fenestration (ONSF — directly protects the optic nerve from CSF pressure); (3) LP shunting. Subtemporal decompression has been used historically but is largely supplanted by shunting and ONSF. MVT exclusion (MRV) is always important in IIH before attributing to idiopathic causes. Serial LPs may be used as a bridge while awaiting surgery, not as primary management.",ref:"claude — IIH with acute visual loss — surgical management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 3-month-old infant develops progressive head enlargement and irritability following a grade IV intraventricular haemorrhage at birth. Head circumference is crossing centile lines. MRI confirms communicating hydrocephalus with cortical mantle preservation. What is the most appropriate management?",opts:["A. Immediate VP shunt insertion — definitive treatment with a programmable valve","B. Repeated serial lumbar punctures — indicated for communicating hydrocephalus in infants","C. Ventricular access device (Ommaya reservoir/ventricular tap reservoir) as a temporary CSF diversion while awaiting definitive shunting when the infant is larger and CSF protein has normalised","D. Endoscopic third ventriculostomy — first-line treatment for post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus in neonates","E. Observation only — head circumference will stabilise with maturation"],ans:2,exp:"Post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus (PHH) in premature infants is a high-risk clinical problem. VP shunt insertion in a small premature infant carries high infection/malfunction rates and cannot be placed immediately when CSF protein is very high (blocks shunt). Interim strategies: (1) Ventricular access device (reservoir/Ommaya) — allows repeated ventricular taps to control ICP and decompress the ventricles while the infant grows and CSF normalises; then definitive VP shunt when feasible. (2) ETV: poor success rate in infants <2 years, especially post-haemorrhagic. Serial LPs are used but have limited drainage in obstructive PHH. Low-pressure programmable valves help once shunting is undertaken.",ref:"claude — post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus neonates",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Which criterion for normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH) is INCORRECT — i.e., which statement about NPH is FALSE?",opts:["A. Hakim's triad consists of gait apraxia, cognitive decline, and urinary incontinence","B. MRI typically shows ventriculomegaly with an Evans index >0.3 and tight sulci at the high convexity/vertex","C. An increased callosal angle (>90°) on coronal MRI is characteristic of NPH","D. CSF tap test (removal of 30–50 mL CSF) is used as a diagnostic and prognostic test","E. CSF outflow resistance (Rout) measurement is used to predict shunt response"],ans:2,exp:"A DECREASED (not increased) callosal angle is characteristic of iNPH. The callosal angle is measured on coronal MRI at the level of the posterior commissure. Normal: >90°. In NPH: the callosal angle is often <90° (typically 60–80°) due to lateral ventricular expansion flattening the angle. An INCREASED callosal angle would suggest normal or small ventricles. This is a classic exam distractor. Other NPH features: Evans index >0.3; tight sulci at vertex (disproportionate sulcal narrowing); periventricular lucency; aqueductal flow void; positive tap test (improved gait/cognition after 50 mL LP drainage).",ref:"claude — NPH diagnostic MRI criteria / callosal angle",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 70-year-old with suspected idiopathic NPH has a VP shunt inserted. Pre-operatively, CSF outflow resistance (Rout) was measured at 14 mmHg/mL/min. Which statement about Rout in NPH is most accurate?",opts:["A. Rout >10 mmHg/mL/min confirms NPH and predicts excellent shunt response in all cases","B. Rout alone is unreliable as a single predictor of shunt response — it must be interpreted alongside clinical findings, tap test response, and other parameters; the Dutch/German iNPH study showed that outcome prediction requires a composite assessment","C. A normal Rout (<10 mmHg/mL/min) excludes NPH","D. Rout is measured by lumbar puncture opening pressure — high opening pressure = high Rout","E. Rout >18 mmHg/mL/min is an absolute contraindication to VP shunting in NPH"],ans:1,exp:"CSF outflow resistance (Rout) is a measure of CSF drainage efficiency measured by infusion tests (constant-rate CSF infusion or bolus injection, measuring pressure response). Elevated Rout suggests poor CSF absorption and supports an NPH diagnosis. However, Rout alone is not sufficient to predict shunt response — the Dutch/German iNPH study showed no single parameter reliably predicts outcome. Composite assessment (clinical triad, tap test response, imaging, Rout, and extended LP drainage) is required. Rout is measured by controlled CSF infusion, not opening pressure alone. There is no absolute cut-off that reliably predicts either response or non-response.",ref:"claude — NPH Rout measurement / Dutch-German iNPH study",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A baby is born with a lumbar myelomeningocele (MMC). During counselling, the parents ask about associated CNS abnormalities. Which statement is correct?",opts:["A. Hydrocephalus complicates 30% of lumbar MMC cases; ETV is equally effective as shunting","B. Chiari I malformation is the characteristic hindbrain anomaly associated with MMC","C. Hydrocephalus affects approximately 80–90% of patients with lumbar MMC; the associated hindbrain malformation is Chiari II (herniation of cerebellar vermis, brainstem, and fourth ventricle through the foramen magnum); ETV has lower success rates than in primary aqueductal stenosis","D. All MMC-associated hydrocephalus presents at birth and requires urgent shunting within 24 hours","E. MMC closure prevents hydrocephalus in all cases"],ans:2,exp:"Lumbar MMC is strongly associated with Chiari II malformation (not Chiari I) — characterised by downward herniation of the cerebellar vermis, brainstem, and fourth ventricle through the foramen magnum, along with associated supratentorial anomalies (callosal dysgenesis, cortical heterotopias). Hydrocephalus occurs in ~80–90% of lumbar MMC cases (less common with sacral MMC). ETV has reduced success rates in this context because Chiari II anatomy and associated arachnoid abnormalities impair normal subarachnoid CSF flow — VP shunting is often preferred. MMC closure does not prevent hydrocephalus but is required urgently to prevent meningitis/CSF leak.",ref:"claude — myelomeningocele / Chiari II / hydrocephalus",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"spinal-trauma":{src:"Standard neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the ASIA impairment scale grades A–E?",a:"A = complete (no motor or sensory below injury level, including sacral S4–5); B = incomplete, sensory only; C = incomplete, motor present but <3/5 in most key muscles below; D = incomplete, motor ≥3/5 in most key muscles below; E = normal motor and sensory.",ref:"ASIA classification"},
{q:"What is sacral sparing and why is it important?",a:"Preservation of any perianal sensation, voluntary anal contraction, or great toe flexion. Its presence means the injury is INCOMPLETE (ASIA B, C, or D) — NOT ASIA A. Sacral sparing carries a much better prognosis for neurological recovery.",ref:"ASIA classification"},
{q:"What is the difference between complete and incomplete cord injury clinically?",a:"Complete (ASIA A): no motor or sensory function below the injury level including sacral segments. Incomplete: any preservation of function below the level, including sacral sparing. Incomplete injuries have significantly better prognosis.",ref:"ASIA"},
{q:"What are the 5 incomplete spinal cord injury syndromes?",a:"Central cord syndrome (most common — arms>legs); Anterior cord syndrome (loss of motor + pain/temp, preserved proprioception/vibration); Brown-Séquard (hemicord); Posterior cord; Conus/Cauda equina.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is central cord syndrome and what causes it?",a:"Most common incomplete cord injury. Disproportionate weakness in arms > legs, with variable sensory loss and bladder dysfunction. Caused by hyperextension injury of a cervical spondylotic spine (usually elderly). Injury to centrally-located corticospinal fibres serving the arms.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is SCIWORA?",a:"Spinal Cord Injury Without Radiological Abnormality — neurological deficit with normal CT and plain X-rays. Seen on MRI (cord contusion/oedema). Most common in children (more elastic ligamentous structures). May result from cord contusion or vascular injury.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the surgical indications in acute traumatic spinal cord injury?",a:"Spinal instability (regardless of neurology); incomplete neurological deficit with mechanically compressive lesion; progressive neurological deterioration; open or penetrating fractures. Timing: early decompression (<24h) may improve neurological outcomes.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the Denis three-column classification of spinal stability?",a:"Anterior column: anterior longitudinal ligament + anterior 2/3 vertebral body/disc. Middle column: posterior 1/3 vertebral body/disc + posterior longitudinal ligament. Posterior column: pedicles, facets, laminae, posterior ligamentous complex. Disruption of ≥2 columns = instability.",ref:"Denis classification"},
{q:"What was the NASCIS 3 trial and what was the study design?",a:"Third National Acute Spinal Cord Injury Study (Bracken 1997). Double-blind RCT, 499 patients, 16 centres. Compared: (1) methylprednisolone 24h vs (2) methylprednisolone 48h vs (3) tirilazad mesylate 48h. All patients received 30 mg/kg bolus then randomised within 8 hours of injury.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.1",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"What was the NASCIS 3 dosing protocol for methylprednisolone in acute SCI?",a:"Bolus: 30 mg/kg IV. Maintenance: 5.4 mg/kg/hour infusion. Duration: 24 hours if started within 3 hours of injury; 48 hours if started 3–8 hours after injury. Must be initiated within 8 hours of injury.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.1–2",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"What was the key finding of NASCIS 3 regarding timing of methylprednisolone?",a:"Patients starting treatment <3 hours: no difference between 24h and 48h regimens. Patients starting 3–8 hours after injury: 48h methylprednisolone showed significantly better motor recovery at 6 weeks (P=.04) and 6 months (P=.01) vs 24h. At 6 months, 59.2% vs 39.3% improved by ≥1 full neurological grade.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.4–5",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"What were the complications of 48-hour methylprednisolone in NASCIS 3?",a:"48h methylprednisolone group had more severe sepsis (2.6% vs 0.6%, P=.07) and severe pneumonia (5.8% vs 2.6%, P=.02) vs 24h group. However, mortality was identical across all 3 groups (P=.97). Other complications were similar.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.6",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"What is the current clinical status of methylprednisolone for acute SCI?",a:"Now widely abandoned as a standard of care. Most guidelines downgraded to an option, not recommendation. Concerns: marginal benefit, significant complications (infection, GI bleed, hyperglycaemia), flawed subgroup analyses in NASCIS trials, failure to replicate in other studies. The AOSpine guideline (2017) suggests against routine use.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997; subsequent practice change",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"How did tirilazad perform in NASCIS 3 compared with methylprednisolone?",a:"48h tirilazad produced motor recovery equivalent to 24h methylprednisolone (not superior). It did not match 48h methylprednisolone in the 3–8 hour subgroup. Conclusion: tirilazad (a lipid peroxidation inhibitor) was not more effective than standard-duration methylprednisolone.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.4–6",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{q:"Where did most neurological recovery occur in NASCIS 3?",a:"85–90% of motor recovery occurred below the lesion level (long tract recovery), not at the injury level (segmental recovery). This indicates that methylprednisolone's effect was primarily on preserving long spinal cord tracts rather than nerve root function at the injury zone.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.6",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 25-year-old diver has T4 complete paraplegia but preserved perianal sensation and voluntary anal contraction. ASIA grade?",opts:["A. ASIA A","B. ASIA B","C. ASIA C","D. ASIA D","E. ASIA E"],ans:1,exp:"Preserved perianal sensation = sacral sparing = incomplete injury = ASIA B (sensory only). ASIA A requires NO sacral sparing. This distinction has major prognostic significance.",ref:"ASIA classification"},
{stem:"An elderly patient falls and develops disproportionate arm weakness > leg weakness with cervical pain. Most likely spinal cord syndrome?",opts:["A. Brown-Séquard syndrome","B. Anterior cord syndrome","C. Central cord syndrome","D. Posterior cord syndrome","E. Cauda equina syndrome"],ans:2,exp:"Central cord syndrome: arms weaker than legs, common in elderly with cervical spondylosis + hyperextension injury. The central corticospinal fibres (arms) are preferentially injured.",ref:"claude — incomplete cord syndromes",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A patient with acute SCI receives a methylprednisolone bolus 5 hours after injury. According to NASCIS 3, what is the recommended maintenance duration?",opts:["A. No maintenance needed after bolus","B. 24 hours","C. 48 hours","D. 72 hours","E. 7 days"],ans:2,exp:"NASCIS 3: if methylprednisolone started 3–8 hours post-injury, maintain for 48 hours (significantly better motor recovery vs 24h, P=.01 at 6 months). If started <3 hours, 24 hours is sufficient. Note: routine use is now widely abandoned.",ref:"NASCIS 3, Bracken 1997, p.1",src_id:"k-nascis3-1997",korky:true},
{stem:"A 22-year-old sustains a right-sided stab wound to the thoracic spinal cord at T5. Examination below the injury reveals: right leg increased tone and upgoing plantar, absent right joint position sense and vibration, but absent pin-prick and temperature sensation on the LEFT. Which statement CORRECTLY describes Brown-Séquard syndrome?",opts:["A. Contralateral loss of motor function and proprioception; ipsilateral loss of pain and temperature","B. Ipsilateral loss of motor function and proprioception; contralateral loss of pain and temperature","C. Ipsilateral loss of all motor and sensory modalities below the injury","D. Bilateral loss of pain and temperature with preserved motor function — central cord pattern","E. Bilateral symmetrical weakness with saddle anaesthesia — cauda equina pattern"],ans:1,exp:"Brown-Séquard (hemicord) syndrome: the corticospinal tract and dorsal columns travel IPSILATERALLY throughout the cord and decussate in the brainstem — so cord hemisection causes ipsilateral motor and proprioception/vibration loss. The spinothalamic tract decussates within 1–2 segments of cord entry — so cord hemisection causes CONTRALATERAL pain and temperature loss. This case (right cord injury) shows right motor/proprioception loss + left pain/temperature loss — the hallmark. Option A reverses the laterality and is the classic exam error. Best prognosis of all incomplete cord syndromes.",ref:"Bank, p.11",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old diver presents after a flexion-distraction neck injury. CT shows bilateral pedicle fractures of C2 with anterior displacement of C2 on C3 of 3.5 mm and a C2–3 disc space widening of 2 mm. He has no neurological deficit. Which fracture classification and management apply?",opts:["A. Hangman fracture type I (Levine-Edwards) — ≤3 mm displacement, no angulation, intact C2–3 disc; treat with rigid cervical collar","B. Hangman fracture type II — >3 mm displacement AND significant angulation; disrupted C2–3 disc; treat with halo-vest immobilisation for 3 months (or ACDF for disc disruption)","C. Hangman fracture type III — bilateral facet dislocation at C2–3 with complete ligamentous disruption; requires surgical reduction and fusion","D. Jefferson fracture — ring-of-C1 burst fracture; treated with halo-vest","E. Os odontoideum — chronic dens anomaly requiring atlantoaxial fusion"],ans:1,exp:"Hangman fracture (traumatic spondylolisthesis of C2): traumatic bilateral pedicle/pars fractures of C2. Levine-Edwards classification: Type I (<3 mm displacement, no significant angulation, intact disc) — stable, rigid collar. Type II (>3 mm displacement, significant angulation, C2–3 disc disruption) — unstable; halo vest or surgical stabilisation (ACDF C2–3 or posterior C1–3 fusion). Type IIA (severe angulation, minimal displacement — flexion-distraction mechanism) — DO NOT apply traction (worsens); halo in extension. Type III (bilateral C2–3 facet dislocation) — most unstable; surgical reduction and fusion. This patient has >3mm displacement + disc widening = Type II.",ref:"claude — Hangman fracture classification and management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 75-year-old falls and sustains an odontoid (dens) fracture. CT shows a transverse fracture through the base of the dens (at the junction with the C2 body), with 4 mm posterior displacement. Which fracture type is this, and what management is associated with the highest risk of non-union?",opts:["A. Type I dens fracture — oblique fracture of the dens tip; stable; treated with collar","B. Type II dens fracture — fracture at the base of the dens, with the poorest blood supply and highest non-union rate (up to 40–50% in elderly); surgical stabilisation often required (anterior screw or C1–C2 fusion)","C. Type III dens fracture — fracture extends into the C2 body; good cancellous bone healing with halo or collar","D. Type IV — comminuted C2 body fracture; non-union uncommon","E. Atlantoaxial instability without fracture — MRI for ligamentous injury"],ans:1,exp:"Anderson and D'Alonzo dens fracture classification: Type I: oblique tip fracture — stable, rare, benign; collar treatment. Type II: fracture at the dens-body junction — HIGHEST non-union risk (avascular zone, poor trabecular bone; non-union rate 30–50% in elderly). Type III: fracture line enters the C2 cancellous body — better blood supply; lower non-union; halo vest or collar often sufficient. Type II in elderly patients (>65, >4 mm displacement, posterior displacement, pre-existing osteoporosis) carries high mortality from halo complications and non-union — surgical options: anterior odontoid screw (preserves rotation) or posterior C1–C2 fusion (higher fusion rate, sacrifices rotation).",ref:"claude — odontoid fracture classification and management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 25-year-old sustains a complete C6 cervical spinal cord injury in a road traffic accident. Twelve hours later, the patient develops bradycardia (HR 38 bpm) and hypotension (BP 80/55 mmHg) despite adequate fluid resuscitation. Temperature is 36.2°C and there is flaccid tone below C6. What is the diagnosis and mechanism?",opts:["A. Neurogenic shock — loss of descending sympathetic control (above T6) causes peripheral vasodilation and unopposed vagal tone; treat with IV atropine for bradycardia and vasopressors (noradrenaline/phenylephrine) for hypotension","B. Spinal shock — transient loss of all spinal cord function below the injury including reflexes; bradycardia is from vagal dominance","C. Hypovolaemic shock — haemorrhage must be excluded; haemodynamic instability is never from spinal cord injury alone","D. Anaphylaxis — IV adrenaline is the first-line treatment","E. Cardiogenic shock — C6 injury causes direct myocardial dysfunction"],ans:0,exp:"Neurogenic shock: high cervical/thoracic SCI (above T6) disrupts the descending sympathetic pathways (T1–L2 lateral horn → superior cervical ganglion). Loss of sympathetic tone causes: (1) peripheral vasodilation → hypotension; (2) unopposed vagal parasympathetic tone → bradycardia. This persists for days–weeks. Treatment: vasopressors (phenylephrine or noradrenaline to maintain MAP ≥85 mmHg for SCI); atropine/glycopyrrolate for symptomatic bradycardia; temporary pacemaker for refractory bradycardia. Note: SPINAL SHOCK is distinct — it refers to the transient loss of ALL reflex activity below the injury level (flaccidity, areflexia, loss of bladder/bowel reflexes), which resolves as the spinal cord recovers (bulbocavernosus reflex return = end of spinal shock).",ref:"claude — neurogenic shock vs spinal shock",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 30-year-old has a complete spinal cord injury at T10. He is being discharged with bladder management instructions. Which statement about long-term bladder management in complete upper motor neuron (UMN) SCI below T6 is correct?",opts:["A. Indwelling urethral catheter is the preferred long-term option — cleanest method and lowest UTI risk","B. Clean intermittent self-catheterisation (CISC) every 4–6 hours is the gold standard — lower UTI rate than indwelling catheter; a parasympathomimetic agent (e.g. oxybutynin) may be added to reduce detrusor overactivity","C. Voiding by suprapubic tapping (Credé manoeuvre) is sufficient — avoids catheterisation entirely","D. Catheterisation is not necessary — T10 injury spares the sacral micturition centre; normal bladder function returns","E. Surgical bladder augmentation is required within 6 months"],ans:1,exp:"In complete UMN SCI (above sacral cord, T10 in this case), the bladder becomes hyperreflexic (spastic detrusor) with detrusor-sphincter dyssynergia (DSD) — the external sphincter contracts simultaneously with the detrusor. Clean intermittent self-catheterisation (CISC) every 4–6 hours is the gold standard: lower UTI rates than indwelling catheter, lower bladder cancer risk, preserves bladder compliance. Anticholinergics (oxybutynin, tolterodine) or botulinum toxin intravesical injection reduce detrusor overactivity/pressure. The Credé manoeuvre risks vesico-ureteric reflux from high intravesical pressure in DSD. Indwelling catheters cause recurrent UTI, bladder neck erosion, and bladder cancer.",ref:"claude — SCI bladder management / CISC",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 40-year-old with ankylosing spondylitis falls from standing height and complains of new neck pain. Neurological examination is initially normal. Cervical X-ray appears unremarkable. Which statement about spinal fractures in ankylosing spondylitis is correct?",opts:["A. Normal X-ray in AS excludes a significant fracture — no further imaging is needed","B. Fractures in AS occur through the ankylosed (bamboo) spine, typically as hyperextension-distraction (3-column) injuries; they are highly unstable and associated with high rates of neurological deterioration; MRI or CT is mandatory","C. AS fractures are stable because the fused spine prevents displacement","D. Conservative management with a collar is appropriate for most AS spinal fractures","E. AS fractures exclusively occur in the cervical spine"],ans:1,exp:"Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) creates a rigid 'bamboo spine' — a long lever arm with fused facets, ossified ligaments, and absent disc mobility. Fractures in AS are: (1) unstable 3-column injuries (the entire ossified segment fractures transversely, usually via hyperextension); (2) often not visible on plain X-ray due to ossification masking fracture lines; (3) high risk of epidural haematoma and delayed neurological deterioration — the rigid spine prevents any deformation, so even small displacement causes cord compression. A normal X-ray does NOT exclude fracture. CT and/or MRI are mandatory. Management is almost always surgical (posterior long-segment fixation — short fixation inadequate in a rigid lever). The patient must be kept immobilised pending imaging.",ref:"claude — ankylosing spondylitis fracture / instability",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A surgeon is planning C1–C2 posterior fixation for atlantoaxial instability. They must choose between the Harms technique (C1 lateral mass screws + C2 pedicle screws) and the Magerl technique (transarticular C1–C2 screws). Which statement about these techniques is correct?",opts:["A. The Magerl technique avoids the vertebral artery because the screw trajectory is entirely lateral","B. The Harms technique requires pre-operative reduction before screw placement, whereas Magerl can be placed in situ","C. The Magerl transarticular technique requires pre-operative assessment of the vertebral artery course (CT angiography); a high-riding vertebral artery (absent or narrow isthmus at C2) is a contraindication to Magerl but not Harms; Harms allows screw placement regardless of VA anatomy","D. The Harms technique provides inferior biomechanical stability compared to Magerl","E. Magerl technique is preferred in all patients as it uses fewer screws"],ans:2,exp:"Magerl transarticular screws pass from C2 posterior cortex through the isthmus (pars) of C2, across the C1–C2 joint, and into the C1 lateral mass — the screw path passes adjacent to the vertebral artery in the C2 isthmus. A high-riding vertebral artery (absent or narrow bony isthmus) is a contraindication to Magerl on that side (VA injury risk). Harms technique: C1 lateral mass screws and C2 pedicle screws are placed separately — more flexible in VA anomaly, allows independent placement, does not require perfect reduction before screw insertion. Biomechanically, both provide excellent stability. Pre-operative CT/CTA is mandatory for both techniques.",ref:"claude — Harms vs Magerl atlantoaxial fixation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"degenerative-spine":{src:"Standard neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What are the clinical features of cauda equina syndrome (CES) and why is it a surgical emergency?",a:"Bilateral leg weakness; saddle anaesthesia (perianal/perineal/genitalia); bladder dysfunction (retention or incontinence); bowel dysfunction; sexual dysfunction. Emergency decompression required — delay causes permanent sphincter and sexual dysfunction.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the difference between CES-R (with retention) and CES-I (incomplete)?",a:"CES-R (retention): painless urinary retention with overflow — worst prognosis, surgery most urgent. CES-I (incomplete): impaired bladder function but not complete retention — still urgent but slightly better prognosis with surgery.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What distinguishes neurogenic from vascular claudication?",a:"Neurogenic (spinal stenosis): pain/weakness on walking worse going downhill; relieved by flexion (sitting, leaning forward); may walk further if bent. Vascular: calf pain, relieved by rest alone (standing), absent pulses, trophic skin changes, ABI <0.9.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the MRI features of cervical myelopathy that indicate surgical urgency?",a:"Cord compression with T2 signal change (myelomalacia) indicates intrinsic cord damage. Combined with clinical myelopathy (hyperreflexia, Lhermitte's, gait disturbance, fine motor impairment) = strong indication for decompression.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What surgical options exist for degenerative cervical spine disease?",a:"Anterior cervical discectomy and fusion (ACDF) — most common, for radiculopathy or single/two-level disease; posterior cervical laminectomy ± fusion; cervical disc arthroplasty (disc replacement); laminoplasty (preserves motion, for multilevel myelopathy).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the common causes of failed back surgery syndrome?",a:"Recurrent disc herniation; epidural fibrosis; adjacent segment disease; wrong level operated; missed diagnosis; spinal instability; psychological factors. Management: pain clinic, repeat imaging, consider further surgery only for structural cause.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What was the SPORT trial for disc herniation?",a:"Spine Patient Outcomes Research Trial (Weinstein 2006, JAMA). RCT of 501 patients with imaging-confirmed lumbar disc herniation + persistent radiculopathy ≥6 weeks. Standard open discectomy vs nonoperative care (PT, NSAIDs, injections, counselling). 13 US spine centres. Mean age 42, 42% women.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.2",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What were the inclusion criteria for SPORT disc herniation?",a:"Age ≥18; imaging-confirmed disc herniation (MRI 97%, CT 3%) at level/side matching clinical symptoms; persistent radiculopathy ≥6 weeks; radicular pain below knee (lower lumbar) or anterior thigh (upper lumbar); positive SLR (30-70°) or femoral tension sign, or neurological deficit (asymmetric reflex, dermatomal sensory loss, myotomal weakness). All were surgical candidates.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.3",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What was the key problem with the SPORT trial?",a:"Massive treatment crossover in both directions: by 2 years, only 60% of patients randomised to surgery actually had surgery, and 45% randomised to nonoperative care crossed over to surgery. This severely undermined the intent-to-treat analysis and biased results toward the null.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.2, p.8",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What were the intent-to-treat results of SPORT disc herniation?",a:"Both groups improved substantially over 2 years. Treatment effects consistently favoured surgery for all primary outcomes (SF-36, ODI) but were SMALL and NOT statistically significant. Sciatica bothersomeness was significantly better with surgery (p=0.003). Self-rated progress also favoured surgery (p=0.04).",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.6-8, Table 5",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What were the as-treated results of SPORT disc herniation?",a:"Strong, statistically significant advantages for surgery at ALL time points through 2 years. At 1 year: SF-36 bodily pain +15.0 (95% CI 10.9-19.2), physical function +17.5 (13.6-21.5), ODI -15.0 (-18.3 to -11.7). The as-treated analysis better reflects the true benefit of surgery, given the massive crossover.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.8",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What were the surgical complications in SPORT disc herniation?",a:"Median operative time 75 min, blood loss 49.5 mL. No perioperative deaths. Dural tear 4%, no intraoperative complications in 95%. Postoperative complications in 5% (superficial wound infection 2%). Reoperation 4% at 1 year, 5% at 2 years (>50% for recurrent herniation at same level). 84% stayed 1 night, 27% same-day.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.6, Table 3",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What herniation levels and types were seen in SPORT?",a:"L5-S1: 59%. L4-5: 35%. L2-3/L3-4: 7%. Herniation types: extruded 67%, protruding 25%, sequestered 7%. Posterolateral location in ~80%. 73% had neurological deficit at baseline (41% reflex, 45% sensory, 42% motor).",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.4, Table 1",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What nonoperative treatments were used in SPORT?",a:"Education/counselling 93%, NSAIDs 61%, injections (including epidural steroids) 56%, opioids 46%, active PT 44%, COX-2 inhibitors 31%, other medical devices 32%, chiropractor 11%. Activity restriction in 29%. Treatment was individualised — no fixed protocol.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.5, Table 2",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{q:"What is the key clinical takeaway from SPORT for lumbar disc herniation?",a:"Both surgery and nonoperative care are effective — most patients improve substantially. Surgery provides faster and greater improvement especially for leg pain/sciatica. The favourable natural history means conservative management is reasonable. No evidence of harm from either approach. No patients developed cauda equina syndrome.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.8",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 68-year-old has sudden bilateral leg weakness and urinary retention for 2 hours. MRI shows large central L4/5 disc prolapse compressing cauda equina. Management?",opts:["A. Conservative management","B. Urgent surgical decompression","C. High-dose IV steroids","D. MRI monitoring every 6 hours","E. Physiotherapy assessment first"],ans:1,exp:"CES with urinary retention (CES-R) = neurosurgical emergency requiring urgent decompression. Delay beyond hours/days causes permanent bladder, bowel, and sexual dysfunction.",ref:"claude — cauda equina syndrome",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 65-year-old has back and leg pain on walking 200m, relieved by sitting and leaning forward. Worse going downhill. Pedal pulses present. Most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Peripheral arterial disease","B. Neurogenic claudication from lumbar spinal stenosis","C. L4/5 disc prolapse","D. Piriformis syndrome","E. Sacroiliac joint dysfunction"],ans:1,exp:"Neurogenic claudication: pain on walking, worse downhill (extension narrows canal), relieved by flexion (sitting/bending). Preserved pulses exclude vascular claudication. Caused by lumbar spinal stenosis.",ref:"claude — spinal stenosis",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"In the SPORT trial for lumbar disc herniation, the intent-to-treat analysis showed no significant difference for primary outcomes. Why?",opts:["A. Surgery was truly no better than conservative care","B. The sample size was too small","C. Massive treatment crossover (45% of non-op crossed to surgery) biased toward the null","D. The follow-up period was too short","E. The outcome measures were invalid"],ans:2,exp:"SPORT had massive crossover: 45% of the nonoperative group had surgery by 2 years, and only 60% of the surgery group had surgery. This mixing of treatments biases intent-to-treat toward the null. The as-treated analysis showed strong, significant advantages for surgery.",ref:"SPORT, Weinstein 2006, p.2, p.8",src_id:"k-sport-2006",korky:true},
{stem:"A 70-year-old presents with progressive hand clumsiness, leg stiffness, and difficulty with fine motor tasks over 18 months. On examination: hyperreflexia in all four limbs, bilateral Hoffman sign, upgoing plantars, marked hand intrinsic wasting, and tongue fasciculations. Jaw jerk is brisk. Sensation is intact throughout. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Cervical spondylotic myelopathy (CSM)","B. Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS)","C. Multiple sclerosis","D. Subacute combined degeneration of the cord","E. Thoracic spinal cord tumour"],ans:1,exp:"This is ALS, not CSM. The critical distinguishing features: (1) Brisk JAW JERK — localises upper motor neuron pathology above the foramen magnum, which excludes CSM (which affects below the foramen magnum). (2) TONGUE fasciculations = LMN involvement of the tongue, not seen in CSM. (3) ABSENT sensory changes — ALS is a pure motor neuron disease; CSM typically causes hand numbness. (4) Extensive hand wasting with fasciculations across multiple levels. CSM produces LMN findings limited to 1–2 cord segments. The triad of ALS: atrophic weakness of hands/forearms (LMN) + LE spasticity (UMN) + diffuse hyperreflexia. Jaw jerk is the key localiser.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1301",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 63-year-old with progressive gait disturbance and hand clumsiness is found to have cervical spondylotic myelopathy on MRI at C3–6. mJOA score (Benzel) is 11 (severe). He is medically fit for surgery. What is the recommended management?",opts:["A. Conservative: rigid cervical collar, anti-inflammatories, low-risk activities for 3 years","B. Surgical decompression — severe myelopathy should be treated operatively","C. Epidural steroid injection to reduce cord inflammation","D. Observation only — CSM often stabilises spontaneously","E. Repeat MRI in 3 months before deciding"],ans:1,exp:"mJOA ≤11 = severe CSM (Benzel classification: mild ≥15, moderate 12–14, severe ≤11). Severe myelopathy is an indication for surgical decompression — benefits are maintained at 5 and 15 years post-op (Level D Class III). Surgery has a limited window: 48% improvement if operated within 1 year of onset vs only 16% after 1 year. Once severe myelopathy is established, complete remission almost never occurs, but surgery can halt progression. Conservative management (collar, anti-inflammatories) is only offered as an alternative to surgery for MILD myelopathy (mJOA >12) in the short-term.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1303–1304",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old with cervical spondylotic myelopathy at C3–7 (5 levels) with preserved cervical lordosis is being considered for surgical decompression. Which approach is most appropriate as the initial procedure?",opts:["A. Anterior cervical discectomy and fusion (ACDF) at all 5 levels","B. Anterior corpectomy at C3–7","C. Posterior cervical laminectomy (with or without fusion)","D. Cervical disc arthroplasty at all 5 levels","E. Observation — 5-level disease is inoperable"],ans:2,exp:"Disease over ≥3 levels (especially 4–5 levels) is a standard indication for the POSTERIOR approach (laminectomy ± fusion, or laminoplasty). While anterior approaches (ACDF/corpectomy) can occasionally treat up to 4 levels, 5-level anterior surgery carries high pseudarthrosis and graft complication rates. The posterior approach is also preferred when: congenital stenosis persists after anterior decompression; primary posterior pathology (ligamentum flavum infolding); and some OPLL cases. Lordosis is PRESERVED here — kyphosis contraindicates posterior laminectomy (the cord won't migrate away from anterior compression). Note: laminectomy without fusion has a 14–47% risk of post-op kyphotic deformity.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1304",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old undergoes posterior cervical laminectomy (C3–6) for CSM. Three days later she develops new right deltoid weakness (MRC 3/5), with mild right shoulder pain, but no other neurological change and no worsening of myelopathy. What is the most likely diagnosis and management?",opts:["A. Cord ischaemia — urgent MRI and surgical re-exploration","B. C5 nerve root palsy — expectant management; most resolve spontaneously","C. New disc herniation at C4/5 — urgent revision discectomy","D. Epidural haematoma — urgent evacuation","E. Wound infection with nerve root involvement — antibiotics and washout"],ans:1,exp:"Post-operative C5 palsy: new deltoid weakness (±biceps) appearing 1–3 days after decompressive cervical surgery, without worsening of baseline myelopathy. Pooled prevalence ~6% after cervical decompression. Aetiology: likely tethering/traction on the C5 nerve root as the cord migrates posteriorly after decompression. Risk factor: C4–5 foraminal diameter <2mm on pre-op axial CT. Management: expectant — physio to prevent contracture, EMG to assess reinnervation. Prognosis: generally good; 75% resolve after anterior approach, 89% after posterior. 48% of mild cases resolve within 3 months. Epidural haematoma causes worsening of myelopathy, not isolated deltoid weakness.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1306–1307",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{stem:"A 60-year-old has an MRI for progressive CSM. T2-weighted sagittal MRI shows a single-level focus of hyperintensity within the spinal cord. T1-weighted MRI at the same level shows corresponding hypointensity. What is the prognostic significance?",opts:["A. Good prognostic sign — T2 hyperintensity alone indicates reversible oedema","B. Poor prognostic sign — combined T2 hyperintensity with T1 hypointensity indicates cord necrosis/myelomalacia","C. No prognostic significance — this is a normal incidental finding","D. Indicates demyelinating disease rather than CSM","E. Indicates complete motor neuron death — surgery is futile"],ans:1,exp:"MRI findings correlating with POOR outcome in CSM (Class III evidence): (1) Multilevel T2 hyperintensity in cord parenchyma. (2) Single-level T2 hyperintensity WITH corresponding T1 hypointensity — this combination indicates cord necrosis/myelomalacia, not reversible oedema. (3) Cord atrophy (transverse area <45mm²). (4) 'Snake eyes' (two bilateral foci of T2 signal) on axial cuts — associated with cystic necrosis. In contrast, single-level T2 hyperintensity WITHOUT T1 changes has uncertain prognostic significance. These findings should inform consent for surgical decompression.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1302",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{stem:"A 52-year-old undergoes 3-level ACDF for CSM. The surgeon notes complete macroscopic removal of disc and osteophyte with endplate preparation and cage insertion, covered by an anterior plate. Per Simpson grading applied to cervical fusion, what is the adjacent segment disease (ASD) rate and timeframe relevant to consent?",opts:["A. ASD occurs in <1% of patients — not worth mentioning in consent","B. ~2.9% per year; approximately 25% develop symptomatic adjacent level changes within 10 years of ACDF","C. ASD is eliminated by multilevel fusion — only single-level fusions are at risk","D. 50% at 5 years — single most common late complication of ACDF","E. ASD only occurs at the level immediately adjacent to the fusion"],ans:1,exp:"Adjacent segment disease (ASD) after ACDF: degeneration at a motion segment adjacent to a previous fusion, manifesting as disc degeneration, stenosis, facet hypertrophy, scoliosis, or listhesis. Rate: 2.9% per year over 10 years of observation. Cumulative: approximately 25% of patients develop symptomatic adjacent level changes within 10 years. Natural progression of disease (not the fusion itself) accounts for a significant proportion. ASD rate was HIGHER with single-level fusion at C5–6 or C6–7 than multilevel fusion — the opposite of option C. Most radiographic ASD is asymptomatic.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1305",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old rugby player is referred for cervical spine assessment after a transient neurapraxia event. Lateral cervical X-ray is taken to assess canal diameter. The AP diameter of the vertebral body at C5 is 18mm; the AP diameter of the spinal canal at the same level is 13mm. What does the Pavlov ratio indicate?",opts:["A. Pavlov ratio 0.72 — below 0.8 threshold, sensitive for transient neurapraxia; poor positive predictive value for CSM","B. Pavlov ratio 0.72 — diagnostic of CSM and mandates surgical decompression","C. Pavlov ratio 1.38 — normal; no risk of canal stenosis","D. Pavlov ratio 0.72 — absolute contraindication to contact sport","E. Pavlov ratio is only valid on MRI, not plain X-ray"],ans:0,exp:"Pavlov ratio (Torg ratio) = AP canal diameter / AP vertebral body diameter at the same mid-VB level. Here: 13/18 = 0.72. Ratio <0.8 is SENSITIVE for transient neuropraxia (as seen in this case) — but has POOR POSITIVE PREDICTIVE VALUE for CSM. Many athletes with Pavlov <0.8 never develop CSM. It is a surrogate marker — MRI is needed to directly assess cord compression. CSM is rare when AP canal diameter >16mm on X-ray. Values ≤10mm are likely to be associated with myelopathy. This should be discussed as a risk factor for neuropraxia in contact sport, not a definitive contraindication.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1301–1302",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true},
{stem:"A 62-year-old with longstanding rheumatoid arthritis develops occipital headache, progressive difficulty walking, and bilateral hand paraesthesias. Examination shows Ranawat Class IIIA myelopathy. MRI reveals anterior atlantoaxial subluxation with C1–2 pannus compressing the cord. What do the Ranawat grades mean and what does IIIA imply for this patient?",opts:["A. Class I = no deficit; Class II = subjective weakness + hyperreflexia; Class III = objective weakness + long tract signs. IIIA = ambulatory — still a candidate for C1–2 fusion","B. Class I = mild; Class II = moderate; Class III = severe quadriplegia. IIIA = ambulatory deficits correctable with physiotherapy alone","C. Ranawat grading applies only to post-traumatic instability, not RA","D. Class IIIA = non-ambulatory — the priority is palliative care","E. Class IIIA requires transoral odontoidectomy before any posterior fusion"],ans:0,exp:"Ranawat classification of myelopathy in RA: Class I = no neural deficit; Class II = subjective weakness + hyperreflexia + dysaesthesias; Class III = objective weakness + long tract signs, subdivided as IIIA (ambulatory) and IIIB (quadriparetic and non-ambulatory). IIIA is ambulatory with objective findings — this patient has symptomatic AAS with myelopathy, which is an indication for surgical stabilisation (C1–2 fusion in most). The key point: once myelopathy is established it may be irreversible; the worse the myelopathy, the higher the risk of sudden death. IIIB carries the worst prognosis and the highest operative urgency.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1376",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In a patient with rheumatoid arthritis and atlantoaxial subluxation (AAS), which measurement most reliably predicts neurological deficit and recovery after surgery — the anterior atlantodental interval (ADI) or the posterior atlantodental interval (PADI)?",opts:["A. ADI — it measures the gap between atlas and odontoid and directly reflects spinal cord compression","B. PADI — it measures the residual space available for the cord and correlates with paralysis severity and surgical recovery","C. Both are equally predictive","D. Neither — MRI signal change is the only reliable predictor","E. ADI >3mm is diagnostic of spinal cord compression"],ans:1,exp:"The ADI only reflects instability of the C1–2 joint; it does NOT correlate with risk of neurological injury or progression from asymptomatic to symptomatic AAS. The PADI (posterior atlantodental interval) = space available for the cord; it correlates with presence and severity of paralysis. PADI ≤14mm is proposed as an indication for surgical stabilisation. Critically: patients with AAS-related paralysis showed NO recovery if pre-op PADI was <10mm. Since pannus also occupies the residual space, PADI underestimates available cord space — MRI is the optimal test for direct cord compression assessment.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1378",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old with RA has AAS with ADI 9mm on flexion X-ray and Ranawat Class II myelopathy. MRI shows reducible anterior subluxation (reduces partially on extension). CT confirms significant C1 bony erosion. After halo traction, the subluxation reduces. What is the definitive surgical plan?",opts:["A. Transoral odontoidectomy first, then maintain in traction awaiting posterior fusion","B. Posterior C1–2 fusion (Magerl or Goel-Harms technique) — reducible AAS with myelopathy is the standard indication","C. Anterior cervical discectomy at C1–2 level","D. Conservative management — collar and anti-inflammatories, as surgical mortality is prohibitive","E. Occipitocervical fusion to C5 mandatory for all RA-related AAS"],ans:1,exp:"Reducible AAS with symptomatic myelopathy (Ranawat ≥II): almost all require surgical treatment — C1–2 fusion in most cases. Since the subluxation reduces with traction, posterior stabilisation alone (C1–2 arthrodesis) is appropriate. Occipitocervical fusion (occiput-C2) is used when decompression is combined with posterior C1 laminectomy. Irreducible cases or those with significant pannus not regressing after fusion may need transoral odontoidectomy, but posterior stabilisation is done FIRST to allow some patients to avoid the anterior operation. Note: operative mortality in RA is 5–15% due to systemic multi-organ involvement.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1379",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with RA undergoes posterior C1–2 fusion for atlantoaxial subluxation. Pre-operatively, MRI showed a significant C1–2 pannus compressing the anterior cord. Post-operatively, the surgeon counsels the patient that the pannus may partially regress. What can accelerate pannus regression after fusion?",opts:["A. High-dose corticosteroids for 6 months post-op","B. TNF-α inhibitors such as etanercept or adalimumab, combined with surgical fusion","C. Transoral odontoidectomy is mandatory to directly remove pannus","D. Pannus never regresses — this is a permanent finding once present","E. Aspirin and NSAIDs — they reduce synovial inflammation"],ans:1,exp:"Pannus (chronic inflammatory granulation tissue around the odontoid) often RECEDES after surgical fusion of C1–2. This regression may be enhanced with TNF-α inhibitors (e.g., etanercept [Enbrel], adalimumab [Humira]) or monoclonal antibodies against TNF-α (e.g., infliximab [Remicade]). This is important because posterior fusion alone may provide sufficient decompression in some cases — avoiding the need for transoral odontoidectomy. Posterior stabilisation is therefore done first; odontoidectomy is reserved for irreducible cases or persistent significant cord compression from pannus that does not regress.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1378",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 67-year-old with severe RA develops progressive occipital headache, diplopia, dysarthria, and lower cranial nerve dysfunction. MRI shows upward migration of the odontoid into the foramen magnum with cervicomedullary compression. CT confirms extensive C1 lateral mass erosion. The cervicomedullary angle on MRI is 128°. What is the diagnosis and initial management?",opts:["A. Anterior atlantoaxial subluxation — treat with C1–2 fusion alone","B. Basilar impression (cranial settling) in RA — attempt cervical traction first; surgical plan depends on reducibility","C. Occipital condyle fracture — immobilise in halo vest","D. Chiari malformation type I — posterior fossa decompression","E. Vertebral artery dissection — anticoagulation"],ans:1,exp:"Basilar impression (BI) in RA: erosive changes of C1 lateral masses → C1 telescopes onto C2 → upward migration of the odontoid, compressing the pons and medulla. Signs: lower cranial nerve dysfunction, downbeat nystagmus, diplopia, INO, sleep apnoea, spastic quadriparesis. Cervicomedullary angle (CMA) <135° correlates with cervicomedullary compression (normal 135–170°). Management: attempt cervical traction (Gardner-Wells tongs, 7–15lbs over several weeks). Reducible cases: posterior occipitocervical fusion ± C1 decompressive laminectomy. Irreducible cases: transoral odontoidectomy required (may perform posterior fusion first). Note: ADI measurements based on odontoid tip are unreliable in RA due to erosion — use Clark station, Redlund-Johnell, or Ranawat criteria.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1379–1380",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old Japanese man presents with progressive bilateral hand paraesthesias and leg stiffness. MRI cervical spine shows a T2-hypointense band anterior to the spinal cord at C3–6, compressing the cord. CT confirms dense calcification of the posterior longitudinal ligament at two levels. He has Nurick grade 3 disability (difficulty walking, unable to work full time). Which statement about management is most accurate?",opts:["A. Conservative management is preferred — OPLL is self-limiting and surgery is rarely needed","B. Surgery provides the greatest benefit in moderate myelopathy (Nurick 3–4); anterior approach with corpectomy is generally favoured","C. Surgery is most effective for severe myelopathy (Nurick 5); laminoplasty is the approach of choice","D. Posterior laminectomy alone is first-line; anterior approach is contraindicated in OPLL","E. OPLL requires urgent surgery within 24 hours regardless of severity"],ans:1,exp:"OPLL management by Nurick grade: (1) Nurick 1–2 (mild): no statistically significant benefit of surgery over conservative care. (2) Nurick 3–4 (moderate): surgery provides a statistically significant reduction in deterioration — this is the group that benefits most. (3) Nurick 5 (severe/complete quadriplegia): surgery is ineffective and carries disproportionate risk. Anterior approach (corpectomy + strut graft ± plate) is generally favoured, though posterior laminectomy or laminoplasty may be acceptable. Key surgical caution: OPLL frequently extends into the dura — risk of dural tear and CSF leak 16–25% with anterior approach; avoid distraction until cord is decompressed.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1371–1372",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 70-year-old man describes bilateral buttock and thigh pain that comes on after walking two blocks. He leans forward on a shopping trolley when walking. Sitting down relieves his pain but it takes 10–15 minutes. His pain varies considerably day-to-day. Pedal pulses are palpable bilaterally. ABI is 1.0. What is the most likely diagnosis and the key clinical feature that distinguishes it from vascular claudication?",opts:["A. Peripheral arterial disease — ABI <0.9 is diagnostic","B. Neurogenic claudication from lumbar spinal stenosis — relief requires positional change (sitting/flexion), not just rest; pain varies day-to-day","C. L4/5 disc herniation causing acute radiculopathy — pain on Valsalva","D. Bilateral trochanteric bursitis — pain worse on lying on affected side","E. Diabetic neuropathy — non-positional burning pain"],ans:1,exp:"Neurogenic claudication (NC): pain provoked by standing or walking; relieved by sitting, squatting, or flexing at the waist (positions that increase canal diameter by reducing ligamentum flavum infolding). Key distinguishing features from vascular claudication: (1) Relief requires POSITION change — standing and resting is usually NOT sufficient (unlike vascular, where rest alone rapidly relieves). (2) Variable day-to-day (62% of NC patients vs 12% of vascular). (3) Shopping cart sign — patients walk further leaning forward. (4) Bicycle well tolerated (waist flexion). (5) Normal pulses and ABI. (6) Valsalva does NOT exacerbate NC. Vascular claudication: immediate relief with rest regardless of position; reliably reproduced at a fixed walking distance.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1328–1332",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old woman presents with 6 months of neurogenic claudication and bilateral leg pain worse going downhill. MRI shows Grade I degenerative spondylolisthesis at L4–5 (anterolisthesis 20%) with severe central canal stenosis. The listhesis moves 4mm on flexion-extension views. What is the recommended surgical management?",opts:["A. Laminectomy alone — fusion is not needed for Grade I listhesis","B. Laminectomy without fusion — interspinous spacer can be added if needed","C. Decompressive laminectomy with posterolateral fusion — evidence supports fusion for stenosis with degenerative spondylolisthesis requiring decompression","D. ALIF alone — indirect decompression is sufficient for Grade I listhesis","E. Conservative management only — surgery is not indicated for Grade I"],ans:2,exp:"Level II evidence (SPORT lumbar stenosis, Herkowitz 1991): posterolateral fusion is recommended for patients with stenosis AND associated degenerative spondylolisthesis who require decompression. The presence of listhesis (even Grade I) plus demonstrated mobility on dynamic X-rays (4mm movement = instability) favours adding fusion to decompression. Without fusion, Grade I spondylolisthesis has a 38% reoperation rate in some series when disc height >6.5mm or facet angles >50° or motion >1.25mm. Pedicle screw instrumentation should be considered when pre-op instability or kyphosis is present or iatrogenic instability is anticipated.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1337–1344",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 67-year-old man undergoes posterior lumbar laminectomy at L3–4 and L4–5 for severe neurogenic claudication with no spondylolisthesis. You are consenting him. Which complication rate should you specifically mention?",opts:["A. Mortality 5%; deep infection 15%; dural tear 30%","B. Mortality 0.32%; dural tear 0.32–13%; deep infection 5.9%; approximately 15% will need fusion at a later date","C. Mortality 2%; dural tear 1%; deep infection 1%; no significant risk of instability","D. 50% chance of requiring revision surgery within 5 years","E. Mortality 0.32%; permanent neurological deficit in 30%; fusion required in 50%"],ans:1,exp:"Lumbar laminectomy outcome data: in-hospital mortality 0.32%; unintended durotomy (dural tear) 0.32–13% (wide range depending on series and complexity); deep infection 5.9%; superficial infection 2.3%; DVT 2.8%. Approximately 15% of patients will need a fusion at a later date (Greenberg consent template). Surgery is most likely to relieve leg pain and improve walking tolerance — back pain alone responds less well. At 5-year follow-up, 27% have symptom recurrence (30% from re-stenosis at operated level, 30% from adjacent segment). Overall good/excellent outcomes in ~64–70% at 1 year.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1340, 1348",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with known OPLL is scheduled for anterior cervical corpectomy. What pre-operative assessment and intraoperative precaution is specifically indicated because of their OPLL diagnosis?",opts:["A. Pre-op echocardiogram; avoid prone positioning","B. Pre-op blood glucose testing (50% have impaired glucose tolerance); video laryngoscopy for intubation to avoid hyperextension; dural tear risk 16–25%","C. Pre-op angiogram; heparin infusion during surgery","D. No special precautions beyond standard anterior cervical surgery","E. Pre-op lumbar drain to protect against CSF leak"],ans:1,exp:"OPLL-specific pre-op considerations: (1) 50% of patients with OPLL have impaired glucose tolerance — check blood glucose pre-op, with attendant anaesthetic and wound-healing implications. (2) Respiratory compromise may occur from ossification of costo-transverse and costo-vertebral ligaments — cardiorespiratory assessment essential. (3) Intubation: use video laryngoscopy (or awake nasotracheal intubation as second choice) — avoid neck hyperextension which can cause spinal cord injury against the OPLL. (4) Dural tear: OPLL often fuses to and invades the dura — anterior decompression carries 16–25% risk of CSF leak. The decision to remove all bone vs leave a thin rim adherent to dura is case-specific. Distraction must be avoided until after cord decompression.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1372",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 49-year-old woman presents with severe low back pain 3 weeks after an L4/5 microdiscectomy. She had initial pain relief then progressive worsening with paraspinal spasm. She is afebrile. ESR is 68 mm/hr and CRP is 11 mg/dl. CT-guided disc biopsy is sent for culture. Which organism accounts for the majority of positive cultures in post-operative discitis?",opts:["A. Staphylococcus epidermidis","B. Streptococcus viridans","C. Staphylococcus aureus","D. Escherichia coli","E. Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],ans:2,exp:"S. aureus accounts for ≈60% of positive cultures in post-operative discitis. Onset is typically 1–4 weeks post-op (80% present by 3 weeks). Importantly, only 10–12% of post-op discitis cases have an associated wound infection — absence of wound signs does not exclude the diagnosis. ESR >20 mm/hr in 96% of cases. WBC is elevated in only 18–30%. Fever present in only 30–50%. Initial empiric treatment: IV anti-staphylococcal antibiotics (vancomycin ± PO rifampicin) + cefepime or meropenem.",ref:"Greenberg, p.380",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old man undergoes L5/S1 microdiscectomy. His post-operative CRP is measured serially: day 3, it peaks at 4.9 mg/dl; by day 10 it is 2.2 mg/dl; on day 18 it has risen again to 10.1 mg/dl and he reports new, severe, diffuse back pain with paraspinal spasm, worsened by any movement. His wound looks clean. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Superficial wound infection","B. Recurrent disc herniation","C. Epidural haematoma","D. Post-operative discitis","E. Pulmonary embolism"],ans:3,exp:"CRP kinetics: after uncomplicated lumbar microdiscectomy, CRP normally peaks ≈day 2–3 (mean 4.6 ± 2.1 mg/dl) and returns to normal between days 5 and 14. A CRP that never decreases, or rises again after initial normalisation, is a strong indicator of post-operative discitis. The pattern of initial pain relief followed by severe back pain, paraspinal spasm, pain exacerbated by virtually any movement, and ESR/CRP that fails to normalise is the classic presentation. NB: 10–12% have associated wound infection; afebrile in up to 70%.",ref:"Greenberg, p.380–381",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 62-year-old man with type 2 diabetes presents with 10 days of progressive thoracic back pain, fever, rigors, and now bilateral leg weakness. MRI shows a posterior thoracic epidural collection from T4–T8 with cord compression. Blood cultures are sent. What is the most common causative organism in spinal epidural abscess (SEA)?",opts:["A. Streptococcus pneumoniae","B. Pseudomonas aeruginosa","C. Staphylococcus aureus","D. Escherichia coli","E. Mycobacterium tuberculosis"],ans:2,exp:"S. aureus is the most common organism in SEA (cultured in >50%), possibly due to its propensity to form abscesses, its ubiquity, and its ability to infect normal and immunocompromised hosts. Commonest risk factors: diabetes (32%), IV drug abuse (18%), chronic renal failure (12%), alcoholism (10%). Site distribution: thoracic ≈50%, lumbar 35%, cervical 15%; 82% are posterior to the cord. Average time from back pain to root symptoms: 3 days; to weakness: 4.5 days; to paraplegia: 24 hrs from weakness. Treatment: early surgical evacuation + antibiotics. Antibiotic-alone management is reserved for those with prohibitive operative risk, paralysis >3 days, or extensive multilevel involvement.",ref:"Greenberg, p.381–386",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 46-year-old man develops severe back pain 6 weeks after lumbar laminectomy. MRI with gadolinium is performed. Which combination of gadolinium-enhancement sites constitutes the triad strongly suggestive of post-operative discitis?",opts:["A. Epidural space, facet joints, and paraspinal soft tissue","B. Vertebral bone marrow, disc space, and posterior annulus fibrosus","C. Thecal sac rim, posterior longitudinal ligament, and disc space","D. Vertebral endplates only — enhancement elsewhere excludes discitis","E. Anterior longitudinal ligament, vertebral body, and epidural space"],ans:1,exp:"The MRI gadolinium-enhancement triad strongly suggestive of post-operative discitis: (1) vertebral bone marrow, (2) disc space, (3) posterior annulus fibrosus. All three together in a symptomatic patient are highly specific; some asymptomatic patients may show 1–2 findings but rarely all three. On T2WI: increased signal in disc and adjacent vertebral bodies (loss of intranuclear cleft). Plain X-ray changes appear on average 3 months post-op (range 1–8 months). CT-guided percutaneous biopsy should be performed if X-rays or MRI are suspicious; send for Gram stain, fungal stain, AFB stain, and aerobic/anaerobic/fungal/AFB cultures.",ref:"Greenberg, p.379",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 47-year-old woman has progressive thoracic myelopathy. MRI and CT confirm a calcified, broad-based central disc herniation at T10–11 compressing the cord. She is listed for open surgical discectomy via a transthoracic approach. On which side is the incision typically made, and why?",opts:["A. Right-sided, always — the aorta is on the left and the right gives better midline access","B. Left-sided for levels at or below the cardiophrenic angle — the inferior vena cava cannot be mobilised as easily as the aorta, so a left-sided approach is preferred for lower thoracic central discs","C. Approach from the side of the disc herniation — always right for a central disc","D. Either side — for a calcified disc the approach side is irrelevant","E. Always use a posterior midline laminectomy for calcified thoracic discs"],ans:1,exp:"For transthoracic (anterolateral) discectomy, the lateral herniation is approached from the MORE INVOLVED side. For CENTRAL discs at or below the cardiophrenic angle (lower thoracic spine, roughly below T5), LEFT-sided approach is preferred — the inferior vena cava is difficult to mobilise, whereas the aorta is more easily retracted. For UPPER thoracic midline lesions, some prefer right-side-up to avoid the artery of Adamkiewicz (which runs on the LEFT in 80%). Laminectomy alone is CONTRAINDICATED for midline/central calcified thoracic disc (high complication rate). 65% of thoracic discs requiring surgery are calcified. Peak incidence: T11–12 (26%). Post-op CXR always obtained regardless of intra-op air leak.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1271–1276",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During elective L4–5 microdiscectomy, the patient develops sudden profound hypotension (BP 65/40 mmHg, HR 130 bpm) while the surgeon is working in the disc space with a pituitary rongeur. The wound appears dry. What is the most likely diagnosis and the appropriate immediate management?",opts:["A. Pulmonary embolism — IV heparin and call cardiology","B. Intraoperative great vessel injury — emergent laparotomy or endovascular treatment","C. Anaphylaxis — IV adrenaline and corticosteroids","D. Epidural haematoma compressing lumbar roots — close wound and get urgent MRI","E. Vasovagal syncope — Trendelenburg position and IV fluids"],ans:1,exp:"Sudden hypotension during lumbar disc space manipulation = great vessel injury until proven otherwise. Injury occurs when instruments breach the anterior longitudinal ligament (ALL). Key anatomy: aortic bifurcation is on the LEFT side of the lower L4 VB — aorta injured at/above L4; common iliac arteries at risk below L4. Veins are more commonly injured than arteries (IVC at/above L4; common iliac veins below L4). Only ≈50% bleed into the disc space (wound appears dry) — the rest bleed into the retroperitoneum. Mortality: 37–67%. Management: emergent laparotomy (or endovascular treatment) by vascular surgeon. Depth of instrument penetration should not exceed 3 cm. Overall DVT/PE rate after lumbar disc surgery is only 0.1% and does not cause acute intraoperative haemodynamic collapse.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1259",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old man undergoes emergency L4/5 microdiscectomy for acute cauda equina syndrome with urinary retention and saddle anaesthesia. Post-operatively he still cannot void. A cystometrogram shows a hypotonic bladder with decreased sensation and increased capacity. Which management strategy and pharmacological agent class is most appropriate to facilitate voiding?",opts:["A. Anticholinergics (e.g., oxybutynin) — suppress detrusor overactivity","B. Clean intermittent catheterisation (CIC) plus an alpha-adrenergic blocker (e.g., tamsulosin) to reduce bladder outlet resistance","C. Indwelling catheter only — surgery has failed; no further intervention helps","D. Beta-3 agonists (e.g., mirabegron) — increase bladder capacity","E. Parasympathomimetics (e.g., bethanechol) are always contraindicated post-discectomy"],ans:1,exp:"CES produces a lower motor neuron (hypotonic/atonic) bladder: decreased sensation, high capacity, low detrusor pressure. Urinary retention is the most consistent finding (sensitivity ≈90%); overflow incontinence may also occur. Key management: (1) CIC every 4 hours — preferred approach (maintains low bladder pressure, prevents overdistension, allows monitoring of recovery). (2) Alpha-adrenergic blockers (tamsulosin 0.4 mg daily) relax bladder neck/proximal urethral smooth muscle, reducing outlet resistance and facilitating voiding when detrusor function recovers. AVOID anticholinergics (oxybutynin etc.) — these suppress any residual detrusor activity in an already hypotonic bladder and worsen retention. Prognosis for bladder function: when total perineal anaesthesia is present, permanent bladder paralysis is likely. Return of bladder function after acute CES onset: only ≈50%.",ref:"Greenberg, p.1254, 1260",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 74-year-old woman with an L1 osteoporotic compression fracture undergoes balloon kyphoplasty. Intraoperatively, fluoroscopy shows cement tracking along a paravertebral vein. Immediately post-procedure she develops acute dyspnoea, oxygen saturations fall to 86%, and ECG shows right heart strain. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Pulmonary fat embolism from marrow manipulation during balloon inflation","B. Pulmonary cement (PMMA) embolism from venous extravasation","C. Tension pneumothorax from trocar placement","D. Cement leakage into the epidural space causing cord compression","E. Anaphylaxis to polymethylmethacrylate cement"],ans:1,exp:"PMMA cement embolism to the pulmonary circulation is a recognised complication of vertebroplasty and kyphoplasty. When cement extravasates into paravertebral or basivertebral veins during injection it can reach the pulmonary vasculature, causing acute dyspnoea, hypoxia, and right heart strain. The fluoroscopic finding of cement tracking venously is the key discriminating feature — fat embolism occurs from marrow but is not associated with cement injection into veins, and epidural cement leakage causes neurological deficit rather than cardiorespiratory compromise. Cement extravasation occurs in ~40% of vertebroplasties; most are asymptomatic; major pulmonary embolism is rare but carries high mortality. Subcutaneous haematoma (the other cited kyphoplasty complication) causes local wound pain, not cardiorespiratory collapse.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old presents with 4 months of progressive thoracic myelopathy. MRI shows a T6 vertebral haemangioma occupying the entire vertebral body with epidural extension and cord compression. CT confirms trabecular destruction and cortical breakthrough. What is the optimal management sequence?",opts:["A. Radiotherapy alone — haemangiomas are radiosensitive and surgery can be avoided","B. Vertebroplasty alone — stabilises the body and relieves cord tension","C. Embolisation followed by decompressive surgery and instrumented stabilisation","D. Decompressive surgery without pre-operative embolisation — immediate decompression takes priority","E. Embolisation alone — reduces venous engorgement and will decompress the cord over weeks"],ans:2,exp:"Aggressive vertebral haemangiomas (with cord compression and cortical breakthrough) require surgery. Pre-operative embolisation is essential because haemangiomas are highly vascular — surgery without it risks catastrophic intraoperative haemorrhage. Embolisation alone does not acutely decompress the cord. Vertebroplasty addresses pain in non-compressive lesions only. Radiotherapy reduces haemangioma size over months and is not appropriate for acute myelopathy. The discriminating principle: all four wrong options each achieve part of the goal but not all three required steps (haemostasis, decompression, stability) in the right order.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A consultant reviews a theatre list. A blood conservation protocol requires pre-operative group and save (G&S) for all procedures with significant haemorrhage risk. Which of the following does NOT routinely require G&S?",opts:["A. L3–5 posterior laminectomy","B. L4–S1 posterior instrumented fusion with pedicle screws","C. L4/5 lumbar microdiscectomy","D. Dorsal root entry zone (DREZ) procedure","E. Revision posterior lumbar surgery for epidural fibrosis"],ans:2,exp:"Lumbar microdiscectomy is a low blood-loss procedure (average 50–100 mL) and does not routinely require group and save. Multi-level laminectomy (200–500 mL average loss), instrumented fusion (500–1500 mL), DREZ (complex cord surface dissection with epidural venous exposure), and revision surgery (adhesion lysis, scarring) all carry substantially higher haemorrhage risk. The key distinction is that microdiscectomy is a targeted, limited decompression without bone decortication or instrumentation.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 67-year-old presents with 8 months of progressive bilateral hand weakness and leg stiffness. Examination: bilateral intrinsic hand muscle wasting, fasciculations in both upper limbs, brisk biceps and triceps reflexes bilaterally, brisk knee and ankle reflexes, upgoing plantars bilaterally, exaggerated jaw jerk. Vibration and joint position sense are entirely normal throughout. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Cervical spondylotic myelopathy (C4–7)","B. Foramen magnum meningioma","C. Motor neurone disease (ALS)","D. Primary progressive multiple sclerosis","E. Bilateral carpal and cubital tunnel syndrome with coincident upper motor neuron signs from another cause"],ans:2,exp:"UMN signs (brisk reflexes, upgoing plantars) combined with LMN signs (wasting, fasciculations) in the complete absence of sensory disturbance is pathognomonic of ALS/MND. The exaggerated jaw jerk confirms bilateral corticobulbar involvement above the pons — a feature of ALS, not of cervical cord compression. CSM causes UMN signs but NOT fasciculations, leaves the jaw jerk normal (the lesion is caudal to the trigeminal motor nucleus), and typically causes some sensory disturbance. A foramen magnum lesion is also below the pons and would not exaggerate the jaw jerk. Preserved sensation throughout excludes MS and most structural cord lesions. The jaw jerk is the decisive discriminating sign.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 42-year-old presents to the emergency department with 6 weeks of low back pain. There is no neurological deficit, no urinary symptoms, no history of malignancy or immunosuppression, and no fever. He is anxious and requests urgent MRI. What is the most appropriate management?",opts:["A. Urgent MRI lumbar spine within 24 hours to exclude serious pathology","B. Reassure, advise continued activity and self-management; no imaging required at this stage","C. Plain X-ray lumbar spine then review in 2 weeks","D. Urgent neurosurgery outpatient referral","E. MRI lumbar spine within 6 weeks, as NICE requires imaging for symptoms lasting more than 4 weeks"],ans:1,exp:"In the absence of red flags (neurological deficit, cauda equina features, suspected malignancy, infection, inflammatory arthritis, significant trauma, or steroid use), imaging for non-specific low back pain of less than 3 months duration is not indicated. NICE NG59 recommends reassurance, exercise, and self-management. Early imaging drives incidental-finding-led intervention and increases surgery rates without improving outcomes. '4-week symptom duration' is NOT a threshold for routine MRI in the absence of red flags — this is a common misconception.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During anterior cervical discectomy and fusion, at which level is the vertebral artery LEAST at risk from lateral retractor displacement or inadvertent lateral bone removal?",opts:["A. C3–4","B. C4–5","C. C5–6","D. C6–7","E. C7–T1"],ans:4,exp:"The vertebral artery typically enters the foramen transversarium at C6 (occasionally C7) and travels within the bony canal from C6 superiorly through C2 before looping around C1 to enter the foramen magnum. At C7–T1, the artery has not yet entered its bony canal and lies laterally in the neck — it is therefore LEAST at risk during ACDF at this level. At C3–6, the vessel is enclosed within the foramen transversarium and is vulnerable to retractor injury, high-speed drilling, or inadvertent lateral exposure. The incidence of vertebral artery injury during ACDF is approximately 0.3–0.5%.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 61-year-old has right-sided low back and buttock pain radiating to the right dorsal foot. Pain is consistently worse on standing and walking and is reliably relieved by sitting. MRI L4–5 shows severe degenerative changes. Which structure's hypertrophy is most likely responsible for compressing the L4 nerve root in the lateral recess?",opts:["A. Inferior articular process of L3 projecting into the L3–4 foramen","B. Superior articular process of L5 encroaching on the L4–5 lateral recess","C. Posterolateral disc herniation at L4–5 compressing the traversing L5 root","D. Ligamentum flavum hypertrophy at L3–4 causing central canal stenosis","E. Far lateral disc herniation at L5–S1 compressing the exiting L5 root"],ans:1,exp:"At L4–5, the lateral recess is bounded posterolaterally by the superior articular process of L5. Hypertrophy of this structure is the primary cause of L4 lateral recess stenosis. The L4 nerve root traverses the lateral recess before exiting under the L4 pedicle. Extension loading (standing, walking) increases facet loading and further narrows the lateral recess — explaining why symptoms are consistently worse on standing. Sitting and lumbar flexion open the recess and relieve symptoms. A posterolateral L4–5 disc would compress the traversing L5 root, and symptoms would be worse with flexion/Valsalva rather than extension. The near-miss here is option C: same level, different structure, different root.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 38-year-old undergoes successful L4/5 microdiscectomy for right-sided sciatica. He asks about the probability of same-level disc reherniation requiring a second operation within the first year. What is the most accurate figure?",opts:["A. Less than 1%","B. 5–10%","C. 15–20%","D. 25–30%","E. Greater than 30%"],ans:1,exp:"Same-level disc reherniation requiring reoperation occurs in approximately 5–10% of cases within the first year — this is the standard counselling figure. Overall 10-year recurrence requiring surgery is approximately 10–15%. Risk factors for recurrence include posterior annular defect >6mm, younger age, higher BMI, and manual labour. Patients should attempt the same conservative management first before revision surgery, as outcomes are comparable. Less than 1% would substantially underestimate the risk and is not supported by the evidence.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 27-year-old, 26 weeks pregnant, presents with 4 weeks of right sciatica radiating to the dorsum of the right foot. Right tibialis anterior power is 4/5 (left 5/5). Bladder function is normal. What is the most appropriate management?",opts:["A. Emergency caesarean section followed by lumbar microdiscectomy","B. Plain radiograph lumbar spine to confirm the disc level, then physiotherapy","C. MRI lumbar spine without gadolinium; conservative management with paracetamol, physiotherapy, and close neurological monitoring","D. Urgent lumbar microdiscectomy under general anaesthesia in the left lateral tilt position","E. Epidural methylprednisolone injection to reduce disc inflammation"],ans:2,exp:"In pregnancy with radiculopathy and mild neurological deficit but intact bladder function, conservative management is first-line: paracetamol (avoid NSAIDs especially after 28 weeks), physiotherapy, and close monitoring. MRI is safe in pregnancy (no ionising radiation) and is the imaging modality of choice; gadolinium should be avoided unless essential. Surgery is reserved for cauda equina syndrome or rapidly progressive complete deficit. Caesarean section at 26 weeks is not indicated for maternal spinal disease without fetal compromise. Plain X-ray is contraindicated (ionising radiation in pregnancy). Epidural steroids are generally avoided in pregnancy. The key trap is option D — 'left lateral tilt' is correct positioning for any surgery in later pregnancy but surgery is not indicated here.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 71-year-old on rivaroxaban 20mg once daily for atrial fibrillation is listed for elective L3–5 posterior laminectomy. Renal function is normal (CrCl 68 mL/min). He takes his last dose on Monday morning. When should surgery be scheduled?",opts:["A. Monday evening — 8 hours allows one half-life clearance","B. Tuesday morning — 24 hours reflects adequate daily-dose clearance","C. Wednesday morning — 48 hours is the minimum for high-bleeding-risk spinal surgery with normal renal function","D. Thursday morning — 72 hours is the standard minimum for all anticoagulants before neuraxial procedures","E. The following Monday — 7 days is required before any spinal operation"],ans:2,exp:"Rivaroxaban has a half-life of 7–11 hours. ESRA/ASRA guidelines recommend ≥48 hours cessation before high-bleeding-risk procedures including spinal surgery in patients with normal renal function. At 24 hours, approximately 50% of anticoagulant activity remains — insufficient for a high-risk spinal procedure. 72 hours is reserved for significant renal impairment (CrCl <30 mL/min). 7 days applies to aspirin discontinuation in high-risk situations, not DOACs. The near-miss is 24h vs 48h: 24h is intuitive (one tablet interval) but pharmacologically insufficient for this risk category.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 54-year-old has 3 months of left-sided low back pain radiating to the dorsum of the left foot and great toe. MRI shows a disc herniation at L4–5 located in the neural foramen (foraminal zone), lateral to the pedicle, not in the lateral recess or central canal. Which nerve root is compressed, and what surgical approach is required if conservative treatment fails?",opts:["A. L5 nerve root; standard posterior hemilaminectomy and medial discectomy","B. L4 nerve root; standard posterior hemilaminectomy and medial discectomy","C. L5 nerve root; far lateral (Wiltse) paramedian approach","D. L4 nerve root; far lateral (Wiltse) paramedian approach","E. L5 nerve root; anterior lumbar interbody fusion (ALIF) for indirect foraminal decompression"],ans:3,exp:"At L4–5, the EXITING nerve root is L4 (exits beneath the L4 pedicle into the L4–5 foramen). A foraminal (far lateral) disc at this level therefore compresses L4, not L5. A standard posterolateral L4–5 disc compresses the TRAVERSING root (L5). This distinction is high-yield: foraminal disc at L4–5 → L4 symptoms (weak dorsiflexion + knee extension, reduced knee jerk); posterolateral L4–5 → L5 symptoms (weak dorsiflexion/eversion, normal knee jerk, reduced ankle jerk if S1 involved). Foraminal access requires a far lateral (Wiltse) paramedian approach — a standard posterior laminotomy cannot reach the disc without sacrificing the facet joint. Options A and C both get the approach right or wrong independently; the candidate must pair the correct root AND the correct approach.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During thoracic posterior instrumented fusion at T6–9, intraoperative fluoroscopy reveals the T7 pedicle screw tip has breached the medial pedicle wall by 4mm with the tip approaching the spinal canal. Neurological monitoring has been stable throughout. What is the most appropriate next step?",opts:["A. Leave the screw in situ; obtain post-operative CT to confirm canal clearance before discharge","B. Remove the screw and insert a longer screw at the same trajectory to improve distal purchase","C. Remove the screw and reinsert with corrected trajectory using image guidance or navigation","D. Leave the screw in situ; a 4mm medial breach is within published safety tolerance for thoracic pedicle screws","E. Remove the screw and abandon fixation at T7, augmenting adjacent levels instead"],ans:2,exp:"A 4mm medial breach at T7 places the screw tip at or within the spinal canal, creating immediate risk of cord injury and late risk from loosening or settling. When identified intraoperatively, the correct response is removal and reinsertion with a corrected trajectory under image guidance (fluoroscopy or intraoperative CT navigation). A longer screw at the same angle perpetuates the medial trajectory. Leaving it in situ is not acceptable with this degree of breach — published safety tolerance for medial breach in the thoracic spine is ≤2mm of cortical violation. Abandoning fixation at that level weakens the construct. Options B and E both involve removing the screw but fail on what comes next — the distinction requires knowing that trajectory correction (not length) is the problem.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old with type 2 diabetes presents with 6 days of mid-thoracic back pain and fever. MRI shows a T5–7 posterior spinal epidural abscess with mild T2 cord signal change. Neurological examination reveals spinal tenderness but no weakness, intact sensation, and normal bladder function. Blood cultures are pending. What is the most appropriate initial management?",opts:["A. Urgent surgical decompression within 6 hours — any cord T2 signal change mandates immediate surgery","B. CT-guided percutaneous aspiration for microbiology and drainage","C. IV broad-spectrum antibiotics pending cultures, neurological observations every 2–4 hours, and repeat MRI at 48 hours if no improvement or any neurological change","D. Oral antibiotics and outpatient review in 1 week — the patient is ambulant and neurologically intact","E. IV antibiotics for 24 hours then mandatory surgical decompression regardless of neurological status"],ans:2,exp:"In neurologically intact patients with spinal epidural abscess, non-operative management (IV antibiotics + strict neurological monitoring) has outcomes comparable to surgery and is appropriate first-line. S. aureus is the causative organism in >50% — empiric cover with vancomycin ± meropenem. Neurological observations every 2–4 hours are mandatory: any new deficit mandates emergency surgery within hours. Cord T2 signal change alone, without deficit, does not mandate immediate surgery. Options A and E incorrectly make surgery automatic — the trigger is neurological deficit or failure of medical treatment, not imaging findings alone. Option D dangerously underestimates urgency and monitoring requirement.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 34-year-old presents with 18 months of progressive bilateral arm pain and temperature loss in a cape distribution. Vibration and joint position sense are entirely normal. MRI shows a T2-hyperintense intramedullary cavity from C3 to C7 with normal cord contour. There is no tonsillar herniation, no craniovertebral junction abnormality, and no obvious intramedullary mass on the initial scan. What is the single most important next investigation?",opts:["A. Gadolinium-enhanced MRI brain to exclude demyelinating plaques","B. Full-length MRI spine with gadolinium to exclude an occult intramedullary mass, arachnoiditis, or tethered cord at the caudal pole of the syrinx","C. CT myelogram of the cervical spine","D. Repeat MRI cervical spine in 6 months to assess progression","E. Lumbar puncture for CSF analysis to exclude inflammatory cause"],ans:1,exp:"Syringomyelia without an obvious structural cause (no Chiari, no craniovertebral junction lesion) requires whole-spine MRI with gadolinium to exclude: (1) intramedullary tumour at the caudal pole of the syrinx — an ependymoma or haemangioblastoma may be small and only visible as an enhancing nodule; (2) spinal cord tethering below the imaged segment; (3) arachnoiditis or adhesions (post-traumatic, post-infectious) blocking CSF flow. Gadolinium of the cervical cord alone is insufficient because the causative lesion may lie below C7. MRI brain is useful if demyelination is suspected but dissociated sensory loss without relapsing-remitting course makes MS less likely. CT myelogram is reserved when MRI is inconclusive. A 6-month wait is inappropriate when a treatable structural cause may be progressive.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true}
]},

"cranial-anatomy":{src:"Standard neurosurgical neuroanatomy",c:[
{q:"What is the pterion and why is it surgically dangerous?",a:"H-shaped suture junction of frontal, parietal, temporal, and sphenoid bones in the temporal fossa. The middle meningeal artery (branch of maxillary → external carotid) runs beneath it. Trauma causes extradural haematoma from arterial laceration.",ref:"claude — neuroanatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What structures pass through the superior orbital fissure?",a:"CN III (oculomotor); CN IV (trochlear); CN V1 (ophthalmic — lacrimal, frontal, nasociliary branches); CN VI (abducens); sympathetic fibres; ophthalmic veins. Injury causes 'superior orbital fissure syndrome' — total ophthalmoplegia + V1 sensory loss.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the cavernous sinus and what structures pass through it?",a:"Dural venous sinus lateral to the sella. Contains CN III, IV, V1, V2 in the wall; CN VI and the ICA run within it. Cavernous sinus thrombosis/tumour causes multiple cranial nerve palsies + proptosis + chemosis.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the significance of the vein of Labbé in temporal craniotomy?",a:"Drains lateral temporal lobe into the transverse sinus. Sacrifice causes venous infarction of the temporal lobe: aphasia (dominant side) or neglect (non-dominant). Must be preserved during temporal/subtemporal approaches.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the contents of the internal acoustic meatus (IAM)?",a:"CN VII (facial nerve), CN VIII (vestibulocochlear nerve — cochlear and superior/inferior vestibular divisions), and the internal auditory artery (labyrinthine artery, branch of AICA). Mnemonic: '7 up, 8 down' — VII is superior, VIII inferior.",ref:"claude — skull base anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the boundaries of the foramen magnum?",a:"Anterior: basion (clivus); Posterior: opisthion (posterior margin of occipital bone). Transmits: medulla/cervical cord junction, vertebral arteries, posterior spinal arteries, anterior spinal artery, spinal accessory nerve (CN XI), meninges.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the venous drainage of the brain?",a:"Superficial: cortical bridging veins → superior sagittal sinus (SSS) + transverse sinus. Deep: internal cerebral veins → vein of Galen → straight sinus → confluens sinuum → transverse → sigmoid → IJV.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What does the middle meningeal artery supply and where does it enter the skull?",a:"Supplies the dura (not the brain). Enters through foramen spinosum (branch of maxillary artery). Anterior branch runs beneath the pterion — most commonly injured in extradural haematoma.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"How do you localise a facial nerve lesion above or below the stylomastoid foramen?",a:"Below stylomastoid foramen (peripheral/parotid): LMN facial weakness only — taste and stapedius spared. Above stylomastoid foramen: LMN weakness PLUS involvement of taste (chorda tympani) and/or hyperacusis (nerve to stapedius). Precise localisation: above stapedius nerve = LMN weakness + hyperacusis + taste loss; between stapedius and chorda tympani = weakness + taste loss (no hyperacusis); above chorda tympani only = weakness alone (if stapedius branch spared). Intracranial/CPA lesion: adds ipsilateral SNHL and tinnitus (CN VIII).",ref:"claude — CN VII anatomy — lesion localisation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What is Parinaud syndrome and what causes it?",a:"Dorsal midbrain (pretectal) syndrome: (1) supranuclear upgaze palsy — cannot look up voluntarily; (2) convergence-retraction nystagmus on attempted upgaze; (3) light-near dissociation — large pupils react to accommodation but not to light. Caused by compression of the dorsal midbrain/periaqueductal grey (rostral interstitial nucleus of the MLF). Commonest cause: pineal region tumour (germinoma most common in adolescents). Also: hydrocephalus, MS, infarct.",ref:"claude — Parinaud/dorsal midbrain syndrome",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What is unique about the trochlear nerve (CN IV)?",a:"CN IV is the only cranial nerve to: (1) exit the DORSAL brainstem (from the inferior colliculus); (2) immediately decussate — crosses to the opposite side; (3) have the longest intracranial course; (4) be the smallest CN (fewest axons). Supplies superior oblique → intorts and depresses the adducted eye. CN IV palsy: vertical diplopia worse on downgaze (e.g. reading, descending stairs) — patient tilts head AWAY from the affected eye (compensatory).",ref:"claude — CN IV anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"Which branch of the facial nerve is at risk in a pterional craniotomy?",a:"The frontal (temporal) branch of CN VII runs superficially within the temporoparietal fascia, crossing the zygomatic arch to supply frontalis and orbicularis oculi. At risk during skin incision and fascial dissection in the pterional approach — injury causes ipsilateral frontalis weakness. Protected by incising between the superficial and deep layers of the temporalis fascia (interfascial dissection) over the zygomatic arch.",ref:"claude — pterional craniotomy / facial nerve protection",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"During a temporal craniotomy, which vein must be preserved to avoid temporal lobe venous infarction?",opts:["A. Vein of Trolard","B. Vein of Labbé","C. Superior sagittal sinus","D. Basal vein of Rosenthal","E. Sphenoparietal sinus"],ans:1,exp:"The vein of Labbé drains the lateral temporal lobe to the transverse sinus. Injury causes venous infarction: aphasia on dominant side, neglect on non-dominant side.",ref:"claude — neuroanatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A patient has a ring-enhancing lesion of the cavernous sinus with right-sided ophthalmoplegia and V1/V2 numbness. Which nerve runs WITHIN the cavernous sinus rather than in its wall?",opts:["A. CN III","B. CN IV","C. CN VI","D. CN V1","E. CN V2"],ans:2,exp:"CN VI (abducens) and the ICA run within the cavernous sinus. CN III, IV, V1, V2 travel in the lateral wall. This is why CN VI palsy is often the first sign of cavernous sinus pathology.",ref:"claude — cavernous sinus anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A patient has ipsilateral LMN facial weakness, hyperacusis, and loss of taste on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue after a temporal bone fracture. Where is the facial nerve injured?",opts:["A. Below the stylomastoid foramen — parotid region","B. Between the stylomastoid foramen and the chorda tympani junction","C. Above the chorda tympani but below the nerve to stapedius","D. Above the nerve to stapedius — proximal to both branches in the mastoid segment","E. At the cerebellopontine angle"],ans:3,exp:"Both taste (chorda tympani) AND hyperacusis (nerve to stapedius) are affected — the lesion must be above both branches, i.e., proximal to the nerve to stapedius in the mastoid/vertical segment of the facial canal, near or at the geniculate ganglion. A lesion below the stapedius branch but above chorda tympani = taste loss + LMN weakness, no hyperacusis. A peripheral lesion (below stylomastoid foramen) = LMN weakness only.",ref:"claude — CN VII localisation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 17-year-old has headaches, an inability to look upwards voluntarily, and pupils that react to near but not to light. MRI shows a pineal region mass compressing the dorsal midbrain. What is this syndrome?",opts:["A. Horner syndrome — sympathetic pathway compression","B. Argyll Robertson pupils — syphilitic midbrain","C. Parinaud syndrome — dorsal midbrain/tectal compression","D. Internuclear ophthalmoplegia — MLF lesion","E. Weber syndrome — CN III and cerebral peduncle"],ans:2,exp:"Parinaud (dorsal midbrain) syndrome: supranuclear upgaze palsy + convergence-retraction nystagmus on attempted upgaze + light-near dissociation (pupils react to accommodation, not light). Caused by dorsal midbrain/periaqueductal grey compression — most commonly by a pineal region tumour (germinoma most common in adolescents/young men). Argyll Robertson pupils are small, irregular, and caused by syphilis — without upgaze palsy.",ref:"claude — Parinaud syndrome / pineal region tumours",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 40-year-old woman is recovering from a right retrosigmoid craniectomy for acoustic neuroma resection. She has a complete right LMN facial palsy. She reports that her right eye feels persistently dry and the nursing staff note she is producing no tears. The cornea is at risk. Which segment of the facial nerve was most likely damaged?",opts:["A. Parotid (extracranial) segment — below the stylomastoid foramen","B. Mastoid segment — between the chorda tympani and the stylomastoid foramen","C. Mastoid segment — between the nerve to stapedius and the chorda tympani","D. Geniculate ganglion or proximal labyrinthine/meatal segment — at or before the greater superficial petrosal nerve (GSPN) branches off","E. Tympanic (horizontal) segment — between the geniculate ganglion and the nerve to stapedius"],ans:3,exp:"The greater superficial petrosal nerve (GSPN) carries parasympathetic preganglionic fibres from the superior salivatory nucleus → geniculate ganglion → GSPN → pterygopalatine ganglion → lacrimal gland (and nasal glands). GSPN branches from the facial nerve at the GENICULATE GANGLION. Loss of lacrimation (dry eye) means the GSPN is non-functional — therefore the lesion must be AT the geniculate ganglion or PROXIMAL to it (labyrinthine segment, meatal/intracanalicular segment, or CPA). In the retrosigmoid approach, the CPA and meatal portions are the exposed segments. Distal lesions (tympanic, mastoid, extracranial) spare the GSPN and lacrimation is preserved. Blood supply of the labyrinthine segment: labyrinthine artery (branch of AICA) — explaining why AICA territory infarcts can cause facial palsy with dry eye. Dry eye after facial palsy requires urgent corneal protection.",ref:"claude — CN VII anatomy — geniculate ganglion / GSPN",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old man undergoes a right pterional craniotomy for an unruptured MCA aneurysm. Post-operatively he cannot raise his right eyebrow but facial sensation is intact and eye closure is normal. What structure was injured and what surgical error caused this?",opts:["A. Supraorbital nerve (V1) — stretched during skin flap elevation, causing sensory loss","B. Frontal (temporal) branch of CN VII — the skin incision was made too inferior and close to the tragus, within the danger zone","C. Temporal branch of V3 — injured in the deep temporal fascia dissection","D. Supratrochlear nerve (V1) — injured by periorbital retraction during approach","E. Zygomatic branch of CN VII — injured at the zygomatic arch during scalp reflection"],ans:1,exp:"The frontalis muscle (raises the eyebrow) is innervated by the FRONTAL (temporal) branch of the facial nerve (CN VII) — NOT the supraorbital nerve (which is sensory V1 only). The frontal branch of CN VII crosses the zygomatic arch within the superficial temporal fascia (temporoparietal fascia/SMAS layer). It is at risk when the pterional skin incision begins too close to the tragus (within 1 cm anterior) or when dissection is carried through the superficial fascia rather than in the sub-galeal or interfascial plane. Standard protection: (1) begin the incision ≥1 cm anterior to the tragus and curve posteriorly; (2) use interfascial dissection over the zygomatic arch — dissecting between the superficial and deep layers of the temporalis fascia to protect the nerve. A patient who cannot raise their eyebrow post-craniotomy has a CN VII frontal branch injury — this is motor, NOT a sensory supraorbital neuropathy.",ref:"claude — pterional approach / CN VII frontal branch protection",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 25-year-old motorcyclist sustains a closed head injury. After recovery he has vertical diplopia on downgaze and when reading. On examination, there is right hypertropia (right eye higher) that worsens when he tilts his head to the right and improves when he tilts to the left. He has no ptosis or pupil abnormality. Which of the following correctly describes this nerve palsy?",opts:["A. Right CN VI palsy — abducens nerve from the pons, ipsilateral horizontal gaze defect","B. Right CN III palsy — he should have ptosis and a dilated pupil if complete","C. Right CN IV palsy; CN IV decussates after exiting the dorsal midbrain — a right CN IV palsy can therefore result from a LEFT-sided dorsal midbrain injury","D. Right CN IV palsy caused by an ipsilateral right-sided dorsal midbrain injury","E. Left CN IV palsy — the head tilt test result described means the left SO is affected"],ans:2,exp:"Right CN IV (trochlear nerve) palsy: superior oblique weakness → failure to depress and intort the adducted right eye → right hypertropia. Diplopia is worse on downgaze and on leftward gaze (adducting the right eye stresses the right SO maximally). Bielschowsky head tilt test: tilting the head to the RIGHT (toward the affected side) worsens the right hypertropia — the affected SO cannot intort the right eye, so it elevates further. Head tilts LEFT to compensate. Corrected with a vertical prism (base-down over the hypertropic eye). UNIQUE ANATOMY: CN IV is the ONLY cranial nerve that (1) exits the DORSAL brainstem (inferior colliculus), (2) immediately DECUSSATES (crosses to the opposite side), and (3) has the longest intracranial course. This means a right CN IV palsy can be caused by a LEFT-sided dorsal midbrain injury — the trauma impacts the dorsal midbrain at the superior medullary velum where both CN IVs decussate, and a left-sided impact damages the right CN IV as it crosses.",ref:"claude — CN IV palsy / Bielschowsky test",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 50-year-old woman has progressive visual failure. Formal perimetry shows loss of the temporal visual field of both eyes with the nasal fields preserved bilaterally (bitemporal hemianopia). MRI shows a large suprasellar mass. Where is the lesion causing this field defect?",opts:["A. Right optic nerve — all fibres from the right retina are affected, causing right monocular blindness","B. Optic chiasm — the decussating nasal fibres from both retinas are compressed, causing bitemporal field loss","C. Right optic tract — post-chiasmal fibres from both eyes on the right are damaged, causing left homonymous hemianopia","D. Right occipital cortex — visual cortex infarct causing contralateral field loss with macular sparing","E. Left optic radiation in the temporal lobe — causing right superior homonymous quadrantanopia"],ans:1,exp:"Bitemporal hemianopia = loss of both temporal visual fields = nasal retinal fibres from both eyes are damaged. Nasal retinal fibres are the ones that decussate at the OPTIC CHIASM (nasal retina sees the temporal field; these fibres cross to represent that temporal field in the contralateral hemisphere). A lesion at the chiasm — most commonly a pituitary tumour expanding superiorly, or a craniopharyngioma — compresses the crossing nasal fibres from both eyes, causing both temporal fields to be lost. Visual pathway anatomy mnemonic: (1) Optic nerve → monocular blindness; (2) Chiasm → bitemporal hemianopia; (3) Optic tract → contralateral homonymous hemianopia (incongruous); (4) Anterior temporal radiation → contralateral superior quadrantanopia ('pie in the sky'); (5) Parietal radiation → contralateral inferior quadrantanopia ('pie on the floor'); (6) Occipital cortex → contralateral homonymous hemianopia with macular sparing (dual blood supply of macula).",ref:"claude — visual pathway / field defect localisation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During elective clipping of an anterior communicating artery (ACoA) aneurysm, a small artery arising from the A1/A2 junction of the right anterior cerebral artery is inadvertently sacrificed. Post-operatively the patient has right-sided hemiplegia with face and arm more severely affected than leg, and right UMN facial weakness. Which artery was damaged and what territory does it supply?",opts:["A. Right pericallosal artery — supplying the medial frontal lobe; leg is typically more affected","B. Right frontopolar artery — supplying the orbital surface of the frontal lobe; causes frontal lobe syndrome","C. Recurrent artery of Heubner (medial striate artery) — supplying the head of the caudate nucleus, anterior limb of the internal capsule, and anterior putamen","D. Anterior choroidal artery — supplying the posterior limb of the internal capsule, optic tract, and choroid plexus","E. Lenticulostriate arteries from the MCA — supplying the body of the caudate and posterior putamen"],ans:2,exp:"The recurrent artery of Heubner (medial striate artery) arises from the A1/A2 junction of the ACA (occasionally from A1 itself) and runs medially and laterally to reach the anterior perforated substance. It supplies: head of caudate nucleus, anterior limb of internal capsule, anterior putamen, and part of the globus pallidus. Occlusion causes contralateral hemiplegia predominantly affecting the face and arm (internal capsule, head of caudate), with relative sparing of the leg. On the dominant side, transient aphasia may also occur. This artery is at particular risk during surgery for ACoA aneurysms due to its intimate relationship with the aneurysm neck. Distinguish: pericallosal territory → leg > arm; anterior choroidal artery → full homonymous hemianopia + hemisensory loss + hemiplegia (posterior limb internal capsule + optic tract); Heubner → face/arm hemiplegia, no visual field defect.",ref:"claude — artery of Heubner / ACA anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgeon performs a transcallosal approach to the lateral ventricle to access a colloid cyst at the foramen of Monro. After opening the corpus callosum, she enters the lateral ventricle. The choroid plexus is not immediately visible. She identifies the thalamostriate vein. In which direction and to which landmark should she follow the thalamostriate vein to locate the foramen of Monro?",opts:["A. Posteriorly — the thalamostriate vein drains to the vein of Galen, which marks the posterior third ventricle","B. Anteriorly — the thalamostriate vein runs to the foramen of Monro, where it joins the internal cerebral vein; the foramen of Monro lies at its anterior terminus","C. Laterally — following the vein to the external capsule identifies the foramen","D. Superiorly — the vein runs over the corpus callosum to the superior sagittal sinus","E. The thalamostriate vein is MEDIAL to the choroid plexus and cannot be used to locate the foramen of Monro"],ans:1,exp:"Anatomy of the foramen of Monro (interventricular foramen): bounded anterosuperiorly by the anterior columns of the fornix, posterolaterally by the anterior pole of the thalamus, and medially by the choroid plexus (which runs through the foramen). The thalamostriate vein runs in the groove between the thalamus and the head of the caudate nucleus, terminating ANTERIORLY at the foramen of Monro — where it makes a characteristic sharp turn (the 'venous angle') to join the internal cerebral vein. During transcallosal surgery, if the choroid plexus is not immediately visible: identify the thalamostriate vein (it runs medial to the choroid plexus in the floor of the lateral ventricle), then follow it ANTERIORLY — it leads directly to the foramen of Monro. Puncturing the fornix anteromedially to reach the third ventricle through the foramen is the next step. DO NOT follow the vein posteriorly (that leads away from the foramen).",ref:"claude — transcallosal approach / foramen of Monro anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgeon is counselling a patient about the risk of visual loss during a pterional approach for an anterior clinoid meningioma. The ophthalmic artery is at risk. Which of the following correctly describes the anatomy of the ophthalmic artery?",opts:["A. It arises from the extracavernous ICA just proximal to the anterior clinoid; it passes LATERAL to the optic nerve through the optic canal","B. It arises from the intracavernous ICA; it passes through the superior orbital fissure with the oculomotor nerve","C. It typically arises from the ICA at the level of the anterior clinoid (as it exits the cavernous sinus); it enters the optic canal running WITHIN the meningeal sheath of the optic nerve, and initially lies INFERIOR then crosses to the MEDIAL side of the optic nerve","D. It is a branch of the middle meningeal artery supplying the optic nerve","E. It arises from the basilar artery and passes through the optic canal as the primary blood supply to the chiasm"],ans:2,exp:"Ophthalmic artery (OA) anatomy: (1) Origin: typically arises from the ICA as it exits the cavernous sinus, at or just distal to the anterior clinoid process (occasionally intracavernous origin, but rare). (2) Course: enters the optic canal WITHIN the dural sheath of the optic nerve (below and lateral to it initially). (3) In the orbit: crosses from the LATERAL to the MEDIAL side of the optic nerve, passing above or below it. The mnemonic is 'OA begins below, crosses above' — it starts inferior-lateral to the nerve and crosses superiorly to become medial. (4) The OA supplies the retinal artery (central retinal artery), ciliary arteries (choroid), dural branches, and is the primary supply to the optic nerve itself. During anterior clinoid or cavernous sinus surgery, the OA is at risk of stretch injury or spasm — always identify and protect it. Blindness from OA compromise is an irreversible devastating complication.",ref:"claude — ophthalmic artery anatomy / anterior clinoid surgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient presents with bilateral 6th nerve palsies (bilateral abducens palsy) and is found to have severe hydrocephalus on CT. The neurosurgical team notes the bilateral 6th nerve palsies as a false localising sign. Why is bilateral or unilateral abducens (CN VI) palsy a false localising sign in raised ICP?",opts:["A. CN VI exits from the midbrain, which is the first structure to be compressed in uncal herniation","B. CN VI has the longest intracranial course of all cranial nerves; it runs over the petrous apex and can be stretched or angulated by downward displacement of the brainstem in the context of raised ICP — the palsy does not indicate a pons lesion","C. CN VI palsy in raised ICP is caused by direct compression of the abducens nucleus in the pons by the herniating temporal lobe","D. CN VI is damaged by the stretching of the tentorium during uncal herniation","E. CN VI palsy in hydrocephalus indicates a direct compressive lesion on the pons"],ans:1,exp:"CN VI (abducens) has the longest intracranial course of any cranial nerve: it exits the pontomedullary junction, traverses the prepontine cistern, passes over the tip of the petrous temporal bone (at Dorello's canal — a fibro-osseous channel beneath the petroclinoid ligament), then enters the cavernous sinus. When ICP rises, the brainstem is displaced caudally. This stretches and angulates CN VI as it bends over the petrous apex, causing a nerve conduction block — even though the primary pathology is supratentorial. The result is a CN VI palsy that does NOT indicate a pons or petrous apex lesion; it indicates raised ICP and is a FALSE LOCALISING SIGN. This is a classic neurosurgical examination concept. Compare with CN III (true localising = uncal herniation compressing the nerve as it exits the midbrain and courses through the tentorial notch).",ref:"claude — CN VI false localising sign / raised ICP",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"An audiologist documents House-Brackmann grade 4 facial palsy after acoustic neuroma surgery. Which description best matches this grade?",opts:["A. Slight weakness noticeable only on close inspection; normal function at rest; complete eye closure with minimal effort; barely perceptible synkinesis","B. Obvious weakness but not disfiguring; complete eye closure with effort; some forehead movement; moderate synkinesis","C. Obvious disfiguring weakness; incomplete eye closure; no forehead movement; barely detectable voluntary movement; severe synkinesis","D. Total paralysis — no movement at all; no synkinesis","E. Slight asymmetry; normal eye closure; only slight synkinesis on smiling"],ans:2,exp:"House-Brackmann grading: Grade 1 = Normal. Grade 2 = Slight (weakness only on close inspection; complete eye closure with minimal effort; slight synkinesis). Grade 3 = Moderate (obvious but not disfiguring weakness; complete eye closure with effort; forehead movement present; moderate synkinesis). Grade 4 = Moderately severe (obvious disfiguring weakness; INCOMPLETE eye closure; NO forehead movement; barely detectable voluntary movement; SEVERE synkinesis). Grade 5 = Severe (barely perceptible motion; incomplete eye closure; no forehead movement; may have asymmetry at rest; synkinesis absent or minimal because there is almost no movement). Grade 6 = Total paralysis (no movement). Key exam traps: (a) grade 4 has severe synkinesis + incomplete eye closure; (b) grade 5 has barely perceptible motion but less synkinesis than grade 4; (c) grade 6 = complete absence of movement.",ref:"claude — House-Brackmann facial nerve grading scale",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"After a retrosigmoid approach for vestibular schwannoma removal, a patient has no voluntary facial movement whatsoever and total flaccid paralysis of all facial muscles including orbicularis oculi. There is no synkinesis. What is the House-Brackmann grade, and does this necessarily predict permanent paralysis?",opts:["A. Grade 4 — obvious disfiguring weakness; severe synkinesis; incomplete eye closure","B. Grade 5 — barely perceptible motion; no forehead movement; incomplete eye closure","C. Grade 6 — total paralysis; no movement; no synkinesis; prognosis depends on nerve continuity at surgery","D. Grade 3 — complete eye closure achievable with full effort","E. Grade 2 — slight weakness only on close inspection"],ans:2,exp:"House-Brackmann grade 6 = TOTAL PARALYSIS — no movement of any facial musculature, complete flaccidity, total asymmetry at rest. NO synkinesis (synkinesis requires residual voluntary movement to produce aberrant regeneration; in total paralysis, no movement = no synkinesis). Prognosis: grade 6 does not inevitably mean permanent paralysis. When the nerve is ANATOMICALLY INTACT (not cut) — e.g. severe neurapraxia/axonotmesis from retraction — recovery can occur over months to 2 years. If the nerve was divided, repair or grafting is required. Facial retraining and physiotherapy aid recovery. Corneal protection is urgent: artificial tears, lubricating ointment, eyelid weight or tarsorrhaphy. Distinguish grade 5 (barely perceptible motion) from grade 6 (NO motion) — this distinction is clinically important for prognosis.",ref:"claude — House-Brackmann grading scale / acoustic neuroma",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with a severe closed head injury exhibits spontaneous motor responses in which both arms are held in flexion at the elbow with wrists pronated and fingers clenched, while both lower limbs are extended and internally rotated. What posture is this, what level of lesion does it indicate, and how does it differ from decerebrate posturing?",opts:["A. Decerebrate posturing — lesion above the red nucleus; arms are extended","B. Decorticate posturing — lesion at or above the level of the midbrain (above the red nucleus); arm flexion, wrist pronation, leg extension; decerebrate involves arm and leg extension and indicates a lower/more severe midbrain-pontine lesion","C. Decorticate posturing — lesion in the medulla; lower limbs flex","D. Flaccid paralysis — lesion at the pontomedullary junction","E. Decerebrate posturing — lesion in the diencephalon; all four limbs flex"],ans:1,exp:"Decorticate posturing ('cortical posturing'): (1) Lesion level: at or above the upper midbrain — above the red nucleus (diencephalon/corona radiata level, e.g. large hemispheric lesion, transtentorial herniation before it reaches the midbrain). (2) Features: UPPER LIMBS — FLEXION at elbow, wrist PRONATION, fingers clenched; LOWER LIMBS — EXTENSION and plantarflexion. Mnemonic: DECORticate = arms Flex at Core (arms curl in). (3) Decerebrate posturing: lesion at or below the red nucleus (midbrain or pons level). Features: UPPER AND LOWER LIMBS BOTH EXTENDED, wrist pronated, feet plantarflexed — more severe injury. Decerebrate indicates deeper midbrain/pontine involvement. Flaccid paralysis = medullary or spinal lesion. Exam trap: 'pronation in wrist' occurs in BOTH decorticate and decerebrate; the distinguishing feature is arm FLEXION (decorticate) vs arm EXTENSION (decerebrate).",ref:"claude — decorticate vs decerebrate posturing",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A medical student asks from which embryological region the cerebral hemispheres are derived. Which answer is correct?",opts:["A. Basal plate of the diencephalon — motor nuclei of the thalamus","B. Alar plate of the prosencephalon (telencephalon) — dorsal, pallial and subpallial divisions generate the cerebral cortex and basal ganglia","C. Alar plate of the rhombencephalon — pontine and cerebellar nuclei","D. Basal plate of the telencephalon — the motor cortex arises from the basal plate","E. Neural crest cells migrating from the mesencephalon — cortical neurones are of neural crest origin"],ans:1,exp:"Embryological origin of the cerebral hemispheres: (1) The brain develops from the neural tube. The neural tube has two regions: ALAR PLATE (dorsal — sensory/associative) and BASAL PLATE (ventral — motor nuclei). (2) The prosencephalon subdivides into: TELENCEPHALON (→ cerebral hemispheres, basal ganglia, hippocampus, amygdala) and DIENCEPHALON (→ thalamus, hypothalamus, retina). (3) The cerebral cortex and basal ganglia arise from the ALAR PLATE of the TELENCEPHALON (part of the prosencephalon). (4) Rhombencephalon: metencephalon (pons, cerebellum) + myelencephalon (medulla). (5) Neural crest cells contribute to peripheral structures — cranial nerve ganglia, meninges, craniofacial skeleton — NOT the cerebral cortex. Common exam trap: confusing diencephalon (thalamus) with telencephalon (hemispheres) — both are prosencephalon, but the hemispheres are specifically telencephalon.",ref:"claude — neuroanatomy embryology / prosencephalon",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient has a lesion of the dentate nucleus of the right cerebellum causing right-sided limb ataxia and dysmetria. The dentate nucleus projects through which pathway to ultimately influence the left motor cortex?",opts:["A. Dentate → ipsilateral red nucleus → corticospinal tract without crossing","B. Dentate → fibres exit via the superior cerebellar peduncle → decussate in the midbrain → contralateral red nucleus → contralateral VL thalamus → contralateral motor cortex (dentatorubrothalamic tract)","C. Dentate → ipsilateral inferior olive → contralateral motor cortex via the spinocerebellar pathway","D. Dentate → ipsilateral thalamus → ipsilateral motor cortex without crossing","E. Dentate → contralateral vestibular nuclei → motor cortex via the medial lemniscus"],ans:1,exp:"Dentatorubrothalamic tract: dentate nucleus (deep cerebellar nucleus) → axons exit via the SUPERIOR CEREBELLAR PEDUNCLE → DECUSSATE at the level of the inferior colliculus in the midbrain (at the decussation of the superior cerebellar peduncles) → synapse in the contralateral RED NUCLEUS (midbrain tegmentum) → continue via the thalamus (VL nucleus) → contralateral primary motor cortex. Key consequence of double decussation: cerebellar lesions cause IPSILATERAL limb ataxia (the dentate projects contralaterally, but the corticospinal tract then decussates again at the medullary pyramids — so net effect is ipsilateral cerebellar control of ipsilateral limb function). The RED NUCLEUS also gives rise to the RUBROSPINAL TRACT, which decussates in the ventral midbrain tegmentum and projects contralaterally to the spinal cord, facilitating arm flexion. Lesions at the red nucleus or superior cerebellar peduncle: contralateral cerebellar signs + ipsilateral CN III palsy = Claude syndrome or Benedikt syndrome.",ref:"claude — dentatorubrothalamic tract / red nucleus / extrapyramidal pathway",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During a transcallosal approach to the third ventricle for a colloid cyst, the surgeon inadvertently opens a CSF space between the two layers of the tela choroidea, superior to the thalamus and inferior to the fornix, exposing the internal cerebral veins. What is this space called, and what is the key surgical danger of entering it?",opts:["A. The quadrigeminal cistern — the main danger is injuring the vein of Galen and basal veins of Rosenthal","B. The velum interpositum — the key danger is injuring the internal cerebral veins, which run within this space and drain the deep cerebral structures","C. The prepontine cistern — the basilar artery is at risk","D. The superior medullary velum — the trochlear nerves are at risk","E. The cistern of the lamina terminalis — the anterior communicating artery complex is at risk"],ans:1,exp:"The velum interpositum is a subarachnoid CSF-containing space (cistern) located between the two layers of the tela choroidea of the third ventricle. Boundaries: inferior = thalamus and pineal region; superior = fornix and body of corpus callosum; contents = INTERNAL CEREBRAL VEINS (ICVs), which run within it to form the vein of Galen posteriorly. It is accessed from above through the corpus callosum (transcallosal route) or through the choroidal fissure (transchoroidal route). Surgical danger: the ICVs drain the deep cerebral structures (thalamus, basal ganglia, caudate, internal capsule) bilaterally — injury causes bilateral deep venous infarction, which is catastrophic. Do NOT confuse with: (1) Superior medullary velum — thin white matter roof of the upper fourth ventricle between the superior cerebellar peduncles (site of the trochlear nerve decussation); (2) Quadrigeminal cistern — posterior to the pineal gland, above the tectum.",ref:"claude — velum interpositum / third ventricle surgical anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A surgeon plans a Dolenc (extradural) approach for a cavernous sinus meningioma. Which sequence of steps correctly describes how the cavernous sinus is exposed extradurally without entering the subarachnoid space?",opts:["A. Suboccipital craniotomy → transection of the tentorium posteriorly → extradural entry to the posterior cavernous sinus","B. Frontotemporal craniotomy → extradural elevation of temporal dura from middle fossa floor → extradural removal of the anterior clinoid process → unroofing of the superior orbital fissure — exposing CN III, IV, V1, and VI and the ICA as it exits the sinus","C. Transsphenoidal approach through the sella → lateral dissection into the cavernous sinus","D. Retroauricular incision → drilling the mastoid → entering the cavernous sinus through the petrous apex","E. Pterional craniotomy → intradural temporal lobe retraction → direct entry to the lateral cavernous sinus wall"],ans:1,exp:"Dolenc extradural approach: (1) Standard frontotemporal (pterional) craniotomy. (2) Extradural elevation of temporal and frontal dura from the middle fossa floor — the dura propria (inner layer of cavernous sinus lateral wall) separates at this plane. (3) Extradural anterior clinoidectomy — drilling the anterior clinoid process exposes the ICA as it exits the cavernous sinus (genu of ICA). (4) Unroofing of the superior orbital fissure exposes CN III, IV, V1, and VI. (5) The cavernous sinus and its neurovascular contents are now accessible EXTRADURALLY — no arachnoid is opened, no brain retracted. The key danger is the ICA (most medial) and CN VI (lies most medial within the cavernous sinus, adjacent to the ICA). Contrast with Kawase's approach (posterior petrosectomy via middle fossa floor drilling for access to petroclival region).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During a translabyrinthine resection of a large acoustic neuroma, the scrub nurse asks the surgeon about the blood supply to the facial nerve within the internal auditory canal. Which vessel provides the primary arterial supply to the intracanalicular facial nerve?",opts:["A. Posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA) — via its lateral medullary branches","B. Labyrinthine (internal auditory) artery — a branch of the anterior inferior cerebellar artery (AICA)","C. Middle meningeal artery — via its petrosal branch to the geniculate ganglion","D. Posterior auricular branch of the facial artery — via mastoid emissary","E. Direct branches from the basilar artery perforators"],ans:1,exp:"The facial nerve within the internal auditory canal (IAC) is supplied by the LABYRINTHINE ARTERY (internal auditory artery) — a branch of the AICA in the majority of cases (occasionally from the basilar artery directly). The labyrinthine artery enters the IAC with CN VII and CN VIII and supplies the cochlea, semicircular canals, and the intracanalicular segment of the facial nerve. More distally (within the facial canal), the geniculate ganglion and tympanic segment receive supply from the petrosal branch of the middle meningeal artery; the mastoid and parotid segments from the stylomastoid artery (branch of posterior auricular artery). Injury to the labyrinthine artery during acoustic neuroma surgery or translabyrinthine approaches devascularises the intracanalicular facial nerve and cochlea, contributing to post-operative facial palsy and sensorineural deafness.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old presents with horizontal diplopia worse on lateral gaze in both directions. Examination shows bilateral limitation of abduction with intact adduction. There are no other cranial nerve abnormalities. What anatomical localisation best explains isolated bilateral abducens palsy?",opts:["A. Both cerebellopontine angles simultaneously — bilateral CPA tumours compressing CN VI","B. The pons — bilateral abducens nuclei or fascicles in the pontine tegmentum; alternatively, bilaterally elevated ICP causing bilateral petrous stretch (false localising sign)","C. The midbrain — bilateral superior colliculus lesion affecting horizontal gaze","D. Both cavernous sinuses — bilateral cavernous sinus thrombosis with bilateral CN VI involvement","E. The occipital cortex — binocular conjugate gaze centre damage"],ans:1,exp:"Bilateral abducens (CN VI) palsy localises to the CN VI nuclei in the pontine tegmentum (bilateral pontine lesion — Wernicke's, MS, basilar thrombosis, pontine glioma) OR represents a bilateral false localising sign from raised ICP (CN VI stretched over the petrous apex as the brainstem descends). The key discriminating question: are there other pontine signs? CN VI nuclei in the pons are adjacent to the facial colliculus (CN VII loops around the CN VI nucleus). A pontine lesion → bilateral horizontal gaze palsy + bilateral peripheral facial weakness + other pontine signs. An isolated bilateral CN VI palsy without other signs → consider false localising (raised ICP), Wernicke's, or leptomeningeal infiltration of both nerves. Bilateral simultaneous CPA lesions would be vanishingly rare. Midbrain lesions affect vertical gaze (CN III, IV), not horizontal.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient presents with left-sided facial palsy and otalgia with vesicles in the external auditory canal (Ramsay Hunt syndrome). In addition to the facial palsy, which combination of findings is MOST consistent with involvement of the geniculate ganglion?",opts:["A. Loss of taste on the anterior two-thirds of the left tongue only — isolated chorda tympani involvement","B. Dry left eye (reduced lacrimation), loss of taste on the anterior two-thirds of the left tongue, and hyperacusis","C. Hyperacusis and loss of taste, with preserved lacrimation — lesion between the GSPN takeoff and the nerve to stapedius","D. Loss of lacrimation only — the GSPN is the only branch affected","E. Preserved taste and preserved lacrimation — only the extracranial facial branches are involved"],ans:1,exp:"Facial nerve branch anatomy: the GREATER SUPERFICIAL PETROSAL NERVE (GSPN) arises from the GENICULATE GANGLION → carries preganglionic parasympathetic fibres for lacrimation (via pterygopalatine ganglion → lacrimal gland). A lesion AT the geniculate affects all branches distal to it: GSPN → DRY EYE; nerve to stapedius → HYPERACUSIS; chorda tympani → TASTE LOSS anterior 2/3 tongue. Result: facial palsy + dry eye + hyperacusis + taste loss. Key differentiator: if lacrimation is PRESERVED, the lesion is DISTAL to the GSPN (between GSPN origin and nerve to stapedius). If lacrimation is LOST and hyperacusis is present but taste intact → impossible with a single-level lesion (chorda is distal to stapedius branch). The geniculate ganglion is also the site most vulnerable to herpes zoster reactivation in Ramsay Hunt syndrome.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During transcallosal approach to the third ventricle, a small bridge of grey matter is noted connecting the right and left thalami across the third ventricular cavity. From which embryological structure does this 'massa intermedia' (interthalamic adhesion) arise?",opts:["A. Telencephalon — the same structure that generates the cerebral hemispheres","B. Diencephalon — the thalami are diencephalic; the interthalamic adhesion is a midline fusion of thalamic grey matter across the third ventricle","C. Mesencephalon — it represents a rostral extension of the tectum","D. Rhombencephalon — displaced pontine nuclei","E. Neural crest — contributing to midline brain structures"],ans:1,exp:"The massa intermedia (interthalamic adhesion) is a band of grey matter connecting the right and left thalami across the third ventricle. It is present in ~70–80% of humans (more common in women). It is derived from the DIENCEPHALON — an extension of thalamic grey matter (not a commissure — it carries few if any crossing fibres). Embryologically: prosencephalon → telencephalon (cerebral hemispheres, basal ganglia) + diencephalon (thalamus, hypothalamus, subthalamus, retina). The massa intermedia is thalamic in origin and is recognised on MRI as a rounded grey matter structure in the middle of the third ventricle. Its absence does not cause neurological deficit.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient sustains an orbital floor fracture extending to the inferior orbital fissure. Which nerve passing through the inferior orbital fissure explains the area of facial numbness over the cheek and lateral orbit that the patient reports?",opts:["A. Lacrimal nerve (CN V1) — through the superior orbital fissure, provides lateral orbital skin sensation","B. Abducens nerve (CN VI) — pure motor, no sensory territory","C. Infraorbital nerve (CN V2) and zygomatic nerve (CN V2) — both traverse the inferior orbital fissure to supply cheek, lateral face, and lateral forehead sensation","D. Trochlear nerve (CN IV) — pure motor to superior oblique","E. Ophthalmic nerve (CN V1) — passes through the superior orbital fissure, not the inferior"],ans:2,exp:"The inferior orbital fissure (IOF) lies between the floor and the lateral wall of the orbit, connecting it to the pterygopalatine fossa medially and the infratemporal fossa laterally. Contents include: infraorbital nerve (CN V2 — becomes the infraorbital nerve, exits via infraorbital foramen to supply lower eyelid, cheek, nose, upper lip), zygomatic nerve (CN V2 — branches into zygomaticotemporal and zygomaticofacial nerves → lateral forehead/cheek sensation), infraorbital artery, and venous connections. CN III, IV, V1 (lacrimal/frontal/nasociliary), and VI all traverse the SUPERIOR orbital fissure. Optic nerve travels through the optic canal. IOF fractures damage V2 branches → cheek numbness + lateral forehead numbness.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A petroclival meningioma is being resected via a combined middle fossa / posterior petrosectomy approach. The surgeon references 'Kawase's triangle' to guide drilling through the petrous apex. Which statement correctly defines Kawase's triangle and the structure that lies within it?",opts:["A. Bounded by the GSPN, arcuate eminence, and lesser petrosal nerve; the cochlea is central and must be avoided","B. Bounded anteriorly by the GSPN, posteriorly by the arcuate eminence — drilling exposes the superior semicircular canal; the anterior petrous carotid canal lies at its medial limit","C. Bounded medially by the GSPN, posteriorly by the arcuate eminence, and laterally by the superior petrosal sinus; drilling here exposes the posterior fossa dura and the petrosal segment of the ICA in the petrous carotid canal","D. Bounded by CN V, the superior petrosal sinus, and the internal auditory canal; the basilar artery lies immediately beneath","E. A triangle bounded by three cranial foramina: ovale, rotundum, and spinosum"],ans:2,exp:"Kawase's triangle (posterior petrosectomy triangle): a surgically relevant area of the petrous bone drilled via the middle fossa to access the posterior fossa extradurally. Boundaries: GSPN (anterolateral), arcuate eminence (posterolateral), and the petrous ridge toward the superior petrosal sinus (medial). Drilling within this triangle: (1) removes bone anterior to the IAC and medial to the cochlea; (2) exposes posterior fossa dura; (3) reveals the petrosal segment of the ICA (petrous carotid canal) at the medial limit. Key surgical hazards: cochlea (anterolateral corner — injury causes ipsilateral deafness); petrous ICA (medial floor); IAC (not opened unless needed); superior petrosal sinus (posterior edge). The approach provides access to petroclival meningiomas and the prepontine cistern without cerebellar retraction.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During a left temporal craniotomy for a posterior temporal lobe GBM, a large cortical bridging vein is identified running from the posterior sylvian fissure to the transverse sinus. What is this vein, and what is the consequence of its sacrifice in the dominant hemisphere?",opts:["A. Vein of Trolard (superior anastomotic vein) — sacrifice causes frontal lobe venous infarction","B. Vein of Labbe (inferior anastomotic vein) — sacrifice causes posterior temporal lobe venous infarction; in the dominant hemisphere this produces Wernicke's (receptive) aphasia and severe communication deficit","C. Basal vein of Rosenthal — sacrifice causes thalamic and basal ganglia venous infarction","D. Superficial middle cerebral vein (sylvian vein) — sacrifice causes insula and lateral temporal infarction","E. Internal cerebral vein — sacrifice causes bilateral deep hemisphere infarction"],ans:1,exp:"The vein of Labbe (inferior anastomotic vein): the major cortical drainage vein of the posterior temporal lobe. It runs posteriorly from the posterior sylvian fissure to the TRANSVERSE SINUS (occasionally sigmoid sinus). Its sacrifice during temporal craniotomy is one of the most feared complications in posterior temporal surgery — it causes posterior temporal venous infarction. In the DOMINANT hemisphere (usually left), this involves Wernicke's area (posterior superior temporal gyrus) → Wernicke's aphasia: fluent, paraphasic speech with severely impaired comprehension. Contrasts with the vein of Trolard (superior anastomotic vein) which drains frontoparietal cortex to the superior sagittal sinus. Preservation of the vein of Labbe is a key principle in posterior temporal surgery — it may constrain the posterior limit of a safe resection.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A trainee asks why CN IV (trochlear nerve) is the cranial nerve MOST LIKELY to be difficult to visualise or inadvertently missed during a standard suboccipital retrosigmoid craniotomy for CPA surgery. Which explanation is correct?",opts:["A. CN IV is embedded within the petrous bone and is only accessible via a middle fossa approach","B. CN IV exits from the DORSAL surface of the midbrain just below the inferior colliculus, immediately decussates, then courses anteriorly around the brainstem to reach the tentorial edge — it is therefore dorsal and superior to the typical suboccipital surgical field","C. CN IV is too small to identify intraoperatively and is never seen at any skull base approach","D. CN IV exits the pons laterally alongside CN VI — both are at risk in retrosigmoid surgery from the same direction","E. CN IV runs medially through the prepontine cistern and is protected from suboccipital approaches by the basilar artery"],ans:1,exp:"CN IV (trochlear nerve) is unique: the ONLY cranial nerve to exit from the DORSAL brainstem — emerging from the dorsal midbrain immediately caudal to the inferior colliculus. It immediately DECUSSATES in the superior medullary velum, then winds anteriorly around the cerebral peduncle to enter the tentorial edge. In a standard suboccipital/retrosigmoid approach, the surgeon works from behind and below — CN IV's dorsal origin is above and medial to the operative field and is not routinely in view. To visualise CN IV, the surgeon must look along the tentorial edge superomedially. Despite being outside the direct field of view, CN IV can be damaged during retrosigmoid surgery if the cerebellum is retracted medially or if the superior petrosal sinus/tentorial edge is manipulated. CN IV palsy is therefore a recognised complication even when it was never directly seen.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A surgeon performs a middle fossa (extradural transtemporal) approach for an acoustic neuroma. The approach involves drilling through the petrous bone and dissecting the middle cranial fossa floor. Which cranial nerve is LEAST likely to be directly encountered or put at risk during the middle fossa floor dissection?",opts:["A. Greater superficial petrosal nerve (GSPN) — runs in a groove in the middle fossa floor and is the first landmark identified","B. CN V3 (mandibular) — exits via foramen ovale in the middle fossa floor","C. CN VII (facial) — runs in the IAC and geniculate ganglion, exposed by petrous drilling","D. CN IX (glossopharyngeal) — exits via the jugular foramen in the posterior fossa and does not traverse the middle cranial fossa floor","E. CN V2 (maxillary) — exits via foramen rotundum in the middle fossa floor"],ans:3,exp:"The middle cranial fossa floor dissection puts at risk: GSPN (the primary anatomical landmark, running in the petrosal groove), geniculate ganglion of CN VII (most superficially positioned structure in the petrous floor — at high risk of injury, even more so than the IAC contents), CN V2 via foramen rotundum, CN V3 via foramen ovale, and the IAC contents (CN VII and CN VIII). CN IX (glossopharyngeal) exits via the JUGULAR FORAMEN — which is located in the POSTERIOR FOSSA, medial and inferior to the petrous temporal bone. CN IX does not traverse the floor of the middle cranial fossa. The middle fossa approach explicitly avoids the posterior fossa unless combined with a petrosal extension. Confusing the jugular foramen location is the most common candidate error on this topic.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true}
]},

"neuropathology":{src:"WHO CNS Tumour Classification 5th ed (2021) + standard knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the WHO 2021 definition of glioblastoma (GBM)?",a:"GBM is now defined as an IDH-WILDTYPE grade 4 astrocytic glioma. IDH-mutant grade 4 tumours are classified as IDH-mutant astrocytoma, grade 4 — NOT as GBM. This is a fundamental change from WHO 2016.",ref:"WHO CNS 2021"},
{q:"What two molecular markers are required to diagnose oligodendroglioma per WHO 2021?",a:"IDH mutation (IDH1 or IDH2) AND 1p/19q codeletion — BOTH required. IDH mutation alone = astrocytoma. 1p/19q codeletion alone is insufficient. It is now a molecular (not histological) diagnosis.",ref:"WHO CNS 2021"},
{q:"What molecular feature defines a diffuse midline glioma?",a:"H3 K27 alteration (H3.3 K27M or H3.1 K27M mutation, or less commonly EZHIP overexpression). Arises in midline structures (thalamus, brainstem, spinal cord). Includes DIPG (diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma). Grade 4 regardless of histology.",ref:"WHO CNS 2021"},
{q:"What are the WHO 2021 grades for CNS tumours?",a:"Grade 1: benign, slow-growing, potentially curable with surgery (e.g. pilocytic astrocytoma, meningioma Grade 1). Grade 2: low-grade, infiltrative. Grade 3: anaplastic, malignant features. Grade 4: highly malignant (e.g. GBM, medulloblastoma, atypical meningioma/hemangiopericytoma).",ref:"WHO CNS 2021"},
{q:"What is the Flexner-Wintersteiner rosette and in which tumour is it seen?",a:"Rosette with a central lumen representing an attempt at photoreceptor differentiation. Seen in retinoblastoma and pineoblastoma. Homer Wright rosettes (without lumen) are seen in medulloblastoma and neuroblastoma.",ref:"claude — neuropathology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the characteristic microscopic appearance of meningioma?",a:"Whorls of meningothelial cells with psammoma bodies (concentric calcified lamellations). Spindle cells, lobular architecture. Most are WHO grade 1. Grade 2 (atypical): ≥4 mitoses/10 HPF, brain invasion, or ≥3 of 5 histological features.",ref:"claude — neuropathology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the main medulloblastoma molecular subgroups and their prognosis?",a:"WNT-activated (best prognosis — ~95% 5yr OS); SHH-activated (intermediate, PTCH1/SUFU/SMO mutations); Group 3 (worst — often MYC amplified, metastatic, young children); Group 4 (intermediate, most common).",ref:"WHO CNS 2021 / Medulloblastoma subgroups"},
],q:[
{stem:"A biopsy shows IDH mutation and 1p/19q codeletion from a 35-year-old with a frontal tumour. WHO 2021 diagnosis?",opts:["A. Astrocytoma, IDH-mutant","B. Glioblastoma, IDH-wildtype","C. Oligodendroglioma, IDH-mutant and 1p/19q-codeleted","D. Diffuse midline glioma, H3 K27-altered","E. Ependymoma"],ans:2,exp:"WHO 2021: IDH mutation + 1p/19q codeletion = oligodendroglioma, IDH-mutant and 1p/19q-codeleted. Both molecular alterations are required for this diagnosis.",ref:"WHO CNS Classification 2021"},
{stem:"A pontine tumour in a 7-year-old shows H3 K27M mutation on biopsy. What is the WHO 2021 grade?",opts:["A. Grade 1","B. Grade 2","C. Grade 3","D. Grade 4 regardless of histology","E. Grading not applicable to brainstem tumours"],ans:3,exp:"WHO 2021: Diffuse midline glioma, H3 K27-altered = Grade 4 regardless of histological appearance. Previously called DIPG when in the pons. Extremely poor prognosis.",ref:"WHO CNS Classification 2021"},
{stem:"The contents of a colloid cyst are sent to neuropathology. Which substance is the characteristic histological finding?",opts:["A. Psammoma bodies — whorled calcifications seen in meningiomas","B. Rosenthal fibres — elongated eosinophilic deposits in astrocytic processes","C. Cholesterol crystals — crystalline material surrounded by histiocytic reaction; the viscous content of colloid cysts is mucinous material containing cholesterol crystals","D. Physaliferous (soap-bubble) cells — vacuolated cells characteristic of chordoma","E. Eosinophilic granular bodies — found in pilocytic astrocytoma and ganglioglioma"],ans:2,exp:"Colloid cysts contain thick, gelatinous green-yellow material. Histologically: the cyst wall is pseudostratified columnar or cuboidal epithelium with mucin-secreting goblet cells; the contents include mucin, cholesterol crystals, hemosiderin, and cellular debris. Cholesterol crystals are the pathognomonic content. They arise from the roof of the third ventricle (paraphysis or ependymal origin) and cause the ball-valve obstruction at the foramen of Monro. Psammoma bodies = meningioma/papillary thyroid carcinoma. Rosenthal fibres = pilocytic astrocytoma and Alexander disease. Physaliferous cells = chordoma.",ref:"claude — colloid cyst neuropathology",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A biopsy of a sacrococcygeal mass in a 55-year-old shows cells with large intracytoplasmic vacuoles surrounded by a myxoid matrix, giving them a 'soap-bubble' or 'physaliferous' appearance. The tumour is centred in the clivus/sacrum on MRI and shows T2 hyperintensity. What is the diagnosis?",opts:["A. Myxopapillary ependymoma — arises from the filum terminale; papillary architecture","B. Chordoma — arises from notochordal remnants; physaliferous (vacuolated) cells in a myxoid matrix; T2-bright on MRI; locally aggressive","C. Chondrosarcoma — cartilaginous matrix on histology; ring-and-arc calcification on CT","D. Giant cell tumour — giant multinucleated cells; osteoclast-like; young adults","E. Sacral schwannoma — spindle cells; S100-positive; Verocay bodies"],ans:1,exp:"Chordoma: arises from notochordal remnants along the axial skeleton. Locations (frequency): sacrococcygeal (50%) > spheno-occipital/clival (35%) > mobile spine (15%). Pathognomonic histology: physaliferous cells (large vacuolated cells containing glycogen/mucin) in a myxoid matrix. MRI: T1 iso-hypointense, T2 markedly hyperintense (myxoid matrix), heterogeneous enhancement, lobulated. Locally aggressive — recurrence common; metastases in ~5–40%. Treatment: wide surgical excision + proton beam radiotherapy (conventional RT less effective due to radio-resistance). Brachyury (T protein) is a specific immunohistochemical marker.",ref:"claude — chordoma histopathology",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A biopsy of a cerebral mass shows high cellularity, nuclear pleomorphism, mitotic figures, and areas of necrosis with pseudopalisading. There is also tumour endothelial proliferation (glomeruloid microvascular proliferation). What are these two features, and what is their diagnostic significance?",opts:["A. Pseudopalisading necrosis and microvascular proliferation are features of anaplastic astrocytoma (WHO grade 3) — they confirm high-grade transformation","B. Pseudopalisading necrosis and microvascular proliferation are the defining features of GBM (WHO grade 4) — either feature alone upgrades a diffuse glioma to grade 4; their absence in an IDH-wildtype astrocytoma still results in grade 4 classification under WHO 2021","C. Only pseudopalisading necrosis is required for GBM diagnosis — microvascular proliferation alone indicates grade 3","D. Both features must be present simultaneously for GBM diagnosis — one alone is insufficient","E. Pseudopalisading necrosis is seen in all gliomas; microvascular proliferation is specific to ependymoma"],ans:1,exp:"WHO 2021 GBM (grade 4) histological criteria: EITHER pseudopalisading necrosis (cells radially oriented around geographic necrosis — reflects rapid growth outpacing vascular supply) OR microvascular proliferation (endothelial and pericyte proliferation forming multilayered glomeruloid tufts) is sufficient to upgrade to grade 4. Anaplastic astrocytoma (grade 3): mitoses present but NEITHER necrosis nor microvascular proliferation. Under WHO 2021: IDH-wildtype glioma with TERT promoter mutation, EGFR amplification, or +7/−10 chromosomal profile is classified as GBM grade 4 even without these histological features.",ref:"claude — GBM vs anaplastic astrocytoma histological criteria",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A biopsy shows a tumour with pseudorosettes — tumour cells radially arranged around vessels with cell-free fibrillar zones. GFAP immunohistochemistry is positive. Which tumour is MOST likely and where does it arise?",opts:["A. Medulloblastoma — Homer-Wright rosettes (without central vessel); posterior fossa","B. Ependymoma — perivascular pseudorosettes (fibrillar zones around vessels, GFAP+) and true ependymal rosettes (cells lining a central canal); can arise anywhere along the ventricular system or spinal canal","C. Retinoblastoma — Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes; intraocular","D. Pineoblastoma — Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes; pineal region","E. PNET (primitive neuroectodermal tumour) — Homer-Wright rosettes"],ans:1,exp:"Rosette types: (1) PERIVASCULAR PSEUDOROSETTES — tumour cells radially arranged around a vessel with cell-free fibrillar zones; GFAP positive; EPENDYMOMA (can arise anywhere along ependymal lining: spinal > posterior fossa > supratentorial). (2) TRUE EPENDYMAL ROSETTES — cells form a central lumen (mimicking ependymal canal); more specific for ependymoma but less common. (3) HOMER-WRIGHT ROSETTES — cells arranged around a central mass of neuropil (no lumen); MEDULLOBLASTOMA and PNETs; synaptophysin positive. (4) FLEXNER-WINTERSTEINER ROSETTES — cells around an apical lumen with photoreceptor differentiation; RETINOBLASTOMA and PINEOBLASTOMA.",ref:"claude — CNS tumour rosette types",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 10-year-old child undergoes biopsy of a posterior fossa cystic mass. Histology shows a biphasic pattern: compact areas with Rosenthal fibres alongside loose areas with eosinophilic granular bodies (EGBs). Which tumour is this, and what is the significance of BRAF status?",opts:["A. Diffuse astrocytoma — IDH mutation and ATRX loss confirm diffuse infiltrating biology; BRAF not relevant","B. Pilocytic astrocytoma — WHO grade 1; biphasic pattern with Rosenthal fibres and EGBs is pathognomonic; KIAA1549::BRAF gene fusion (most common in cerebellar pilocytic) drives MEK-ERK activation and is IDH-wildtype","C. Ependymoma — pseudorosettes and GFAP positive; BRAF not relevant","D. Ganglioglioma — binucleated neurons plus glial component; BRAF V600E mutation common","E. Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma (PXA) — spindle cells and xanthomatous changes; BRAF V600E in 60%"],ans:1,exp:"Pilocytic astrocytoma (WHO grade 1): pathognomonic histology = BIPHASIC pattern with (1) compact areas containing Rosenthal fibres (elongated glassy eosinophilic deposits in astrocytic processes) and (2) loose areas with eosinophilic granular bodies (EGBs — degenerate protein bodies). BRAF: KIAA1549::BRAF gene FUSION occurs in >70% of cerebellar pilocytic astrocytomas — creates constitutive BRAF-MEK-ERK pathway activation. IDH-wildtype. This fusion is NOT a BRAF V600E point mutation (which occurs in some non-cerebellar pilocytic and BRAF-driven tumours). Targeted therapy: MEK inhibitors (selumetinib, trametinib) for progressive/recurrent pilocytic tumours with BRAF fusion.",ref:"claude — pilocytic astrocytoma histopathology and BRAF",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"neuroradiology":{src:"Standard neuroradiology + Radiopaedia",c:[
{q:"What does DWI (diffusion-weighted MRI) show in acute ischaemia and what is the timecourse?",a:"Restricted diffusion = bright on DWI + dark on ADC map. Becomes positive within minutes to 1–2 hours of ischaemia. Remains bright for 7–14 days. Essential for distinguishing acute from chronic infarct.",ref:"claude — MRI neuroimaging",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the CT evolution of an intracerebral haemorrhage over time?",a:"Hyperacute: mixed/isodense. Acute (first few days): hyperdense (dense clot). Subacute (1–3 weeks): becomes isodense then hypodense as haemoglobin breaks down. Chronic: hypodense (haemosiderin remains → T2* dark on MRI).",ref:"CT brain — ICH evolution"},
{q:"What is the CT evolution of a subdural haematoma over time?",a:"Acute (0–3 days): hyperdense. Subacute (3–21 days): isodense (can be missed — look for midline shift). Chronic (>21 days): hypodense. Mixed-density = rebleed into chronic SDH.",ref:"CT brain — SDH evolution"},
{q:"What is the CT appearance of a typical extradural haematoma (EDH)?",a:"Biconvex (lenticular) hyperdense collection, bounded by suture lines (dura is attached at sutures, so EDH cannot cross them). Most common in temporal region. Often arterial (middle meningeal artery) — lucid interval then rapid deterioration.",ref:"CT brain — EDH"},
{q:"What MRI sequences are used to detect haemorrhage at different stages?",a:"Acute (deoxyhaemoglobin): isointense T1, dark T2. Subacute early (intracellular methaemoglobin): bright T1, dark T2. Subacute late (extracellular metHb): bright T1, bright T2. Chronic (haemosiderin): dark on T2/T2* (GRE/SWI).",ref:"MRI haemorrhage signal changes"},
{q:"What is susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI) used for in neuroradiology?",a:"Highly sensitive for blood products (haemosiderin, deoxyhaeomglobin), calcium, and iron. Used to detect cerebral microhaemorrhages (CAA, DAI, hypertensive small vessel disease), cavernomas, and venous malformations.",ref:"claude — neuroradiology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What does FLAIR MRI show that T2 does not?",a:"FLAIR suppresses CSF signal (nulls free water) so periventricular lesions, SAH, and cortical pathology are not obscured by adjacent bright CSF. Essential for MS plaques, leptomeningeal disease, and SAH detection >24h.",ref:"claude — MRI",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the key angiographic features of an arteriovenous malformation (AVM)?",a:"Tangle of abnormal vessels (nidus) with early arterial filling of draining veins (arteriovenous shunting). No capillary phase. Enlarged feeding arteries and draining veins. Flow-related aneurysms may be present on feeding vessels.",ref:"claude — cerebrovascular imaging",src_id:"claude-ai"},
],q:[
{stem:"A CT brain shows a crescent-shaped collection over the right hemisphere that is isodense with brain. Performed 3 weeks post-head injury. Most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Acute SDH","B. Subacute SDH","C. Chronic SDH","D. EDH","E. SAH"],ans:1,exp:"SDH evolution: Acute (0–3d) = hyperdense; subacute (3–21d) = isodense; chronic (>21d) = hypodense. At 3 weeks, isodense = subacute SDH. Can be missed — look for mass effect and midline shift.",ref:"CT brain — SDH evolution"},
{stem:"An MRI sequence shows a lesion that is dark on T2 and T2*/SWI imaging but was not visible on CT. Most likely this represents:",opts:["A. Acute oedema","B. Demyelination","C. Haemosiderin from old haemorrhage","D. Acute infarction","E. Calcification in a meningioma"],ans:2,exp:"Haemosiderin (chronic blood products) is dark on T2 and very dark on T2*/SWI due to magnetic susceptibility. T2*/SWI is far more sensitive than CT for detecting old microhaemorrhages and cavernomas.",ref:"MRI — haemorrhage signal evolution"},
{stem:"A head CT on day 3 post-trauma shows a subdural collection. The radiologist reports the collection as 'isodense to brain' on CT. What does this signal indicate, and what MRI sequences would be most helpful?",opts:["A. Isodense on day 3 indicates a simple effusion with no blood product","B. An isodense subdural collection on CT at 3 days typically represents a subacute haemorrhage (blood products in transition from hyper to hypo-dense, occurring around days 3–14 as proteins denature); MRI FLAIR and T1 will show hyperintense signal; T2*/SWI may show haemosiderin if older blood is present","C. Isodense collection at day 3 = chronic SDH — no acute component; drain with burr hole","D. Isodense signal means the collection is purely CSF — no haematoma","E. All SDHs are isodense on CT regardless of timing"],ans:1,exp:"CT haematoma signal evolution: hyperacute (0–6h): isodense; acute (6–72h): HYPERDENSE (>55 HU due to clot retraction and protein concentration); SUBACUTE (3–14 days): becomes ISODENSE (as protein denatures); chronic (>3 weeks): HYPODENSE. An isodense SDH at day 3 is in the acute-to-subacute transition — easily missed on CT, can be seen on MRI. MRI: subacute haemorrhage is T1-BRIGHT (extracellular methaemoglobin — paramagnetic shortening of T1). FLAIR also shows hyperintensity. T2*: dark (deoxyhaemoglobin in acute, haemosiderin in chronic). Low-attenuation SDH = CSF or mixture; high = fresh blood.",ref:"claude — CT/MRI haematoma signal evolution",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Which statement correctly describes the mechanism underlying functional MRI (fMRI)?",opts:["A. fMRI detects electrical activity directly using magnetoencephalography (MEG) principles","B. fMRI uses the BOLD signal — neural activation increases local blood flow (neurovascular coupling), delivering more oxyhaemoglobin and diluting deoxyhaemoglobin; as deoxyhaemoglobin is paramagnetic (T2* shortening), its reduction causes relative T2* signal INCREASE in active regions","C. fMRI detects decreased oxyhaemoglobin in active brain regions — oxyhaemoglobin is paramagnetic","D. BOLD fMRI requires gadolinium contrast injection to detect haemodynamic changes","E. fMRI directly measures neuronal glucose consumption using 18F-fluorodeoxyglucose"],ans:1,exp:"fMRI BOLD (blood oxygen level-dependent) signal mechanism: (1) Neuronal activation → increased local cerebral blood flow via neurovascular coupling (glutamate → astrocyte → vasodilation). (2) CBF increase exceeds O2 consumption → ratio of oxyhaemoglobin to deoxyhaemoglobin INCREASES locally. (3) DeoxyHb is paramagnetic (unpaired electrons → T2* shortening → dark on T2*). OxyHb is diamagnetic (no effect on T2*). (4) Reduced deoxyHb → reduced T2* shortening → INCREASED T2* signal in active regions. This is the BOLD signal. No gadolinium needed. The signal change is small (~1–5%) — statistical analysis of many repeated trials needed to detect it.",ref:"claude — fMRI BOLD mechanism",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 40-year-old presents with headache and vertigo. MRI shows a well-circumscribed posterior fossa mass that is restricted on DWI (bright on DWI, dark on ADC). The mass does not enhance with gadolinium and shows heterogeneous T2 signal. Which diagnosis does DWI restriction most strongly suggest?",opts:["A. Arachnoid cyst — follows CSF on all sequences including DWI (not restricted)","B. Epidermoid cyst — DWI restriction (bright diffusion, dark ADC) due to the viscous keratin-debris contents; epidermoids follow CSF on T1/T2 but are distinguished by DWI restriction — the single most useful MRI sequence","C. Dermoid cyst — T1-bright (fat content); rupture causes chemical meningitis","D. Meningioma — hyperdense on CT; dural-based; homogeneous T2 signal","E. Vestibular schwannoma — centred in the IAC; widening of the internal auditory canal"],ans:1,exp:"Epidermoid cyst (cholesteatoma) vs arachnoid cyst: both appear CSF-like on T1 (dark) and T2 (bright), making them indistinguishable on standard sequences. DWI is the KEY differentiating sequence: Epidermoid = RESTRICTED DIFFUSION (bright on DWI, dark on ADC) — due to viscous keratin/cellular debris impeding water diffusion. Arachnoid cyst = FREE diffusion (follows CSF on DWI, bright on ADC). Epidermoids creep around neurovascular structures ('cauliflower' shape), do not enhance, and can arise in the CPA (after vestibular schwannoma and meningioma, epidermoid is the third most common CPA mass).",ref:"claude — epidermoid vs arachnoid cyst / DWI",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 25-year-old presents after a road traffic accident. MRI of the brain shows multiple small punctate lesions at the grey-white matter junction, corpus callosum, and dorsal brainstem. The lesions are hypointense on T2* (GRE/SWI) but are not visible on CT or standard T1/T2. GCS was 8 at presentation. What is the most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Multiple small haemorrhagic metastases — request chest CT and tumour markers","B. Diffuse axonal injury (DAI) — traumatic shearing of axons and microvasculature at grey-white matter interfaces; T2*/SWI is the most sensitive sequence for detecting microhaemorrhagic foci at characteristic DAI sites","C. Multiple cavernous malformations — familial CCM syndrome","D. Multiple sclerosis — periventricular and juxtacortical demyelination; does not involve grey-white junction characteristically","E. Cerebral amyloid angiopathy — cortical microhaemorrhages in elderly patients; not seen after trauma"],ans:1,exp:"Diffuse axonal injury (DAI) is caused by rotational/acceleration-deceleration forces that shear axons and small blood vessels at sites of maximum shear stress: grey-white matter junction (most common), corpus callosum (especially splenium), dorsal brainstem. CT is insensitive (haemorrhages are micro-scale). MRI: T2*/GRE or SWI shows 'blooming' hypointense foci (deoxyHb/haemosiderin in microhaemorrhages). DWI can also show axonal injury. Grading: Grade 1 = grey-white junction; Grade 2 = + corpus callosum; Grade 3 = + brainstem. Grade 3 DAI correlates with vegetative state. DAI is the primary pathological substrate of prolonged unconsciousness without focal CT abnormality.",ref:"claude — diffuse axonal injury / SWI",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"vascular-avm":{src:"Standard neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the Spetzler-Martin AVM grading system?",a:"Score 1–5 based on: SIZE (<3cm=1, 3–6cm=2, >6cm=3) + ELOQUENCE (non-eloquent=0, eloquent=1) + VENOUS DRAINAGE (superficial=0, deep=1). Grades I–II: low surgical risk. Grade IV–V: high surgical risk, consider radiosurgery or observation.",ref:"Spetzler-Martin 1986"},
{q:"What brain regions are considered eloquent for AVM grading?",a:"Sensorimotor cortex; language areas (Broca's, Wernicke's); visual cortex; thalamus; hypothalamus; internal capsule; brainstem; cerebellar peduncles; deep cerebellar nuclei.",ref:"Spetzler-Martin grading"},
{q:"What are the three treatment modalities for intracranial AVMs?",a:"Microsurgical resection (immediate cure, best for SM I–II); stereotactic radiosurgery (Gamma Knife — best for small <3cm deep AVMs, 2–3 year obliteration latency, ongoing haemorrhage risk during this period); endovascular embolisation (adjunct only, rarely curative).",ref:"claude — AVM management",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the annual haemorrhage risk of an unruptured AVM?",a:"Approximately 2–4% per year for unruptured AVMs. Higher if deep venous drainage, single draining vein, or high flow. Ruptured AVM: re-bleed risk ~6–18% in first year.",ref:"claude — / ARUBA trial context",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is a cavernous malformation (cavernoma) and how does it appear on MRI?",a:"Cluster of abnormally enlarged capillary-type vessels without intervening brain. Classic MRI: 'popcorn' lesion on T2 with T2* dark haemosiderin rim (blooming). Familial in some (CCM1/2/3 mutations). Annual bleed risk ~0.5–3%.",ref:"claude — cerebrovascular malformations",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What was the ARUBA trial (Mohr 2014) — design and population?",a:"A Randomised trial of Unruptured Brain AVMs. Prospective multicentre RCT, 39 sites, 9 countries. 226 enrolled (114 interventional, 110 medical management; 223 with data). Adults ≥18, unruptured AVM on imaging, mRS ≤1 at baseline. Excluded: previous haemorrhage, prior treatment, AVM unsuitable for eradication. Mean age 44.5; 41% women. 62% SM grade I–II. Published Lancet 2014;383:614–21.",ref:"ARUBA, p.1–2",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What was the primary outcome of ARUBA and what were the results?",a:"Primary: time to composite endpoint of death or symptomatic stroke. Stopped early (April 2013) after second interim analysis — log-rank Z=4.10 exceeded stopping boundary of 2.87. At mean follow-up 33.3 months: 10.1% (11/109) medical management vs 30.7% (35/114) interventional therapy. HR 0.27 (95% CI 0.14–0.54) in favour of medical management. As-treated: HR 0.19 (0.09–0.38). Medical management superior.",ref:"ARUBA, p.4–5",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What were the functional and safety outcomes in ARUBA (Mohr 2014)?",a:"mRS ≥2 at 30 months: 15.1% (medical) vs 46.2% (interventional); RR 0.33. Strokes: 12 events (0.039/pt-yr) medical vs 45 (0.144/pt-yr) interventional (p<0.0001). Focal neurological deficits unrelated to stroke: 1 vs 14 (p=0.0008). Deaths: all-cause 1.8% vs 2.6% (NS); AVM-related 0% vs 1.8%. Seizures and headaches: no significant difference. Natural history in medical arm: spontaneous rupture 2.2%/year (95% CI 0.9–4.5).",ref:"ARUBA, p.5–6",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What intervention types were used in the ARUBA interventional arm, and what are the trial's key limitations?",a:"Interventions: embolisation alone (30), radiotherapy alone (31), embolisation + radiotherapy (15), embolisation + neurosurgery (12), neurosurgery alone (5). Key limitations: (1) stopped early at 33 months — below planned 5 years, cannot capture long-term benefit after complete cure; (2) 20 patients in interventional arm had not yet received treatment at analysis; (3) recruited lower SM grade AVMs than the wider AVM population; (4) complication rates consistent with literature (surgery 29%, embolisation 25%, radiotherapy 13%).",ref:"ARUBA, p.5–7",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
{q:"How should the ARUBA trial (Mohr 2014) be interpreted clinically?",a:"ARUBA showed medical management superior to intervention for unruptured AVM at 33 months. BUT: (1) applies to UNRUPTURED AVMs only; (2) trial stopped early — interventional cure may reduce long-term risk beyond the observation window; (3) most enrolled AVMs were lower SM grade (amenable to intervention); (4) intervention group still included patients mid-treatment. Clinical interpretation: conservative/medical management is the default for unruptured AVM; intervention should be considered carefully on a case-by-case basis, particularly for young patients with low-grade AVMs where cure is achievable.",ref:"ARUBA, p.6–7",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 35-year-old has a 2cm AVM in non-eloquent parietal cortex, superficial venous drainage (SM grade I) presenting with a seizure. Preferred treatment?",opts:["A. Conservative management","B. Radiosurgery alone","C. Microsurgical resection","D. Embolisation alone","E. Antiepileptics and annual MRI"],ans:2,exp:"SM grade I AVM (small, non-eloquent, superficial drainage) = lowest surgical risk. Microsurgical resection achieves immediate cure. Radiosurgery has 2–3 year obliteration latency with ongoing haemorrhage risk.",ref:"Spetzler-Martin — treatment selection"},
{stem:"The ARUBA trial (Mohr 2014) randomised 223 adults with unruptured AVMs to medical management vs interventional therapy. The trial was stopped early. Which best describes the primary outcome?",opts:["A. Interventional therapy significantly reduced death or stroke compared with medical management","B. Medical management significantly reduced death or stroke compared with interventional therapy (HR 0.27, p<0.0001)","C. No significant difference was found between groups","D. Interventional therapy was superior in SM grade I–II AVMs","E. The trial was stopped early due to harm from medical management"],ans:1,exp:"ARUBA: medical management superior — 10.1% vs 30.7% primary endpoint (HR 0.27 [0.14–0.54], p<0.0001). Stopped by DSMB for superiority of medical management at 33.3 months median follow-up. mRS ≥2 also lower (15.1% vs 46.2%). Spontaneous rupture rate 2.2%/yr in medical arm. Caveat: early termination means long-term post-cure benefit not captured.",ref:"ARUBA, p.4–5",src_id:"k-aruba-2014",korky:true},
{stem:"Regarding spinal cavernous malformations, which of the following statements is INCORRECT?",opts:["A. They are associated with familial syndromes (CCM1, CCM2, CCM3 gene mutations)","B. Concurrent intracranial cavernomas are well-recognised in familial cases","C. They most commonly occur in the cervical spinal cord","D. Haemorrhagic presentation is best demonstrated on gradient echo (T2*) or susceptibility-weighted MRI","E. Surgical resection is considered for symptomatic lesions with progressive neurological deficit or recurrent haemorrhage"],ans:2,exp:"Spinal cavernomas most commonly occur in the THORACIC (dorsal) cord — not cervical. The cervical cord is the second most common site. Familial forms (CCM gene mutations — cavernoma multigene panel) are well-established, with concurrent intracranial lesions common in familial cases. Gradient echo and SWI sequences detect haemosiderin deposits ('blooming' artefact), producing the pathognomonic 'popcorn ball' appearance on T2*. Symptomatic lesions causing progressive deficit or recurrent haemorrhage are managed by microsurgical excision.",ref:"Bank, p.4",src_id:"k-bank-mcqs",korky:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old presents with 4 months of progressive lower limb spasticity and bladder dysfunction. MRI spine shows serpiginous flow voids on the posterior cord surface at multiple levels and T2 intramedullary hyperintensity from T4 to T10. Which diagnosis and treatment are correct?",opts:["A. Transverse myelitis — treat with IV methylprednisolone","B. Intramedullary astrocytoma — biopsy and radiotherapy","C. Spinal dural arteriovenous fistula (SDAVF) — arterialized venous hypertension causes progressive myelopathy; treat by interrupting the arterialised vein close to the fistula surgically or by endovascular embolisation","D. Spinal cord infarction — IV alteplase if within 4.5 hours","E. Myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein (MOG) antibody disease — plasma exchange"],ans:2,exp:"Spinal DAVF: a low-flow arteriovenous shunt between a dural branch of a radicular artery and the perimedullary venous plexus. The fistula raises venous pressure → perimedullary venous engorgement → reduced spinal cord perfusion → progressive myelopathy. MRI hallmarks: (1) perimedullary flow voids on dorsal cord surface (dilated draining veins); (2) T2 intramedullary hyperintensity (oedema/ischaemia), worst at lower thoracic/conus. DSA confirms the level of fistula (typically single level T5–L2). Treatment: surgical interruption of the arterialized vein at the fistula site (close to the fistula on the dural sleeve) OR endovascular embolisation with NBCA/Onyx (higher recurrence rate than surgery). Prognosis: improvement in ~80% if treated before fixed deficit.",ref:"claude — spinal DAVF diagnosis and treatment",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old has a routine MRI showing a small asymptomatic lesion in the right cerebellar hemisphere. It appears as a tubular, branching vascular structure that does not show arterial pulsation on flow-sensitive sequences. There is no haemorrhage. Follow-up MRI 2 years later shows no change. What is this lesion, and what is its management?",opts:["A. Cavernous malformation — haemorrhagic; characteristic popcorn appearance; surgical if symptomatic","B. Developmental venous anomaly (DVA) — a normal variant of venous drainage; low haemorrhage risk (~2% per year); almost always managed conservatively — do NOT resect DVA as it drains normal brain","C. Arteriovenous malformation — requires intervention with ARUBA data supporting medical management for unruptured AVMs","D. Haemangioblastoma — requires MRI contrast for diagnosis; cystic with enhancing nodule","E. Capillary telangiectasia — common incidental finding; no treatment needed; but may haemorrhage if combined with cavernoma"],ans:1,exp:"Developmental venous anomaly (DVA): represents a normal variant of medullary venous drainage — a collection of radially arranged medullary veins draining into an enlarged transcortical/transmedullary collector vein ('caput medusae' appearance on MRI). DVAs are the most common vascular malformation found at autopsy (~2.5% of brains). They DO NOT require treatment. CRITICAL RULE: DVAs MUST NOT BE RESECTED — they drain normal brain parenchyma; resection causes venous infarction. Low haemorrhage risk (~0.15–2% per year, often from an associated cavernoma). If a DVA is found adjacent to a cavernoma (mixed malformation), the cavernoma can be excised but the DVA must be preserved.",ref:"claude — developmental venous anomaly (DVA)",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Which acoustic window of transcranial Doppler allows insonation of the middle cerebral artery (MCA), anterior cerebral artery (ACA), posterior cerebral artery (PCA), and terminal internal carotid artery (TICA)?",opts:["A. Transorbital (orbital) window","B. Transforaminal (occipital) window","C. Transtemporal (temporal) window","D. Submandibular window","E. Transcranial (parietal) window"],ans:2,exp:"Transtemporal window: insonates MCA, ACA, PCA, and TICA (before its bifurcation). Transorbital window: ophthalmic artery (OA) and ICA siphon. Transforaminal (occipital) window: distal vertebral arteries (VA) and basilar artery (BA). Submandibular window: more distal extracranial ICA.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.1",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"The pulsatility index (PI) in transcranial Doppler is calculated using which formula, and what does it measure?",opts:["A. PI = mean velocity / (peak systolic − end diastolic); measures upstream resistance","B. PI = (peak systolic velocity − end diastolic velocity) / mean velocity; measures resistance distal to the insonated site","C. PI = (peak systolic + end diastolic) / mean velocity; measures cerebral perfusion pressure","D. PI = end diastolic velocity / peak systolic velocity; measures autoregulatory reserve","E. PI = mean velocity × heart rate; measures cerebral blood flow"],ans:1,exp:"Gosling equation: PI = (peak systolic velocity − end diastolic velocity) / mean velocity. PI is a reliable marker of vascular resistance distal to the insonated site. A raised PI indicates increased downstream resistance (e.g. raised ICP, distal stenosis); a reduced PI suggests decreased downstream resistance (e.g. AVM).",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A TCD examination reveals increased flow velocity and decreased pulsatility index (PI) at the insonation site. Which vascular scenario best explains this pattern?",opts:["A. Focal stenosis at the insonation site — increased FV due to narrowing, PI raised by downstream obstruction","B. Downstream obstruction proximal to insonation — FV decreases at the insonated vessel","C. Downstream AVM — low distal resistance causes increased FV and decreased PI at the insonation site","D. Raised ICP — high distal resistance raises PI and reduces FV","E. Proximal ICA stenosis — reduced FV at all downstream vessels"],ans:2,exp:"An arteriovenous malformation (AVM) creates a low-resistance shunt. Ohm's law applied to cerebrovascular haemodynamics: decreased downstream resistance → increased CBF → increased FV at the insonation site AND decreased PI (PI is a marker of distal resistance, so low resistance = low PI). Contrast with: focal stenosis (increased FV but PI is raised by downstream effects); raised ICP (decreased FV, increased PI).",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"According to accepted TCD guidelines, what is the normal mean flow velocity of the middle cerebral artery?",opts:["A. 40 ± 10 cm/s","B. 50 ± 11 cm/s","C. 55 ± 12 cm/s","D. 65 ± 15 cm/s","E. 39 ± 9 cm/s"],ans:2,exp:"Normal MCA mean flow velocity: 55 ± 12 cm/s, measured at a depth of 30–60 mm via the transtemporal window, flow directed toward the probe. The basilar artery is 41 ± 10 cm/s; ACA is 50 ± 11 cm/s (away from probe); VA is 38 ± 10 cm/s (away). TCD measurements are influenced by age, PaCO₂, cardiac output, blood viscosity, and vasoactive medications.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.3 (Table 1)",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In a patient with suspected patent foramen ovale (PFO) and cryptogenic stroke, TCD is performed as an alternative to transoesophageal echocardiography. What is the correct TCD technique and timing criterion for a positive result?",opts:["A. Inject 5 mL plain saline; a shower of microbubbles in the MCA >60 seconds after injection indicates a right-to-left shunt","B. Inject 10 mL agitated saline IV while the patient performs a Valsalva manoeuvre; a shower of high signal air emboli detected in the MCA within 5–10 seconds of injection indicates a right-to-left cardiac shunt; detection after >1 minute suggests a pulmonary shunt","C. Inject gadolinium contrast; any signal detected within 30 seconds confirms intracardiac shunting","D. Rapid IV injection of 20 mL saline without Valsalva; bubbles detected in the basilar artery confirm PFO","E. Agitated saline is injected; detection in the ACA within 2 minutes confirms a pulmonary shunt"],ans:1,exp:"TCD for PFO detection: administer agitated saline (10 mL) IV and ask the patient to perform a Valsalva manoeuvre to increase right atrial pressure. Positive result: shower of high signal material (air emboli = HITS — high intensity transient signals) detected in the MCA within 5–10 seconds of injection. TCD has comparable sensitivity and specificity to transoesophageal echocardiography for right-to-left cardiac shunts. If air is not detected until >1 minute after injection, a pulmonary (not cardiac) shunt should be suspected — this distinction cannot be made by TEE.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"What TCD waveform pattern is characteristically seen in a brain-dead patient, and what is its physiological explanation?",opts:["A. Continuous high-velocity flow in both systole and diastole — brain death abolishes cerebrovascular resistance","B. Absent diastolic flow only; systolic flow is preserved — confirming absence of autoregulation","C. Reverberating (oscillating) pattern — normal forward flow in systole and reversed flow in diastole, with zero net flow per unit time; may progress to complete absence of signal in advanced brain death","D. Low-velocity monophasic flow — confirms global cerebral ischaemia","E. Turbulent high-velocity flow reflecting compensatory collateral recruitment"],ans:2,exp:"TCD in brain death: very high distal brain resistance (brain swollen, no perfusion) causes the characteristic reverberating or oscillating pattern — forward flow in systole followed by reversed flow in diastole, with zero net cerebral perfusion per unit time. In advanced brain death this may progress to complete absence of any Doppler signal. TCD is NOT a standard component of the UK clinical brain death examination but may be used as a useful adjunct when clinical testing cannot be completed.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 34-year-old man has an unruptured AVM. Spetzler-Martin grade III (6 cm, eloquent motor cortex, superficial venous drainage). He presents after a mild seizure. The neurologist quotes the ARUBA trial. What does ARUBA show, and does it apply to this patient?",opts:["A. ARUBA showed that intervention (surgery, SRS, embolisation) is superior to medical management for unruptured AVMs of all grades","B. ARUBA randomised 226 patients with unruptured AVMs to intervention vs medical management; at 33-month follow-up, medical management had significantly fewer stroke-or-death events (10.1% vs 30.7%); limitations include short follow-up, heterogeneous intervention types, and exclusion of ruptured AVMs — high-grade (SM IV–V) AVMs may benefit more from observation; SM grade III remains controversial","C. ARUBA excluded AVMs in eloquent cortex — this patient's data is not applicable","D. ARUBA compared SRS alone vs surgery — medical management was not a study arm","E. ARUBA showed no difference between intervention and medical management"],ans:1,exp:"ARUBA (A Randomised trial of Unruptured Brain AVMs, Mohr 2014, Lancet): unruptured AVMs randomised to intervention (any combination: surgery/SRS/embolisation/combined) vs medical management alone. Stopped early: stroke/death 30.7% (intervention) vs 10.1% (medical), HR 0.27, p=0.0002. Key limitations: short follow-up (average 33 months vs lifetime AVM risk), heterogeneous interventions (some incomplete SRS), majority SM I–III. Critics argue that SM I–II AVMs that are completely cured by surgery may have better long-term outcomes than medical management. ARUBA does not cover ruptured AVMs (which have higher rebleed risk, typically favour intervention). Grade III remains the most controversial — multidisciplinary assessment required.",ref:"claude — ARUBA trial limitations",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During microsurgical AVM resection, indocyanine green (ICG) videoangiography is used intraoperatively. After apparent complete nidus excision, ICG angiography shows no residual filling of the nidus or early venous draining vein. What is the significance and what should the surgeon do next?",opts:["A. ICG confirming no residual flow means the resection is definitively complete — post-operative DSA is unnecessary","B. Intraoperative ICG showing no residual nidus or arterialized draining vein provides strong real-time confirmation of complete AVM excision; however, post-operative DSA remains the gold standard — ICG misses deep perforating feeders or small residual nidus outside the ICG imaging plane and should not replace post-operative DSA","C. ICG only detects venous flow — a negative ICG does not exclude arterial feeders; DSA is mandatory within 24 hours","D. ICG confirmation of complete resection means DSA can be deferred for 3 months — to allow haemostasis","E. A negative ICG during AVM surgery is unreliable because ICG does not cross the blood-brain barrier"],ans:1,exp:"Intraoperative ICG videoangiography: injected IV (~0.2 mg/kg), ICG binds to plasma proteins and remains intravascular; near-infrared excitation (780 nm) and emission (830 nm) allows real-time visualisation of arterial, capillary, and venous filling. For AVM surgery: confirms absence of arterial filling in residual nidus and that the previously arterialized draining vein has changed from bright arterial to normal venous pattern. ICG ADVANTAGES: immediate real-time feedback during surgery — allows on-table revision if residual nidus found. LIMITATION: field of view limited to the exposed surface; small perforating feeders or deep components may not be visualised. Post-operative DSA remains the gold standard for confirming complete obliteration before clearing the patient.",ref:"claude — ICG videoangiography in AVM surgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"peripheral-nerve":{src:"Standard neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the Sunderland classification of nerve injuries (grades 1–5)?",a:"1 (neuropraxia): conduction block, intact myelin, full recovery. 2 (axonotmesis): axonal disruption, endoneurium intact, good recovery. 3: axon + endoneurium disrupted. 4: only epineurium intact. 5 (neurotmesis): complete division — requires surgical repair.",ref:"Sunderland classification"},
{q:"What is the rate of peripheral nerve regeneration?",a:"~1mm/day (or ~1 inch/month). Used to calculate expected time to reinnervation after injury — guides timing of surgical repair. Tinel's sign advances distally as regenerating axons grow.",ref:"claude — peripheral nerve physiology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the clinical features of carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS)?",a:"Compression of median nerve at wrist. Symptoms: pain/paraesthesia in thumb, index, middle, and radial half of ring finger (median distribution). Worse at night, relieved by shaking the hand. Late: thenar wasting and weakness of thumb opposition (APB).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What nerve is compressed in cubital tunnel syndrome and what are its features?",a:"Ulnar nerve at the elbow (cubital tunnel). Symptoms: ring and little finger paraesthesia; intrinsic hand weakness (hypothenar, interossei, medial two lumbricals); clawing of ring/little fingers; Froment's sign positive.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the Tinel's sign and what does it indicate?",a:"Percussion over a regenerating nerve elicits tingling distally at the level of regenerating axon tips. Advancing Tinel's sign distal to the injury site indicates active axonal regeneration — a good prognostic sign.",ref:"claude — peripheral nerve",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the indications for nerve repair vs grafting?",a:"Primary repair (epineural or group fascicular): if ends can be approximated without tension. Nerve graft (sural nerve most common): if gap >2–3cm preventing tension-free repair. Conduits: small diameter sensory gaps <3cm.",ref:"claude — peripheral nerve surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2) — genetics, hallmark, and associated tumours?",a:"Autosomal dominant. Mutation in NF2 tumour suppressor gene (chromosome 22q12) encoding merlin/schwannomin. Hallmark: bilateral vestibular schwannomas (present in up to 90%). Also: meningiomas (multiple), ependymomas (especially cervical), other schwannomas. Presents in adolescence/young adulthood.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.1",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
{q:"Why are traditional treatments for NF2-related vestibular schwannomas unsatisfactory?",a:"Surgery: damages the vestibular nerve — often causes deafness. High risk in bilateral disease (contralateral ear may be the only hearing ear). Stereotactic radiosurgery (Gamma Knife): facial nerve weakness, trigeminal neuropathy, vestibular dysfunction, increased risk of secondary malignancy. Neither treats both tumours definitively; neither offers hearing preservation reliably.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.1",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What is the biological rationale and dosing for bevacizumab in NF2-related vestibular schwannomas?",a:"Vestibular schwannomas overexpress VEGF-1 (vascular endothelial growth factor). Bevacizumab is a humanised monoclonal antibody against VEGF — anti-angiogenic, originally approved for colorectal and breast cancer. Dose in NF2: 5 mg/kg IV every 2 weeks (infusion 90 min initially, reduced to 30 min). Scheduled for up to 1 year in Mautner 2010.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.2",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
{q:"What tumour volume changes and hearing outcomes were seen with bevacizumab in Mautner 2010?",a:"Both patients: >40% tumour volume reduction. Patient 1 (6 months): left VS 10.4→5.9 mL (43% reduction), brainstem compression relieved, significant hearing improvement (subjective + objective — able to converse by phone again). Patient 2 (3 months): right VS 7.3→4.3 mL (41% reduction); NO hearing improvement yet at 3 months. Hearing improvement appears time-dependent — evident at 6 months but not at 3.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.3",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
{q:"Which tumours respond and which do not respond to bevacizumab in NF2 (Mautner 2010)?",a:"RESPOND: progressive vestibular schwannomas (>40% volume regression in both patients). ALSO RESPONDED (unexpected): syrinx associated with intramedullary tumour substantially decreased. DID NOT RESPOND: meningiomas (not in a progressive phase); intramedullary tumours themselves. The authors propose bevacizumab works on tumours in an active growth phase with high VEGF expression.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.4",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A patient has radial nerve injury after humeral shaft fracture. No recovery at 3 months. Next step?",opts:["A. Observe 6 more months","B. NCS and EMG to assess recovery","C. Immediate surgical exploration","D. Tendon transfer","E. Amputation"],ans:1,exp:"NCS/EMG at 3 months can detect early reinnervation (nascent motor units) before clinical signs. If no evidence of reinnervation at 3–6 months, surgical exploration/repair/grafting should be considered.",ref:"claude — peripheral nerve surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 24-year-old with NF2 has a 4 cm right vestibular schwannoma with progressive brainstem compression. The left VS was resected 3 years ago resulting in total left hearing loss — the right ear is her only hearing ear. Surgery carries a very high risk of deafness. What medical treatment may induce tumour regression and preserve hearing?",opts:["A. Dexamethasone","B. Bevacizumab 5 mg/kg IV every 2 weeks","C. Temozolomide chemotherapy","D. Imatinib (Gleevec)","E. No medical treatment is effective — re-attempt surgery"],ans:1,exp:"Bevacizumab (anti-VEGF monoclonal antibody) induces >40% vestibular schwannoma volume regression in NF2 patients (Mautner 2010; Plotkin 2009 NEJM). The biological rationale: VS overexpress VEGF-1. Dose: 5 mg/kg IV q2 weeks. Hearing improvement is seen at 6 months. Benefits: postpones surgery, may improve hearing preservation if surgery later required. Side effects: hypertension (most common), epistaxis/bleeding risk, thromboembolism. Erlotinib (EGFR inhibitor) is an alternative but requires daily oral dosing with more skin toxicity.",ref:"Mautner 2010, p.4",src_id:"k-mautner-2010",korky:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old motorcyclist has complete loss of median nerve function after a forearm laceration. Surgical exploration 4 weeks later shows complete nerve transection. Which nerve injury classification and management applies?",opts:["A. Neuropraxia — focal demyelination with intact axons; spontaneous recovery expected within weeks without surgery","B. Axonotmesis — axons disrupted but sheath intact; regeneration occurs without surgical repair","C. Neurotmesis — both axon and sheath disrupted; surgical repair is required","D. Axonotmesis — requires emergency re-exploration within 24 hours","E. Neuropraxia — surgical repair needed to restore the myelin sheath"],ans:2,exp:"Neurotmesis = complete disruption of axon AND epineurium (as in transection). Surgical repair (direct suture or nerve grafting) is required — regeneration rarely restores normal function without it. Neuropraxia: focal conduction block, axons intact, recovers spontaneously (days–weeks). Axonotmesis: axons disrupted but sheath intact — Wallerian degeneration distally, but preserved sheath guides regeneration (1 mm/day, ~1 inch/month) without surgery. EMG is not useful within 3 weeks of injury. Delayed repair (3–8 weeks) often preferred over immediate — allows tissue viability assessment, stronger epineurium for suturing.",ref:"Bank, p.14",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"Nerve conduction studies are performed on a 45-year-old woman with a 6-month history of numbness and tingling in the thumb, index, and middle fingers, worse at night and relieved by shaking. Which NCS finding most reliably confirms carpal tunnel syndrome?",opts:["A. Prolonged motor distal latency >4.5 ms in the median nerve","B. Prolonged median sensory distal latency >3.7 ms across the wrist — the most sensitive early NCS finding in CTS","C. Absent median SNAP (sensory nerve action potential)","D. Reduced amplitude of median motor CMAP","E. Slowed median nerve conduction velocity in the forearm segment"],ans:1,exp:"Sensory nerve conduction across the wrist is the most sensitive NCS parameter for early CTS. Sensory distal latency >3.7 ms (at 14 cm, antidromic or orthodromic) is the diagnostic threshold. In mild CTS, motor studies may be normal. Motor distal latency >4.5 ms indicates more severe involvement. The segmental slowing is localised to the carpal tunnel (wrist-to-palm) — the forearm segment is unaffected. Absent SNAP indicates severe or longstanding CTS. NCS confirms the diagnosis and grades severity: mild (sensory only), moderate (motor DL prolonged), severe (absent SNAP).",ref:"claude — carpal tunnel syndrome NCS criteria",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old has left foot drop after a proximal fibular fracture. Examination shows: weak ankle dorsiflexion, weak toe extension, reduced sensation on the dorsum of the foot. Ankle eversion is also weak. Which nerve is injured?",opts:["A. L5 nerve root — weak dorsiflexion + weak eversion + reduced dorsal foot sensation","B. L4 nerve root — ankle dorsiflexion weakness, but eversion is preserved","C. Common peroneal nerve — divides into deep (dorsiflexion) and superficial peroneal (eversion); injury above the division causes both dorsiflexion AND eversion weakness + dorsal foot sensory loss","D. Deep peroneal nerve alone — causes dorsiflexion weakness and first web-space numbness; eversion is preserved","E. Superficial peroneal nerve alone — causes eversion weakness and dorsolateral foot sensory loss"],ans:2,exp:"Eversion is the key discriminator in foot drop: Eversion is performed by peroneus longus/brevis, innervated by the SUPERFICIAL PERONEAL nerve (branch of the common peroneal nerve). DEEP PERONEAL: dorsiflexion + first webspace sensation — eversion PRESERVED. COMMON PERONEAL: both deep and superficial branches affected → dorsiflexion weak + eversion weak + dorsal foot sensation loss. L5 root: similar to CPN (dorsiflexion weak, eversion weak) but also causes hamstring weakness and may affect TFL; no sensory loss on dorsal foot only — medial leg may be affected. L4 root: mainly ankle dorsiflexion (via deep peroneal contribution) but eversion is PRESERVED. The presence of eversion weakness here confirms CPN or L5 (not deep peroneal alone).",ref:"claude — foot drop differential diagnosis",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 60-year-old presents with weakness of the right hand, particularly difficulty with key grip and a claw-like deformity of the ring and little fingers. Examination shows weakness of the interossei and hypothenar muscles, with intact thenar (abductor pollicis brevis) strength. There is sensory loss over the little finger and medial half of the ring finger. Which nerve is injured and at what level?",opts:["A. Median nerve at the wrist (carpal tunnel) — causes thenar wasting and thumb-index-middle numbness","B. Ulnar nerve at the elbow (medial epicondyle) — intrinsic hand muscle weakness (interossei, hypothenar), medial 1.5-finger sensory loss; thenar is spared because APB is median-innervated","C. Radial nerve at the spiral groove — causes wrist drop and dorsal hand sensory loss","D. C8/T1 nerve root — Klumpke-type palsy with Horner syndrome and bilateral hand changes","E. Anterior interosseous nerve — loss of precision pinch (FPL + FDP II/III) with no sensory loss"],ans:1,exp:"Ulnar nerve at the elbow: most common ulnar nerve entrapment site (cubital tunnel). Features: intrinsic muscle wasting (hypothenar, first dorsal interosseous, all interossei), claw hand (ring and little fingers — 'ulnar paradox': claw worse in low ulnar lesions because FDP intact), sensory loss medial 1.5 fingers and medial palm. Thenar muscles (APB, opponens, FPB superficial head) are MEDIAN-innervated — preserved in ulnar neuropathy. Key sign: Froment's sign (adductor pollicis weak → thumb flexes at IPJ when pinching). Carpal tunnel: median nerve, thenar wasting, thumb-index-middle sensory loss. Anterior interosseous: motor only (no sensory), loss of OK sign (FPL + FDP II/III).",ref:"claude — ulnar nerve anatomy / cubital tunnel",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 50-year-old presents with right shoulder pain radiating to the thumb and index finger, with numbness in those fingers. Examination reveals weakness on testing elbow flexion and brachioradialis. The biceps reflex is reduced. Which nerve root is affected and which muscle specifically tests this level?",opts:["A. C5 root — shoulder abduction weakness; deltoid tests C5","B. C6 root — weakness of elbow flexion (biceps, brachioradialis), brachioradialis specifically tests C6; sensory loss thumb and index; reduced biceps reflex","C. C7 root — triceps weakness and reduced triceps jerk; dorsal forearm and middle finger sensory loss","D. C8 root — hand intrinsics and finger flexors; ring and little finger sensory loss","E. T1 root — hand intrinsics; medial arm sensory loss; Horner syndrome if root avulsion"],ans:1,exp:"C6 radiculopathy: pain/sensory loss in the C6 dermatome (thumb, index finger, lateral forearm); motor: elbow flexion (biceps C5/C6, brachioradialis C6 > C5); the brachioradialis reflex is C6-mediated and is most specifically affected at C6 root level. ECRL (extensor carpi radialis longus) is also primarily C6 — wrist extension testing helps confirm. Biceps reflex: C5/C6 — may be reduced but is less specific. Differentiating C5 from C6: C5 affects shoulder abduction (deltoid) and biceps reflex; C6 affects brachioradialis and adds thumb/index sensory loss.",ref:"claude — C6 radiculopathy clinical features",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old develops progressive ascending limb weakness over 3 days, starting in the feet and reaching the thighs. He had a diarrhoeal illness 3 weeks ago. Reflexes are globally absent. NCS shows prolonged distal latencies and reduced nerve conduction velocities with absent F-waves. CSF shows elevated protein (2.8 g/L) with normal cell count. Which diagnosis and immediate concern apply?",opts:["A. MS relapse — treat with IV methylprednisolone","B. Guillain-Barré syndrome (acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy) — main acute risk is respiratory failure; monitor FVC closely; treat with IVIG or plasma exchange","C. Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (CIDP) — onset over years; treat with steroids","D. Botulism — descending paralysis from cranial nerves; no sensory symptoms","E. Myasthenic crisis — fatigable proximal weakness; decremental response on repetitive nerve stimulation"],ans:1,exp:"Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS): post-infectious ascending flaccid paralysis, areflexia, mild sensory symptoms. Preceding illness (Campylobacter, CMV, EBV, flu) 2–4 weeks prior is the classic trigger. CSF: albuminocytological dissociation — raised protein with normal/near-normal cell count. NCS: demyelinating pattern (prolonged DL, slow CV, absent F-waves, conduction block). Immediate risk: respiratory failure — monitor FVC (forced vital capacity) every 4 hours; intubate if FVC <20 mL/kg or falling rapidly. Autonomic instability (HR swings, BP lability) is also life-threatening. Treatment: IVIG 0.4 g/kg/day × 5 days OR plasma exchange (equal efficacy); steroids are NOT effective in GBS.",ref:"claude — Guillain-Barré syndrome diagnosis and management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During examination of the brachial plexus anatomy: a surgeon is planning resection of a posterior triangle neck tumour. Which statement about brachial plexus organisation is correct?",opts:["A. The long thoracic nerve (nerve to serratus anterior) arises from the lateral cord","B. The medial pectoral nerve arises from the posterior cord","C. The brachial plexus roots emerge between the anterior and middle scalene muscles; the C5 and C6 roots commonly unite to form the upper trunk in the posterior triangle","D. The ulnar nerve arises from the lateral cord alone","E. The musculocutaneous nerve is a terminal branch of the medial cord"],ans:2,exp:"Brachial plexus organisation: ROOTS emerge between anterior and middle scalene muscles. C5+C6 → upper trunk; C7 → middle trunk; C8+T1 → lower trunk. Each trunk divides into anterior and posterior divisions. Anterior divisions → lateral cord (C5-C7) and medial cord (C8-T1). Posterior divisions → posterior cord (C5-T1). POSTERIOR CORD: axillary + radial nerves; also upper/lower subscapular nerves and thoracodorsal nerve. LATERAL CORD: musculocutaneous nerve (C5-C7) + lateral head of median nerve. MEDIAL CORD: ulnar nerve (C8-T1) + medial head of median nerve + medial cutaneous nerves. Long thoracic nerve arises from C5, C6, C7 ROOTS directly (before trunk formation), not from cords.",ref:"claude — brachial plexus anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
]},

"paeds":{src:"Standard paediatric neurosurgical knowledge",c:[
{q:"What are the common posterior fossa tumours in children in frequency order?",a:"Medulloblastoma (most common malignant paediatric brain tumour — from the vermis); cerebellar pilocytic astrocytoma (most common overall paediatric brain tumour, best prognosis); ependymoma (floor of fourth ventricle); DIPG (diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma).",ref:"claude — paediatric neuro-oncology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the presentation of medulloblastoma and where does it arise?",a:"Midline cerebellar vermis. Presents with truncal ataxia, morning headache/vomiting (raised ICP from hydrocephalus), papilloedema. CSF seeding common. On CT: hyperdense, midline posterior fossa mass with hydrocephalus. Enhances on MRI.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the MRI features that distinguish cerebellar pilocytic astrocytoma from medulloblastoma?",a:"Pilocytic: lateral, cystic with mural nodule (enhancing nodule + non-enhancing cyst). Medulloblastoma: midline/vermian, solid, hyperdense on CT. Both cause hydrocephalus. Pilocytic has excellent prognosis with complete resection.",ref:"claude — paediatric neuroradiology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is Chiari I malformation and how does it present?",a:"Tonsillar herniation >5mm below foramen magnum. Presents with suboccipital headache (worse with Valsalva/cough), neck pain, myelopathy, syringomyelia (50%), lower cranial nerve deficits. Management: posterior fossa decompression (craniectomy + duraplasty ± C1 laminectomy).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the difference between Chiari I and Chiari II?",a:"Chiari I: tonsillar herniation >5mm, usually adults/older children, associated with syringomyelia. Chiari II: caudal displacement of medulla + cerebellum + fourth ventricle through foramen magnum; associated with myelomeningocele (open spina bifida), lumbosacral myelomeningocele, and severe hydrocephalus.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is craniopharyngioma and what are its key features?",a:"Benign (WHO grade 1) epithelial tumour arising from Rathke's pouch remnants. Suprasellar location. Bimodal age: children (5–14yr) and adults (50–74yr). Presents with visual failure (bitemporal hemianopia), pituitary dysfunction, raised ICP. Calcification in 90% on CT. Two types: adamantinomatous (children) and papillary (adults).",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is deformational plagiocephaly (DP) and how does it differ from craniosynostosis?",a:"DP = skull asymmetry due to external forces (positional moulding) — NOT premature suture fusion. Classic: unilateral occipital flattening, ipsilateral ear anteriorly displaced, ipsilateral forehead prominent → parallelogram shape on bird's-eye view. Craniosynostosis: premature fusion of one or more cranial sutures causing a fixed deformity with ridging — requires surgical correction. DP does not warrant surgery in most cases.",ref:"Couture 2013, p.1",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{q:"Why did deformational plagiocephaly increase and what are the risk factors?",a:"Cause: AAP 'Back to Sleep' campaign (1992) promoted supine sleeping to prevent SIDS — SIDS fell 50% but DP incidence rose dramatically; now affects up to 1 in 5 infants. Risk factors: prematurity, breech presentation, assisted delivery, first-born child, maternal age >35, male sex.",ref:"Couture 2013, p.1",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What is the Argenta classification for deformational plagiocephaly?",a:"Type I: posterior occipital flattening only. Type II: + ipsilateral ear anterior displacement. Type III: + ipsilateral forehead prominence (bossing). Type IV: + malar asymmetry. Type V: + attempts at vertical skull decompression (temporal bossing, vertical growth). Progressive severity I→V. Type VI: central flattening — separate entity. Type I managed by repositioning; Types II-V by helmet therapy.",ref:"Couture 2013, p.2",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What are the treatment options for deformational plagiocephaly and when is each used?",a:"Observation: minimal deformity (Type I). Repositioning (counterpositioning + tummy time): mild-moderate or age <4 months — encourages neck muscle development. Helmet therapy: moderate-severe (Argenta II+), or ≥6 months if repositioning has failed. Active moulding helmet: Class V at ≥9 months, or patients >18 months. Surgery: not warranted for DP — only for true craniosynostosis.",ref:"Couture 2013, p.2",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What were the correction rates by Argenta type in Couture 2013 (n=1050)?",a:"Overall correction to Type I or 0: 81.6% (857/1050). By type: II=92.7%, III=85.0%, IV=73.2%, V=47.9%. Higher severity = lower correction rate AND longer time to correction (Type III 53% longer than II; IV 75% longer; V 81% longer; p<0.0001 for all). Prefabricated off-the-shelf helmet ($500-600) was as effective as custom helmets ($2000-4000).",ref:"Couture 2013, p.3",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{q:"What folic acid supplementation is recommended for neural tube defect (NTD) prevention?",a:"Standard: 400 micrograms (0.4 mg) daily, ideally 1 month before conception and for the first 12 weeks of pregnancy. High dose (5 mg daily): previous NTD-affected pregnancy, family history, antiepileptic drugs (valproate, carbamazepine), diabetes, obesity (BMI >30), malabsorption. The neural tube closes by day 28 of gestation — supplementation must begin BEFORE conception. Most NTDs occur in women on standard intake who simply haven't started early enough.",ref:"claude — folic acid / NTD prevention (NICE)",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What are the diagnostic criteria and key eye findings in neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1)?",a:"NIH criteria: ≥2 of: (1) ≥6 café-au-lait macules (>5mm prepubertal, >15mm adult); (2) ≥2 neurofibromas or 1 plexiform neurofibroma; (3) axillary/inguinal freckling (Crowe's sign); (4) optic pathway glioma; (5) ≥2 Lisch nodules; (6) distinctive bony lesion (sphenoid dysplasia, tibial cortical thinning); (7) first-degree relative with NF1. Eye: Lisch nodules = dome-shaped melanocytic iris hamartomas on slit-lamp, asymptomatic, present in >90% of adults with NF1. Optic pathway glioma (pilocytic astrocytoma) in ~15% of NF1.",ref:"claude — NF1 diagnostic criteria (NIH consensus)",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{q:"What are the 4 molecular subtypes of medulloblastoma and which has the best prognosis?",a:"1) WNT-activated (~10%) — BEST prognosis (low risk, >90% 5-yr EFS); mandatory β-catenin (CTNNB1) mutation testing. 2) SHH-activated, TP53-wildtype (~20%) — standard risk in most cases. 3) SHH-activated, TP53-mutant (~10%) — high risk. 4) Non-WNT/non-SHH group 3 (~25%) and group 4 (~35%, most common) — standard to high risk. 4 histological types: classic, desmoplastic/nodular (D/N), extensive nodularity (MBEN), large cell/anaplastic (LC/A — worst).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p747",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{q:"What is the Chang (M) staging system for medulloblastoma and what staging workup is required?",a:"M0 = no metastasis; M1 = microscopic tumour cells in CSF; M2 = gross nodular seeding in cerebellar/cerebral subarachnoid space or 3rd/lateral ventricles; M3 = gross nodular seeding in spinal subarachnoid space; M4 = metastasis outside CNS. Required staging: MRI entire neuraxis (brain + spine) with gadolinium — ideally PRE-op or within 2–3 weeks post-op — PLUS post-operative LP for CSF cytology. 10–35% have seeded at diagnosis.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p748–749, Table 43.1",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{q:"What distinguishes medulloblastoma from ependymoma on imaging in the posterior fossa?",a:"Medulloblastoma protrudes into the 4th ventricle from the POSTERIOR ROOF (fastigium — apex of the roof); typically midline/vermian, solid, hyperdense on CT. Ependymoma more commonly arises from the FLOOR or lateral recesses of the 4th ventricle and may extend through the foramina of Luschka ('plastic' ependymoma). Both enhance; calcification occurs in ~20% of medulloblastoma.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p748",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 9-year-old has morning headaches, vomiting, truncal ataxia, and papilloedema. MRI shows a midline posterior fossa mass involving the vermis with obstructive hydrocephalus. Most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Pilocytic astrocytoma","B. Medulloblastoma","C. Ependymoma","D. DIPG","E. Craniopharyngioma"],ans:1,exp:"Medulloblastoma: midline vermian location, solid, truncal ataxia, obstructive hydrocephalus. Hyperdense on CT. CSF seeding common. Most common malignant posterior fossa tumour in children.",ref:"claude — paediatric neuro-oncology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 7-year-old has a lateral cystic posterior fossa mass with an enhancing mural nodule. Obstructive hydrocephalus present. Most likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Medulloblastoma","B. Ependymoma","C. Pilocytic astrocytoma","D. DIPG","E. Haemangioblastoma"],ans:2,exp:"Cerebellar pilocytic astrocytoma: lateral, cystic with enhancing mural nodule — classic appearance. Most common paediatric brain tumour overall. Excellent prognosis with complete resection (WHO grade 1).",ref:"claude — paediatric neuroradiology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 14-month-old is referred with Argenta Type III deformational plagiocephaly. The parents were told by their GP that helmet therapy is too late as the fontanelle has closed. What does the evidence show?",opts:["A. The GP is correct — helmet therapy is ineffective after 9 months","B. Helmet therapy can still be offered up to 18 months — time to correction is not significantly different from younger infants","C. Surgery should be offered at this stage","D. Helmet therapy is effective only up to 12 months, after which correction rates fall to zero","E. Repositioning alone is adequate at this age"],ans:1,exp:"Couture 2013 (n=1050): patients in the >12 month group did NOT have significantly longer time to correction than the <3 month group. Overall correction rate was 81.6%; Type III specifically corrected in 85% with passive helmet therapy. The study supports helmet therapy from birth to 18 months of age. Earlier treatment optimises outcome, but age alone is not a contraindication. The fontanelle closure threshold is not supported by this data.",ref:"Couture 2013, p.4",src_id:"k-couture-2013",korky:true},
{stem:"Which of the following is NOT commonly associated with myelomeningocele?",opts:["A. Hydrocephalus requiring CSF diversion in the majority of affected infants","B. Chiari II malformation","C. A midline dorsal spinal mass with skin, bone, and dural defects apparent at birth","D. Mandatory permanent urinary incontinence — all patients will be incontinent regardless of treatment","E. Tethered spinal cord requiring surgical release if neurological deterioration develops with growth"],ans:3,exp:"Myelomeningocele is associated with hydrocephalus (~85%), Chiari II malformation (cerebellar tonsil/brainstem herniation through the foramen magnum), and the visible dorsal midline sac at birth with exposed neural placode. Tethered cord does occur and may require surgical release. HOWEVER, mandatory permanent urinary incontinence is NOT universal — the majority of patients can achieve social urinary continence through clean intermittent self-catheterisation (CISC), exploiting residual dysmorphic bladder innervation.",ref:"Bank, p.7",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 2-year-old is referred with skin markings over the lower back. Which of the following is NOT a recognised cutaneous stigma of occult spinal dysraphism warranting spinal MRI?",opts:["A. Midline lumbar capillary haemangioma","B. Focal hairy patch (hypertrichosis) over the thoracolumbar spine","C. Dermal sinus located above the midsacrum","D. Midline subcutaneous lipoma","E. Café-au-lait spot over the thoracolumbar spine"],ans:4,exp:"Café-au-lait spots are associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 (>6 spots ≥1.5 cm in adults) — NOT spinal dysraphism. The four genuine cutaneous stigmata of occult dysraphism mandating MRI are: (1) midline capillary haemangioma, (2) focal hairy patch/hypertrichosis, (3) dermal sinus above the midsacrum (a coccygeal/pilonidal sinus is benign — only sinuses above the midsacrum overlie potential intradural pathology), (4) midline subcutaneous lipoma. All four may overlie tethered cord, lipomyelomeningocele, or diastematomyelia.",ref:"Bank, p.7",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old woman with a previous child born with a lumbosacral myelomeningocele is planning another pregnancy. What folic acid advice is correct?",opts:["A. Standard 400 micrograms daily, start at 6 weeks gestation","B. 5 mg daily, starting at least 1 month before conception, continuing for the first 12 weeks","C. 400 micrograms daily, starting 1 month before conception","D. 5 mg daily only after a positive pregnancy test in the first trimester","E. No supplementation — myelomeningocele is not caused by folate deficiency"],ans:1,exp:"Women with a previous NTD-affected pregnancy require HIGH-DOSE folic acid: 5 mg daily (vs standard 400 mcg). Must start at least 1 month before conception — the neural tube closes by day 28, before most women know they are pregnant. Continue for the first 12 weeks. Other high-risk groups for 5 mg: antiepileptics (valproate, carbamazepine), diabetes, malabsorption, family history, obesity (BMI >30).",ref:"claude — high-dose folic acid / NTD recurrence prevention",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old woman who is 12 weeks pregnant undergoes a routine first-trimester anomaly scan. Appearances are consistent with a lumbosacral neural tube defect. The couple ask whether starting high-dose folic acid immediately could prevent further progression of the defect or reduce its severity. What is the most accurate advice?",opts:["A. Start 5 mg folic acid daily now — it may still reduce the severity of an established NTD in the second trimester","B. Start 400 micrograms folic acid daily — standard supplementation is still beneficial after the first trimester","C. Folic acid supplementation cannot help at this stage — the neural tube closes by day 28 of gestation, well before the current gestational age","D. Refer urgently for fetal in-utero surgery to repair the defect — this is the only intervention that prevents myelomeningocele-related disabilities","E. Folic acid has no established role in preventing neural tube defects"],ans:2,exp:"The neural tube forms and closes during the first 4 weeks of gestation: the anterior neuropore closes approximately day 25, and the caudal neuropore closes around day 28. At 12 weeks' gestation, the neural tube has been closed — or failed to close — more than 8 weeks earlier. Folic acid supplementation must begin BEFORE conception (ideally at least 1 month before) to be effective. Commencing supplementation at 12 weeks cannot influence an NTD that formed in the first 4 weeks. The couple should be counselled about the diagnosis, management of MMC (surgical closure within 36 hours of birth), associated conditions (Chiari II, hydrocephalus in 65–85%), and the recurrence risk — which mandates 5 mg folic acid daily before the next conception.",ref:"Greenberg, p.280–281",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A neonate is born at term with an open lumbosacral myelomeningocele (MMC). The parents ask about likely associated conditions and the recommended timing of surgical closure. Which of the following correctly describes MMC associations and immediate management?",opts:["A. Chiari I malformation (tonsillar herniation >5 mm); hydrocephalus requiring CSF diversion in ≈20%; closure can safely be deferred to 2–4 weeks of age","B. Chiari II malformation; hydrocephalus requiring CSF diversion in 65–85% of affected infants; latex allergy in 73%; MMC should be closed within 36 hours of birth","C. Chiari II malformation; hydrocephalus in only 10–20%; latex allergy in <5%; closure within 72 hours is standard","D. No cerebellar malformation is associated with open MMC; hydrocephalus affects 50%; closure within 5 days is acceptable","E. Chiari I malformation; hydrocephalus requiring CSF diversion in 85%; closure ideally within 6 hours of birth"],ans:1,exp:"MMC associations: (1) Chiari II malformation — NOT Chiari I. Chiari II involves caudal displacement of the medulla, pons, fourth ventricle, and cerebellum through the foramen magnum; it is present in virtually all MMC patients. (2) Hydrocephalus develops in 65–85% of patients with thoracolumbar MMC, most requiring CSF diversion. (3) Latex allergy: 73% of MMC patients are sensitised to latex due to repeated mucosal exposure during urological procedures — a latex-free environment is mandatory from birth. (4) Closure timing: MMC should be closed within 36 hours of birth. Delay increases the risk of ventriculitis, meningitis, and neurological deterioration. Hydrocephalus is treated after MMC closure, usually within days to weeks.",ref:"Greenberg, p.281–295",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 10-year-old girl presents with progressive visual field loss and symptoms of growth failure over 3 months. MRI shows a suprasellar cystic and solid mass. CT demonstrates nodular calcification within the cyst wall. The team suspect adamantinomatous craniopharyngioma. Which statement about this tumour type is correct?",opts:["A. It occurs almost exclusively in adults aged 40–55 years and carries BRAF V600E mutations in 81–95% of cases","B. It shows a bimodal age distribution (peaks at 5–15 years and 45–60 years); 90% of cases demonstrate at least two of: cyst formation, prominent calcification, and contrast enhancement in the cyst walls","C. It is typically solid with rare calcification and arises primarily from the infundibular recess of the floor of the third ventricle","D. It is associated with CTNNB1 mutations but rarely calcifies, unlike papillary craniopharyngioma which calcifies in >90%","E. It is associated with BRAF V600E mutations and a bimodal age distribution identical to papillary craniopharyngioma"],ans:1,exp:"Adamantinomatous craniopharyngioma (ACP) key facts: (1) Bimodal age distribution — childhood peak 5–15 years, adult peak 45–60 years. (2) Molecular: ≥95% show CTNNB1 mutations and aberrant nuclear β-catenin expression (absent in papillary CP). (3) Imaging 'ninety-percent rule': 90% of ACPs show at least 2 of the 3 'C' features — Cyst formation, prominent Calcifications, and Contrast enhancement in cyst walls. Cyst fluid usually contains cholesterol crystals. Compare with papillary craniopharyngioma (PCP): adults only (mean age 40–55); 81–95% carry BRAF V600E mutations; typically solid or partially cystic; rarely calcified; arises from infundibular recess of the 3rd ventricle floor. Both are WHO grade 1 but now considered molecularly and histologically distinct tumours.",ref:"Greenberg, p.849–851",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 7-year-old boy presents with a 6-week history of head tilt to the right noticed by parents and teachers. The optometrist finds his eyes are normal and he denies diplopia. On examination he has a broad-based gait and cannot walk in a straight line. He had no recent throat infection or trauma. What is the most appropriate first investigation?",opts:["A. X-ray cervical spine — to exclude atlantoaxial instability","B. Neuro-ophthalmology referral — to assess for an occult fourth nerve palsy as the cause of compensatory head tilt","C. MRI brain with gadolinium — to exclude a posterior fossa mass","D. MRI cervical spine — to exclude C1–2 subluxation or intrinsic cord tumour","E. Ultrasound neck — to look for cervical lymphadenopathy (Grisel syndrome)"],ans:2,exp:"Head tilt in a child has multiple causes: (1) Ocular — compensatory tilt for fourth (trochlear) nerve palsy to reduce diplopia; (2) Posterior fossa tumour — cerebellar involvement produces ipsilateral head tilt and cerebellar ataxia; (3) Craniocervical junction pathology — atlantoaxial subluxation (Down syndrome, JIA, post-URTI Grisel syndrome); (4) Inflammatory lymphadenopathy. The key features pointing to a posterior fossa mass in this child are the neurological signs: broad-based ataxic gait without diplopia, localising to the cerebellum rather than the cervical spine or eye. Tumours to consider include medulloblastoma (midline vermis, truncal ataxia), pilocytic astrocytoma (lateral, cystic), and ependymoma. MRI brain with gadolinium is the priority. C-spine imaging is appropriate if the brain MRI is normal and history favours a cervical cause.",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 2-year-old girl undergoes surgical exploration for an anorectal anomaly. Pre-operative MRI shows a hemisacrum (partial sacral agenesis) and a presacral cystic mass. What is the diagnosis and the most important aspect of management?",opts:["A. Spinal muscular atrophy — no presacral mass is expected; this is an incidental finding","B. Currarino triad (hemisacrum + anorectal malformation + presacral mass) — the presacral mass must be excised and histologically examined as teratomas carry malignant transformation risk","C. Caudal regression syndrome — no surgical treatment is needed for the presacral mass","D. Sacral chordoma — radical sacrectomy is required immediately","E. Spina bifida occulta — the presacral cyst is a simple epidermoid and can be observed"],ans:1,exp:"Currarino triad comprises: (1) hemisacrum (scimitar-shaped partial sacral agenesis on plain X-ray or CT — the hallmark radiological sign); (2) anorectal malformation (anorectal stenosis or atresia); (3) presacral mass — which may be an anterior sacral meningocele, mature teratoma, or enteric/neurenteric cyst. It is caused by mutations in the MNX1 (HLXB9) gene on chromosome 7q36 and follows autosomal dominant inheritance with variable penetrance. The presacral mass is critical: mature teratomas have a risk of malignant transformation, and anterior meningoceles can cause meningitis if not recognised and managed appropriately. Biopsy/excision of the presacral mass is mandatory. Sacral approach (posterior) combined with abdominal approach if needed. Distinguish from isolated caudal regression syndrome (no presacral mass, no familial mutation).",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery / Currarino triad",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 5-month-old boy is brought to the emergency department by his parents after a brief seizure. CT head shows bilateral posterior fossa subdural collections and bilateral frontoparietal subdural haematomas of mixed density. There is no history of trauma. The parents' account is inconsistent. On examination he has macrocephaly and frontotemporal atrophy on imaging. Which metabolic diagnosis must be excluded as a mimic of non-accidental injury before attributing these findings to abuse?",opts:["A. Phenylketonuria — causes progressive brain damage but not subdural haematomas","B. Glutaric aciduria type 1 (GA1) — causes bilateral SDH in infancy without trauma, due to fragile bridging veins over frontotemporal atrophy","C. Maple syrup urine disease — causes cortical oedema but not subdural collections","D. Congenital hypothyroidism — a common cause of atraumatic SDH in infants","E. Methylmalonic acidaemia — invariably fatal in infancy; survivors have no subdural collections"],ans:1,exp:"Glutaric aciduria type 1 (GA1) is an autosomal recessive organic aciduria (glutaryl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency) that can closely mimic non-accidental injury. Key features: (1) macrocephaly in early infancy due to frontotemporal atrophy and enlarged subarachnoid spaces, which stretches bridging veins; (2) bilateral subdural haematomas occurring after trivial or no trauma; (3) may have retinal haemorrhages; (4) metabolic crises triggered by intercurrent illness producing acute striatal injury. The diagnosis is made by urine organic acid analysis (elevated glutaric and 3-hydroxyglutaric acids) or blood acylcarnitine profile (elevated C5-DC). GA1 must be excluded by metabolic testing before a formal diagnosis of NAI is made — failure to do so has led to miscarriages of justice. Other mimics of NAI include: external hydrocephalus (benign enlargement of subarachnoid spaces), haemophilia, and rarely hereditary spherocytosis.",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery / metabolic mimics of NAI",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 3-year-old girl presents with macrocephaly, developmental delay, and a sunset sign. MRI shows a large suprasellar arachnoid cyst compressing the third ventricle and obstructing the foramina of Monro, causing obstructive hydrocephalus. She has bitemporal visual field defects. What is the preferred surgical treatment?",opts:["A. VP shunt to the arachnoid cyst cavity — to drain the cyst independently of the ventricular system","B. Craniotomy and open microsurgical excision of the cyst wall","C. Endoscopic ventriculocystostomy — fenestrating the cyst wall into the lateral ventricle endoscopically, combined with ETV where feasible","D. Conservative management with serial imaging — suprasellar arachnoid cysts resolve spontaneously in most children before age 5","E. Transcallosal microsurgical marsupialization into the third ventricle"],ans:2,exp:"Suprasellar arachnoid cysts (SAC) cause symptoms by compressing the third ventricle and optic apparatus, producing obstructive hydrocephalus, visual failure, and endocrine dysfunction. The preferred surgical treatment is endoscopic ventriculocystostomy — creating a fenestration between the cyst cavity and the ventricle endoscopically, often combined with endoscopic third ventriculostomy (ETV) to treat the associated hydrocephalus. This avoids an indwelling shunt with its lifetime failure and revision risk. VP shunting of the cyst alone has a high recurrence rate and does not address the ventricular hypertension. Open craniotomy is reserved for failed endoscopic attempts. Expectant management is not appropriate when visual field defects and developmental delay are already established.",ref:"claude — paediatric neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 3-month-old girl presents with her first focal motor seizure affecting the right arm and face. On examination, there is a port-wine stain (capillary vascular malformation) covering the entire left forehead and upper eyelid. MRI brain with gadolinium shows left parieto-occipital leptomeningeal enhancement. CT shows early gyral calcification in the left occipital region. What is the diagnosis and which medications should be commenced?",opts:["A. Tuberous sclerosis complex — start vigabatrin; the skin lesion is an ash-leaf hypopigmented macule","B. Sturge-Weber syndrome — start an antiepileptic drug and low-dose aspirin (antiplatelet therapy); refer ophthalmology to screen for glaucoma","C. Neurofibromatosis type 1 — the skin lesion is a café-au-lait macule; start carbamazepine","D. PHACE syndrome — the skin lesion is a segmental haemangioma; refer for cardiac and aortic arch imaging","E. Incontinentia pigmenti — the skin lesion is a linear vesicular rash; no antiepileptic is needed at first seizure"],ans:1,exp:"Sturge-Weber syndrome (encephalotrigeminal angiomatosis): (1) Port-wine stain (PWS) in the V1 (ophthalmic) distribution of CN V — upper face/forehead/upper eyelid; NOT a haemangioma. (2) Ipsilateral leptomeningeal angiomatosis → reduced cortical perfusion → chronic ischaemia → cortical atrophy + 'tram-track' gyral calcification (best seen on CT). (3) Focal epilepsy (often drug-resistant). (4) Ipsilateral glaucoma in 30–50%. (5) Hemiparesis contralateral to the affected hemisphere. Management: (a) AEDs — early seizure control; (b) Low-dose aspirin (1–5 mg/kg/day) — reduces thrombotic episodes within the angioma and may reduce seizure frequency; (c) Ophthalmology referral — glaucoma monitoring and treatment. Note: NOT all infants with a V1 PWS develop Sturge-Weber — MRI is used to identify leptomeningeal involvement.",ref:"claude — Sturge-Weber syndrome",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 7-year-old child with Sturge-Weber syndrome has intractable seizures despite three antiepileptic drugs, with multiple seizures daily, progressive hemiparesis, and significant cognitive decline. MRI shows extensive left hemisphere leptomeningeal angiomatosis with marked cortical atrophy. What surgical option should now be considered?",opts:["A. Continue trying further antiepileptic medications — Sturge-Weber always responds eventually to pharmacotherapy","B. Functional hemispherectomy (or hemispherical disconnection) — may achieve seizure freedom and prevent further cognitive decline; earlier surgery optimises neuroplasticity","C. Stereotactic radiosurgery to the area of maximal leptomeningeal angioma","D. Ventriculoperitoneal shunt to reduce ventricular pressure","E. Systematic bevacizumab infusions to reduce angioma vascularity"],ans:1,exp:"Drug-resistant epilepsy in Sturge-Weber with progressive cognitive decline and hemiparesis is an indication for surgical evaluation. Options: (1) FUNCTIONAL HEMISPHERECTOMY or hemispherical disconnection (peri-insular hemispherotomy): disconnects the affected hemisphere, preventing seizure propagation while preserving eloquent function in the contralateral hemisphere. Seizure freedom in ~60–70% of cases. KEY PRINCIPLE: early surgery (before established severe cognitive decline, while neuroplasticity is maximal) gives the best cognitive outcomes — the contralateral hemisphere reorganises language and motor function more effectively in younger children. Delay worsens prognosis. (2) Focal cortical resection: if the epileptogenic zone is well-localised and distinct from eloquent cortex — less common in Sturge-Weber as the angioma is usually extensive. Aspirin and AEDs continue as adjuncts post-surgery. Radiosurgery is not established as treatment for Sturge-Weber.",ref:"claude — Sturge-Weber syndrome / hemispherectomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 5-year-old presents with a persistent 'cock-robin' head position — head rotated to the left with the chin tilted down and to the right — for 12 days following a bout of tonsillitis. He is now afebrile. There is no history of trauma or neck injury. Palpation reveals left SCM spasm. Plain X-ray of the cervical spine shows atlantoaxial asymmetry. What is the most likely diagnosis and appropriate initial management?",opts:["A. Muscular torticollis from SCM fibrosis — physiotherapy and Botox injection","B. Atlantoaxial rotatory fixation (Grisel syndrome) — initial management: NSAIDs and a soft collar; if no resolution within 1 week, halter traction; dynamic CT C-spine is diagnostic","C. C1–2 fracture-dislocation — immediate operative stabilisation","D. Acute bacterial meningitis — LP and IV antibiotics","E. Posterior fossa tumour causing compensatory head tilt — urgent MRI brain"],ans:1,exp:"Atlantoaxial rotatory fixation (AARF) / Grisel syndrome: (1) Pathophysiology: C1 rotates on C2 and becomes fixed due to inflammatory ligamentous laxity following pharyngeal infection (tonsillitis, adenoiditis, otitis media) or head-neck surgery (e.g. adenoidectomy). (2) Presentation: 'cock-robin' posture — contralateral rotation and ipsilateral tilt of the head to the contracted SCM; persistent >7 days; child resists correction. (3) Investigation: DYNAMIC CT C-SPINE is diagnostic — shows fixed C1 rotation on C2 (no correction despite head movement). (4) Classification (Fielding): Type 1 = rotatory fixation without anterior displacement (ADI ≤3 mm, most common). (5) Management: Acute (<1 month): NSAIDs, soft collar, analgesics — spontaneous resolution common. No resolution at 1 week: soft halter traction (in-patient). Chronic (>3 months) or neurological deficit: halo traction followed by C1–2 fusion if reduction not maintained. MRI only if neurological signs suggest cord compromise.",ref:"claude — atlantoaxial rotatory fixation / Grisel syndrome",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A neonate delivered by forceps develops a boggy swelling over the right parietal bone. The swelling is first noticed 12 hours after birth, is firm and well-demarcated, and does not cross the midline or the coronal suture. Which statement about diagnosis and management is correct?",opts:["A. Caput succedaneum — crosses suture lines; present at birth; managed by surgical drainage","B. Cephalhaematoma — subperiosteal blood collection contained by sutural attachments; does NOT cross suture lines; re-aspiration is NOT recommended as it significantly increases infection risk; resolves spontaneously over weeks to months","C. Cephalhaematoma — does not cross sutures; requires urgent surgical drainage to prevent skull erosion","D. Subgaleal haemorrhage — does not cross sutures; requires blood transfusion in most cases","E. Cephalhaematoma — resolves within 48 hours; aspiration is recommended at 3–4 weeks to prevent calcification"],ans:1,exp:"Cephalhaematoma: haemorrhage between the periosteum and the outer skull table (subperiosteal). Key feature: periosteum fuses firmly to bone at suture lines → collection is strictly CONTAINED within one cranial bone and DOES NOT CROSS SUTURE LINES. Delayed presentation (6–24 hours) because subperiosteal bleeding is slow. Usually parietal. Commonly after forceps/vacuum delivery. Resolution: spontaneous over weeks to months — may calcify leaving a bony ridge (usually remodels by age 1–2 years). MANAGEMENT: no aspiration/drainage — aspiration risks introducing infection into the haematoma (osteomyelitis risk). Jaundice from haematoma resorption may require phototherapy. DISTINGUISH FROM: (1) Caput succedaneum — crosses sutures, present at BIRTH, within soft tissues ABOVE the periosteum (subcutaneous oedema), resolves within 48–72 hours; (2) Subgaleal haemorrhage — crosses sutures, within the galeal space, can accumulate massively (entire scalp), causes hypovolaemic shock — DANGEROUS.",ref:"claude — cephalhaematoma / neonatal scalp swellings",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 25 kg child is admitted after a posterior fossa tumour resection. You are calculating the appropriate daily maintenance intravenous fluid volume using the Holliday-Segar formula. What is the correct calculation?",opts:["A. 1000 ml/day (100 ml/kg for the full 25 kg)","B. 1200 ml/day","C. 1500 ml/day","D. 1600 ml/day (1000 + 500 + 100)","E. 2500 ml/day (100 ml/kg × 25 kg)"],ans:3,exp:"Holliday-Segar formula: First 10 kg → 100 ml/kg/day = 1000 ml. Next 10 kg (10–20 kg) → 50 ml/kg/day = 500 ml. Each additional kg above 20 kg → 20 ml/kg/day. For a 25 kg child: 1000 + 500 + (5 × 20) = 1000 + 500 + 100 = 1600 ml/day. As a continuous infusion: 1600 ÷ 24 ≈ 67 ml/hour. Quick formula for children >20 kg: 1500 + [20 × (weight − 20)]. For 25 kg: 1500 + 100 = 1600 ml/day. Neurosurgical note: in post-craniotomy paediatric patients, use isotonic (0.9% NaCl ± 5% glucose) fluids — hypotonic solutions risk hyponatraemia and cerebral oedema. Target euvolaemia. Adjust for fever (+12% per 1°C above 37°C), excess losses (e.g. significant CSF drainage), or fluid restriction if raised ICP.",ref:"claude — Holliday-Segar paediatric fluid requirements",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 9-year-old boy presents with bitemporal hemianopia and intermittent morning headaches. MRI shows a smooth-walled, non-enhancing, CSF-intensity cyst in the suprasellar cistern causing obstructive hydrocephalus. There is no solid enhancing component. What is the surgical treatment of choice?",opts:["A. Ventriculoperitoneal shunt — diverts CSF downstream and is the simplest treatment","B. Endoscopic cisternoventriculostomy (fenestration of the cyst into the ventricular system)","C. Open pterional craniotomy and cyst excision","D. Ommaya reservoir placement with periodic aspiration every 4–6 weeks","E. Conservative surveillance with annual MRI — most suprasellar cysts resolve spontaneously"],ans:1,exp:"Symptomatic suprasellar arachnoid cysts causing hydrocephalus or neuro-ophthalmic/endocrine symptoms are best managed by endoscopic fenestration (cisternoventriculostomy) — a stoma is created between the cyst and the ventricular system, equalising CSF pressure without implanting a permanent shunt. VP shunting alone addresses downstream hydrocephalus but leaves the cyst intact with risk of shunt dependence and cyst re-expansion if the shunt fails. Open craniotomy carries greater morbidity. Ommaya reservoirs are reserved for intracystic drug delivery in cystic tumours, not structural cysts. An enhancing mural nodule would change the diagnosis to craniopharyngioma and alter management.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 12-year-old with known neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) attends ophthalmology review. Which of the following ocular findings is LEAST likely to be associated with NF1?",opts:["A. Lisch nodules (melanocytic iris hamartomas)","B. Optic pathway glioma causing progressive visual loss","C. Pulsatile exophthalmos from sphenoid wing dysplasia","D. Choroidal hamartomas visible on infrared scanning","E. Uveal melanoma"],ans:4,exp:"NF1 ocular features: Lisch nodules (pathognomonic iris hamartomas present in >90% of adults), optic pathway gliomas (15–20%, usually pilocytic astrocytoma, often in the chiasm/optic nerve), pulsatile exophthalmos from sphenoid wing dysplasia (orbital wall absent → pulsating globe), and choroidal hamartomas. Uveal (ocular) melanoma is NOT a recognised feature of NF1 — it is associated with ocular melanocytosis and BAP1 germline mutations. NF2 (not NF1) is associated with posterior subcapsular lens opacities ('snowflake' cataracts). The NF1 recall question asks specifically about which eye finding is NOT included — melanoma is the correct answer.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 6-year-old girl is investigated for constipation since infancy and is found on plain X-ray to have a 'scimitar sacrum' — partial agenesis of the sacrum forming a curved sickle shape. What triad of associated anomalies should be actively excluded?",opts:["A. Sacral agenesis, lumbosacral lipomyelomeningocele, and Chiari II malformation","B. Partial sacral agenesis, presacral mass (anterior sacral meningocele or teratoma), and anorectal malformation — the Currarino triad","C. Sacral agenesis, tethered spinal cord by thickened filum terminale, and syringomyelia","D. Sacral agenesis, caudal regression syndrome from maternal diabetes, and single umbilical artery","E. Hemisacral agenesis, Chiari I malformation, and hydrosyringomyelia"],ans:1,exp:"Currarino triad (autosomal dominant, MNX1 gene): (1) partial sacral agenesis — the 'scimitar' or hemisacrum; (2) presacral mass — anterior sacral meningocele, mature teratoma, or enteric cyst; (3) anorectal malformation — imperforate anus, anal stenosis, or rectovaginal fistula. Any child with a hemisacrum should have MRI of the lumbar spine and pelvis to identify a presacral mass before biopsy or surgery (inadvertent biopsy of an anterior meningocele causes meningitis). Constipation since infancy is the most common presenting feature. Chiari II and lipomyelomeningocele are associated with open NTDs, not hemisacral agenesis.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 27-week preterm neonate develops progressive post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus (PHH) after bilateral grade III intraventricular haemorrhage. Head circumference is crossing centiles upward. The ventricular index is above the P97 line. The infant weighs 980g. What is the most appropriate management strategy?",opts:["A. Urgent VP shunt insertion — delay causes progressive white matter injury","B. Serial lumbar punctures (20 mL/kg per tap) as the primary definitive treatment","C. Oral acetazolamide and furosemide to reduce CSF production until spontaneous resolution","D. Ventricular access device (Ommaya reservoir or subgaleal shunt) to drain CSF temporarily until the infant reaches sufficient size and CSF protein normalises for definitive shunting","E. Conservative management — PHH resolves spontaneously in the majority of premature neonates without intervention"],ans:3,exp:"PHH in preterm neonates requires a BRIDGING STRATEGY: the infant is too small (<1.5 kg) and medically fragile for a definitive VP shunt, but progressive ventricular enlargement demands treatment to protect white matter. A ventricular access device (VAD — Ommaya reservoir or subgaleal shunt) allows controlled CSF drainage until the infant reaches ~1.5–2 kg and CSF protein falls (<1.5g/L) to allow permanent shunt insertion. Serial LPs bridge time but are ineffective for obstructive PHH and do not prevent shunt dependence. Acetazolamide + furosemide (UKISS trial) was shown to cause MORE neurological harm than benefit in preterm PHH and should NOT be used. Spontaneous resolution occurs in <15% of progressive PHH — conservative management is inappropriate.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 5-month-old boy is brought to the emergency department. His parents report he has been 'off' for 24 hours. He has no reported history of trauma. On examination, bilateral subdural haematomas of mixed density (acute on chronic) are found on CT. Dilated fundoscopy confirms bilateral retinal haemorrhages. Skull X-ray shows a healing right parietal fracture. What is the single most important immediate action?",opts:["A. Urgent craniotomy for evacuation of the acute-on-chronic subdural collection","B. Notify the paediatric safeguarding team, secure the child in a place of safety, initiate SCAN team referral, and contact the police","C. Discuss birth injury as the likely explanation with the parents","D. Discharge with urgent MRI arranged by the GP and outpatient follow-up","E. Arrange haematology review to exclude bleeding diathesis before any safeguarding referral"],ans:1,exp:"The constellation of bilateral subdural haematomas (acute on chronic = multiple injury episodes), retinal haemorrhages, and a healing skull fracture in an infant with no reported trauma history is the classic presentation of non-accidental injury (NAI). The immediate priority is safeguarding: notify the safeguarding lead, secure the child (place of safety), initiate the SCAN (Suspected Child Abuse and Neglect) team referral, and involve police. Haematology screening (to exclude bleeding diathesis) is an important investigation — but must NOT delay safeguarding action, as the child remains at ongoing risk. Craniotomy is rarely indicated for NAI SDHs. Birth injury is not a credible explanation for a healing skull fracture in a 5-month-old.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old woman has a 5-year-old son with Down syndrome (trisomy 21) and is planning another pregnancy. She asks her GP whether taking folic acid before conception will reduce the risk of having another child with Down syndrome. Which advice is most accurate?",opts:["A. Yes — 5mg folic acid daily for 3 months pre-conception reduces the risk of chromosomal trisomies","B. Yes — 400 micrograms daily is standard and reduces the risk of all common congenital abnormalities including Down syndrome","C. No — folic acid prevents neural tube defects (NTDs) caused by failure of neural tube closure; it does not reduce the risk of trisomy 21 (which arises from meiotic non-disjunction); genetic counselling and pre-natal diagnosis are the appropriate referrals","D. Yes — 5mg folic acid is indicated because Down syndrome has a neural tube component","E. No — folic acid supplementation is only indicated after a previous pregnancy with an NTD; no supplementation is needed here"],ans:2,exp:"Folic acid supplementation reduces the risk of NEURAL TUBE DEFECTS (NTDs: spina bifida, anencephaly) — which arise from failure of neural tube closure in weeks 3–4 of embryonic development. It has NO effect on chromosomal trisomies such as Down syndrome (trisomy 21), which result from meiotic non-disjunction during oogenesis. Standard pre-conception folic acid: 400 micrograms/day for low-risk women; 5mg/day for HIGH-RISK NTD situations (previous NTD pregnancy, maternal epilepsy on anti-epileptics, high BMI, diabetes). For a previous child with Down syndrome: the appropriate advice is genetic counselling, karyotyping of the couple, and discussion of pre-natal diagnostic options (chorionic villus sampling, amniocentesis).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 10-year-old boy has a large craniopharyngioma. MRI shows a mixed solid-cystic mass with the solid component intimately adherent to the floor of the third ventricle and hypothalamus. Bilateral temporal hemianopia is present; visual acuity is 6/9 bilaterally. At MDT, which management approach is most likely to produce the best long-term outcome?",opts:["A. Aggressive gross total resection — complete removal avoids radiotherapy and has the best disease-free survival","B. Biopsy only — craniopharyngioma is benign; observation and serial MRI are appropriate","C. Planned subtotal resection or cyst decompression, followed by adjuvant radiotherapy — avoids catastrophic hypothalamic injury while achieving equivalent local tumour control","D. Stereotactic radiosurgery alone — avoids open surgery entirely in a child","E. Intracystic bleomycin for all craniopharyngiomas regardless of morphology"],ans:2,exp:"Aggressive gross total resection (GTR) for craniopharyngioma adherent to the hypothalamus carries a high risk of 'hypothalamic syndrome': severe obesity, hyperphagia, diabetes insipidus, cognitive impairment, and sleep disorders — a profoundly quality-of-life-impairing complication. Contemporary evidence supports a shift to planned SUBTOTAL RESECTION (or cyst decompression to restore vision) followed by adjuvant RADIOTHERAPY: this achieves equivalent local control rates to GTR while substantially reducing hypothalamic morbidity. Intracystic bleomycin is used for selected predominantly cystic lesions in some centres. The exam trap is defaulting to GTR as the oncological reflex — the discrimination is recognising when NOT to operate radically.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During repair of a thoracic myelomeningocele, the neurosurgeon needs to identify the neural placode before reconstructing the neural tube. In the unfolded thoracic MMC placode, where are the dorsal column fibres located?",opts:["A. Centrally — adjacent to the central canal, maintaining their normal dorsomedial position","B. Dorsally — on the exposed outer surface of the placode, facing the surgeon","C. Laterally — displaced to the lateral margins of the unfolded placode because the cord has opened outward","D. Ventrally — the placode is fully inverted so dorsal columns face the sac floor","E. Absent — the placode contains no identifiable dorsal column fibres"],ans:2,exp:"In myelomeningocele, the neural tube fails to close and everts ('unfolds') into an open placode. The normal dorsal surface becomes the exposed outer (superficial) surface — the pia mater is on the outside. As the cord unfolds laterally, structures that are normally POSTERIOR (dorsal columns) are displaced to the LATERAL margins of the placode. The ventral surface (anterior horn cells, motor roots) is deepest. This anatomy matters for repair: the central canal is opened and the placode is re-tubularised, bringing the lateral margins (dorsal columns) together to reform the dorsal cord. Preserving these lateral fibres is essential to maintain sensory function. The exposed outer surface is pial, not the dorsal column itself.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 5-year-old child is brought to the emergency department with a 3-week history of progressive head tilt to the right noticed by his parents. There is no history of trauma. Eye movements are full. He is apyrexial with no lymphadenopathy. Neck movements are restricted but gait is unaffected. What is the most appropriate initial investigation?",opts:["A. Plain X-rays of the cervical spine — to exclude atlantoaxial rotatory fixation","B. MRI brain and cervical spine — to exclude posterior fossa tumour, intrinsic cord lesion, or Chiari malformation","C. CT head — to exclude hydrocephalus","D. Blood cultures, CRP, and ESR — to exclude infectious aetiology","E. Physiotherapy referral — head tilt in children is almost always benign muscular torticollis"],ans:1,exp:"Unexplained head tilt in a child without trauma and without clear diagnosis requires MRI of the brain and cervical spine to exclude: (1) posterior fossa tumour (medulloblastoma, ependymoma, astrocytoma) — tumours can cause head tilt via CN IV palsy, cerebellar asymmetry, or tonsillar herniation; (2) Chiari I malformation with or without syringomyelia; (3) intrinsic brainstem or cervical cord lesion. Plain X-ray may show atlantoaxial asymmetry (AARF) but misses intracranial pathology — it is not sufficient as the sole investigation. CT head irradiates the lens and posterior fossa is poorly seen. Blood cultures are appropriate if fever/adenopathy suggests infection, but this child is apyrexial.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A term neonate, delivered by forceps, has a 1.5 cm smooth depression of the right parietal bone noted on examination at 12 hours of life. The neonate is alert, feeding normally, and has no neurological deficit. CT head shows a 'ping-pong ball' fracture with no intracranial haemorrhage and no indriven bone fragment. What is the most appropriate management?",opts:["A. Urgent surgical elevation in theatre under general anaesthesia — the depression must be corrected within 24 hours","B. Bedside vacuum extraction using a breast pump or paediatric vacuum device to elevate the fracture","C. Conservative management — observe neurologically; most ping-pong fractures remodel spontaneously within weeks to months without intervention","D. Transfer to tertiary centre for neurosurgical craniectomy and custom plate fixation","E. Lumbar puncture to exclude subarachnoid haemorrhage before deciding on management"],ans:2,exp:"Ping-pong skull fractures are greenstick-type depressions of the neonatal skull without bone penetration or intracranial injury, typically caused by forceps delivery or prolonged pressure in utero. In a neurologically intact neonate with no intracranial haemorrhage, conservative management is appropriate — the highly compliant neonatal skull remodels spontaneously under intracranial pressure over weeks to months in most cases. Surgical intervention is reserved for: persistent depression not remodelling by 3–4 weeks, underlying intracranial haematoma requiring evacuation, or neurological deficit. Bedside vacuum elevation is used in some centres but is not universally first-line. The trap is option A — surgical urgency is not warranted in a neurologically intact neonate with an uncomplicated greenstick depression.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 3-month-old with known myelomeningocele and a functioning VP shunt suddenly develops stridor, apnoeic episodes, and poor feeding. MRI confirms Chiari II malformation with posterior fossa crowding. What is the FIRST step in management?",opts:["A. Immediate posterior fossa decompression under general anaesthesia","B. Check shunt function — plain shunt series and CT head to assess ventricular size","C. Emergency intubation and tracheostomy planning","D. Halter cervical traction","E. High-dose dexamethasone to reduce posterior fossa oedema"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg key concept for symptomatic Chiari II: 'always check the shunt first.' Brainstem symptoms in an MMC patient may be caused by shunt malfunction (raised ICP transmitted to the posterior fossa) rather than primary brainstem compression. Only after confirming a functioning shunt should expeditious posterior fossa decompression be considered.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p305",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the most common presenting symptom of Chiari I malformation?",opts:["A. Progressive arm weakness and wasting","B. Syringomyelia-related dissociated sensory loss ('cape' distribution)","C. Suboccipital headache, often exacerbated by cough or Valsalva (tussive headache), present in 69% of cases","D. Downbeat nystagmus","E. Hydrocephalus with papilloedema"],ans:2,exp:"Pain is the most common symptom (69%), especially headache felt in the suboccipital region, typically exacerbated by neck extension or Valsalva including coughing (tussive headache). Weakness is present in 56%, numbness 52%. 15–30% of patients with adult Chiari I are asymptomatic.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p297–299",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Regarding MRI diagnosis of Chiari I malformation, which statement about tonsillar descent criteria is most accurate?",opts:["A. Tonsillar descent >5mm is pathognomonic; the diagnosis cannot be made without this finding","B. Tonsillar descent >5mm below the foramen magnum is often cited but is neither essential nor diagnostic of the condition — clinical correlation is required","C. Tonsillar descent of any degree below the foramen magnum confirms Chiari I","D. Both tonsils must descend >10mm for a confident diagnosis","E. The medulla must also be displaced below the foramen magnum in all cases"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg: 'cerebellar tonsillar herniation on MRI: criteria vary, >5mm below the foramen magnum is often cited, but is neither essential nor diagnostic of the condition.' Tonsillar herniation identified radiographically is of limited prognostic value and requires clinical correlation. Tonsillar descent may be asymptomatic; conversely, symptomatic Chiari I can exist without 5mm descent.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p297–300",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which feature is characteristic of Chiari type II but absent in Chiari type I?",opts:["A. Syringomyelia in 30–70%","B. Cerebellar tonsillar herniation below the foramen magnum","C. Caudal dislocation of the medulla and a medullary kink (present in 55%), with myelomeningocele in the overwhelming majority","D. Hydrocephalus in up to 9%","E. Suboccipital headache as the most common presentation"],ans:2,exp:"Table 17.1 (Greenberg): Chiari II — caudal dislocation of medulla (yes), medullary kink present in 55%, myelomeningocele rarely absent, hydrocephalus rarely absent, usual presentation is infancy with progressive HCP/respiratory distress. Chiari I — medullary dislocation unusual, medullary kink absent, myelomeningocele only may be present, usual presentation is young adult with cervical pain/headache.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p297, Table 17.1",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In a child with Chiari II malformation who has become symptomatic, which symptom is most commonly present?",opts:["A. Apnoeic spells (58%)","B. Stridor (56%)","C. Neurogenic dysphagia / swallowing difficulties (69%)","D. Opisthotonos (18%)","E. Downbeat nystagmus"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg Table of findings in symptomatic Chiari II: swallowing difficulties (neurogenic dysphagia) 69% — most common; apnoeic spells 58%; stridor 56%; aspiration 40%; arm weakness 27%; opisthotonos 18%. Neonates present more severely than older children.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p306",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the approximate rate of complete or near-complete symptom resolution following posterior fossa decompression for symptomatic Chiari II malformation in a series of operated patients?",opts:["A. 20%","B. 40%","C. 55%","D. 68%","E. 90%"],ans:3,exp:"Greenberg (p307): '68% had complete or near-complete resolution of symptoms, 12% had mild to moderate residual deficits, and 20% had no improvement. In general, neonates fared worse than older children.' Overall mortality in operated patients at follow-up was 37.8%. Bilateral vocal cord paralysis was a particularly poor prognostic indicator.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p307",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Anencephaly results from failure of closure of which embryonic structure, and what is the recurrence risk in subsequent pregnancies?",opts:["A. Posterior (caudal) neuropore; 1% recurrence risk","B. Anterior (rostral) neuropore; 3% recurrence risk","C. Notochordal canal; 5% recurrence risk","D. Roof plate of the rhombencephalon; 10% recurrence risk","E. Neural crest dorsal migration; 0.5% recurrence risk"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p310): Anencephaly (AKA exencephaly) is due to failure of fusion of the anterior neuropore. Neither the cranial vault nor scalp covers the partially destroyed brain. Uniformly fatal. Risk of recurrence in future pregnancies: 3%. Myelomeningocele — the most common open NTD — is most common in the lumbar region.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p310",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What neural tube defect risk is associated with maternal valproic acid use during pregnancy, and what effect does carbamazepine have?",opts:["A. Valproic acid 0.1% NTD risk; carbamazepine no additional risk","B. Valproic acid 1–2% NTD risk; carbamazepine doubles the incidence of myelomeningocele","C. Valproic acid 5% NTD risk; carbamazepine halves the incidence","D. Valproic acid 10% NTD risk; carbamazepine has same risk as valproic acid","E. Both drugs carry identical 2–3% NTD risk"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p315): Valproic acid during pregnancy is associated with a 1–2% risk of NTD. Folate antagonists such as carbamazepine double the incidence of myelomeningocele. The MTHFR C677T polymorphism (TT genotype, ~10% of population) also increases NTD risk via reduced folate enzyme activity and elevated homocysteine.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p315",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In a woman who previously had a child with a neural tube defect, what dose of folic acid is recommended and what reduction in NTD recurrence has been demonstrated?",opts:["A. 0.4 mg/day; 25% reduction in recurrence","B. 2 mg/day; 45% reduction","C. 4 mg/day; 71% reduction in recurrence","D. 10 mg/day; 80% reduction","E. 0.4 mg/day; same benefit as in standard-risk women"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p315): 4 mg/day in a carrier or woman with a previous child with NTD was associated with a 71% reduction in recurrence of NTD. Standard supplementation (no NTD history): 0.4 mg/day. Folate administration must begin before conception — the neural tube closes by day 28. Vitamin B12 levels should be confirmed normal.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p315",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Regarding maternal serum AFP screening for neural tube defects, which statement is most accurate?",opts:["A. Screening is performed at 10–12 weeks; sensitivity for spina bifida is 70%","B. A high maternal serum AFP (≥2 multiples of the median) at 15–20 weeks has 91% sensitivity for spina bifida and 100% sensitivity for anencephaly; closed NTDs are likely to be missed","C. AFP screening reliably detects all forms of spina bifida including skin-covered (closed) lesions","D. Ultrasound has replaced AFP as screening is unreliable","E. AFP is only useful after 28 weeks when levels are highest"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p315): Maternal serum AFP done at 15–20 weeks gestation. Sensitivity: 91% for spina bifida, 100% for anencephaly. Closed/skin-covered NTDs (≈20% of spina bifida) will likely be missed — they do not communicate with amniotic fluid. Prenatal ultrasound detects 90–95% of spina bifida cases. Amniocentesis: amniotic fluid AFP elevated with open NTDs, peaked at weeks 13–15; carries ≈6% fetal loss risk.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p315",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is craniolacunia (Lückenschädel) and with which condition is it classically associated?",opts:["A. Gyral erosions of the inner table from chronic raised ICP, associated with Chiari I","B. Round skull defects with sharp borders separated by irregularly branching bands of bone, seen in 85% of Chiari II patients on skull X-ray; NOT caused by raised ICP","C. Linear skull fractures from the birth canal, associated with forceps delivery","D. Progressive skull thinning due to hydrocephalic pressure, associated with aqueduct stenosis","E. Premature fusion of cranial sutures causing skull deformity, associated with craniosynostosis"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p306): Craniolacunia (AKA Lückenschädel) is present in 85% of Chiari II on skull films. Appearance: round defects in the skull with sharp borders, separated by irregularly branching bands of bone. It is critically NOT due to increased ICP — a common misconception. Other Chiari II skull findings: low-lying internal occipital protuberance, enlarged foramen magnum in 70%.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p306",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During suboccipital craniectomy for Chiari I malformation, what is the specific risk of removing too much occipital bone?",opts:["A. Vertebral artery injury at C1 level","B. Occipital sinus laceration causing uncontrolled haemorrhage","C. Cerebellar ptosis (cerebellar sag) — cerebellar hemispheres herniate through the enlarged foramen magnum, re-creating the compression that the surgery aimed to relieve","D. CSF fistula via the ethmoid sinuses","E. Injury to the posterior inferior cerebellar artery origin"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p309): 'Excessive removal of occipital bone may allow the cerebellar hemispheres to herniate through the FM (cerebellar ptosis AKA cerebellar sag) which may re-create the compression at the foramen magnum.' Bone removal should not exceed ~3 cm above the foramen magnum; the emphasis is to decompress the tonsils by opening the FM and the upper cervical spine inferiorly, not by widely opening the posterior fossa.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p309",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 10-year-old girl undergoes resection of a medulloblastoma. Molecular testing confirms WNT-activated subtype with CTNNB1 mutation; histology is classic; no spinal metastases on MRI. What is her risk group and approximate 5-year event-free survival?",opts:["A. Very high risk — WNT-activated tumours in girls carry the worst prognosis","B. Low risk — WNT-activated medulloblastoma has the best prognosis, 5-year EFS >90%; clinical trials are investigating reduced-dose radiotherapy","C. High risk — CTNNB1 mutation is a poor prognostic marker","D. Standard risk — WNT-activated has the same prognosis as SHH-activated TP53-wildtype","E. Risk group cannot be determined without histological subtype"],ans:1,exp:"WNT-activated medulloblastoma is the LOW-RISK group with the BEST prognosis: 5-year EFS >90%. CTNNB1 (β-catenin) mutation is MANDATORY TESTING for this subtype. Optional additional criteria: β-catenin nuclear immunopositivity and monosomy 6. Frequency: ~10% of all medulloblastomas; M:F ratio 3:1 (male predominance). Because of the excellent prognosis, clinical trials are investigating reduced-dose/reduced-volume CSI to limit long-term neurocognitive and endocrine toxicity. Compare: non-WNT/non-SHH group 4 (35%, most common) = standard risk; SHH-activated TP53-mutant = high risk.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p747–750",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A child is staged post-operatively for medulloblastoma. MRI shows a 7mm enhancing nodule in the thoracic spinal subarachnoid space. CSF cytology is negative. Using the Chang M-staging system, what is the correct M stage?",opts:["A. M0 — no evidence of metastasis","B. M1 — microscopic tumour cells in CSF","C. M2 — gross nodular seeding in cerebellar/cerebral subarachnoid space or in the 3rd or lateral ventricles","D. M3 — gross nodular seeding in spinal subarachnoid space","E. M4 — metastasis outside the CNS"],ans:3,exp:"Chang M staging: M0 = no metastasis; M1 = microscopic tumour cells in CSF; M2 = gross nodular seeding in CEREBELLAR/CEREBRAL subarachnoid space or in the 3rd or lateral ventricles; M3 = gross nodular seeding in SPINAL subarachnoid space; M4 = metastasis outside the CNS. A thoracic spinal nodule = M3. CSF cytology negative = not M1. Staging requires BOTH full neuraxis MRI (ideally pre-op or within 2–3 weeks post-op) AND post-operative LP for CSF cytology. 10–35% of medulloblastomas have disseminated at diagnosis.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p749, Table 43.1",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"On MRI, what feature most reliably distinguishes medulloblastoma from ependymoma of the posterior fossa?",opts:["A. Calcification — only ependymoma calcifies; medulloblastoma never does","B. Enhancement — only medulloblastoma enhances with gadolinium","C. Origin from the ROOF versus FLOOR of the 4th ventricle: medulloblastoma protrudes from the posterior roof (fastigium); ependymoma typically arises from the floor or lateral recesses","D. Age — medulloblastoma exclusively affects infants <2 years; ependymoma affects adults","E. T2 hypointensity — specific to medulloblastoma"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p748): MDB protrude into the 4th ventricle from the POSTERIOR ASPECT (ROOF — the fastigium, Latin for summit); ependymomas more commonly arise from the FLOOR or lateral recesses of the 4th ventricle, often extending through the foramina of Luschka (hence the 'plastic' ependymoma that squeezes through the foramina). Both tumours enhance and may calcify (~20% of MDB). Ependymoma shows heterogeneous signal due to calcification/haemorrhage. Location of origin within the 4th ventricle is the key discriminating feature on sagittal MRI.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p748",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What craniospinal irradiation (CSI) dose is used for a child with high-risk medulloblastoma (large-cell/anaplastic, M3 disease)?",opts:["A. 23.4 Gy CSI + boost to 54–55.8 Gy at primary site — standard for all medulloblastomas","B. CSI is avoided in all children <10 years because of neurocognitive toxicity","C. 54 Gy to the primary tumour + 18 Gy craniospinal axis, with adjuvant chemotherapy including cisplatin, lomustine, and vincristine","D. 36 Gy whole-brain radiotherapy only — spine irradiation is not required even with M3 disease","E. Chemotherapy alone for high-risk disease — surgery is followed by salvage RT only on relapse"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p749): High- and very-high-risk medulloblastoma: conventional fractionated CSI once daily = 54 Gy to primary tumour + 18 Gy to craniospinal axis + chemotherapy (cisplatin, lomustine, vincristine, cyclophosphamide, etoposide ± methotrexate). Standard/low-risk: reduced-dose CSI 23.4 Gy + boost to 54–55.8 Gy at primary site. In children <3–4 years with non-disseminated disease, chemotherapy can delay the need for radiotherapy in 20–40%. SHH-activated adults may respond to SMO inhibitors (vismodegib).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p749",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"What percentage of children require a permanent VP shunt following posterior fossa tumour resection for medulloblastoma?",opts:["A. <5% — hydrocephalus always resolves with tumour removal","B. 10–15%","C. 30–40%","D. 60–70%","E. >80% — permanent shunting is almost always required"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p749): 30–40% of children require permanent VP shunts following posterior fossa resection. The remaining 60–70% have resolution of hydrocephalus after tumour debulking. The risk of shunt-related tumour seeding has been quoted as high as 10–20% historically, but this is probably an overestimate. Tumour filters are now rarely used. EVDs are typically placed peri-operatively and removed once shunt independence is confirmed.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p749",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During medulloblastoma resection, the tumour is found to be firmly adherent to the floor of the 4th ventricle (brainstem) at the level of the facial colliculus. What is the correct surgical principle?",opts:["A. Aggressive bipolar coagulation and resection of the floor attachment is mandatory to achieve gross total resection — residual >1.5 cm² at the brainstem is unacceptable","B. It is better to leave a small tumour remnant on the brainstem floor than to risk causing neurological deficit by aggressive dissection","C. If the tumour invades the floor, surgery should be abandoned and radiotherapy given as primary treatment","D. Intraoperative MRI must confirm GTR — the operation should not end with any residual on the floor","E. The brainstem floor can be safely resected en bloc using a retromastoid corridor"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p749): 'Invasion of or attachment to the floor of the fourth ventricle (brainstem in the region of the facial colliculus) often limits excision. It is better to leave a small residual on the brainstem (these patients do fairly well) than it is to chase every last remnant into the brainstem (neurological deficit is more likely with this).' Residual >1.5 cm² on early post-op MRI is a prognostic marker for high-risk disease, but neurological morbidity from aggressive brainstem dissection outweighs the benefit of GTR at this location.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p749",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which combination of features classifies a medulloblastoma as STANDARD RISK in the current molecular-histological risk stratification?",opts:["A. WNT-activated, CTNNB1 mutation, classic histology, age >16 — this is LOW risk","B. Non-WNT/non-SHH group 3, classic histology, no metastases at diagnosis, total or near-total resection","C. SHH-activated, TP53-mutant, classic histology, M0 disease","D. Non-WNT/non-SHH group 4, large cell/anaplastic histology, M2 disease","E. SHH-activated, TP53-wildtype, desmoplastic/nodular histology, infant"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg Table 43.2: Standard-risk tumours require ALL of: (1) total or near-total surgical resection; (2) no CNS metastases on MRI of brain and spine; (3) no tumour cells on CSF cytology; (4) no clinical evidence of extra-CNS metastases. And classification as one of: SHH-activated TP53-wildtype with classic histology; OR non-WNT/non-SHH group 4 with classic histology and no metastases and no favourable chromosomal findings; OR non-WNT/non-SHH group 3; OR WNT with classic histology age ≥16 years (WNT <16 = low risk). Low risk: WNT-activated (any age <16), OR SHH-TP53wt infant with D/N or MBEN histology. SHH-TP53mut = high risk.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p750, Table 43.2",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 14-month-old infant presents with a rapidly growing posterior fossa mass with CSF dissemination. Histology shows poorly differentiated embryonal cells with rhabdoid morphology. Which molecular finding is diagnostic?",opts:["A. CTNNB1 (β-catenin) mutation — confirms WNT-activated medulloblastoma","B. Loss of nuclear SMARCB1 expression in tumour cells — diagnostic of atypical teratoid/rhabdoid tumour (AT/RT)","C. C19MC amplification — diagnostic of ETMR (embryonal tumour with multilayered rosettes)","D. BRAF V600E mutation — confirms papillary craniopharyngioma in this age group","E. TP53 mutation — confirms SHH-activated TP53-mutant medulloblastoma"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p754): Atypical teratoid/rhabdoid tumour (AT/RT) is diagnosed by: (1) CNS embryonal tumour with a polyimmunophenotype; AND (2) loss of nuclear SMARCB1 protein expression in tumour cells (or SMARCA4 expression loss in rare cases), OR a DNA methylation profile aligned with AT/RT. Rhabdoid cells are desirable but not essential. AT/RT accounts for 17% of embryonal tumours. Age: primarily infants — >90% <5 years; 33% ≤1 year. Location: anywhere along neuraxis; 33% have CSF dissemination at diagnosis. 3 molecular subtypes: AT/RT-SHH, AT/RT-TYR, AT/RT-MYC. Prognosis: poor. Formerly misdiagnosed as medulloblastoma.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p754–755",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"An 18-month-old is diagnosed with a large supratentorial posterior temporal mass. MRI shows a heterogeneous tumour with haemorrhage and necrosis. CSF cytology shows malignant cells. Histology returns: 'embryonal tumour with rhabdoid cells and loss of SMARCB1 nuclear expression.' What is the correct WHO grade and what is the characteristic genetics?",opts:["A. WHO grade 2 — SMARCB1 loss is a benign finding associated with low-grade ependymoma","B. WHO grade 4 — biallelic inactivation of SMARCB1 (or rarely SMARCA4) is the hallmark molecular feature of AT/RT","C. WHO grade 3 — SMARCB1 loss is the hallmark of malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumour (MPNST)","D. WHO grade 4 — SMARCB1 loss confirms ETMR with C19MC amplification","E. WHO grade 1 — the rhabdoid appearance is a benign reactive change"],ans:1,exp:"AT/RT is WHO grade 4. Key molecular feature: biallelic inactivation of SMARCB1 (also known as INI1, hSNF5, or BAF47) — a tumour suppressor gene on chromosome 22q11.2 encoding a subunit of the SWI/SNF chromatin remodelling complex. Rarely, SMARCA4 is inactivated instead. Confirmed by loss of nuclear INI1/SMARCB1 immunostaining. AT/RT occurs primarily in infants <2 years; it can arise anywhere in the neuraxis (supratentorial location more common with advancing age). 33% have CSF dissemination at presentation. Many cases were previously misdiagnosed as medulloblastoma before molecular characterisation.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p754–755",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Which type of single-suture craniosynostosis is most common, and what characteristic skull deformity does it produce?",opts:["A. Coronal synostosis — produces brachycephaly (bilateral) or anterior plagiocephaly (unilateral); accounts for 18% of CSO","B. Metopic synostosis — produces trigonocephaly with a midline ridge and hypotelorism","C. Lambdoid synostosis — rare (1–9% of CSO), produces posterior plagiocephaly or a palpable trough","D. Sagittal synostosis — the most common single-suture CSO (80% male); produces scaphocephaly or dolichocephaly with OFC near-normal but biparietal diameter markedly reduced","E. Frontosphenoidal synostosis — produces proptosis and shallow orbits as part of a craniofacial syndrome"],ans:3,exp:"Greenberg (p266): Sagittal synostosis is the MOST COMMON CSO affecting a single suture. 80% male. It produces a palpable keel-like sagittal ridge and dolichocephaly (elongated skull with high forehead/frontal bossing) or scaphocephaly ('boat-shaped skull' with prominent occiput). OFC remains close to normal, but biparietal diameter is markedly reduced. As many as 44% of patients with non-syndromic sagittal synostosis have elevated ICP. Surgical Tx: linear strip craniectomy from coronal to lambdoid suture, ideally within first 3–6 months; strip width ≥3 cm. After ≈1 yr of age, more extensive cranial remodelling is usually required.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p266–267",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 4-month-old girl has right-sided forehead flattening with elevation of the right supra-orbital margin and an asymmetric eye appearance (the right eye appears larger). What is the most likely diagnosis, and which serious complication should be actively sought?",opts:["A. Right lambdoid synostosis — risk of posterior fossa CSF collection requiring drainage","B. Positional plagiocephaly ('lazy lambdoid') — benign; treat with repositioning and physiotherapy","C. Right coronal synostosis — the elevated supra-orbital margin produces the harlequin eye sign; the orbit rotates outward and can cause amblyopia","D. Right metopic synostosis — produces trigonocephaly and hypotelorism, not an asymmetric orbit","E. Right sagittal synostosis — produces biparietal narrowing, not orbital or forehead asymmetry"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p267–268): Unilateral coronal CSO → anterior plagiocephaly: forehead on the affected side is flattened/concave above the eye; contralateral forehead is prominent. The supra-orbital margin is higher on the affected side → HARLEQUIN EYE SIGN. The orbit rotates outward on the abnormal side and can produce AMBLYOPIA — an important complication requiring ophthalmological follow-up. Bilateral coronal CSO → brachycephaly. Coronal synostosis accounts for 18% of CSO, is more common in females. Crouzon syndrome (coronal + basal sutures) and Apert syndrome (same + syndactyly) are associated syndromes — both caused by FGFR mutations and show autosomal dominant inheritance.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p267–268",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which feature most reliably distinguishes Apert syndrome from Crouzon syndrome, both of which cause craniosynostosis with FGFR mutations and autosomal dominant inheritance?",opts:["A. Crouzon has hydrocephalus as a common feature; Apert rarely has hydrocephalus","B. Apert has syndactyly of digits 2, 3, and 4 and hydrocephalus is common; Crouzon lacks digital anomalies and hydrocephalus is rare","C. Crouzon involves the sagittal suture only; Apert involves the coronal and basal sutures","D. Apert has autosomal recessive inheritance; Crouzon is autosomal dominant","E. Only Crouzon causes maxillary hypoplasia and proptosis — Apert does not affect the face"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg Table 15.4 (p271): Both Apert and Crouzon are caused by FGFR (fibroblast growth factor receptor) gene mutations and are autosomal dominant. Both cause CSO of coronal and basal skull sutures, maxillary hypoplasia, shallow orbits, and proptosis. Key distinguishing features: APERT adds (1) SYNDACTYLY of digits 2, 3, and 4 (acrosyndactyly) and (2) shortened upper extremities, and (3) HYDROCEPHALUS IS COMMON. In Crouzon, HCP is RARE. Apert is sporadic in 95% of cases (new mutations); Crouzon is sporadic in only 25%. Kleeblattschädel syndrome (cloverleaf skull): trilobular skull with craniosynostosis — may occur in isolation or with Apert's/thanatophoric dwarfism.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p271, Table 15.4",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 5-month-old infant has flattening of the right occiput. On examination, the right ear appears shifted anteriorly and there is bulging of the right cheek and forehead. Plain skull X-ray shows no sclerosis of the lambdoid suture. What is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the first-line treatment?",opts:["A. True right lambdoid synostosis — bone scan needed; early surgical strip craniectomy within 6–18 months","B. Positional plagiocephaly ('lazy lambdoid') — the anterior ear shift and parallelogram shape confirm a positional deformity; treat with repositioning and consider moulding helmet if severe","C. True right lambdoid synostosis — the anterior ear shift is the hallmark; refer immediately for craniotomy","D. Bilateral lambdoid synostosis — brachycephaly with both ears displaced anteriorly and inferiorly; urgent surgery required","E. Metopic synostosis presenting atypically — trigonocephaly must be excluded by CT"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p268): Positional (postural) plagiocephaly ('lazy lambdoid') is distinguished from true lambdoid synostosis by head shape: positional → PARALLELOGRAM shape (ipsilateral ear ANTERIORLY displaced, ipsilateral cheek and forehead bulging). True lambdoid synostosis → TRAPEZOID shape (ipsilateral ear POSTERIORLY displaced, contralateral frontal bossing). In positional plagiocephaly, skull X-ray shows no sclerosis of the lambdoid suture. First-line Tx: repositioning — place infant on unaffected side or abdomen. If repositioning fails, trial of moulding helmet (note: no controlled study has proven helmet efficacy). Surgery required in only ≈20% of true lambdoid synostosis cases; ideal age 6–18 months. Bone scan needed in equivocal cases: increased isotope uptake at synostotic suture (vs. normal uptake in positional deformity).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p268–270",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In tethered cord syndrome in children, which is the most common presenting sign or symptom, and what is the radiographic criterion for the diagnosis?",opts:["A. Bladder dysfunction (present in 40%) is most common; radiographic criterion is conus below L1","B. Cutaneous stigmata (present in 54%) is most common; criterion is filum diameter >1 mm","C. Pain (present in 37%) is most common in children; criterion is conus below L3 + filum >2 mm","D. Gait difficulty with lower extremity weakness (present in 93%) is most common; radiographic criterion is conus below L2 + filum diameter >2 mm (normal filum <1 mm)","E. Progressive scoliosis (present in 29%) is most common; radiographic criterion is conus below L4"],ans:3,exp:"Greenberg Table 16.3 (p291): Presenting signs/symptoms of tethered cord in children: gait difficulty with LE weakness 93%; sensory deficit 70%; cutaneous findings 54% (hypertrichosis 22%, sub-Q lipoma 15%); pain in back/leg/foot 37%; bladder dysfunction 40% (as sole deficit: 4%); scoliosis 29%. Radiographic criteria (p291–292): low conus medullaris BELOW L2 + thickened filum terminale >2 mm diameter (normal filum <1 mm; >2 mm is pathological). Note: tethered cord syndrome can also occur WITHOUT a low-lying conus — symptoms may be explained by 'tautness' of the cord. Radiographically, differentiate from congenitally low-lying conus (filum diameter generally normal in the latter; conus should not be below L3).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p291–292, Table 16.3",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"How does adult-onset tethered cord syndrome differ from the childhood form in terms of predominant symptoms?",opts:["A. Adults present predominantly with progressive scoliosis and foot deformities, as in the childhood form","B. Adult tethered cord most commonly presents with pain in 86% — often perianal and perineal, diffuse and bilateral; the childhood form has pain uncommonly (usually in back and legs, not perianal)","C. Childhood tethered cord is more painful (90%) than adult tethered cord (30%) because of growth-related cord traction","D. Both adult and childhood forms present identically; the distinction is age of diagnosis, not symptom pattern","E. Adult tethered cord presents with urinary frequency and urgency as the sole symptom in the majority of cases"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg Table 16.4 (p292): Adult tethered cord — PAIN in 86%, often PERIANAL & PERINEAL, diffuse and bilateral, occasionally shock-like. Motor: usually presents as leg weakness. Urological: frequency, urgency, sensation of incomplete emptying, stress/overflow incontinence. Cutaneous stigmata in <50% (vs 80–100% in childhood). Aggravating factors: trauma, manoeuvres stretching the conus, lumbar spondylosis, disc herniation, spinal stenosis. Childhood tethered cord — pain UNCOMMON; usually in back and legs, NOT perianal/perineal. Motor: gait abnormalities, regression of gait training. Foot deformities are COMMON in childhood (progressive cavovarus, club foot) but NOT SEEN in adults. Outcome of surgical release: adult form — good for pain relief (50% improvement after first release) but POOR for return of bladder function.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p292, Table 16.4",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Before surgical untethering of the spinal cord, which pre-operative investigation is strongly recommended by Greenberg, even in a patient who appears clinically continent?",opts:["A. Pre-operative electromyography of the anal sphincter — to document baseline neurophysiology","B. Intraoperative neuromonitoring setup (MEP and SSEP) — must be confirmed before skin incision","C. Cystometrogram — post-operative changes in bladder function are not uncommon (possibly due to stretching of lower cauda equina fibres), and baseline urodynamics must be documented","D. CT myelogram — to define the exact level of cord tethering before surgery","E. MRI of the whole spine with gadolinium — to exclude concurrent syrinx at every level"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p292): 'Preoperative cystometrogram is strongly recommended, especially if the patient seems continent (postoperative changes in bladder function are not uncommon, possibly due to stretching of the lower fibres of the cauda equina).' Intra-operative electrical stimulation and recording of anal sphincter EMG are more definitive for identifying the filum terminale from nerve roots (the filum is identified by: a characteristic squiggly vessel on its surface; whiter appearance under microscope; ligamentous-like strands running through it). Surgical principle: if only abnormality is a thickened, shortened filum → limited lumbosacral laminectomy + division of filum once identified. In MM, re-tethering after untethering is common; CSF leak rate post-op: 15%.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p292",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which statement correctly distinguishes Type I from Type II split cord malformation (SCM)?",opts:["A. Type I (diplomyelia): two hemicords in a single dural tube, separated by a fibrous septum; skin stigmata common in two-thirds","B. Type II (diastatomyelia): two hemicords each in a separate dural tube with a bony osseo-cartilaginous septum; spina bifida occulta at the split level","C. Type I (diastatomyelia): two hemicords each with its own central canal, in separate dural tubes, separated by a bony osseo-cartilaginous septum; two-thirds have overlying skin stigmata (nevi, hypertrichosis, lipoma, dimple, haemangioma) and neurogenic foot deformity","D. Both types are identical radiologically; distinction is made by genetics only","E. Type I is treated by filum section alone; Type II requires bony septum removal and dural reconstitution"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p292–293): TYPE I SCM (=diastatomyelia): two hemicords, each with own central canal and pia, EACH WITHIN A SEPARATE DURAL TUBE, separated by a DURAL-SHEATHED RIGID OSSEO-CARTILAGINOUS (BONY) MEDIAN SEPTUM. Abnormal spine at the level of the split (absent disc, dorsal hypertrophic bone). 2/3 have skin stigmata. Orthopedic foot deformity (neurogenic high arches) common. Treatment: untethering + REMOVE BONY SEPTUM + reconstitute dura as single tube. TYPE II SCM (=diplomyelia): two hemicords WITHIN A SINGLE DURAL TUBE, separated by a NON-RIGID FIBROUS SEPTUM. Usually NO spine abnormality at the split level, but spina bifida occulta in lumbosacral region. Treatment: untethering at spina bifida occulta level, occasionally at split level.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p292–293",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During surgery for Type I split cord malformation (diastatomyelia), at what point in the operation should the tethered filum be divided?",opts:["A. The filum should be divided first to release cord tension — this makes it safer to then remove the bony septum","B. The filum and bony septum should be divided simultaneously under direct vision","C. The bony median septum must be removed and the dura reconstituted as a single tube BEFORE the tethered filum is cut — cutting the filum first allows the cord to retract up against the septum","D. Division of the filum is a separate staged procedure, performed 6 weeks after bony septum removal","E. In Type I SCM the filum does not require division — only the bony septum needs to be removed"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p292): ✖ 'DO NOT cut the tethered filum until after the median septum is removed to avoid having the cord retract up against the septum.' This is a cardinal intraoperative rule for Type I SCM. Sequence: (1) start at normal anatomy and work toward the defect (these spines are often distorted and rotated); (2) remove bony septum; (3) reconstitute dura as a single tube; (4) THEN divide the filum. Additional notes: in Type I, symptoms are most commonly due to cord tethering and usually improve with untethering. The spines are often very distorted — always begin at normal anatomy above and below the level of the split.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p292–293",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"What are the three components of the classic Dandy-Walker malformation triad, and what is the reported frequency of hydrocephalus in this condition?",opts:["A. Complete absence of cerebellar vermis + enlarged posterior fossa + aqueductal stenosis; hydrocephalus in <20%","B. Callosal dysgenesis + cystic 4th ventricle dilation + hydrocephalus; hydrocephalus in 50%","C. Absent/hypoplastic cerebellar vermis + cystic dilation of the 4th ventricle projecting posteriorly + hydrocephalus; hydrocephalus present in 75–95%","D. Cerebellar tonsillar herniation below the foramen magnum + cystic posterior fossa + hydrocephalus; hydrocephalus in 40%","E. Absent cerebellar vermis + lissencephaly + hydrocephalus; hydrocephalus in 60%"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p272): Classic Dandy-Walker malformation (DWM) triad: (1) complete or near-complete ABSENCE OF THE CEREBELLAR VERMIS; (2) CYSTIC DILATION OF THE 4TH VENTRICLE projecting posteriorly; (3) HYDROCEPHALUS present in 75–95%. Incidence: 1 per 25,000–35,000 live births. Posterior fossa is often enlarged → elevated tentorium and torcula-lambdoid inversion (torcular Herophili above the lambdoid suture — opposite of normal). Associated CNS anomalies: callosal dysgenesis 17–33%, occipital encephalocele 7%, heterotopias, polymicrogyria, aqueductal stenosis. Treatment: shunting of cyst and/or ventricles (usually both), or endoscopic cyst fenestration; ETV if aqueduct is open. Outcome: 50% cognitively impaired; ataxia and spasticity common; seizures in 15%.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p272",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the WHO grade, 10-year survival, and the most important surgical principle for cystic cerebellar pilocytic astrocytoma?",opts:["A. WHO grade 2; 10-year survival 70%; entire cyst including cyst wall and nodule must be resected en bloc","B. WHO grade 1; 10-year survival >95%; for a cystic PCA with enhancing mural nodule, only the nodule requires resection — the cyst wall is not neoplastic","C. WHO grade 1; 10-year survival 60%; post-operative radiotherapy is mandatory to prevent recurrence","D. WHO grade 2; 10-year survival >90%; cyst drainage is sufficient — nodule can be monitored by serial MRI","E. WHO grade 3; 10-year survival 40%; aggressive resection of all enhancing tissue is required"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p689–693): PCA is WHO GRADE 1 with 10-year survival >95% after surgical resection. Surgical principle for cystic PCA: ★ for cystic PCAs with enhancing mural nodule, only the NODULE needs to be resected — the CYST WALL IS NOT NEOPLASTIC and does not need to be removed (biopsy-proven negative for neoplasm in 3 cases). Exception: 'false cyst' where cyst wall is thick and enhancing — this neoplastic wall MUST be resected. Post-op XRT: NOT recommended routinely due to high complication rate over the long survival interval; follow with serial MRI; re-operate if recurrence occurs; XRT reserved for non-resectable recurrence or malignant histology. 94% of PCAs enhance with contrast (unlike most low-grade diffuse astrocytomas).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p689–693",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Which CNS tumour is the principal tumour associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), and what proportion of NF1 patients develop it?",opts:["A. Bilateral vestibular schwannomas — the defining tumour of NF1, occurring in >90% of patients","B. Meningioma — NF1 predisposes to multiple meningiomas; 40% lifetime risk","C. Pilocytic astrocytoma — the principal CNS tumour of NF1; 15–20% of NF1 patients develop PCA, most commonly as optic pathway gliomas","D. Ependymoma — the most common intramedullary tumour in NF1, arising in 30% of patients","E. Glioblastoma — NF1 patients have a 25% lifetime risk of high-grade transformation"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p691): Pilocytic astrocytoma (PCA) is the PRINCIPAL CNS TUMOUR associated with NF1. 15–20% of NF1 patients develop PCAs. NF1-associated PCAs are most common as optic pathway gliomas (p.694) and may be bilateral. NF1 patients have only 1 NF1 wildtype gene copy; loss of this copy by a 'second hit' (point mutation, LOH, or DNA hypermethylation) results in overactivation of RAS and MAPK pathway → PCA development. Note: BILATERAL vestibular schwannomas define NF2, not NF1. PCA is also the main tumour in Noonan syndrome and encephalocraniocutaneous lipomatosis (MAPK pathway germline mutations).",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p691",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the most common molecular alteration in pilocytic astrocytoma, and what pathway does it activate?",opts:["A. IDH1 R132H mutation — found in >80% of PCAs; used to distinguish PCA from diffuse astrocytoma","B. KIAA1549::BRAF fusion gene — activates the MAPK pathway; present in nearly all PCAs and most prevalent (75%) in cerebellar PCAs","C. MGMT promoter methylation — the key prognostic marker predicting response to temozolomide in PCA","D. EGFR amplification — the most common alteration in adult PCA; targeted by erlotinib","E. 1p/19q co-deletion — the hallmark molecular marker required for the WHO diagnosis of PCA"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p691): The most common genetic abnormality in PCAs is KIAA1549::BRAF fusion, which ACTIVATES THE MAPK PATHWAY. This alteration is involved in nearly all PCAs and is most prevalent (75%) in CEREBELLAR PCAs specifically. PCAs are the principal CNS tumour associated with NF1 — NF1 patients lose NF1 wildtype function → RAS/MAPK overactivation. Because of the high frequency of BRAF abnormalities, research is ongoing into BRAF and/or MEK inhibitors (e.g., trametinib). IDH1 mutation is characteristic of diffuse gliomas (grade 2–3), NOT pilocytic astrocytoma — IDH mutation can help distinguish PCA from infiltrating astrocytoma histologically. 1p/19q co-deletion characterises oligodendroglioma.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p691",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 10-year-old presents with headaches and cerebellar ataxia. MRI shows a posterior fossa cystic lesion with an enhancing mural nodule. What is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the characteristic histological appearance?",opts:["A. Ependymoma — characterised by perivascular pseudorosettes; arises from the floor of the 4th ventricle","B. Medulloblastoma — densely cellular with Homer Wright rosettes; arises from the roof (fastigium) of the 4th ventricle","C. Pilocytic astrocytoma — biphasic histology with compacted astrocytes containing Rosenthal fibres and loose myxoid areas with eosinophilic granular bodies","D. Haemangioblastoma — highly vascular with lipid-laden stromal cells; typically supratentorial in children","E. DNET — dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumour characterised by 'floating neurons' in a mucin-rich matrix"],ans:2,exp:"Greenberg (p689–693): The classic presentation is a cerebellar cystic lesion with an enhancing mural nodule = PILOCYTIC ASTROCYTOMA (formerly 'cystic cerebellar astrocytoma'). PCA comprises 27–40% of paediatric posterior fossa tumours. Histology is BIPHASIC: (1) compacted astrocytes with long bipolar processes ('pilocytic' = hair-like) containing ROSENTHAL FIBRES (sausage/corkscrew-shaped cytoplasmic eosinophilic inclusions of glial filament aggregates; stain bright red on Masson trichrome); (2) loose myxoid areas with stellate astrocytes, microcysts, and EOSINOPHILIC GRANULAR BODIES. Imaging: 94% enhance; little/no surrounding oedema; 66% are cystic with enhancing mural nodule. WHO grade 1; 10-year survival >95%.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p691–693",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Following incomplete resection of a pilocytic astrocytoma in a 7-year-old, the neuro-oncology team debates post-operative radiotherapy. What does Greenberg recommend?",opts:["A. Radiotherapy should be given immediately after subtotal resection — it reduces 5-year recurrence from 60% to 15%","B. Chemotherapy is preferred over radiotherapy in younger patients for residual/recurrent PCA; radiotherapy is reserved for non-resectable recurrence or malignant histology","C. Stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS) is the standard of care for residual PCA in children under 12","D. Temozolomide chemotherapy + radiotherapy (as in GBM protocol) is recommended for incomplete resections","E. Radiotherapy is contraindicated in children under 10 regardless of tumour grade"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p693): For PCA, post-op XRT is NOT recommended even after incomplete resection. Rationale: high 5- and 10-year survival rates (>95%), plus the HIGH COMPLICATION RATE of radiotherapy over this time interval. Many incompletely resected tumours enlarge minimally if at all over 5, 10, or even 20 years. Recommended approach: follow with serial CT or MRI; re-operate if recurrence occurs (re-operation is PREFERRED over XRT if possible). XRT indications: non-resectable recurrence OR recurrence with malignant histology. CHEMOTHERAPY IS PREFERABLE TO XRT IN YOUNGER PATIENTS when systemic treatment is required. Targeted therapy research: BRAF/MEK inhibitors (e.g., trametinib) under investigation due to high frequency of KIAA1549::BRAF fusions.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p693",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 5-year-old presents with weeks of headache, vomiting, and bilateral abducens palsy with right peripheral facial weakness. MRI shows a mass arising from the floor of the 4th ventricle with obstructive hydrocephalus. What is the most likely diagnosis, and why does this tumour produce these cranial nerve palsies?",opts:["A. Medulloblastoma arising from the roof (fastigium) of the 4th ventricle — cranial nerve palsies from direct invasion of the dorsal brainstem","B. Posterior fossa ependymoma arising from the floor of the 4th ventricle — invasion of the facial colliculus produces CN VI (abducens) and CN VII (peripheral facial) palsy","C. Pilocytic astrocytoma of the cerebellar hemisphere — cranial nerve involvement is rare; presents with limb ataxia","D. Choroid plexus papilloma arising from the lateral recess — characteristically causes hydrocephalus without cranial nerve palsies","E. DIPG (diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma) — cranial nerve palsies from intrinsic pontine invasion"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p728–730): Posterior fossa ependymoma most often arises from the FLOOR of the 4th ventricle. The FACIAL COLLICULUS is a small bump in the floor of the 4th ventricle produced by the INTERNAL GENU of the VII nerve as it deviates posteriorly AROUND the VI nerve nucleus. Invasion of the facial colliculus produces: (1) PERIPHERAL CN VII PALSY (from VII nerve), and (2) ABDUCENS PALSY (from VI nucleus). Compare: medulloblastoma arises from the ROOF (posterior, fastigium). Staging workup: MRI of entire neuraxis (brain + full spine) with and without contrast — 11% of posterior fossa ependymomas have drop mets to the spinal cord. Median age at presentation: 6 years.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p729–730",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Following gross total resection of a posterior fossa ependymoma in a 5-year-old, what is the recommended post-operative workup and radiotherapy approach?",opts:["A. Adjuvant chemotherapy alone — radiotherapy is avoided in all children under 10 due to neurocognitive toxicity","B. LP at 2 weeks post-op (10cc CSF for cytology for drop mets); post-op XRT to tumour bed (59.4Gy, 3D conformal); spinal XRT only if drop mets or positive CSF cytology","C. Prophylactic craniospinal irradiation (CSI) is mandatory for all ependymomas regardless of CSF cytology","D. MRI at 6 weeks post-op is sufficient — radiotherapy is deferred until recurrence","E. LP at 6 months post-op with whole-brain radiation 45Gy if CSF positive"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p731): Post-op workup: perform LP ≈2 weeks post-op, send ≈10cc CSF for cytology to quantify malignant cells (EVD-derived CSF is NOT as sensitive as LP). Radiotherapy: post-op XRT improves outcomes — 5-year survival 40–80% with XRT vs 20–40% without; 50% survival time 2 years longer with XRT. Recent recommendation: 3D conformal XRT 59.4Gy to tumour bed + 1cm margins (vs traditional 45–48Gy). Spinal XRT: only if drop mets OR positive CSF cytology (prophylactic spinal is CONTROVERSIAL). Chemotherapy: very limited role; does NOT benefit newly diagnosed cases. XRT avoided in age <3 years due to side effects — in these patients, chemotherapy may delay XRT. Ependymomas rank 2nd only to medulloblastoma in radiosensitivity.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p731–732",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the 5-year survival difference between paediatric and adult posterior fossa ependymoma, and what is the most important prognostic factor?",opts:["A. Paediatric 5-year survival 70–80%, adult 20–30%; molecular subtype (ZFTA fusion) is the most important prognosticator","B. Paediatric 5-year survival 20–30%, adult up to 80%; GROSS TOTAL RESECTION is the most important prognosticator — extent of resection correlates with OS in both adults and children","C. Paediatric and adult 5-year survival are equivalent at 50%; age has no prognostic significance","D. Paediatric 5-year survival 60%, adult 40%; post-op radiotherapy dose is the most important prognosticator","E. Paediatric 5-year survival 80%, adult 30%; the most important factor is CSF cytology at diagnosis"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p732): 5-year survival: PAEDIATRIC group 20–30% (worse prognosis with younger age, especially <24 months); ADULT group up to 80%. GTR (gross total resection) is the MOST IMPORTANT PROGNOSTICATOR for OS in both adults and children — the risk of recurrence is highest following subtotal resection. Post-op XRT (after GTR) further improves outcomes. Treatment failure: tumours tend to recur at the site of origin; 9–25% of failures are due to drop metastases. Age <24 months has significantly worse outcome (5YS lower) than age 24–35 months. NB: histopathological grading (grade 2 vs 3) is NOT highly correlated with overall outcome — molecular stratification is increasingly important.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p732",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"The most common molecular driver of supratentorial ependymoma in paediatric patients is a fusion involving which gene, and what is its clinical significance?",opts:["A. IDH1::RELA fusion — associated with favourable outcome in children","B. ZFTA (formerly C11orf95)::RELA fusion — accounts for 66–84% of paediatric supratentorial ependymomas; associated with worse outcome compared to other ependymoma subtypes","C. KIAA1549::BRAF fusion — the principal driver of pilocytic astrocytoma, occasionally seen in ependymoma","D. YAP1::MAMLD1 fusion — the most common driver, associated with excellent prognosis in all ages","E. H3 K27M mutation — the hallmark of DIPG, sometimes misclassified as ependymoma"],ans:1,exp:"Greenberg (p727): Supratentorial ependymoma, ZFTA fusion-positive (formerly 'RELA fusion-positive'): ZFTA (formerly C11orf95) is most commonly fused with RELA, generating ZFTA::RELA fusion. Accounts for 20–58% of adult and 66–84% of PAEDIATRIC supratentorial ependymomas. Homozygous deletion of CDKN2A/CDKN2B is an independent risk factor for worse OS in ZFTA::RELA-fused ependymomas. L1CAM and p65 (RELA) immunoreactivity are desirable diagnostic markers. Prognosis: worse outcome than other ependymoma subtypes (preliminary data). Compare: YAP1::MAMLD1 fusion — isolated to young children, M:F 0.3:1, 6–7% of paediatric supratentorial ependymomas, FAVOURABLE prognosis.",ref:"Greenberg 10e, p727–728",src_id:"greenberg",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"neuro-icu":{src:"Standard neurocritical care knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the Monro-Kellie doctrine?",a:"The cranial vault is a rigid box with fixed volume (brain ~80%, blood ~10%, CSF ~10%). An increase in one component must be compensated by reduction in another. Once compensatory mechanisms are exhausted, ICP rises exponentially with small volume increases.",ref:"Monro-Kellie doctrine"},
{q:"What is the normal ICP and what defines raised ICP?",a:"Normal ICP: 5–15 mmHg. Raised ICP: >20 mmHg consistently. Treat if sustained >20–25 mmHg. Target CPP (MAP−ICP) ≥60 mmHg in adults.",ref:"claude — ICP physiology",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the first-line and second-line treatments for raised ICP after TBI?",a:"First-line: head elevation 30°; analgesia/sedation; temperature control; normocapnia; EVD drainage; treat seizures. Second-line: osmotherapy (mannitol 0.25–1g/kg or hypertonic saline); induced barbiturate coma; decompressive craniectomy; therapeutic hypothermia.",ref:"claude — ICP management",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the signs of brain herniation syndromes?",a:"Uncal (transtentorial): ipsilateral CN III palsy (pupil dilation) then contralateral hemiparesis — then Cushing's triad. Cushing's triad: hypertension + bradycardia + irregular respirations (late sign of severe raised ICP).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What was the Santarius 2009 trial and what was the key result?",a:"Single-centre RCT (Cambridge, Lancet 2009). 215 patients with chronic subdural haematoma (CSDH) undergoing burr-hole evacuation, randomised to subdural drain vs no drain. Stopped early by DSMB due to significant benefit. Recurrence: drain 9.3% (10/108) vs no drain 24% (26/107), p=0.003. 6-month mortality: drain 8.6% vs no drain 18.1%, p=0.042.",ref:"Santarius 2009, Lancet, p.1",src_id:"k-santarius-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What surgical technique was used in the Santarius CSDH trial?",a:"Two 14mm burr holes ~7cm apart over maximum haematoma width. Dura opened with cruciate incision and coagulated with bipolar. Subdural space washed out with warm Ringer's lactate. Drain group: soft silicone drain (4.7mm external diameter) inserted into subdural space, tunnelled ≥5cm, connected to dependent collection bag for 48 hours then removed.",ref:"Santarius 2009, Lancet, p.2-3",src_id:"k-santarius-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What was the level of evidence from Santarius 2009 for CSDH drain use?",a:"Level 1 evidence (RCT) that a subdural drain after burr-hole evacuation of CSDH is safe and reduces recurrence (9.3% vs 24%, p=0.003) and 6-month mortality (8.6% vs 18.1%, p=0.042). No increase in surgical or medical complications. Trial stopped early. This is the strongest evidence for drain use in CSDH.",ref:"Santarius 2009, Lancet, p.1",src_id:"k-santarius-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What are the key epidemiological facts about CSDH from Santarius 2009?",a:"Incidence: ~5/100,000/year general population; 58/100,000/year for age ≥70. Expected to increase as elderly population doubles by 2030. Mainly affects elderly. Recurrence after surgical evacuation: 5-30% without drain. Three surgical techniques: twist-drill craniostomy, burr-hole craniostomy (most popular), and craniotomy.",ref:"Santarius 2009, Lancet, p.1",src_id:"k-santarius-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What did the Santarius trial show about complications of drain use in CSDH?",a:"Medical and surgical complications were similar between drain and no-drain groups. Drain insertion was judged safe in the vast majority — only 4 of 269 screened patients were excluded because drain insertion was judged unsafe preoperatively, and 14 had no room in the subdural space. No excess morbidity from drain use.",ref:"Santarius 2009, Lancet, p.1, p.4",src_id:"k-santarius-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the difference between mannitol and hypertonic saline for ICP?",a:"Both are osmotic agents. Mannitol: causes diuresis (may worsen hypovolaemia), contraindicated if hypotensive. Hypertonic saline: expands intravascular volume, does not cause diuresis — preferred if hypotensive. Both reduce brain water osmotically.",ref:"claude — ICP — osmotherapy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the criteria for decompressive craniectomy in TBI?",a:"Refractory raised ICP (>25mmHg for >1h) despite maximal medical treatment, with salvageable brain. Large contralateral SDH removal also an indication. DECRA and RESCUEicp trials showed reduced mortality but more survivors with severe disability.",ref:"DECRA / RESCUEicp trials"},
{q:"What ventilation targets are used in neurocritical care?",a:"Target: PaO₂ >13 kPa (avoid hypoxia); PaCO₂ 4.5–5.0 kPa (normocapnia). Hyperventilation (PaCO₂ 3.5–4.0 kPa) causes cerebral vasoconstriction — brief use for acute herniation only. Avoid hypocapnia <3.5 kPa (severe vasoconstriction → ischaemia).",ref:"claude — neurocritical care",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What was the key finding of Sivakumar 1994 regarding hyponatraemia in neurosurgical patients?",a:"All 21 patients with hyponatraemia + natriuresis were hypovolaemic (none hypervolaemic), supporting cerebral salt wasting (CSW) over SIADH as the predominant cause. Fluid replacement corrected hyponatraemia in all patients within 72 hours.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.1",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"How does SIADH differ from cerebral salt wasting (CSW) in volume status?",a:"SIADH = hypervolaemic/euvolaemic (dilutional hyponatraemia, fluid overload). CSW = hypovolaemic (renal sodium loss → water follows → volume depletion). Both share: low serum Na, low serum osmolality, high urine Na, urine osm > serum osm. Key differentiator: CVP and volume status.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.1, p.5",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"What is the correct treatment for CSW vs SIADH?",a:"CSW: fluid + salt replacement (isotonic saline >50 ml/kg/day + oral salt 12 g/day). If anaemic (Hct <33%): blood transfusion. SIADH: fluid restriction (800 ml/day). Sivakumar showed most neurosurgical hyponatraemia is CSW, so fluid restriction is usually wrong and potentially harmful.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.2",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"Why is fluid restriction dangerous in neurosurgical patients with hyponatraemia?",a:"Wijdicks et al. showed that 21 of 44 SAH patients with hyponatraemia managed with fluid restriction developed cerebral infarction. Most neurosurgical patients with hyponatraemia are hypovolaemic (CSW), so fluid restriction worsens hypovolaemia and risks ischaemia.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.5",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"How is volume status assessed in Sivakumar's protocol for neurosurgical hyponatraemia?",a:"CVP measurement (bedside, practical): CVP ≤5 cm saline = hypovolaemia; CVP 6–10 = normal; CVP >13 = hypervolaemia. Total blood volume (Cr-51 labelled RBCs): <60 ml/kg = hypovolaemia (normal 65–75). CVP correlates well with blood volume in non-critically ill patients.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.2",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"What are the biochemical inclusion criteria shared by both SIADH and CSW?",a:"Serum Na <130 mEq/L; urine spot Na >20 mEq/L; serum osmolality <270 mOsm/kg; urine osmolality > serum osmolality; normal adrenal, thyroid, renal, and liver function. These criteria alone cannot distinguish SIADH from CSW — volume status is required.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.1",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"What is Vingerhoets' classification of neurosurgical hyponatraemia by timing?",a:"Acute syndrome (<3 days post-insult): elevated serum ADH, responds to fluid restriction (may be true SIADH). Delayed syndrome (>1 week): normal or depressed ADH, resistant to fluid restriction — consistent with CSW, requires fluid + salt replacement.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.5",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"What is the role of ADH levels in distinguishing SIADH from CSW?",a:"ADH levels are unreliable for distinguishing SIADH from CSW because stress, pain, and raised ICP (common in neurosurgical patients) cause appropriate ADH elevation. Hypovolaemia itself stimulates ADH release. Volume status (CVP) is more practical and reliable.",ref:"Sivakumar 1994, p.5",src_id:"k-sivakumar-1994",korky:true},
{q:"What is the first-choice surgical procedure for pyogenic cerebral abscess and why? (Smith 2009)",a:"Burrhole aspiration (image-guided). Smith 2009 showed NO significant difference between burrhole aspiration and craniotomy in re-operation rate, antibiotic duration, discharge GCS, length of stay, or GOS (p>0.05 for all). Burrhole preferred due to its advantages in speed and scale of surgery.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.1 (abstract), p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the effect of surgical delay on outcome in cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Delay from imaging to surgery showed a trend to worse GOS (p=0.132, not significant) but caused a statistically significant increase in length of hospital stay (p=0.003). The most significant predictors of outcome/length of stay were delay to neurosurgery and need for re-operation (ANOVA p=0.001).",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the most common cause of delayed surgery for cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Misidentification as a neoplastic lesion on contrast-enhanced CT scan. Abscesses staged and treated in a less urgent manner when mistaken for tumour. Advanced MRI (DWI) is now used to expedite correct diagnosis.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.5",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What are the most common presenting symptoms/signs of cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Pyrexia 91.2%, headache 51.6%, decreased GCS 43.5%, focal neurological deficit 32.3%, seizures 29.0%. The classical triad of pyrexia + headache + focal deficit is present in only a minority of patients. Only 8.1% had both normal CRP and WBC.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.2",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What are the most common predisposing risk factors for cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"ENT infection 27.9% (ear or sinus); Immunosuppression 16.4%; IV drug use 9.8%; Congenital/structural heart disease 6.6%; Open head injury 4.9%; Systemic sepsis 4.9%. Importantly, 21% had NO identifiable predisposing factor.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.2",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the most common organism cultured from cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Streptococcus milleri — found in 40.3% of samples (alone or in combination). Also: no growth 16.1%, Staph aureus 12.9%, mixed anaerobes 9.7%, Haemophilus sp. 6.5%, fungal 6.5%. All fungal abscesses had underlying haematological malignancy.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.3",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"Is lumbar puncture recommended in suspected cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"NO. LP is not recommended: (1) diagnostic yield is low — only 3/9 taps (33%) gave positive culture in this series; (2) risk of cerebral herniation due to the underlying mass lesion. Rupture into CSF/contamination of CSF tends to be a fatal event.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the mortality of surgically treated cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"9.7% (6/62). Causes: 2 deaths from pre-existing malignancy, 2 from Clostridium difficile complications, and 2 from neurological damage from the abscess (1 fungal, 1 Streptococcus milleri). 33.9% of patients required anticonvulsant medication.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.3",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the effect of pre-operative empirical antibiotics on cerebral abscess management? (Smith 2009)",a:"Empirical antibiotics significantly impaired microbiological culture (p=0.020) — associated with failure to grow an organism — but gave NO benefit in outcome (p=0.973). Blindly treating before drainage risks C. diff complications and optimal antibiotic selection requires positive culture.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What are the predictors of worse outcome in cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Older age (p=0.023), lower admission GCS (p=0.005), higher admission CRP (p=0.056, trend), delay to surgery, and need for re-operation. Surgical method (burrhole vs craniotomy) does NOT predict outcome.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"How does diffusion-weighted MRI (DWI) help distinguish cerebral abscess from tumour?",a:"Abscesses show restricted diffusion — low apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) in the central cavity. Tumours (including high-grade glioma) have higher ADC. DWI allows distinction when contrast CT is equivocal. Spectroscopy also shows characteristic amino acid peaks in abscess (plus elevated lactate in both).",ref:"Smith 2009, p.5",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"What is the typical antibiotic duration for cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Mean IV antibiotics 34 days (range 1–151 days); 80% then receive oral antibiotics (mean 24.1 days). Most patients in this series received 3–4 weeks IV rather than the traditionally recommended 6–8 weeks, with comparable outcomes. Antibiotic duration is tailored to clinical response and follow-up imaging/inflammatory markers.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.5",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{q:"When is craniotomy (rather than burrhole aspiration) preferred for cerebral abscess? (Smith 2009)",a:"Fungal abscesses (associated with haematological malignancy) — craniotomy and resection recommended. Some advocate craniotomy for Nocardia sp. (though others use stereotactic aspiration). For standard bacterial abscess, burrhole aspiration is first choice.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A TBI patient in ICU has ICP 30 mmHg and CPP 55 mmHg despite head elevation and EVD drainage. Next step?",opts:["A. Dexamethasone IV","B. Mannitol 0.25–1 g/kg IV bolus","C. Furosemide","D. Phenobarbitone infusion","E. Increase PEEP"],ans:1,exp:"For raised ICP refractory to first-line measures, osmotherapy with mannitol (0.25–1 g/kg IV bolus) is the next step. Dexamethasone has no role in traumatic ICP elevation (it is used for tumour-related oedema).",ref:"claude — ICP management",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A patient has acute ICP crisis — fixed dilated pupil on right, left hemiparesis. What is this herniation syndrome?",opts:["A. Central herniation","B. Upward herniation","C. Tonsillar herniation","D. Uncal (transtentorial) herniation","E. Subfalcine herniation"],ans:3,exp:"Uncal herniation: the uncus of the temporal lobe herniates over the tentorium, compressing ipsilateral CN III (dilated pupil, ptosis) and then the contralateral cerebral peduncle (contralateral hemiparesis — Kernohan's notch).",ref:"claude — herniation syndromes",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 45-year-old with recent dental treatment presents with 3-day history of headache, fever, and right arm weakness. CT head shows a ring-enhancing lesion in the left frontal lobe. He has been started on IV co-amoxiclav in the emergency department. Which is the most important next management step?",opts:["A. MRI with DWI to confirm diagnosis then proceed to surgery","B. Lumbar puncture to identify causative organism","C. Proceed to urgent burrhole aspiration without further delay","D. Extend antibiotic course to cover Strep milleri and defer surgery","E. Dexamethasone to reduce oedema before surgery"],ans:2,exp:"Urgent surgical drainage (burrhole aspiration) is the priority — Smith 2009 showed delay significantly worsens outcome and lengthens hospital stay. LP is contraindicated (risk of herniation; low diagnostic yield). Pre-op antibiotics impair culture without improving outcome. DWI is useful if diagnosis is in doubt, but here the picture is strongly consistent with abscess — do not delay surgery for further imaging. Dexamethasone is not routinely recommended.",ref:"Smith 2009, p.4–5",src_id:"k-smith-2009",korky:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical patient undergoes elective craniotomy. Post-operatively, routine thromboprophylaxis is being planned. Which statement regarding DVT prophylaxis in neurosurgical patients is correct?",opts:["A. Pharmacological prophylaxis (LMWH) should begin immediately before surgery to ensure peak levels intraoperatively","B. Mechanical prophylaxis (TED stockings or intermittent pneumatic compression devices) should begin on the day of surgery; LMWH is typically added 24–48 hours post-operatively once haemostasis is confirmed","C. UFH is preferred over LMWH for neurosurgical patients because it is more rapidly reversible","D. TED stockings and IPCs are equivalent alternatives — either alone is sufficient without LMWH","E. LMWH should be withheld for at least 2 weeks post-craniotomy in all patients"],ans:1,exp:"Mechanical prophylaxis (TEDs and/or IPCs) should begin on the day of surgery in all neurosurgical patients. Pharmacological prophylaxis with LMWH is added 24–48 hours after intracranial surgery (or 12–24 hours for spinal), once haemostasis is established. NICE and BTF guidelines support LMWH over UFH for efficacy. IPCs and TEDs are complementary, not equivalent alternatives — TEDs alone are insufficient. Delaying LMWH for 2 weeks is unnecessarily prolonged and increases VTE risk.",ref:"claude — neurosurgical VTE prophylaxis guidelines",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with known severe COPD (FEV1 40% predicted) requires urgent craniotomy for a cerebral abscess. Pre-operative ABG on air shows: pH 7.34, PaCO2 8.3 kPa, PaO2 7.1 kPa, HCO3 33 mmol/L. Which statement about this ABG and anaesthetic management is correct?",opts:["A. This is acute respiratory acidosis — immediately intubate and ventilate to normalise PaCO2","B. This is compensated type 2 (hypercapnic) respiratory failure — raised bicarbonate reflects chronic renal compensation; target ventilation to the patient's usual PaCO2, not normal values","C. This is metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation — treat the alkalosis first","D. High-flow oxygen should be administered freely as the hypoxic drive is a myth in COPD","E. Bicarbonate infusion should be given pre-operatively to correct the acidosis"],ans:1,exp:"This ABG shows type 2 (hypercapnic) respiratory failure with chronic compensation: pH mildly low (7.34), very high PaCO2 (8.3 kPa), elevated HCO3 (33 mmol/L, metabolic compensation), and hypoxaemia. In severe COPD, the patient's baseline PaCO2 is chronically elevated. Intraoperative ventilation must target the patient's own baseline PaCO2 (not normal 4.5–5 kPa) to avoid respiratory alkalosis. Post-extubation, high-flow oxygen can suppress hypoxic drive in type 2 failure — titrate O2 to SpO2 88–92% in known CO2 retainers.",ref:"claude — ABG interpretation / COPD ventilation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical patient is on day 3 post-craniotomy for SAH. Serum sodium is 127 mmol/L. Urine sodium is 65 mmol/L, urine osmolality 420 mOsm/kg. BP 95/60, HR 105, CVP 2 cmH2O. Which diagnosis best explains these findings and what is the correct treatment?",opts:["A. SIADH — fluid restriction to 1 litre/day","B. Cerebral salt wasting (CSW) — IV fluid replacement with 0.9% NaCl ± hypertonic saline; volume expansion","C. Diabetes insipidus — replace free water with 5% dextrose; consider DDAVP","D. Psychogenic polydipsia — fluid restriction","E. Adrenal insufficiency — steroid replacement"],ans:1,exp:"Both SIADH and CSW cause hyponatraemia with high urine sodium and high urine osmolality, making them easy to confuse. The key differentiator is volume status: SIADH is euvolaemic/mildly hypervolaemic (normal/elevated CVP, normal BP); CSW is hypovolaemic (low CVP, tachycardia, hypotension) due to natriuretic peptide-driven renal sodium wasting. This patient is clearly hypovolaemic (CVP 2, BP 95/60) = CSW. Treatment: IV fluid ± hypertonic saline to replace volume and sodium. SIADH treatment (fluid restriction) would be dangerous in CSW — it would worsen hypovolaemia in post-SAH patients, precipitating vasospasm.",ref:"claude — SIADH vs CSW differentiation",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 30-year-old sustains a severe TBI (GCS 6). In ICU, the intensivist proposes several physiological targets. Which target is INCORRECT according to current evidence-based TBI management guidelines?",opts:["A. Maintain CPP 60–70 mmHg","B. Target ICP <20 mmHg","C. Maintain haemoglobin >12 g/dL with liberal transfusion policy","D. Maintain normoglycaemia with blood glucose 4–10 mmol/L","E. Maintain normocapnia (PaCO2 4.5–5.0 kPa) except for acute herniation"],ans:2,exp:"An Hb target of >12 g/dL is NOT recommended in TBI. Brain Trauma Foundation and RCP guidelines support a transfusion threshold of 7–9 g/dL (similar to general ICU); there is no evidence that liberal transfusion (Hb >12) improves outcomes in TBI, and overtransfusion carries risks. Correct targets: ICP <20 mmHg (treat above); CPP 60–70 mmHg (augment with vasopressors if needed); blood glucose 4–10 mmol/L (strict normoglycaemia risks hypoglycaemia); normocapnia (PaCO2 4.5–5.0 kPa) except brief hyperventilation for acute herniation.",ref:"claude — Brain Trauma Foundation TBI targets",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient with a severe TBI and refractory intracranial hypertension is commenced on a barbiturate coma (high-dose IV pentobarbital) to reduce ICP. Which complication is NOT typically associated with prolonged barbiturate coma?",opts:["A. Cardiovascular depression requiring vasopressor support","B. Hypothermia","C. Diarrhoea and increased bowel transit","D. Immunosuppression and susceptibility to infection","E. EEG burst suppression pattern"],ans:2,exp:"Barbiturate coma causes significant cardiovascular depression (reduced cardiac output, hypotension — often requiring vasopressors), hypothermia (direct temperature reduction), immunosuppression, and EEG burst suppression (the pharmacodynamic endpoint). Barbiturates typically cause gut ileus and constipation — NOT diarrhoea. Diarrhoea is not a recognised barbiturate complication; this is a deliberate distractor in recall-bank questions. The major concern is cardiovascular instability: barbiturate coma must be conducted with continuous arterial monitoring and vasopressor/inotrope support.",ref:"claude — barbiturate coma complications",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During sitting-position posterior fossa craniotomy, the end-tidal CO2 (EtCO2) monitoring shows a sudden drop from 4.8 kPa to 2.1 kPa, accompanied by a decrease in SpO2 and hypotension. What is the most likely cause and immediate priority?",opts:["A. Endotracheal tube displacement (accidental extubation) — reintubate immediately","B. Venous air embolism — flood the surgical field with saline, lower the head, aspirate through central line, 100% O2","C. Tension pneumothorax — needle decompression","D. Malignant hyperthermia — stop volatile agent, dantrolene","E. Anaphylaxis to contrast — adrenaline and steroids"],ans:1,exp:"A sudden fall in EtCO2 during sitting craniotomy is venous air embolism until proven otherwise. Air enters open venous sinuses/diploic veins; it is swept to the pulmonary circulation causing dead space ventilation (gas exchange impaired) → EtCO2 drops while PaCO2 rises. Simultaneously: hypotension (obstructed cardiac output), desaturation. Management: (1) flood surgical field with saline; (2) compress neck veins; (3) lower the patient (Durant's manoeuvre — left lateral head-down reduces RV air lock); (4) aspirate air via CVP catheter; (5) 100% FiO2; (6) vasopressors/CPR if cardiovascular collapse. Precordial Doppler is the most sensitive monitor for VAE.",ref:"claude — venous air embolism management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old patient with a devastating brainstem haemorrhage has been on the ventilator for 5 days with GCS 3. The clinical team plans to perform formal brainstem death testing. During the examination, a painful stimulus applied to the great toe produces a withdrawal flexion response in the ipsilateral leg. Which statement is correct?",opts:["A. This withdrawal response confirms residual brainstem function — brainstem death testing cannot proceed","B. Withdrawal of the leg to painful stimulus is a spinal reflex mediated at the spinal cord level; it does not require brainstem activity and does not preclude a diagnosis of brainstem death","C. This response indicates the patient is in a minimally conscious state — further neurological assessment needed","D. The withdrawal response suggests the patient may be aware of pain — sedation should be increased before testing","E. All spinal reflexes must be absent before brainstem death testing can be performed"],ans:1,exp:"The UK brainstem death protocol states that clinicians must 'take care to distinguish central response from primitive spinally-mediated reflexes that can be ignored in this context.' Limb withdrawal to a peripheral painful stimulus is a spinal cord-level reflex that does not require brainstem or cortical participation — it can persist and indeed become exaggerated after complete brainstem cessation. The brainstem reflexes that are specifically tested (and must be absent) are: pupillary response (mesencephalon, II+III), corneal reflex (pons, V+VII), oculo-vestibular reflex (pons, VIII+III+IV+VI), motor responses in the cranial nerve distribution to supraorbital/nail-bed stimulation, and cough/gag (medulla, IX+X). A limb withdrawal is none of these.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"An anaesthetist is choosing inhalational versus intravenous agents for a patient requiring craniotomy for a glioma. Which anaesthetic agent increases cerebral blood flow (CBF) and may raise intracranial pressure?",opts:["A. Propofol — reduces CMRO2 and CBF; safe for neuroanesthesia","B. Thiopentone (thiopental) — reduces CBF and CMRO2; protective in cerebral ischaemia","C. Isoflurane — volatile agent causing dose-dependent cerebral vasodilation and increased CBF at >1 MAC","D. Etomidate — reduces CMRO2; used for ICP-sensitive induction","E. Ketamine — traditionally avoided in neuro patients due to increasing ICP, but isoflurane is also a concern"],ans:2,exp:"Volatile anaesthetic agents (isoflurane, sevoflurane, desflurane) cause dose-dependent cerebral vasodilation → increased CBF and potentially elevated ICP, particularly at >1 MAC. This is termed 'flow-metabolism uncoupling.' Intravenous agents (propofol, thiopentone, etomidate) reduce cerebral metabolic rate (CMRO2) and CBF — making them preferable for ICP-sensitive patients. Ketamine has historically been avoided (increases CBF/ICP) but newer evidence in controlled ventilation is more nuanced. For neurosurgical anaesthesia, total intravenous anaesthesia (TIVA) with propofol is commonly used to maintain tight ICP control.",ref:"claude — neuroanesthesia / cerebral blood flow pharmacology",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 28-year-old patient with a posterior fossa tumour (sitting position) is being operated upon. Fifteen minutes into the procedure, the precordial Doppler detects a characteristic 'mill-wheel' murmur, EtCO2 drops abruptly, and BP falls to 70/40. After flooding the field and lowering the head, the anaesthetist aspirates air from the central venous catheter. The patient remains haemodynamically unstable. What is the next priority?",opts:["A. Administer IV adrenaline (epinephrine) and begin CPR immediately","B. Insert a chest drain for suspected pneumothorax","C. Vasopressor support (noradrenaline/phenylephrine) and 100% FiO2; consider cardiopulmonary resuscitation if cardiac arrest","D. Request urgent echocardiogram before any further intervention","E. Administer IV dexamethasone for anaphylaxis"],ans:2,exp:"This is a massive venous air embolism causing haemodynamic collapse. After initial manoeuvres (flooding field, lowering head, aspirating CVP), ongoing haemodynamic instability requires: vasopressors to maintain coronary and cerebral perfusion, 100% FiO2 (nitrogen washout reduces bubble size), and CPR if cardiac arrest occurs. Durant's manoeuvre (left lateral head-down) is maintained to reduce air lock in the right ventricle outflow tract. Paradoxical air embolism through a patent foramen ovale (PFO) is a risk — preoperative bubble echo to identify PFO in sitting-position patients is good practice.",ref:"claude — massive venous air embolism management",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"Post-operatively after a clipping of a ruptured anterior communicating artery aneurysm, a patient passes 500 mL of urine per hour for 3 consecutive hours. Serum sodium is 148 mmol/L. Urine osmolality is 75 mOsm/kg (very dilute). Serum osmolality is 308 mOsm/kg. What is the diagnosis and treatment?",opts:["A. SIADH — restrict fluids to 500 mL/day","B. Cerebral salt wasting (CSW) — rapid IV saline replacement","C. Cranial diabetes insipidus — replace free water deficits and consider DDAVP (desmopressin)","D. Osmotic diuresis from mannitol — no specific treatment needed","E. Primary polydipsia — fluid restriction"],ans:2,exp:"Cranial diabetes insipidus (CDI) is caused by ADH deficiency following hypothalamic or posterior pituitary injury — common after aneurysm surgery near the anterior communicating artery, pituitary surgery, or severe TBI. Features: massive polyuria (>300 mL/h or >30 mL/kg/day), very dilute urine (osmolality <200 mOsm/kg), rising serum sodium (hypernatraemia), raised serum osmolality. Treatment: replace free water deficits (5% dextrose or oral water); DDAVP (desmopressin) 1–2 mcg IV/SC to replace ADH. SIADH and CSW both cause hyponatraemia — opposite picture. Distinguish CDI from osmotic diuresis (mannitol causes dilute urine but serum osmolality would reflect mannitol load, and it is self-limiting).",ref:"claude — cranial diabetes insipidus post-neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"According to the Monro-Kellie hypothesis, what are the approximate percentage contributions of brain, cerebrospinal fluid, and blood to the total intracranial volume?",opts:["A. Brain 70%, CSF 20%, blood 10%","B. Brain 80%, CSF 15%, blood 5%","C. Brain 85%, CSF 10%, blood 5%","D. Brain 90%, CSF 5%, blood 5%","E. Brain 75%, CSF 15%, blood 10%"],ans:2,exp:"The Monro-Kellie hypothesis states the cranium is a fixed rigid container with contents: brain ~85%, CSF ~10% (150 ml), and blood ~5% (50–75 ml). Any increase in one compartment must be compensated by reduction in another to maintain constant ICP. Blood, despite being the smallest compartment, provides the most rapid ICP compensation because cerebral venous volume can be altered almost immediately. CSF provides the largest compensation but changes occur slowly.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with severe TBI has mean arterial pressure 85 mmHg, central venous pressure 8 mmHg, and intracranial pressure 20 mmHg. What is the cerebral perfusion pressure?",opts:["A. 57 mmHg","B. 65 mmHg","C. 73 mmHg","D. 77 mmHg","E. 85 mmHg"],ans:0,exp:"CPP = MAP − (CVP + ICP) = 85 − (8 + 20) = 57 mmHg. CVP at head level is often negligible in clinical practice, giving the simplified CPP = MAP − ICP. Normal adult CPP is 70–90 mmHg. The Brain Trauma Foundation recommends target CPP 50–70 mmHg in TBI; above 70 mmHg potential benefits do not outweigh the risk of acute lung injury.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.1",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"The Brain Trauma Foundation recommends targeting cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) within what range in traumatic brain injury?",opts:["A. 40–60 mmHg","B. 50–70 mmHg","C. 60–80 mmHg","D. 70–90 mmHg","E. ≥90 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"The Brain Trauma Foundation recommends a target CPP of 50–70 mmHg in TBI. Levels above 70 mmHg should be avoided as potential benefits do not outweigh the risk of developing acute lung injury. Normal adult CPP is 70–90 mmHg but injured brain autoregulation is often impaired, making pressure-passive flow predominant. Patients with intact autoregulation may tolerate higher CPP but this is not standard practice.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the recommended PaCO₂ target in patients with severe traumatic brain injury without refractory intracranial hypertension?",opts:["A. 3.5–4.0 kPa","B. 4.0–4.5 kPa","C. 4.5–5.3 kPa","D. 5.3–6.0 kPa","E. 6.0–7.0 kPa"],ans:2,exp:"Normocapnia (PaCO₂ 4.5–5.3 kPa) should be maintained after brain injury. CBF is normally reduced in the first 24 h after TBI, so hypocapnia further decreases CBF and risks cerebral ischaemia. Moderate hypocapnia (PaCO₂ 4.0–4.5 kPa) is a stage 2 option only for refractory ICP. Hyperventilation to severe hypocapnia should be strictly avoided as routine management. Prolonged hypocapnia is also ineffective — CBF returns to baseline after 6–8 h due to CSF pH adaptation.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"At 1.5 MAC, which volatile anaesthetic agent best preserves cerebral autoregulation and is therefore favoured during neuroanaesthesia?",opts:["A. Isoflurane","B. Desflurane","C. Sevoflurane","D. Halothane","E. All preserve autoregulation equally at 1.5 MAC"],ans:2,exp:"At 0.5 MAC, isoflurane, desflurane, and sevoflurane all minimally delay but preserve cerebral autoregulation. At 1.5 MAC, autoregulation is considerably reduced by isoflurane and desflurane. Sevoflurane produces much less cerebral vasodilation and delays but preserves autoregulatory response even at 1.5 MAC, making it the favoured volatile agent for neuroanaesthesia. All volatiles are intrinsic vasodilators and decrease CMRO₂ in a dose-dependent manner.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"In the RESCUEicp trial protocol, at what stage and under what criteria were patients randomised to decompressive craniectomy versus continued medical management?",opts:["A. Stage 2: ICP >20 mmHg for >15 min despite sedation and head elevation","B. Stage 3: ICP >25 mmHg for 1–12 hours despite stages 1 and 2 measures","C. Stage 2: ICP >25 mmHg for >30 min despite osmotherapy and EVD","D. Stage 3: ICP >30 mmHg for any duration after failed barbiturate therapy","E. Stage 1: persistent ICP >20 mmHg after optimised ventilation and sedation"],ans:1,exp:"Patients in RESCUEicp were randomised at stage 3 when ICP remained >25 mmHg for 1–12 hours despite stage 1 (sedation, analgesia, head elevation) and stage 2 (EVD, osmotherapy, moderate hypocapnia PaCO₂ 4.0–4.5 kPa, therapeutic hypothermia ≥34°C) measures. Barbiturates were NOT permitted at stage 2 — reserved as the primary option for the medical arm at stage 3. This contrasts with DECRA (ICP >20 mmHg for 15 min, stage 1 only, diffuse TBI).",ref:"Aberdeen, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-rescueicp",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient with severe TBI fails stage 1 ICP management. Which of the following is a stage 2 option in the RESCUEicp tiered ICP management protocol?",opts:["A. Barbiturate infusion","B. Decompressive craniectomy","C. Therapeutic hypothermia (not below 34°C)","D. Bilateral craniectomy","E. High-dose dexamethasone"],ans:2,exp:"Stage 2 options in the RESCUEicp protocol: EVD (ventriculostomy), pharmacologic blood-pressure augmentation, osmotherapy (mannitol, hypertonic saline, loop diuretics), moderate hypocapnia (PaCO₂ 4.0–4.5 kPa), and therapeutic hypothermia (not below 34°C). Barbiturates were specifically NOT permitted at stage 2 — reserved as the primary medical option at stage 3. Decompressive craniectomy is the stage 3 surgical option, offered when ICP >25 mmHg persists for 1–12 h after exhausting stages 1 and 2.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-rescueicp",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"How does the UK definition of brain-stem death differ from that used in North America and Australia?",opts:["A. The UK requires whole-brain death (cortex + brainstem); NA/Australia accept brainstem cessation alone","B. The UK accepts irreversible cessation of brainstem function alone as sufficient for death; NA and Australia require whole-brain death including the cerebral hemispheres","C. The definitions are clinically identical; the terminology differs only for medicolegal purposes","D. The UK requires ancillary imaging confirmation in every case; NA/Australia rely on clinical testing alone","E. The UK uses the term 'brain death'; NA/Australia use 'brainstem death'"],ans:1,exp:"UK Code of Practice (Academy of Medical Royal Colleges, 2008): death is confirmed when there is irreversible and complete loss of brainstem function — this is considered sufficient to establish loss of both the capacity for consciousness and the capacity to breathe. Countries including North America and Australia apply a 'whole brain death' criterion, requiring cessation of function of the entire brain including the cerebral hemispheres. Hence the UK uses the term 'brain-stem death' while these other jurisdictions use 'brain death'. The UK position is that brainstem loss alone is sufficient for the diagnosis of death.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 52-year-old patient with massive intracerebral haemorrhage fulfils the pre-conditions for brainstem death testing. Which of the following correctly describes who may perform the clinical examination?",opts:["A. Any two registered doctors who have been caring for the patient during the admission","B. Two physicians working together; at least one must be a consultant; both must have been fully GMC-registered for more than 5 years; neither may be involved in the care of potential organ recipients","C. One consultant and one specialist registrar, provided both have experience in critical care","D. Two consultants, one of whom may be part of the transplant retrieval team","E. Any consultant — a second examiner is required only if the first set of tests is inconclusive"],ans:1,exp:"UK Code of Practice: clinical examination must be carried out by two physicians working together, and must be repeated (two complete sets of tests). At least one of the doctors must be a consultant. Both must have been fully registered with the GMC for more than 5 years. NEITHER must be potentially involved in the care of patients who might be in receipt of organs donated by the patient — this directly excludes members of the transplant team.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"During brainstem death testing, the examiner tests the corneal reflex and the cough reflex. Which pairing correctly identifies the brainstem level and cranial nerves mediating each reflex?",opts:["A. Corneal = medulla (IX, X); cough = pons (V, VII)","B. Corneal = pons (V and VII); cough = medulla (IX and X)","C. Corneal = mesencephalon (II, III); cough = pons (V, VII)","D. Corneal = pons (VIII, III, IV, VI); cough = medulla (IX, X)","E. Corneal = medulla (X); cough = pons (VIII)"],ans:1,exp:"UK brainstem death protocol anatomical levels: pupils fixed (mesencephalon, CN II and III); corneal reflex absent (pons, CN V and VII); oculo-vestibular reflexes absent (pons, CN VIII, III, IV, VI); no motor response in cranial nerve distribution (tests multiple levels); cough and gag absent (medulla, CN IX and X — suction catheter to carina for cough, spatula to posterior pharynx for gag). Loss of all these reflexes plus apnoea demonstrates irreversible cessation of brainstem function from midbrain through to medulla.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"What is the correct technique for testing the oculo-vestibular reflex during brainstem death assessment?",opts:["A. Rapidly instil 10 ml of warm water into each ear; observe for nystagmus","B. Slowly inject at least 50 ml of ice cold water over one minute into each external auditory meatus in turn; confirm clear access to the tympanic membrane first; observe for any eye movement during or after injection","C. Irrigate both ears simultaneously with 50 ml ice cold water; nystagmus indicates preserved function","D. Administer 20 ml ice cold water rapidly; rotational eye movement indicates preserved reflex arc","E. Irrigate with warm then cold water 5 minutes apart and compare directional nystagmus"],ans:1,exp:"UK BSD protocol: oculo-vestibular reflexes are absent if no eye movements are seen during or following the slow injection of at least 50 ml of ice cold water over one minute into each external auditory meatus in turn. Before testing, clear access to the tympanic membrane must be established by direct inspection. The reflex arc: CN VIII (afferent, pons) → CN III, IV, VI (efferent). If bilateral facial or ear injury prevents access on one or both sides, ancillary testing should be considered.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"During the apnoea test for brainstem death, ventilatory rate has been reduced to allow CO₂ to accumulate. At what point may the patient be disconnected from the ventilator, and what must the ABG confirm at that moment?",opts:["A. ETCO₂ >5.0 kPa; ABG shows PaCO₂ ≥5.0 kPa and pH <7.45","B. ETCO₂ >6.0 kPa; ABG confirms PaCO₂ ≥6.0 kPa and pH <7.40","C. ETCO₂ >7.0 kPa; ABG confirms PaCO₂ ≥7.0 kPa regardless of pH","D. ETCO₂ >5.3 kPa (normal upper limit); no ABG required before disconnection","E. ETCO₂ >8.0 kPa; ABG confirms PaCO₂ ≥8.0 kPa and SaO₂ <90%"],ans:1,exp:"UK apnoea test protocol: once ETCO₂ rises above 6.0 kPa, check ABG to confirm PaCO₂ is at least 6.0 kPa AND pH is less than 7.40. If cardiovascular stability is maintained, disconnect from the ventilator and deliver O₂ at 5 L/min via an endotracheal catheter. Observe for 5 minutes. The ABG confirmation before disconnection ensures an adequate CO₂ stimulus is present to provoke any residual respiratory drive. SaO₂ must be >95% before disconnection.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"After 5 minutes of apnoea during brainstem death testing, a repeat ABG is performed. What must it show for absence of respiratory drive to be confirmed?",opts:["A. PaCO₂ has fallen back toward 5.0 kPa — CO₂ washout during apnoea confirms the test","B. PaCO₂ has fallen by at least 1.0 kPa from the pre-disconnect value","C. A minimum of a further 0.5 kPa rise in PaCO₂ above the pre-disconnect value","D. PaCO₂ must now exceed 8.0 kPa — a higher absolute threshold is required after 5 minutes","E. pH >7.50, confirming respiratory alkalosis from absence of CO₂ production"],ans:2,exp:"UK apnoea test protocol: after 5 minutes of apnoea, repeat ABG must confirm a minimum of a further 0.5 kPa rise in PaCO₂ above the value measured at disconnection (which was already ≥6.0 kPa). This confirms that CO₂ is continuing to rise — the expected result of metabolic production without ventilatory clearance — and that no respiratory effort occurred to clear it. Loss of respiratory drive is confirmed; mechanical ventilation is then resumed.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"The first set of brainstem death tests is completed at 10:00 and confirms absence of brainstem function. A short interval elapses and the second set of tests is completed at 11:30, also confirming absence of brainstem function. When is the legal time of death?",opts:["A. 11:30 — death is only confirmed when the second set of tests is complete and irreversibility is established","B. 10:45 — the midpoint between the two sets of tests","C. 10:00 — the time of completion of the first set of tests","D. The time the decision was made to withdraw ventilatory support","E. The time organ retrieval commences, if the patient becomes a donor"],ans:2,exp:"UK Code of Practice (Academy of Medical Royal Colleges): the legal time of death is the time of completion of the first set of brainstem death tests. Both sets are required to confirm irreversibility, but the legal timestamp of death is recorded as when the first examination demonstrated absence of brainstem function — not the second. This is a counterintuitive and frequently tested fact.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Formal brainstem death testing is planned for a patient with massive TBI. The clinical team identifies that extensive bilateral facio-maxillary fractures prevent access to test the oculo-vestibular and corneal reflexes on either side. What does UK guidance recommend in this situation?",opts:["A. Proceed with clinical testing of available reflexes — bilateral facial injury is not an exclusion criterion","B. Testing must be abandoned entirely — a full set of clinical tests must be possible or death cannot be confirmed","C. Consider ancillary testing (e.g. CT angiography or neurophysiological testing) of cerebral perfusion or function to supplement or replace the clinical examination that cannot be completed","D. A single experienced consultant may perform the test alone if bilateral testing is not possible","E. Wait a minimum of 72 hours for facial swelling to resolve before repeating assessment"],ans:2,exp:"UK Code of Practice: death cannot be diagnosed by the testing of brainstem reflexes alone when a comprehensive neurological examination is not possible — for example, due to extensive facio-maxillary injuries. In such cases, ancillary testing should be considered. Other indications for ancillary testing include: residual sedation, paediatric hypoxic brain injury, inability to exclude a primary metabolic or pharmacological derangement, and high cervical cord injury. Available ancillary investigations include CT angiography (increasingly available), nuclear medicine cerebral perfusion studies, and EEG — each with specific limitations.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.3-4",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A patient with aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH) is admitted to the neurocritical care unit. You plan TCD monitoring for cerebral vasospasm. Which statement correctly describes the timing and monitoring schedule?",opts:["A. Vasospasm is most likely in the first 48 hours; daily TCD should be performed from day 1 to day 7","B. Vasospasm typically occurs between 3 and 21 days after SAH, can last 12–16 days, and increases mortality 1.5- to 3-fold; the recommended TCD protocol is a baseline study on day 0 and then daily during days 3 to 10","C. Vasospasm is rare after day 7; TCD monitoring beyond day 7 is not indicated","D. TCD should be performed only when clinical deterioration occurs — routine monitoring adds no value","E. A single TCD on day 3 is sufficient to exclude clinically significant vasospasm"],ans:1,exp:"Vasospasm after aneurysmal SAH: typically occurs 3–21 days after the ictus and may last 12–16 days. It is associated with 1.5- to 3-fold increased mortality during the first 2 weeks. TCD protocol: baseline on day 0 (earliest possible) then daily TCD during days 3–10. TCD can detect rising FV 1–2 days before clinical symptoms — allowing early initiation of triple H therapy. MFV 120 cm/s = mild spasm; >180 cm/s = severe spasm.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A SAH patient on day 5 has an MCA mean flow velocity (MFV) of 145 cm/s on TCD. Her ICA MFV is 40 cm/s. What is the Lindegaard ratio, and which severity category does this represent?",opts:["A. Ratio 3.6 — moderate vasospasm","B. Ratio 6.8 — critical vasospasm","C. Ratio 2.8 — mild vasospasm","D. Ratio 5.1 — severe vasospasm","E. Ratio 7.5 — critical vasospasm"],ans:0,exp:"Lindegaard ratio = MCA MFV / ipsilateral ICA MFV = 145 / 40 = 3.6. According to TCD criteria (Table 3): Moderate vasospasm = MFV 120–150 cm/s with MCA/ICA ratio 3–5.9. A ratio ≥3 distinguishes true vasospasm from hyperaemia (which causes high MFV but a normal or low ratio because ICA flow also rises). Normal: MFV <85, ratio <3. Mild: MFV <120, ratio <3. Moderate: MFV 120–150, ratio 3–5.9. Severe: MFV 151–200, ratio >6. Critical: MFV >200, ratio >6.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.4 (Table 3)",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A child aged 10 with sickle cell disease undergoes TCD screening for stroke risk. The MCA mean flow velocity (MFV) is 195 cm/s. How should this result be classified, and what is the associated 3-year stroke risk if left untreated?",opts:["A. Normal (≤200 cm/s threshold) — no action required; re-screen in 12 months","B. Conditional (171–199 cm/s) — increase monitoring frequency but transfusion not yet required","C. Abnormal (≥200 cm/s) — this 195 cm/s result is in the conditional range; MFV ≥200 cm/s would be abnormal and carry a 40% 3-year stroke risk requiring transfusion","D. Conditional (171–199 cm/s) — this result carries a high stroke risk; transfusion is required if MFV reaches 200 cm/s","E. Normal — sickle cell TCD thresholds only apply to vessels other than the MCA"],ans:2,exp:"TCD criteria for sickle cell disease: MFV ≤170 cm/s = normal; MFV 171–199 cm/s = conditional (increased monitoring); MFV ≥200 cm/s = abnormal (requires transfusion). An MFV ≥200 cm/s carries a 40% stroke risk within 3 years. Transfusion reducing HbS to <30% of total haemoglobin reduces this stroke risk by 70% compared with standard care. Screening applies to children aged 2–16. This patient's MFV of 195 cm/s is conditional — it requires increased monitoring frequency (every 3 months rather than every 6 months for normal results).",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"TCD examination of the MCA on the left side shows increased flow velocity at a depth of 50 mm. Downstream (deeper insonation) shows reduced FV. The ipsilateral ACA shows reverse flow via the anterior communicating artery. Which pattern does this represent and what is the likely diagnosis?",opts:["A. Downstream AVM — low distal resistance increases MCA FV and decreases PI","B. Focal MCA stenosis — increased FV at the stenotic site with decreased FV downstream and compensatory collateral flow through the ACoA","C. Raised ICP — increased PI globally with reduced FV in all insonated vessels","D. Left carotid occlusion — absent flow in the TICA; collateral from right ACA via ACoA","E. Normal TCD variant — bidirectional flow in the ACA is expected"],ans:1,exp:"TCD signs of focal arterial stenosis: (1) increased FV at the stenotic site; (2) decreased FV downstream from the stenotic site; (3) decreased FV proximal to the stenosis and increased PI. Compensatory collateral flow is an additional TCD sign — reverse OA flow indicates ipsilateral carotid occlusion; reversed/increased first-segment ACA flow indicates shunting via the ACoA to supply the downstream ischaemic territory. Total occlusion: no Doppler signal at the occluded site.",ref:"Aberdeen TCD, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-tcd",korky:true,recall:true},
]},

"neurophysiology":{src:"Standard intraoperative neurophysiological monitoring knowledge",c:[
{q:"What does SSEP (somatosensory evoked potential) monitoring detect?",a:"Integrity of the dorsal column-medial lemniscal pathway (sensory). A >50% amplitude decrease OR >10% latency increase is a critical warning sign. Used in spine surgery, posterior fossa surgery, carotid endarterectomy, aortic surgery.",ref:"claude — IONM",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What does MEP (motor evoked potential) monitoring detect?",a:"Integrity of the corticospinal (motor) pathway. More sensitive than SSEPs for detecting motor deficits. Combined SSEP+MEP monitoring is more complete. MEP loss = immediate action required.",ref:"claude — IONM",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the critical warning criteria for SSEP and MEP changes intraoperatively?",a:"SSEP: >50% amplitude decrease OR >10% latency increase. MEP: any significant amplitude decrease or loss. Both: immediately notify surgeon, optimise physiology (MAP, temperature, anaesthetic depth).",ref:"claude — IONM critical criteria",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is electromyography (EMG) monitoring used for in spine surgery?",a:"Continuous free-running EMG detects nerve root irritation (spontaneous discharge). Triggered EMG used to assess pedicle screw placement — stimulation threshold <6–8 mA suggests screw violation of cortex.",ref:"claude — spine IONM",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the Stagnara wake-up test?",a:"Patient is woken intraoperatively to assess voluntary motor function during spinal deformity surgery. Now largely replaced by IONM (MEP monitoring), but still used as backup or if IONM is not available.",ref:"claude — spine surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What physiological factors can cause false-positive IONM changes?",a:"Anaesthetic depth (especially volatile agents suppress MEPs — prefer TIVA with propofol/remifentanil); hypotension (CPP reduction); hypothermia; hypoxia; technical factors (electrode displacement). Must distinguish physiological from surgical causes.",ref:"claude — IONM — confounders",src_id:"claude-ai"},
],q:[
{stem:"During deformity correction surgery, SSEP amplitude drops 60% and MEPs are lost bilaterally at L1–L2. Immediate action?",opts:["A. Continue — can lag clinical signs","B. Halt surgery, notify anaesthetist, optimise MAP, consider reversing last surgical step","C. Administer IV methylprednisolone","D. Wake-up test only if deficit persists","E. Reduce PEEP and increase FiO2"],ans:1,exp:"Critical IONM change = immediate action: halt surgery, optimise MAP (>80 mmHg), correct anaesthetic depth, reverse last surgical step. The Stagnara wake-up test can confirm neurological status. Do NOT continue.",ref:"IONM — critical response"},
{stem:"A patient is 3 days post-trans-sphenoidal surgery. He passes 800 mL of urine per hour with a urine osmolality of 60 mOsm/kg. Serum sodium rises to 152 mmol/L. The pontine micturition centre is mentioned in an anatomy tutorial. Which statement about the micturition centre is correct?",opts:["A. The pontine micturition centre (PMC) is located in the hypothalamus — it mediates voluntary bladder control","B. The PMC is located in the dorsal pons (Barrington's nucleus) — it coordinates detrusor contraction and external urethral sphincter relaxation; lesions above the PMC cause detrusor overactivity; lesions below cause detrusor-sphincter dyssynergia","C. The sacral micturition centre (S2–4) is the primary voluntary micturition control centre — the pons is only involved in coordination of defecation","D. Bladder control is mediated by the frontal lobe alone — the brainstem has no direct role","E. The PMC is in the midbrain tectum"],ans:1,exp:"Pontine micturition centre (PMC / Barrington's nucleus, dorsal pons): the key supraspinal micturition coordinator. It projects to S2–4 sacral cord: (1) excites detrusor (via pelvic nerve parasympathetics); (2) INHIBITS external urethral sphincter (pudendal nerve) — allowing coordinated voiding. Lesions ABOVE the PMC (cerebral cortex, basal ganglia): detrusor overactivity (urgency incontinence) — the cortex normally inhibits the PMC. Lesions BELOW the PMC but above the sacral cord (spinal cord): detrusor-sphincter dyssynergia (DSD) — both detrusor and sphincter contract simultaneously, causing incomplete bladder emptying and high intravesical pressure. Sacral cord lesions: flaccid bladder (acontractile detrusor).",ref:"claude — pontine micturition centre / neurological bladder control",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"An anaesthetist is monitoring SSEPs (somatosensory evoked potentials) during a scoliosis correction procedure. She notes that the SSEP amplitudes are reduced by 40% compared to baseline. She mentions that SSEPs are difficult to interpret. Which statement about SSEP monitoring in spinal surgery is correct?",opts:["A. SSEPs monitor the corticospinal (motor) tracts directly — amplitude reduction implies motor cord injury","B. SSEPs monitor the dorsal column-medial lemniscal pathway; they are affected by volatile anaesthetic agents (which reduce amplitude and increase latency); reliable SSEP interpretation requires keeping anaesthetic depth constant during the critical surgical period","C. SSEPs are not affected by any anaesthetic agents — changes indicate only surgical spinal cord injury","D. SSEPs are the only monitoring modality needed for scoliosis surgery — MEPs add no additional information","E. A 40% amplitude reduction alone, even with stable latency, is a definitive indicator of spinal cord injury requiring immediate surgical halt"],ans:1,exp:"SSEPs monitor the DORSAL COLUMNS (sensory tracts) — they do NOT monitor the corticospinal (motor) tracts directly. Both SSEPs and MEPs are required for comprehensive spinal cord monitoring (motor + sensory). Key SSEP caveat: VOLATILE ANAESTHETIC AGENTS (isoflurane, sevoflurane) reduce SSEP amplitude and prolong latency in a dose-dependent manner — changes in anaesthetic depth can mimic spinal cord injury. Total intravenous anaesthesia (TIVA) with propofol provides more stable SSEP baseline. Alarm criteria: amplitude decrease >50% and/or latency increase >10% from baseline. A 40% drop is approaching the threshold — reassess anaesthetic depth first before attributing to cord injury.",ref:"claude — SSEP monitoring / anaesthetic effects",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"During nerve conduction studies, an F-wave is measured. What does the F-wave assess that standard nerve conduction velocity (NCV) does not?",opts:["A. F-waves measure sensory nerve conduction specifically — standard NCV measures motor nerves only","B. F-waves reflect proximal motor conduction (nerve root and plexus) by measuring the antidromic discharge of alpha motor neurons; they can detect proximal pathology (radiculopathy, Guillain-Barré, plexopathy) where distal NCV is normal","C. F-waves assess the integrity of the neuromuscular junction","D. F-waves are produced only in upper motor neuron lesions — they are absent in peripheral neuropathy","E. F-wave latency measures the conduction velocity in the H-reflex arc"],ans:1,exp:"F-wave physiology: a supramaximal motor nerve stimulus antidromically activates alpha motor neurons in the anterior horn; a proportion re-discharge orthodromically (the F-wave), arriving at the recording electrode after the M-wave. F-wave latency reflects total proximal + distal motor conduction time. Clinical use: detects PROXIMAL nerve pathology (root level, plexus) where distal NCV may be normal — GBS (early: absent F-waves even with preserved distal conduction), radiculopathy, plexopathy. F-waves are prolonged or absent in demyelinating conditions. The H-reflex (monosynaptic reflex arc) is the electrophysiological equivalent of the Achilles (S1) or biceps (C6) reflex.",ref:"claude — F-wave neurophysiology",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Regarding the Rexed laminae of the spinal cord grey matter, which statement correctly pairs a lamina with its function?",opts:["A. Lamina I (marginal zone) is in the ventral horn and contains alpha motor neurons","B. Lamina IX (ventral horn) contains alpha motor neurons innervating skeletal muscle; Lamina I and II (dorsal horn superficial) process pain and temperature from primary afferents; Laminae III–VI (dorsal horn deep) process proprioception and other sensory modalities","C. Lamina VII (Clarke's column) is in the dorsal horn and contains preganglionic sympathetic neurons only","D. Lamina IX is in the dorsal horn and processes joint position sense","E. The spinothalamic tract originates from cells in lamina IX"],ans:1,exp:"Rexed laminae: 10 laminae, I–X, from dorsal to ventral. DORSAL HORN: I (marginal nucleus — pain/temperature from Aδ/C fibres); II (substantia gelatinosa — pain modulation, enkephalin interneurons); III–IV (nucleus proprius — mechanoreception); V–VI (wide dynamic range neurons — convergent input). INTERMEDIATE ZONE: VII (includes Clarke's column T1–L2 — receives proprioception from Ia, inputs to spinocerebellar tract; lateral column contains sympathetic preganglionic IML). VIII — propriospinal interneurons. VENTRAL HORN: IX — alpha and gamma motor neurons (voluntary muscle); large multipolar cells visible on microscopy. X — around central canal. The spinothalamic tract originates from DORSAL HORN cells (laminae I, IV, V) — axons decussate in the anterior commissure.",ref:"claude — Rexed laminae / spinal cord anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A nerve conduction study is performed on a 70-year-old. Results are compared to a younger patient using the same NCS protocol in the same room. Which factors most explain reduced NCV in the elderly patient?",opts:["A. Increased myelin thickness and axonal diameter in older patients accelerates NCV","B. Peripheral nerve NCV decreases with age (due to axonal loss, reduced myelin thickness, and reduced fibre density) and with lower ambient temperature — both must be accounted for when interpreting NCS results","C. Age has no effect on NCV — only temperature affects nerve conduction in adults","D. NCV increases linearly with age due to progressive myelination","E. Ambient temperature has no effect on nerve conduction studies — results are temperature-independent"],ans:1,exp:"Nerve conduction velocity (NCV) is affected by: (1) AGE: NCV decreases ~1–2 m/s per decade above 40 — due to axonal loss, reduced myelination, and decreased internodal length. Sensory amplitudes also decline with age. (2) TEMPERATURE: NCV decreases ~1–2 m/s per °C reduction in limb temperature — cool limbs (winter, peripheral vascular disease) slow conduction and can mimic peripheral neuropathy. Skin temperature must be standardised (>32°C for arms, >30°C for legs) or a temperature correction factor applied. Failure to account for these factors leads to over-diagnosis of peripheral neuropathy in elderly patients.",ref:"claude — NCV factors / age and temperature",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"Over the linear range of the PaCO₂–CBF relationship (2.7–10.5 kPa), by approximately how much does cerebral blood flow change for each 1 kPa change in PaCO₂?",opts:["A. 1–3 ml/100g/min","B. 5–8 ml/100g/min","C. 11–15 ml/100g/min","D. 20–25 ml/100g/min","E. 30–40 ml/100g/min"],ans:2,exp:"CBF changes by approximately 11–15 ml/100g/min for each 1 kPa change in PaCO₂ within the linear range of 2.7–10.5 kPa. The upper plateau (PaCO₂ 10.5 kPa) nearly doubles CBF; the lower plateau (2.7 kPa) halves CBF. Decreasing PaCO₂ from 5.3 to 2.7 kPa reduces whole-brain volume by 10–14 ml — clinically useful for acute ICP reduction. CO₂ reactivity is mediated by CO₂ diffusion across the blood–brain barrier, reducing extracellular pH and directly dilating vascular smooth muscle.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"After a step change in arterial PaCO₂, within what time does the CBF response begin, and when does it plateau?",opts:["A. Onset <30 s; plateau at 5 min","B. Onset within 1 min; plateau at 12 min","C. Onset within 5 min; plateau at 30 min","D. Onset within 10 min; plateau at 60 min","E. Onset within 2 min; plateau at 20 min"],ans:1,exp:"The CBF/CBV response to altered PaCO₂ begins within 1 minute and plateaus at 12 minutes. This rapid onset makes acute hyperventilation useful for immediate ICP reduction. The effect is not sustained: CBF returns to baseline after 6–8 hours of sustained hypocapnia due to CSF pH adaptation — which is why chronic hyperventilation is not recommended in TBI management.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.4",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"For every 1°C decrease in brain temperature, by approximately what percentage does the cerebral metabolic rate (CMR) decrease?",opts:["A. 2%","B. 5%","C. 7%","D. 10%","E. 15%"],ans:2,exp:"For every 1°C decrease in brain temperature, CMR and CBF decrease by approximately 7%. CBF is nearly halved at 27°C. CMRO₂ is as low as 10% of normal at 18°C — the basis for deep hypothermic circulatory arrest. Mild hypothermia (32–34°C) is used post-cardiac arrest and as a treatment for refractory raised ICP, but has failed to improve outcomes in TBI. Hyperthermia increases CMR and CBF between 37–42°C; protein degradation occurs above 42°C.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Cerebral autoregulation maintains constant CBF over what range of mean arterial pressure, and what is the primary mechanism mediating this myogenic response?",opts:["A. MAP 30–120 mmHg; prostacyclin-mediated vasodilation","B. MAP 50–150 mmHg; mediated by endothelium-derived relaxing factor/nitric oxide (EDRF/NO)","C. MAP 60–160 mmHg; adenosine-mediated vasoconstriction","D. MAP 40–130 mmHg; angiotensin II myogenic response","E. MAP 50–130 mmHg; acetylcholine parasympathetic tone"],ans:1,exp:"Cerebral autoregulation maintains constant CBF between MAP 50–150 mmHg via a myogenic mechanism: increased MAP raises transmural vessel tension, causing smooth muscle depolarisation and precapillary vasoconstriction. The response occurs within 1–10 seconds and is mediated primarily by EDRF/nitric oxide. Above and below the plateau, CBF becomes pressure-passive. Chronic hypertension shifts the entire curve to the right (higher upper and lower limits).",ref:"Aberdeen, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"A 65-year-old with longstanding hypertension undergoes emergency neurosurgery. Compared with a normotensive patient, what is the effect of chronic hypertension on cerebral autoregulation?",opts:["A. Shifts the curve left; patient tolerates lower MAPs without ischaemia","B. Widens the autoregulatory range to MAP 40–180 mmHg","C. Shifts the curve right; patient risks ischaemia at MAPs safe in normotensive individuals","D. Abolishes autoregulation; CBF becomes entirely pressure-passive","E. Lowers the lower limit to MAP 30 mmHg due to vascular hypertrophy"],ans:2,exp:"Chronic arterial hypertension shifts both upper and lower limits of autoregulation to higher values — a rightward shift. The lower limit may be ~70–80 mmHg rather than 50 mmHg. This means hypertensive patients risk cerebral hypoperfusion at MAPs well-tolerated in normotensive individuals. Anaesthetic and postoperative blood pressure management must account for this, as excessive antihypertensive treatment can cause cerebral ischaemia.",ref:"Aberdeen, p.3",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"In healthy adults, what is the approximate cerebral blood flow (CBF) in grey matter versus white matter, and what is the whole-brain average?",opts:["A. Grey 50–60 ml/100g/min; white 40–50; average 45–55","B. Grey 100–110 ml/100g/min; white 20–25; average 45–55","C. Grey 70–80 ml/100g/min; white 30–40; average 50–60","D. Grey 45–55 ml/100g/min; white 10–15; average 30–35","E. Grey 120–130 ml/100g/min; white 40–50; average 80–90"],ans:1,exp:"Grey matter CBF is approximately 100–110 ml/100g/min versus 20–25 ml/100g/min in white matter — a ~4–5-fold difference reflecting greater neuronal metabolic activity. Whole-brain average CBF is 45–55 ml/100g/min. The brain is only 2% of body mass but receives 12–15% of resting cardiac output. Grey matter CMRO₂ (4–4.5 ml/100g/min) is approximately 5 times that of white matter (0.7–1.0 ml/100g/min).",ref:"Aberdeen, p.2",src_id:"aberdeen-cerebral-physiology",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
]},

"functional":{src:"Standard functional neurosurgery knowledge",c:[
{q:"What is the surgical target for DBS in Parkinson's disease?",a:"Subthalamic nucleus (STN) — most common target. Improves tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia, and motor fluctuations. Allows medication reduction. Globus pallidus internus (GPi) is an alternative with fewer cognitive side effects.",ref:"claude — Parkinson's DBS",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the neurosurgical options for essential tremor?",a:"Thalamotomy (VIM thalamus) or DBS of VIM thalamus — very effective for tremor. Focused ultrasound thalamotomy (HIFU) — non-invasive, unilateral. Thalamic DBS preferred for bilateral tremor.",ref:"claude — essential tremor surgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the neurosurgical options for trigeminal neuralgia?",a:"Microvascular decompression (MVD) — gold standard if vascular compression; longest durable relief (~80% at 1yr). Percutaneous procedures: balloon compression, glycerol rhizolysis, RF thermocoagulation (immediate relief, higher recurrence). Stereotactic radiosurgery (Gamma Knife — delayed effect).",ref:"claude — TGN treatment",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What characterises trigeminal neuralgia (TGN) clinically?",a:"Paroxysmal, unilateral, severe lancinating pain in V2/V3 distribution (rarely V1). Triggered by light touch (eating, talking, wind). Seconds to 2 minutes duration. Between attacks: completely pain-free. Most common cause: vascular compression of CN V at the REZ.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the most common cause of trigeminal neuralgia amenable to MVD?",a:"Vascular compression of the trigeminal nerve at the root entry zone (REZ), most commonly by the superior cerebellar artery (SCA) or AICA. MVD moves the vessel away from the nerve using a Teflon sponge.",ref:"claude — TGN MVD",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the role of anterior cingulotomy in pain surgery?",a:"Interrupts anterior cingulate cortex — reduces the affective/emotional component of chronic pain. Used for refractory cancer pain and sometimes chronic non-cancer pain. Does not eliminate sensation but reduces suffering/distress.",ref:"claude — functional neurosurgery",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What was the Anand 2011 study on MVD for TN — design and population?",a:"Retrospective cohort using the US National Inpatient Sample (NIS) database 1999–2008. 3,273 MVD procedures for trigeminal neuralgia. Median age 57. 31.5% aged ≥65, 10.7% aged ≥75. Largest study at the time examining age-related outcomes in MVD.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.202",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What is the in-hospital mortality for MVD in elderly vs younger patients (Anand 2011)?",a:"Age ≥65 vs <65: 0.68% vs 0.13% (OR 5.1, CI 1.32–19.8, p=0.0087). Age ≥75 vs <75: 1.16% vs 0.21% (OR 5.6, CI 1.58–20.1, p=0.0026). Overall: <0.5% across all ages. 10 in-hospital deaths total; mean age 70.8; iatrogenic haemorrhage most common cause.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.204",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"Which complications are increased in elderly patients undergoing MVD for TN (Anand 2011)?",a:"Any complication: 7.36% in ≥65, 10.0% in ≥75 vs lower in younger. Significantly increased with age: cardiac, pulmonary, thromboembolic, and cerebrovascular complications. NOT significantly increased: CNS infection, wound complications.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.205",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What are the discharge outcome differences for elderly MVD patients (Anand 2011)?",a:"Elderly patients had longer hospital stays and were significantly less likely to be discharged directly home (vs nursing facility or rehabilitation). No significant difference in total hospital charges between age groups.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.205",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What is the main conclusion of Anand 2011 on MVD in the elderly?",a:"MVD is feasible in elderly patients but complications increase progressively with age. Age should be viewed as a surrogate for surgical risk, not an absolute contraindication. Careful patient selection based on physiological fitness is key. Alternatives (percutaneous procedures, radiosurgery) carry no procedural mortality but have higher recurrence/failure rates.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.207",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"How do MVD outcomes in TN compare to percutaneous alternatives in terms of efficacy and safety (Anand 2011 context)?",a:"MVD: best long-term pain relief (~80% at 1yr), most durable, but requires GA and posterior fossa craniotomy with associated risks. Percutaneous procedures (RF thermocoagulation, glycerol rhizolysis, balloon compression): no procedural deaths, done under sedation, but higher recurrence. Radiosurgery (Gamma Knife): non-invasive, no procedural mortality, delayed effect (weeks–months), less durable.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.202",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the most common cause of in-hospital death after MVD in Anand 2011?",a:"Iatrogenic haemorrhage. Of 10 in-hospital deaths in the entire NIS cohort (3,273 patients), the mean age of those who died was 70.8 years. This underlines that operative bleeding complications, likely from posterior fossa dissection, are the primary mortality driver in elderly MVD.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.205",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{q:"What was the Liu 2014 meta-analysis on DBS for Parkinson's disease — design and included studies?",a:"Systematic review and meta-analysis. MEDLINE/PubMed, EMBASE, Web of Knowledge, Cochrane; to April 2013. 6 eligible RCTs, 563 patients. All compared GPi DBS vs STN DBS for advanced pharmacotherapy-refractory PD. Primary outcome measures: UPDRSIII (motor function on and off medication), UPDRSII (ADLs, on medication), LED (levodopa-equivalent dosage), BDI-II (Beck Depression Inventory). Published J Neurosurg 2014.",ref:"Liu 2014, p.1–2",src_id:"k-liu-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What were the motor function and ADL outcomes comparing GPi vs STN DBS (Liu 2014)?",a:"UPDRSIII on-medication: no significant difference (SMD 0.68, p=0.63, 5 studies, 518 patients). UPDRSIII off-medication: no significant difference (SMD 1.83, p=0.47). UPDRSII ADLs on-medication: no significant difference (SMD 0.03, p=0.97). Conclusion: GPi and STN DBS equally improve motor function and activities of daily living in advanced PD.",ref:"Liu 2014, p.3–5",src_id:"k-liu-2014",korky:true},
{q:"How did GPi and STN DBS differ in medication reduction and psychiatric outcomes (Liu 2014)?",a:"LED (levodopa-equivalent dosage): STN DBS significantly superior — greater medication reduction (pooled SMD 222.95 [95% CI 129.27–316.64], p<0.00001, 5 studies, 540 patients). BDI-II (Beck Depression Inventory): GPi DBS significantly superior — greater improvement in depression scores (SMD -2.28 [95% CI -3.73 to -0.84], p=0.002, 3 studies, 382 patients). Summary: STN = better for reducing medication burden; GPi = better for psychiatric/mood symptoms.",ref:"Liu 2014, p.5",src_id:"k-liu-2014",korky:true},
{q:"Based on Liu 2014, how does the choice between GPi and STN DBS affect clinical decision-making in Parkinson's disease?",a:"Motor outcomes: equivalent — both targets work equally well. Choose STN if: patient benefits from medication reduction (reduces dyskinesias, lowers drug burden). Choose GPi if: patient has significant depression or psychiatric comorbidity — GPi provides greater relief from depressive symptoms. STN may require more careful parameter management to avoid psychiatric side effects. Neither target universally superior; decision should incorporate patient profile, surgeon experience, and institutional preference.",ref:"Liu 2014, p.5–8",src_id:"k-liu-2014",korky:true},
{q:"What are the DBS targets for different movement disorders?",a:"Parkinson's disease: STN (most common — reduces medication, improves all motor features) or GPi (equivalent motor benefit, better for psychiatric/mood comorbidity — Liu 2014). Essential tremor: VIM thalamus (highly effective for tremor; STN/GPi are NOT used for ET). Dystonia: GPi. OCD: nucleus accumbens / anterior limb of internal capsule. Tourette's: CM thalamus or GPi. Key exam trap: ET target = VIM (not STN, not GPi).",ref:"claude — DBS targets / Liu 2014",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
],q:[
{stem:"A 65-year-old with medically refractory Parkinson's disease has disabling tremor and motor fluctuations. She is cognitively intact. Best surgical intervention?",opts:["A. Thalamotomy","B. Pallidotomy","C. STN deep brain stimulation","D. Corpus callosotomy","E. Anterior cingulotomy"],ans:2,exp:"STN-DBS is the standard surgical treatment for medically refractory Parkinson's disease. Improves all cardinal features and motor fluctuations, and allows medication reduction. Cognitive intactness is required.",ref:"claude — Parkinson's DBS",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"A 58-year-old has right-sided V2/V3 lancinating pain triggered by eating, lasting seconds, pain-free between episodes. First-line medical treatment?",opts:["A. Amitriptyline","B. Gabapentin","C. Carbamazepine","D. Opioids","E. Aspirin"],ans:2,exp:"Carbamazepine (sodium channel blocker) is the first-line treatment for trigeminal neuralgia, with strong evidence. If medically refractory, surgical options include MVD (if vascular compression on MRI), percutaneous procedures, or radiosurgery.",ref:"claude — TGN management",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"An 82-year-old with medically refractory TN has clear vascular compression on MRI and good functional status. Which statement about MVD in his age group is best supported by evidence?",opts:["A. MVD is absolutely contraindicated above age 80","B. MVD mortality is similar to younger patients — age alone should not alter decision","C. MVD carries higher mortality and complication rates in ≥75 but remains feasible with careful selection","D. Percutaneous procedures are always preferred over MVD above age 70","E. Radiosurgery provides equivalent long-term pain relief to MVD and should be preferred in all elderly patients"],ans:2,exp:"Anand 2011 (NIS, n=3,273): mortality in ≥75 was 1.16% vs 0.21% in younger (OR 5.6, p=0.003); complication rate 10.0%. Age is a surrogate for risk, not an absolute contraindication. MVD remains feasible with careful patient selection. Percutaneous procedures have no procedural mortality but higher recurrence; radiosurgery is non-invasive but less durable than MVD.",ref:"Anand 2011, p.207",src_id:"k-anand-2011",korky:true},
{stem:"A meta-analysis (Liu 2014) compared GPi vs STN deep brain stimulation for advanced Parkinson's disease across 6 RCTs (563 patients). Which statement best reflects the results?",opts:["A. STN DBS was superior to GPi DBS for both motor function and depression outcomes","B. GPi DBS was superior to STN DBS for motor function and activities of daily living","C. GPi and STN DBS produced equivalent motor outcomes; STN DBS allowed greater medication reduction; GPi DBS improved depression scores more","D. STN DBS was significantly superior across all outcome measures including mood","E. GPi and STN DBS were equivalent across all outcomes including medication requirements"],ans:2,exp:"Liu 2014: UPDRSIII (on/off) and UPDRSII — no significant difference (both targets equivalent for motor and ADL outcomes). LED: STN superior (p<0.00001) — allows greater medication reduction. BDI-II: GPi superior (p=0.002) — greater improvement in depression. Clinical implication: STN preferred when medication reduction is a priority; GPi preferred when psychiatric/mood symptoms are prominent.",ref:"Liu 2014, p.5",src_id:"k-liu-2014",korky:true},
{stem:"A 56-year-old with intractable right-sided cancer pain undergoes a left anterolateral cordotomy at C2. What is the expected immediate result?",opts:["A. Ipsilateral (right-sided) loss of pain and temperature appreciation below the lesion","B. Contralateral (right-sided) loss of two-point discrimination and proprioception","C. Ipsilateral (right-sided) loss of fine touch, vibration, and joint position sense","D. Contralateral (right-sided) loss of pain and temperature appreciation below the lesion","E. Bilateral loss of pain and temperature appreciation below the lesion"],ans:3,exp:"Cordotomy divides the anterior spinothalamic tract, which decussates within 1–2 cord segments at the level of entry — NOT in the brainstem. A left cordotomy interrupts right-sided pain/temperature fibres already travelling contralaterally. Result: contralateral (right-sided) analgesia below the lesion. Dorsal columns (proprioception, vibration, two-point discrimination) travel ipsilaterally and are not affected. For bilateral cancer pain, bilateral cordotomy is required but carries a risk of respiratory compromise at high cervical levels (involvement of ipsilateral phrenic nerve/reticulospinal tracts).",ref:"Bank, p.8",src_id:"k-bank-neuro-surgery",korky:true},
{stem:"A 64-year-old has disabling bilateral upper limb essential tremor unresponsive to propranolol and primidone. He is being considered for DBS. Which target is most appropriate?",opts:["A. Subthalamic nucleus (STN)","B. Globus pallidus internus (GPi)","C. Nucleus accumbens","D. Ventral intermediate nucleus (VIM) of the thalamus","E. Centromedian thalamic nucleus"],ans:3,exp:"VIM thalamus is the DBS target for essential tremor — highly effective for tremor suppression. STN and GPi are used for Parkinson's disease (STN preferred for motor fluctuations and medication reduction; GPi for psychiatric comorbidity per Liu 2014). Nucleus accumbens is used for OCD. Centromedian thalamus is used for Tourette's or chronic pain. For bilateral tremor, bilateral VIM DBS is preferred over bilateral thalamotomy (high dysarthria/ataxia risk). Focused ultrasound (HIFU) thalamotomy is a non-invasive unilateral alternative.",ref:"claude — DBS targets — essential tremor",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 42-year-old woman with multiple sclerosis has severe bilateral adductor spasm causing skin breakdown and impaired nursing care. She is on maximum oral baclofen with inadequate response. She undergoes a baclofen screening test: a 50 mcg intrathecal bolus produces a significant reduction in spasticity. Which of the following would be a contraindication to intrathecal baclofen pump implantation?",opts:["A. Ashworth Scale grade 4 spasticity","B. Significant renal impairment (eGFR 25 mL/min/1.73m²)","C. Confirmed allergy to baclofen","D. Obesity (BMI 38)","E. Previous spinal surgery with instrumentation at L4–5"],ans:2,exp:"Indications for intrathecal baclofen (ITB) pump: spasticity that is disabling or impairs care, inadequate response to oral agents (baclofen, diazepam, tizanidine), positive response to ITB trial dose (typically 50–100 mcg intrathecal bolus). Contraindications include: (1) CONFIRMED ALLERGY to baclofen — absolute contraindication; (2) active systemic infection — infection of implanted device carries serious risk; (3) CSF flow obstruction that would prevent drug distribution; (4) inability to attend for pump refills; (5) coagulopathy (relative). Renal impairment is NOT a contraindication — intrathecal baclofen is delivered locally into the CSF and has minimal systemic absorption; elimination is primarily via CSF turnover, not renal clearance. Ashworth grade 4 (severe spasticity) IS an indication, not a contraindication. Previous spinal surgery is a relative complexity, not a contraindication per se.",ref:"claude — intrathecal baclofen pump",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 55-year-old woman with cervical cancer has intractable bilateral leg pain from pelvic and lumbar metastases. Her pain is bilateral and below the umbilicus. She is bed-bound from pain and has a prognosis of approximately 6–9 months. She is not responding to high-dose opioids. Which surgical pain procedure is most appropriate?",opts:["A. Unilateral anterolateral cordotomy at C2 — contralateral analgesia below the lesion","B. Commissural (midline) myelotomy — bilateral division of decussating spinothalamic fibres at the midline commissure of the cord for bilateral below-waist cancer pain","C. Bilateral rhizotomy at L2–S2 — ablation of individual nerve roots supplying the legs","D. Anterior cingulotomy — interrupts affective component of pain, most appropriate for bilateral pain","E. Bilateral cordotomy at C2 — safe because the procedure is straightforward when performed bilaterally"],ans:1,exp:"For bilateral below-waist cancer pain: (1) Commissural myelotomy is the procedure of choice — the spinothalamic fibres from both sides decussate in the ventral commissure of the spinal cord as they ascend from their level of entry. A midline incision through the commissure bilaterally interrupts pain from both sides below the level of the myelotomy. The main risk is inadvertent anterior spinal artery injury (ASA runs in the ventral fissure — midline approach risks this). (2) Unilateral cordotomy would only address contralateral pain — not bilateral. (3) Bilateral C2 cordotomy is hazardous — the phrenic nerve originates at C3–5 and the reticulospinal tracts at high cervical levels; bilateral ablation risks respiratory failure (Ondine's curse), especially during sleep. (4) Rhizotomy addresses individual dermatomes and is impractical for diffuse bilateral below-waist pain. Cordotomy and myelotomy are best suited for cancer pain with limited prognosis.",ref:"claude — surgical pain procedures / myelotomy",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 27-year-old woman presents with left-sided trigeminal neuralgia affecting V1 and V2. She is otherwise well. MRI brain shows no vascular compression but does show a small area of signal change in the pons ipsilaterally. On examination she also has a mild left abducens (CN VI) palsy. What is the most likely underlying diagnosis?",opts:["A. Typical trigeminal neuralgia — vascular compression too small to see on MRI; the CN VI palsy is a coincidence","B. Secondary trigeminal neuralgia from a posterior fossa meningioma compressing CN V and CN VI together","C. Demyelinating disease (multiple sclerosis) — a trigeminal neuralgia-like presentation in a young patient with additional cranial nerve signs strongly suggests a CNS demyelinating plaque","D. Cavernous sinus thrombosis — CN V and CN VI are both in the cavernous sinus","E. Cerebellar pontine angle epidermoid — these mimic TN and frequently compress multiple cranial nerves"],ans:2,exp:"Typical trigeminal neuralgia (idiopathic TN) is a clinical diagnosis of exclusion, characterised by paroxysmal, unilateral, lancinating pain in CN V distribution triggered by light touch, without any other neurological deficit. The presence of ADDITIONAL CRANIAL NERVE ABNORMALITIES (here, CN VI palsy on the same side), young age, pontine signal change on MRI, and female sex together point strongly to SECONDARY TN from demyelinating disease (multiple sclerosis). An MS plaque at the root entry zone of CN V can cause TN-like pain, and adjacent brainstem involvement explains the CN VI palsy. This is sometimes called 'symptomatic TN.' A referral to neurology for MS workup (cerebrospinal fluid oligoclonal bands, evoked potentials) is required. Typical TN does not cause cranial nerve palsies — their presence always demands investigation for a secondary cause.",ref:"claude — secondary trigeminal neuralgia / MS",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 52-year-old with failed back surgery syndrome (FBSS) has persistent bilateral leg pain with a neuropathic quality (burning, allodynia, electrical sensations). He has undergone two previous lumbar operations. MRI shows moderate fibrosis around the nerve roots but no specific compressible pathology. Which intervention is most appropriate next?",opts:["A. Third lumbar re-operation — further decompression of the nerve roots","B. High-dose opioids — neuropathic pain responds well to strong opioids","C. Spinal cord stimulation (SCS) — the primary indication in FBSS with neuropathic leg pain is the best-evidenced non-pharmacological intervention","D. Intrathecal morphine pump — preferred over SCS for bilateral leg pain","E. Gabapentin and amitriptyline only — no interventional treatment is appropriate in FBSS"],ans:2,exp:"Spinal cord stimulation (SCS) is the most evidence-based interventional treatment for failed back surgery syndrome (FBSS) with predominant neuropathic LEG pain. The PROCESS RCT showed SCS + conventional medical management superior to conventional management alone for FBSS at 6 months and beyond. Key indication for SCS: LEG pain (radicular neuropathic component) > back pain — SCS works by stimulating the dorsal columns and inducing paraesthesia that covers the painful area. Pure axial back pain without leg pain responds poorly. Other NICE-approved SCS indications include: refractory angina (no further revascularisation possible), peripheral ischaemia/critical limb ischaemia (inoperable), complex regional pain syndrome (CRPS). Complete spinal cord injury is a CONTRAINDICATION to SCS (requires intact dorsal column pathways). First-line pharmacological treatment for neuropathic pain: amitriptyline, duloxetine, pregabalin, or gabapentin — NOT NSAIDs, not strong opioids as first-line.",ref:"claude — spinal cord stimulation / FBSS",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 62-year-old man has recurrent episodes of severe lancinating pain triggered by swallowing, yawning, and coughing. The pain is localised to the right ear, tonsillar fossa, and angle of the jaw, lasting seconds to a minute. It has been mistaken for trigeminal neuralgia. Examination is neurologically normal. What is the most likely diagnosis and first-line treatment?",opts:["A. Trigeminal neuralgia (V3 distribution) — carbamazepine","B. Geniculate neuralgia (CN VII intermediate nerve) — gabapentin","C. Glossopharyngeal neuralgia — carbamazepine first-line; microvascular decompression of the CN IX root if refractory","D. Post-herpetic neuralgia of the oropharynx — pregabalin","E. Eagle syndrome (elongated styloid process) — styloidectomy"],ans:2,exp:"Glossopharyngeal neuralgia (GPN): episodic lancinating pain in the distribution of CN IX — ear, throat, tonsil, angle of jaw, and occasionally the vagal territory (causing cardioinhibitory syncope). The key distinguishing trigger is SWALLOWING (eating, drinking, talking, yawning, coughing) — not facial touch as in trigeminal neuralgia. The pain territory (throat/ear/jaw angle vs. midface/chin) also differs from TN. Carbamazepine is first-line (same pharmacological rationale as TN). For refractory cases: MVD of the CN IX/X root exit zone; CN IX sectioning ± CN X upper fibres (vagal cardioinhibitory variant may additionally require pacemaker implantation). Eagle syndrome (elongated styloid process) causes a dull, chronic throat pain — not paroxysmal, not triggered by swallowing in the same episodic fashion.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old woman presents with a 3-year history of progressive, involuntary, unilateral twitching of the right facial muscles, beginning at the orbicularis oculi and gradually involving all right facial muscles. The movements persist during sleep. MRI shows no intra-axial pathology. What is the most likely diagnosis and preferred definitive treatment?",opts:["A. Essential blepharospasm — botulinum toxin to bilateral upper face muscles","B. Hemifacial spasm from vascular compression of the right CN VII root exit zone — botulinum toxin for symptomatic control; microvascular decompression (MVD) for definitive cure","C. Facial myokymia — rippling unilateral movement associated with demyelination; treat the underlying CNS disease","D. Right focal motor cortex irritability — anticonvulsants","E. Tourette syndrome — SSRI and CBT"],ans:1,exp:"Hemifacial spasm (HFS): unilateral synchronous contraction of all facial muscles ipsilateral to CN VII compression at its root exit zone (REZ). Features: (1) begins at orbicularis oculi, spreads to involve all ipsilateral facial muscles (orbicularis oris, platysma); (2) PERSISTS DURING SLEEP — the key distinguishing feature from tics (which cease during sleep); (3) usually caused by a tortuous AICA or PICA compressing the CN VII REZ at the pontomedullary junction. Treatment: (a) BOTULINUM TOXIN injections every 3–4 months — safe, effective, repeat treatments; (b) MVD of CN VII REZ — curative in ~90% of cases (Barker series); risks include SNHL and facial palsy. Distinguish: facial myokymia (fine rippling, not synchronous, associated with MS or brainstem tumour); blepharospasm (bilateral, upper face only); tics (resolve during sleep, suppressible).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 67-year-old man undergoes left globus pallidus internus (GPi) DBS lead implantation for Parkinson's disease. During electrode placement there is unexpected bleeding at the electrode trajectory. Post-operatively he develops a right-sided homonymous hemianopia. Which structure was most likely damaged by the haematoma?",opts:["A. Left optic nerve — direct injury during the stereotactic trajectory","B. Left optic tract — passing medial to the internal capsule beneath the diencephalon","C. Left optic radiation (geniculocalcarine tract) — immediately posterior to the GPi in the posterior limb of the internal capsule and temporal white matter; haematoma extension damages visual fibres running to the occipital cortex","D. Right occipital cortex — contrecoup vascular injury from the procedure","E. Left thalamic radiation — carrying somatosensory rather than visual fibres"],ans:2,exp:"GPi (globus pallidus internus) location: in the basal ganglia, medial to the putamen, lateral to the posterior limb of the internal capsule (PLIC). DBS trajectories pass through frontal or parietal cortex. The GPi is immediately ANTERIOR to the optic radiation — visual fibres from the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) pass through the PLIC and temporal/parietal white matter (the optic radiation / geniculocalcarine tract). A haematoma at or just posterior to the GPi target can injure the optic radiation, causing contralateral homonymous hemianopia. Left-sided haematoma → RIGHT homonymous hemianopia (visual fibres from the left LGN represent the right visual field). This is a recognised complication of pallidal DBS specifically (the STN is more medially placed and not as close to the optic radiation).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 58-year-old man with type 2 diabetes has 6 months of constant bilateral burning foot pain and bilateral distal sensory loss consistent with diabetic peripheral neuropathy. He has not received any pharmacological treatment for this pain. Which agent is recommended as first-line by NICE (NG173)?",opts:["A. Ibuprofen (NSAID) — reduces peripheral neuroinflammation","B. Oral morphine (strong opioid) — the most effective treatment for severe chronic pain of any cause","C. Amitriptyline, duloxetine, gabapentin, or pregabalin — any of these as monotherapy is NICE-first-line for neuropathic pain","D. Tramadol — recommended as first-line for all neuropathic pain syndromes","E. Topical capsaicin 0.025% cream alone — systemic therapy is not indicated for peripheral neuropathic pain"],ans:2,exp:"NICE NG173 (Neuropathic Pain, 2023): first-line pharmacological treatments for neuropathic pain are: (1) amitriptyline (low-dose TCA, e.g. 10–25mg nocte); (2) duloxetine (SNRI, especially for diabetic neuropathy and chemotherapy-induced neuropathy); (3) gabapentin; (4) pregabalin. Any one of these four is a valid first-line choice — selection is guided by comorbidities, side-effect profile, and patient preference. NSAIDs are NOT effective for neuropathic pain (neuropathic mechanism is not primarily inflammatory). Strong opioids are NOT first-line — they are third-line adjuncts. Tramadol is second or third-line. The common FRCS trap: defaulting to NSAIDs or opioids. Neuropathic pain requires agents targeting neural hypersensitivity (sodium/calcium channel stabilisation, monoamine modulation).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 32-year-old with idiopathic primary generalised dystonia has failed all oral medications (trihexyphenidyl, baclofen, tetrabenazine). Which brain target is recommended for deep brain stimulation?",opts:["A. Subthalamic nucleus (STN) — the standard Parkinson's disease target","B. Ventral intermediate nucleus of thalamus (VIM) — the standard essential tremor target","C. Globus pallidus internus (GPi) — the established, NICE-approved target for primary generalised dystonia","D. Nucleus accumbens — target for OCD and depression","E. Centromedian nucleus of thalamus — target for epilepsy and Tourette syndrome"],ans:2,exp:"DBS targets by indication: (1) Parkinson's disease → STN or GPi; (2) Essential tremor → VIM thalamus; (3) Primary generalised dystonia → GPi (bilateral) — supported by randomised evidence; response takes weeks to months, in contrast to Parkinson's where benefit is immediate; DYT1 (TOR1A) dystonia has the best GPi DBS response; (4) OCD → anterior limb of internal capsule / nucleus accumbens; (5) Epilepsy → ANT (anterior nucleus of thalamus, SANTE trial) or centromedian nucleus; (6) Tourette syndrome → centromedian-parafascicular thalamic complex. GPi for dystonia is the key FRCS answer — candidates often confuse GPi (PD/dystonia) with VIM (tremor) or STN (PD).",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true},
{stem:"A 62-year-old man undergoes MVD for right trigeminal neuralgia. After careful exploration of the CN V root entry zone, the surgeon finds NO vascular compression. What is the most appropriate intraoperative next step?",opts:["A. Place Teflon padding between CN V and adjacent dura prophylactically — the beneficial effect of MVD does not require an actual vascular compressor","B. Abandon the procedure immediately — without confirmed compression, no further intraoperative action is appropriate","C. Perform partial sensory rhizotomy (selective section of the medial sensory root fibres) — provides pain relief when no compressor is found, at the cost of controlled partial facial numbness","D. Perform complete CN V root section — highest pain control rate with acceptable permanent sensory loss","E. Inspect and decompress the petrosal vein, then close regardless of compression status"],ans:2,exp:"When MVD reveals NO vascular compression of CN V: (1) ABANDONING the procedure is not appropriate — the patient is already at risk; (2) PARTIAL SENSORY RHIZOTOMY (PSR) is the preferred salvage — selective sectioning of the medial fibres of the CN V sensory root causes controlled numbness in V2/V3 territory while preserving V1 and the corneal reflex; provides pain relief in ~80% of cases. (3) COMPLETE rhizotomy offers higher pain relief but risks anaesthesia dolorosa (deafferentation pain — severe, burning, untreatable) and keratitis from V1 loss — unacceptable risk profile. (4) Teflon placement without a verified compressor has no evidence of benefit. (5) Petrosal vein decompression: venous compression is recognised but more controversial; assuming it exists without seeing it is not appropriate. PSR is the accepted fallback when MVD intention cannot be fulfilled.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 35-year-old presents with involuntary sustained contraction of the right sternocleidomastoid causing persistent head rotation to the right and left shoulder elevation (idiopathic cervical dystonia). Which statement about genetics and aetiology is most accurate?",opts:["A. Cervical dystonia is a purely psychogenic condition — it resolves with psychotherapy alone","B. Most cases of idiopathic cervical dystonia are sporadic without an identifiable genetic mutation; it is a genuine neurological condition of basal ganglia dysfunction; TOR1A (DYT1) mutation is rare in focal dystonias and more characteristic of primary generalised dystonia","C. All cases of focal dystonia are caused by TOR1A (DYT1) gene mutation, inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern","D. Cervical dystonia is caused by dopamine deficiency — L-DOPA is the first-line treatment","E. Idiopathic cervical dystonia is classified as a functional (psychogenic) movement disorder unless proven otherwise"],ans:1,exp:"Idiopathic cervical dystonia: (1) Most cases are sporadic — no identifiable single gene mutation; familial cases exist but genetic causes in focal dystonias are uncommon. (2) It is a neurological condition — basal ganglia and cerebellar circuit dysfunction underlie the sustained agonist-antagonist co-contraction. It is NOT routinely psychogenic (though functional overlay can coexist). (3) TOR1A (DYT1): the most common genetic cause of primary GENERALISED dystonia (childhood-onset, limb-predominant, especially Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry) — rarely causes focal cervical dystonia. (4) Dopamine-responsive dystonia (Segawa disease, GCH1 mutation) is a rare, L-DOPA-responsive childhood-onset condition — not idiopathic adult CD. (5) First-line treatment for CD: botulinum toxin injections to the overactive muscles (SCM, splenius capitis, levator scapulae) — highly effective. Oral baclofen/trihexyphenidyl as adjuncts.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai",recall:true}
]},

"ethics":{src:"UK medical law and ethics (MCA 2005, GMC, case law)",c:[
{q:"What are the four principles of Beauchamp and Childress?",a:"Autonomy (respect patient's right to decide); Beneficence (act in patient's best interest); Non-maleficence (do no harm); Justice (fair distribution of resources and equal treatment).",ref:"Beauchamp & Childress"},
{q:"What is the Mental Capacity Act 2005 test for capacity?",a:"A person lacks capacity if they cannot: (1) understand relevant information; (2) retain it; (3) use or weigh it to make a decision; (4) communicate their decision. Capacity is decision-specific and time-specific. Presume capacity unless proven otherwise.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005"},
{q:"Who can consent for an incapacitous adult in England?",a:"In England, no one can consent for an incapacitous adult (unlike children where parents consent). Treatment is given in the patient's best interests under the MCA. A Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA) for health/welfare, or a court-appointed deputy, may make decisions if the LPA covers the decision.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005"},
{q:"What is Gillick competence?",a:"A child under 16 may consent to treatment if they have sufficient intelligence and understanding of the proposed treatment. Decision-specific. A competent child's consent is valid. However, a Gillick-competent child's refusal can be overridden by parents or courts in England if refusal would be harmful.",ref:"Gillick v West Norfolk (1986)"},
{q:"What is the Montgomery ruling and how does it affect consent?",a:"Montgomery v Lanarkshire (2015): doctors must ensure patients are aware of any material risks involved in treatment, and reasonable alternatives. 'Material' = what a reasonable person in the patient's position would want to know. Replaced the Bolam standard for consent.",ref:"Montgomery v Lanarkshire [2015] UKSC 11"},
{q:"What is the Bolam test and when does it apply?",a:"A doctor is not negligent if they act in accordance with a responsible body of medical opinion. Applies to clinical management (diagnosis, treatment). The Montgomery ruling REPLACED Bolam for consent/information disclosure.",ref:"Bolam v Friern Hospital [1957]"},
{q:"What is a DNAR (Do Not Attempt Resuscitation) order?",a:"A clinical decision that CPR should not be attempted if the patient has a cardiac or respiratory arrest. Can be made by a senior clinician in discussion with the patient (if capacitous) or family. Patient can refuse CPR if capacitous. Cannot be imposed against a patient's capacitous wishes to be resuscitated.",ref:"UK DNACPR guidance / GMC"},
{q:"What is the Duty of Candour in the NHS?",a:"A statutory duty (Health and Social Care Act 2008) for registered providers to be open and honest when care causes unexpected harm. Requires informing the patient/family, apologising, and providing an explanation. The SBNS has published a position statement on this.",ref:"Health and Social Care Act 2008 / Duty of Candour"},
],q:[
{stem:"A 45-year-old with a brain tumour refuses life-saving surgery. He understands the risks and can articulate his reasons. What is the correct action?",opts:["A. Perform surgery — life preservation overrides autonomy","B. Seek a court order","C. Respect his decision — a capacitous adult may refuse treatment","D. Ask next of kin to consent","E. Consult ethics committee and proceed"],ans:2,exp:"A capacitous adult has an absolute right to refuse medical treatment, even if it results in death. The duty is to ensure the patient has adequate information and has capacity, then respect their decision. Next of kin cannot consent for a capacitous adult.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005 / Re MB (1997)"},
{stem:"A 14-year-old refuses urgent craniotomy for a brain abscess citing religious beliefs. Her parents consent. What is the legal position in England?",opts:["A. Her refusal must be respected — she is Gillick competent","B. Parental consent is sufficient to authorise the operation","C. Court order required","D. Proceed without consent in an emergency","E. Wait until she turns 16"],ans:1,exp:"In England, parental consent overrides a competent child's refusal when treatment is clearly in their best interests and refusal would result in serious harm (Re W [1992]). In a genuine emergency, treatment can also proceed without consent to preserve life.",ref:"Re W (1992) / Children Act 1989"},
{stem:"Which legal case established that doctors must disclose 'material risks' to patients — replacing the Bolam standard for consent?",opts:["A. Bolam v Friern Hospital (1957)","B. Bolitho v City and Hackney (1997)","C. Montgomery v Lanarkshire (2015)","D. Chester v Afshar (2004)","E. Re MB (1997)"],ans:2,exp:"Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board [2015] UKSC 11: the Supreme Court held that the Bolam test does not apply to consent. Doctors must disclose material risks — what a reasonable patient in the claimant's position would want to know.",ref:"Montgomery v Lanarkshire [2015] UKSC 11"},
{stem:"A 35-year-old man with Down syndrome lives independently in a supported living arrangement. He attends the outpatient clinic with his parents for evaluation of cervical myelopathy requiring anterior cervical discectomy and fusion. He converses coherently about his symptoms and appears to understand the proposed surgery and its risks when explained in clear language. Who is the most appropriate person to provide consent for this procedure?",opts:["A. The patient himself, if capacity is confirmed using the MCA 2005 four-stage test","B. His parents, as their son has a learning disability that precludes valid consent","C. The Independent Mental Capacity Advocate (IMCA) on behalf of the patient","D. The care home manager, as his primary carer","E. The treating neurosurgeon, acting in best interests under the Doctrine of Necessity"],ans:0,exp:"Having Down syndrome does NOT automatically mean a person lacks decision-making capacity. Under the MCA 2005, s.1: capacity is PRESUMED unless proven otherwise. The four-stage test — can the patient (1) understand the information, (2) retain it, (3) use or weigh it, and (4) communicate a decision? — must be applied to the specific decision at hand. If he passes all four stages, he has capacity and can consent himself. His parents have no automatic legal authority to consent for an adult child with capacity — they are consultees, not decision-makers. IMCA is only engaged when a patient LACKS capacity AND has no appropriate family or friends to consult, AND the decision constitutes serious medical treatment or long-term accommodation change; it does not apply when the patient has capacity or when family members are available. The care home manager has no authority over medical consent.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005 / MCA Code of Practice",recall:true},
{stem:"A 15-year-old boy requires urgent surgery for a posterior fossa haematoma causing obstructive hydrocephalus. Significant intraoperative haemorrhage is anticipated, and the anaesthetist advises that transfusion may be essential. The patient, who is a Jehovah's Witness, objects to blood transfusion. His estranged mother (with parental responsibility) consents to surgery including transfusion if required. His father (also with parental responsibility) refuses any transfusion. The clinical team considers the risk of death without transfusion capability to be unacceptable. What is the correct legal position in England?",opts:["A. Both parents must agree — the divergence of parental opinion means no surgery can proceed without a court order","B. The patient's objection must be respected — at 15 he is Gillick competent and his refusal is legally binding","C. Surgery including potential transfusion can proceed — one parent's consent is sufficient, and a parent's consent overrides a competent minor's refusal when refusal poses a serious threat to life (Re W [1992])","D. A court order is required before surgery commences — this is mandatory when parents disagree","E. The father's refusal takes precedence as the resident parent"],ans:2,exp:"(1) Both parents hold parental responsibility; either parent's consent alone is sufficient for the treating team to proceed — it is not necessary to obtain both parents' agreement (as long as no court order prohibits it). (2) In England, a child under 16 may be Gillick competent to consent to treatment, but a Gillick-competent minor's REFUSAL of life-saving treatment can be overridden by a person with parental responsibility or by the court (Re W [1992]). This applies to all children under 18 where parental responsibility is held. (3) In genuine emergency where life is immediately at risk, treatment can also proceed under emergency powers without consent. Key exam teaching: a Gillick-competent child can AGREE to treatment (that is then valid) but CANNOT veto treatment that is overwhelmingly in their best interests — this asymmetry is a deliberate feature of English law.",ref:"Re W (1992) / Gillick v West Norfolk (1986) / Children Act 1989",recall:true},
{stem:"One emergency theatre is available. Three patients simultaneously require urgent surgery: (A) a 22-year-old woman with a ruptured ectopic pregnancy and haemorrhagic shock (BP 65/40, HR 142, Hb 4.9 g/dl); (B) a 45-year-old man with hydrocephalus from a posterior fossa tumour, GCS 12, currently stable; (C) a 55-year-old woman with acute non-perforated appendicitis, stable, already on IV antibiotics. In which order should these patients be prioritised?",opts:["A. B first (hydrocephalus), then A (ectopic), then C (appendicitis) — the neurosurgical patient has priority in a neurosurgical theatre","B. A first (ruptured ectopic), then B (hydrocephalus), then C (appendicitis) — A has immediately life-threatening haemorrhage","C. C first (appendicitis), then A (ectopic), then B (hydrocephalus) — appendicitis will perforate if untreated","D. A first (ruptured ectopic), then C (appendicitis), then B (hydrocephalus) — appendicitis deteriorates faster than stable hydrocephalus","E. All three can safely wait until a second theatre team arrives"],ans:1,exp:"Theatre prioritisation is determined by the immediacy of the threat to life. (A) Ruptured ectopic with haemorrhagic shock is the most immediately life-threatening: systolic BP 65 = Class III–IV haemorrhagic shock, cardiac arrest is imminent without haemorrhage control. This patient is first. (B) Hydrocephalus with GCS 12 is urgent but clinically stable at the moment — a short delay while the ectopic is managed is acceptable. (C) Non-perforated appendicitis on IV antibiotics can safely wait several hours without significant deterioration. The common trap is to prioritise the neurosurgical case on specialty grounds or to prioritise appendicitis on the grounds of perforation risk — both are incorrect. The principle is: the patient at greatest risk of dying within minutes takes precedence, regardless of specialty or the nature of the theatre.",ref:"GMC Good Medical Practice / Ethical principles: Justice, Non-maleficence",recall:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical trainee reads a randomised trial comparing two approaches for lumbar microdiscectomy. The paper reports that wound infection occurred in 3% of Group A and 11% of Group B; a chi-square test gives p=0.03. Which statement is correct?",opts:["A. p=0.03 means there is a 3% probability that the null hypothesis is true — i.e., 97% probability that the intervention works","B. Chi-square is appropriate here; p=0.03 means there is a 3% probability of observing a difference this large by chance if there were truly no difference between groups","C. Chi-square is the wrong test — a t-test should be used when comparing two independent proportions","D. p=0.03 proves that Approach A causes lower infection rates — causation is established","E. p=0.03 is not statistically significant — the threshold is p<0.01"],ans:1,exp:"(1) Chi-square test: the correct statistical test to compare CATEGORICAL (non-numerical / proportional) data between two independent groups — e.g., 'infected vs not infected' in Group A vs Group B. (2) p-value interpretation: p=0.03 means that IF the null hypothesis were true (no difference between groups), a result at least as extreme would occur by chance with probability 3% (approximately 1 in 33). It does NOT mean '3% probability the null hypothesis is true' — the p-value makes no probability statement about the hypothesis. (3) p<0.05 = statistically significant by convention (corresponds to 1 in 20 chance by chance). (4) p<0.05 does NOT prove causation. (5) t-test: compares MEANS of continuous normally-distributed data. Wilcoxon or Mann-Whitney U: for non-parametric continuous data. Chi-square: for categorical proportions between independent groups. McNemar's chi-square: for paired categorical data.",ref:"Research methods / statistics — FRCS (SN) syllabus",recall:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical SpR notices that an anaesthetic consultant managing their lists has been making repeated calculation errors, appears confused during procedures, and several theatre nurses have raised informal concerns. The SpR believes patient safety is at risk. What is the most appropriate initial action?",opts:["A. Contact the GMC directly and file an immediate fitness to practise concern","B. Discuss the concerns with the neurosurgical clinical director — they are the most senior person the SpR knows","C. Raise concerns with a senior colleague within the anaesthetic department (e.g., the anaesthetic clinical director or lead consultant)","D. Take no action — the SpR is not in a supervisory role over an anaesthetic consultant","E. Speak to the individual consultant directly; if behaviour continues, escalate to the hospital chief executive"],ans:2,exp:"GMC Good Medical Practice (2024): all doctors have a professional duty to raise concerns when they believe patient safety is at risk. Silence is not an option. The appropriate route for concerns about a colleague from another department is: (1) Raise concerns with a SENIOR COLLEAGUE WITHIN THAT COLLEAGUE'S OWN SPECIALTY — typically the anaesthetic clinical director or a consultant of equivalent seniority. They have clinical governance authority within their department. The neurosurgical clinical director has no authority over the anaesthetic department. (2) If departmental channels fail, escalate to the medical director or trust's designated person for safety concerns. (3) GMC referral is for serious ongoing concerns not addressed internally, or situations of immediate danger. (4) Approaching the individual directly first may be appropriate if safe and comfortable; but alone is often insufficient when behaviour suggests a health or conduct issue. The hospital CEO is not the appropriate first contact.",ref:"GMC Good Medical Practice 2024 / Raising Concerns",recall:true},
{stem:"During an elective lumbar decompression, an unexpected finding raises clinical suspicion of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) in the patient. Standard autoclaving has been used throughout the procedure. What is the correct action regarding the surgical instruments?",opts:["A. Standard autoclaving (134°C, 3 minutes) reliably destroys prions — no additional measures are required","B. Glutaraldehyde immersion for 30 minutes will adequately decontaminate the instruments","C. Standard autoclaving does not reliably inactivate prions; instruments should be quarantined pending CJD confirmation; if confirmed, instruments used on high-risk tissue should be destroyed or subject to specialist chemical decontamination (sodium hydroxide or hypochlorite) before any extended steam cycle","D. Prion precautions are only required once CJD is confirmed — suspected cases do not warrant additional instrument management","E. Re-processing these instruments is safe as spinal cord is not a high-risk tissue for CJD transmission"],ans:2,exp:"Prion proteins (PrP-Sc) are exceptionally resistant to standard decontamination: steam autoclaving at routine cycles (134°C, 3 min), UV irradiation, formaldehyde, and glutaraldehyde do NOT reliably inactivate prions. Glutaraldehyde FIXES prion proteins to surfaces and may increase adherence, worsening the problem. NICE/DH CJD guidance: (1) Use DISPOSABLE instruments where possible when CJD is suspected or known. (2) If reusable instruments are used: QUARANTINE them and do not re-use pending confirmation. (3) If CJD confirmed: ideally DESTROY instruments used on high-risk tissue (brain, spinal cord, dural graft, posterior eye); if destruction is not possible, specialist decontamination may reduce (but cannot eliminate) infectivity. (4) High-risk tissues include brain, spinal cord, and posterior eye; these precautions apply even to SUSPECTED cases. Spinal cord IS a high-risk tissue.",ref:"NICE/DH Guidance on CJD — instrument decontamination",recall:true},
{stem:"A 12-year-old boy requires urgent craniotomy for a posterior fossa haematoma. Intraoperative haemorrhage requiring blood transfusion is anticipated. The patient has been raised as a Jehovah's Witness and agrees to the surgery. His mother (who has parental responsibility) consents to surgery including blood transfusion. His father (also with parental responsibility) strongly objects to any transfusion on religious grounds. The clinical team believes the risk of death without transfusion capability is unacceptable. What is the legal position?",opts:["A. Both parents must agree before surgery can proceed — divergence of parental opinion requires a court order","B. The father's refusal takes precedence because his religious beliefs must be respected under the Human Rights Act","C. The mother's consent alone is sufficient; either parent with parental responsibility may consent independently; the child's agreement and the mother's consent authorise the team to proceed including transfusion","D. The child is too young to hold a view that carries any legal weight","E. The team must await formal assessment of Gillick competence by a specialist before proceeding"],ans:2,exp:"In England, both parents share parental responsibility after a child's birth (if both registered). EITHER parent's consent for medical treatment is legally sufficient — it is not necessary to obtain agreement from both, unless a court order specifically requires it. The father's refusal does NOT override the mother's consent. For a 12-year-old, Gillick competence may exist (under-16s can consent to treatment if they understand the nature and consequences), but Gillick competence confers the right to AGREE to treatment — not to veto it. A Gillick-competent minor's refusal of life-saving treatment can be overridden by a parent with parental responsibility (Re W [1992]) or by the courts. In this scenario: mother consents + child agrees + life is at immediate risk → proceed with surgery and transfusion capability. The father's refusal does not have legal force in the face of the mother's consent.",ref:"Re W (1992) / Gillick v West Norfolk (1986) / Children Act 1989 / MCA 2005",recall:true},
{stem:"A 45-year-old man sustains a severe TBI. After 2 weeks in ICU his GCS is M3E2V1 (total 6). He has no advance decision to refuse treatment (ADRT) and no Lasting Power of Attorney. His wife attends a meeting and tells the team that 'he always said he would never want to live with severe disability — he'd rather die.' Who has the legal authority to make the decision about whether to continue life-sustaining treatment?",opts:["A. The wife — she knows his wishes best and should make the decision","B. The treating consultant, acting in the patient's best interests under the Mental Capacity Act 2005, having consulted all relevant parties including the wife","C. The hospital legal department must make this decision","D. An Independent Mental Capacity Advocate (IMCA) must be appointed and their recommendation followed","E. A court ruling is required before any decision about life-sustaining treatment can be made"],ans:1,exp:"Under the Mental Capacity Act 2005 (England and Wales): (1) When an adult lacks capacity (as here — GCS M3, no purposeful response), the TREATING CLINICIAN (consultant in charge) is the decision-maker for medical treatment decisions, acting in the patient's best interests under MCA s.4. (2) The wife's views are critically important and must be actively sought and considered — she may be able to provide information about the patient's previously expressed wishes and values. However, she does NOT have legal authority to consent or withhold consent unless she holds a registered Lasting Power of Attorney for Health and Welfare. (3) IMCA: appointed when a patient lacks capacity AND has no appropriate family/friends to consult — does NOT apply here as the wife is available. (4) Court: required for highly contested cases or when CANH (clinically assisted nutrition and hydration) withdrawal is considered in prolonged disorders of consciousness (following NHS Trust v Y). For general treatment decisions it is not required. The treating consultant, consulting the wife and MDT, is the appropriate decision-maker.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005 / MCA Code of Practice / NHS Trust v Y [2018]",recall:true},
{stem:"At the end of a lumbar laminectomy, the surgeon notices an area of dural damage and CSF leak that occurred during the procedure. The tear was repaired intraoperatively. The patient's post-operative recovery is uncomplicated. Is the surgeon obliged to tell the patient what happened?",opts:["A. No — the leak was repaired and caused no harm; there is no duty to disclose something that was fixed","B. Yes — the duty of candour (CQC Regulation 20 and GMC guidance) requires that patients are told when something unexpected happens that could cause harm, even if harm was avoided; the patient must be informed and apologised to","C. Only if the patient directly asks whether any complications occurred","D. Only if the hospital trust requires it — there is no individual clinician duty","E. Only if the patient experiences symptoms post-operatively that might be related"],ans:1,exp:"The Duty of Candour (CQC Regulation 20, statutory since April 2015; also Francis Report 2013; GMC Good Medical Practice 2024) requires that when a patient is harmed or experiences an unintended or unexpected incident — even if harm was avoided or minimal — the patient must be: (1) Told as soon as practicable; (2) Offered an apology; (3) Given a full account of what happened; (4) Informed of further enquiries being made. This applies to ALL healthcare providers and individual clinicians. An intraoperative dural tear and CSF leak is an 'unintended incident' even if repaired. Failure to disclose is a breach of professional obligation and potentially constitutes dishonesty under GMC standards. The patient may need monitoring for post-op headache, and knowledge of the event is clinically relevant to their post-operative care.",ref:"CQC Regulation 20 / GMC Good Medical Practice 2024 / Francis Report 2013",recall:true},
{stem:"A researcher wishes to compare pain scores (measured on a visual analogue scale, not normally distributed) between two independent groups: patients who received physiotherapy versus those who did not. Which statistical test is most appropriate?",opts:["A. Chi-square test — for comparing two proportions","B. Student's t-test — for comparing means of two groups","C. Mann-Whitney U test (Wilcoxon rank-sum test) — for comparing two independent groups of non-parametric/non-normally distributed continuous or ordinal data","D. Pearson correlation — for assessing the relationship between two continuous variables","E. ANOVA — for comparing three or more groups"],ans:2,exp:"Mann-Whitney U test (also called Wilcoxon rank-sum test): the correct NON-PARAMETRIC test for comparing TWO INDEPENDENT groups when data is: (1) ordinal, or (2) continuous but NOT normally distributed, or (3) the sample size is too small to assume normality. Pain VAS scores are continuous but commonly non-normally distributed — Mann-Whitney is appropriate. Distinguish from: (1) Wilcoxon SIGNED-RANK test — for two PAIRED (matched) non-parametric groups; (2) Student's t-test — for two independent groups with NORMALLY DISTRIBUTED continuous data; (3) Chi-square — for CATEGORICAL proportions; (4) ANOVA — for THREE OR MORE groups with parametric data; (5) Kruskal-Wallis — non-parametric equivalent of ANOVA (3+ groups). Exam mnemonic: 'Mann-Whitney = two independent non-normal groups; Wilcoxon signed-rank = two paired non-normal groups'.",ref:"Research methods / statistics — FRCS (SN) syllabus",recall:true},
{stem:"A 54-year-old patient has been confirmed brain-stem dead following a massive intracerebral haemorrhage. The family wish to proceed with organ donation. Which of the following is an absolute contraindication to solid organ donation under UK guidance?",opts:["A. Treated haematological malignancy in remission for 5 years","B. HIV infection (HIV-positive antibody status; clinically well; undetectable viral load on treatment)","C. Known nvCJD (new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease)","D. Active pulmonary tuberculosis on treatment for 8 weeks","E. Age 88 years"],ans:2,exp:"UK organ donation guidance absolute contraindications: (1) Known or suspected nvCJD and other neurodegenerative diseases associated with infectious agents. (2) Known HIV disease — but NOT HIV infection alone. HIV-positive status with undetectable viral load is not an absolute contraindication (option B). Active TB, age >90, and malignancy in remission are relative (not absolute) contraindications — donation may still proceed if the alternative for the recipient is imminent death. Age 88 is below the >90 relative threshold.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.4-5",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"Following brainstem death confirmation, the organ donation specialist nurse reviews the potential donor's medical history. Which combination of findings would most likely lead to donation being declined under UK guidance?",opts:["A. Age 86, well-controlled hypertension, treated non-melanoma basal cell carcinoma 2 years ago","B. Disseminated metastatic colorectal carcinoma — a relative contraindication; donation highly likely to be declined","C. Cutaneous melanoma excised with wide margins 6 years ago, no recurrence","D. HIV-positive status — absolute contraindication regardless of viral load","E. Type 1 diabetes mellitus — listed as an absolute contraindication to kidney donation"],ans:1,exp:"UK guidance relative contraindications — donation is highly likely to be declined: disseminated malignancy; melanoma (except local melanoma treated >5 years before donation — option C at 6 years is now acceptable); treated malignancy within 3 years (except non-melanoma skin cancer — option A is non-melanoma, so acceptable); age >90; known active tuberculosis; untreated bacterial sepsis. HIV disease is an absolute contraindication, but HIV infection alone (positive status, well-controlled) is not. Non-melanoma skin cancer is explicitly excluded from the malignancy contraindication. Diabetes is not listed as a contraindication.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A patient with a catastrophic brain injury has not fulfilled brainstem death criteria. The ICU consultant and MDT agree that continued ventilatory support is no longer in the patient's best interests. The organ donation nurse asks to join the family meeting. Which statement correctly describes the ethical and legal boundary between withdrawal of treatment and organ donation?",opts:["A. The donation nurse should attend the withdrawal meeting — early involvement improves donation rates without ethical conflict","B. Donation after cardiac death should be proposed to the family before the withdrawal decision is finalised, to allow informed consent for both decisions simultaneously","C. The decision to withdraw life-sustaining treatment must be fully independent from any subsequent discussion about organ donation; the issue of donation should not be raised until the family has accepted the withdrawal decision, unless the family raises it first","D. Members of the transplant team may attend the withdrawal meeting to provide clinical advice on organ viability","E. Once withdrawal is planned, it is acceptable to modify the timing of withdrawal to optimise organ perfusion before cardiac arrest"],ans:2,exp:"UK Code of Practice: any decision to withdraw life-sustaining cardio-respiratory organ support must be fully independent from any subsequent discussion about organ donation. The withdrawal decision must be based solely on what is in the patient's best interests and must be robust enough to bear objective scrutiny. It must not involve staff potentially involved in transplantation of organs from the patient. Unless raised by the family themselves, the issue of donation should not be discussed until the decision to withdraw has been accepted by the family. Donation after Cardiac Death (DCD) is a separate pathway that may follow — but the two decisions must remain ethically and temporally distinct.",ref:"Aberdeen neuro-death, p.5",src_id:"aberdeen-neuro-death",korky:true,recall:true},
{stem:"In a neurosurgical outpatient clinic, waiting times follow a normal distribution with a mean of 2 hours and a standard deviation of 1 hour. What percentage of patients are seen within 4 hours?",opts:["A. ~68% (within 1 SD of the mean)","B. ~84% (up to mean + 1 SD)","C. ~95% (within 2 SDs of the mean, i.e. between 0 and 4 hours)","D. ~97.5% (4 hours is 2 SDs above the mean; 97.5% of the distribution lies below this point)","E. ~99.7% (within 3 SDs of the mean)"],ans:3,exp:"Normal distribution properties: 68% within 1 SD; 95% within 2 SDs; 99.7% within 3 SDs. Here: mean = 2 hours, SD = 1 hour. 4 hours = mean + 2 SDs. The TOTAL area within mean ± 2 SDs = 95% (roughly). BUT the question asks 'within 4 hours' — this is a ONE-SIDED question (below the upper limit of mean + 2 SDs). The area below mean + 2 SDs = 97.5% (because the 5% outside the ±2 SD range is split: 2.5% above and 2.5% below; negative waiting times are impossible, so practically all patients are above zero). Therefore: 97.5% of patients are seen within 4 hours. This is a standard FRCS exam question testing the 68–95–99.7 rule and understanding of one- vs two-tailed normal distribution proportions.",ref:"Research methods / statistics — FRCS (SN) syllabus",recall:true},
{stem:"An Independent Mental Capacity Advocate (IMCA) is required by law under the Mental Capacity Act 2005. In which situation must an IMCA be appointed?",opts:["A. Whenever a patient lacks decision-making capacity, to represent their best interests","B. When a patient lacks capacity, has no appropriate family members or friends to consult, AND the decision involves either serious medical treatment or a long-term change in accommodation","C. Only for patients detained under the Mental Health Act","D. Whenever family members disagree with the clinical team about a patient's care","E. Only when the patient has previously expressed a wish for an IMCA in their advance decision"],ans:1,exp:"IMCA (Independent Mental Capacity Advocate) service — statutory duty under MCA 2005 s.37–39: An IMCA MUST be instructed when ALL of the following apply: (1) The patient LACKS CAPACITY to make the specific decision; AND (2) There is NO appropriate person to consult — no family member, friend, or carer who is willing and able to be involved (other than paid carers); AND (3) The decision involves either: (a) SERIOUS MEDICAL TREATMENT (e.g. major surgery, starting/stopping treatment likely to have serious consequences) as defined by the Secretary of State; OR (b) a long-term move in accommodation. An IMCA is NOT required when: family members or friends ARE available to consult; or the patient has capacity. The IMCA's role is to represent the patient's interests and values — NOT to consent or refuse on behalf of the patient; the treating clinician still makes the best-interests decision. The IMCA provision does NOT apply to detained patients under the MHA (separate safeguards exist).",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005 ss.37–39 / MCA Code of Practice Chapter 10",recall:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical SpR is asked by a patient's employer's insurance company to urgently provide a detailed report on a patient who recently had carpal tunnel decompression surgery. The letter describes the surgery as 'urgent' and time-critical, though the procedure was in fact elective. What is the most appropriate course of action?",opts:["A. Provide a detailed report immediately — the insurance company's legal team has authority to access medical records","B. Refuse entirely — employment insurance companies have no right to any medical information","C. Obtain the patient's written consent before releasing any information; write a complete and accurate report that correctly represents the clinical urgency; do not describe elective surgery as urgent","D. Write a vague report that minimises the clinical details to protect the patient's interests","E. Forward the request directly to the clinical director without taking any personal action"],ans:2,exp:"Medical confidentiality and reports for third parties: (1) Patient's written CONSENT is required before any information is disclosed to an employer, insurer, or solicitor — unless specific legal exceptions apply. (2) When consent is obtained, the report must be COMPLETE and ACCURATE — under GMC Good Medical Practice, you must not withhold relevant information, write a dishonestly vague report, or mislead a third party (even to benefit the patient). Misrepresenting a procedure as 'urgent' when it was elective is dishonest and a breach of GMC obligations. (3) The Access to Medical Reports Act 1988 gives patients the right to see reports written about them for employment or insurance purposes before they are sent. (4) Writing a deliberately vague or inaccurate report is professional misconduct. The 'irt6/rq30 insurance report' scenario tests that: (a) consent must precede disclosure; (b) accuracy is mandatory; (c) misrepresenting urgency is wrong.",ref:"GMC Good Medical Practice 2024 / Access to Medical Reports Act 1988 / Confidentiality guidance",recall:true},
{stem:"A patient is listed for elective resection of a posterior fossa meningioma. Pre-operative review reveals he was previously investigated — but not formally diagnosed — for suspected sporadic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (sCJD). Which instrument protocol is correct?",opts:["A. Standard autoclave sterilisation at 134°C for 3 minutes is sufficient to eliminate prion risk","B. Use single-use (disposable) instruments for all brain-contact equipment wherever possible; any non-disposable instruments used must be quarantined and managed per NHS/NICE prion guidance pending diagnostic clarification","C. Postpone the operation indefinitely until formal CJD exclusion — no elective surgery is possible in a suspected CJD case","D. Chemical sterilisation with glutaraldehyde adequately inactivates prions on standard surgical instruments","E. Normal hospital decontamination eliminates prion risk in patients who have not received a formal CJD diagnosis"],ans:1,exp:"Prions are resistant to standard autoclaving (134°C, 3 min), chemical disinfectants (glutaraldehyde, formaldehyde, alcohol, chlorine dioxide at standard concentrations), UV radiation, and ionising radiation. NICE and NHS national prion guidance: (1) Use DISPOSABLE single-use instruments wherever possible for all brain-contact surgery in patients with known or suspected prion disease. (2) Non-disposable instruments used on high-risk tissue (brain, spinal cord, posterior eye, olfactory epithelium) must be QUARANTINED post-procedure and assessed per national protocol — typically incineration if sCJD is confirmed, or quarantine pending case classification. (3) Standard autoclave is insufficient for prion inactivation — extended cycles (134°C, 18 min in a porous load autoclave) reduce but do not eliminate prion infectivity. (4) 'Not yet formally diagnosed' does not reduce the risk — a suspected case requires the same precautionary protocol. The operation may proceed with disposable instruments and appropriate precautions.",ref:"NICE guidelines on CJD and surgical instruments / NHS England Prion Disease Policy",recall:true},
{stem:"A professor recruits four groups of patients with different grades of lumbar spondylosis. At a single outpatient appointment, all patients complete pain questionnaires, neurological examinations, and MRI scans. No follow-up is arranged. What study design is this?",opts:["A. Randomised controlled trial — patients are allocated to four groups by the investigator","B. Prospective cohort study — four groups are identified and followed forward in time","C. Case-control study — cases with spondylosis are compared with controls without spondylosis retrospectively","D. Cross-sectional study — all groups are assessed at a single point in time with no longitudinal follow-up","E. Retrospective cohort study — data is extracted from historical case records"],ans:3,exp:"Cross-sectional study: data is collected from all groups simultaneously at a SINGLE POINT IN TIME. Key features: (1) no randomisation — groups defined by pre-existing disease characteristics; (2) no follow-up — this is a 'snapshot' of prevalence, not incidence; (3) cannot establish temporal causality. Contrast: RCT (randomisation, intervention); prospective cohort (exposure then outcome, followed forward); case-control (outcome identified first, exposure investigated retrospectively); retrospective cohort (historical records, followed forward). Cross-sectional studies are used to estimate disease prevalence and associations, to generate hypotheses, and for needs assessment. They are subject to prevalence-incidence bias — only patients surviving to the time of assessment are captured.",ref:"Research methods and statistics — FRCS (SN) syllabus",recall:true},
{stem:"A randomised trial of anterior versus posterior cervical discectomy reports a p-value of 0.04 for the primary outcome (patient-reported pain at 1 year). Which interpretation is most accurate?",opts:["A. There is a 4% probability that the null hypothesis is true","B. If there were truly no difference between the groups, a result as extreme as this would occur by chance in 4% of similar studies — i.e., a 1 in 25 probability of this result arising under the null hypothesis","C. There is a 96% probability that anterior discectomy is superior","D. The result is clinically meaningful and should immediately change neurosurgical practice","E. It is impossible that this result arose by chance"],ans:1,exp:"The p-value represents the probability of observing a test result at least as extreme as the one obtained, ASSUMING THE NULL HYPOTHESIS IS TRUE. It does NOT tell you: the probability the null hypothesis is true (option A); the probability of treatment superiority (option C); clinical significance (option D); or certainty (option E). P = 0.04 means: under the assumption of no true effect, a result this extreme or more extreme would arise by chance 4% of the time (1 in 25). This falls below the conventional threshold of 0.05 (1 in 20). Key FRCS traps: (a) p <0.05 does not prove the hypothesis — it is a probability statement about the data given the null hypothesis; (b) statistical significance ≠ clinical significance; (c) a large sample can make a clinically trivial difference statistically significant.",ref:"Research methods and statistics — FRCS (SN) syllabus",recall:true},
{stem:"A 90-year-old woman with severe dementia (Barthel 30/100) is brought from her care home with GCS 9 after a witnessed fall. CT shows an acute-on-chronic right subdural haematoma with 12mm midline shift. She has no advance decision and no prior recorded wishes about surgery or resuscitation. Her son insists she would have wanted 'everything done.' What is the most appropriate approach?",opts:["A. Proceed immediately to burr hole drainage — the son has consented and urgent decompression is the correct response to midline shift","B. Decline all treatment — patients with dementia should not be offered surgical intervention","C. Conduct a structured best-interests assessment under the MCA: collate information about her known values and wishes, consult the multidisciplinary team, involve the family as consultees (not decision-makers), and reach a proportionate clinical decision — surgery is not automatically indicated or contraindicated","D. Seek a Court of Protection order before any decision — no action is legally possible until judicial authority is granted","E. Transfer immediately to palliative care without further assessment"],ans:2,exp:"Patients lacking capacity require a BEST INTERESTS decision under the Mental Capacity Act 2005 — not proxy consent from the next of kin. The son is a consultee, not a decision-maker. Key steps: (1) Explore her known values, preferences, and prior expressions — care home records, GP notes, family accounts of her stated wishes. (2) Consider clinical prognosis: severe dementia + baseline Barthel 30 + 90 years of age — realistic functional recovery from neurosurgery may be very limited. (3) Surgery may still be in her best interests (e.g., if she had expressed a strong wish to live regardless), or it may not — the decision is individual, not categorical. (4) Court of Protection is NOT needed for urgent decisions — the treating clinician can and must make the best-interests decision. (5) Families' insistence on treatment does not override a proportionate best-interests analysis. Neither immediate operation nor immediate palliative care is correct without assessment.",ref:"Mental Capacity Act 2005 s.4 / MCA Code of Practice Chapter 5",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A 15-year-old Jehovah's Witness requires urgent blood transfusion during surgery after major haemorrhage. He is oriented, has clearly confirmed his refusal of blood products, and is otherwise competent for his age. His parents are separated: his mother (with whom he lives; holds parental responsibility) agrees to transfusion. His father (also holds parental responsibility) refuses. What is the legally and ethically correct action?",opts:["A. Respect his refusal — a competent 15-year-old's decision must be treated as equivalent to an adult's","B. Proceed with blood transfusion — in a life-threatening emergency, ONE parent with parental responsibility consenting to life-saving treatment is legally sufficient to authorise it; moreover, the court can override a minor's refusal of life-saving treatment","C. Withhold transfusion until BOTH parents agree — a single parental consent is insufficient when the other parent with parental responsibility actively objects","D. Obtain an urgent Court of Protection order — no clinical action is legally possible until judicial authority is granted","E. Transfuse and document without seeking any further consent or judicial review"],ans:1,exp:"UK law on minors and refusal of life-saving treatment: (1) Under 16, even a Gillick-competent minor's REFUSAL of life-saving treatment CAN be overridden by a parent OR by the court (Re E [1993]; Re W [1992]). This distinguishes minors from adults, who have an absolute right to refuse. (2) When parents DISAGREE about a life-saving intervention: one parent with parental responsibility consenting to life-saving treatment is legally sufficient — the other parent's refusal cannot constitute an effective veto on emergency care. The mother's consent is sufficient. (3) In practice: transfuse on the mother's consent and document thoroughly. An emergency court application (inherent jurisdiction) should follow as soon as practicable when there is parental disagreement. (4) Blood products should never be withheld from a minor in a life-threatening situation on the basis of the minor's religious beliefs alone — the minor's refusal is a factor in best-interests assessment, not a veto.",ref:"Re E (A Minor) [1993] / Re W (A Minor) [1992] / MCA 2005 / Children Act 1989",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A single emergency theatre is available simultaneously for three patients: (1) a 34-year-old woman with a ruptured ectopic pregnancy and haemodynamic instability (BP 78/40, HR 135); (2) a 28-year-old man with obstructive hydrocephalus and GCS 12 requiring emergency VP shunt; (3) a 62-year-old with acute appendicitis, not yet peritonitic. In what order should they be listed?",opts:["A. Ruptured ectopic → VP shunt → appendicectomy — haemodynamic instability from haemorrhage is imminently fatal (minutes); acute hydrocephalus neurologically threatens within hours; appendicitis can safely wait","B. VP shunt → ruptured ectopic → appendicectomy — neurological emergencies always precede general surgical emergencies","C. Appendicectomy → ruptured ectopic → VP shunt — appendicitis carries the greatest long-term morbidity without early surgery","D. Ruptured ectopic → appendicectomy → VP shunt — all abdominal emergencies precede neurological procedures","E. They are equally urgent — simultaneous sequential listing is the only fair approach"],ans:0,exp:"Emergency theatre triage uses a framework of IMMINENCE and REVERSIBILITY: (1) RUPTURED ECTOPIC with BP 78/40 and HR 135 — exsanguinating haemorrhage causing death within MINUTES without surgical control. Absolute priority. (2) OBSTRUCTIVE HYDROCEPHALUS GCS 12 — acute ICP elevation risking herniation within HOURS; a genuine neurological emergency but NOT immediately fatal in the same minute-level window. Second. (3) ACUTE APPENDICITIS (not peritonitic) — urgent but safely deferrable by several hours without materially worsening prognosis. Third. The principle: seconds-to-death situations override minutes-to-death situations, which override hours-to-death situations. The trap is option B — candidates may assume that a neurosurgical emergency takes precedence, but uncorrected haemodynamic instability from haemorrhage kills faster than acute hydrocephalus.",ref:"NCEPOD prioritisation / FRCS SN ethics syllabus",recall:true,hard:true},
{stem:"A neurosurgical SpR is offered a financial contribution by a medical device company toward purchasing reference books for the department. She is uncertain whether accepting is appropriate. What is the most appropriate course of action?",opts:["A. Accept without informing anyone — minor educational gifts from industry are universally acceptable","B. Refuse entirely — the GMC prohibits all interactions between clinicians and the medical device industry","C. Consult the Trust's conflict of interest policy, discuss with the clinical director, declare the contribution transparently if proceeding, and only accept if satisfied it will not influence clinical decision-making — modest genuinely educational benefits may be acceptable when declared","D. Accept provided the total value is under £50 — this is the GMC-approved threshold for industry gifts","E. Accept and record it in the personal surgical logbook only"],ans:2,exp:"GMC Good Medical Practice 2024 — benefits from commercial organisations: (1) You must not allow gifts, hospitality, or benefits to affect your prescribing, referral, or clinical decisions. (2) All such arrangements must be DECLARED to your employer and in relevant professional contexts. (3) Educational benefits from industry may be permissible only if: they are modest and genuinely educational; they are transparent; and they do not create a conflict of interest or appearance of inducement. (4) There is NO specific GMC monetary threshold (e.g. '£50') — the principle is transparency and independence, not an absolute amount. (5) Cash gifts are never acceptable. (6) The Trust's conflict of interest policy takes precedence locally — it must be consulted. Accepting without declaration or review is a breach of GMC obligations, even for small amounts.",ref:"GMC Good Medical Practice 2024 — conflicts of interest and commercial relationships",recall:true}
]},

"spinal-anatomy":{src:"Standard neurosurgical anatomy",c:[
{q:"At what level does the spinal cord end (conus medullaris) in adults?",a:"L1–L2 in adults. Below this is the cauda equina (collection of lumbosacral nerve roots). In neonates, the cord ends lower (~L3). LP should be performed below L3–L4 or at L4–L5 to avoid the cord.",ref:"claude — neuroanatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the incomplete spinal cord injury syndromes?",a:"Central cord (most common); Anterior cord (loss of motor + pain/temperature, preserved proprioception); Brown-Séquard (hemicord — ipsilateral motor/proprioception loss, contralateral pain/temperature loss); Posterior cord (rare — loss of proprioception/vibration); Conus medullaris; Cauda equina.",ref:"claude",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is Brown-Séquard syndrome?",a:"Cord hemisection: ipsilateral motor (corticospinal) deficit + ipsilateral loss of proprioception/vibration/fine touch (dorsal columns); CONTRALATERAL loss of pain and temperature (spinothalamic) 1–2 levels below injury. Best prognosis of incomplete syndromes.",ref:"claude — SCI syndromes",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the blood supply territories of the spinal cord?",a:"Anterior two-thirds: anterior spinal artery (ASA, from vertebral arteries + artery of Adamkiewicz at T8–L2). Posterior one-third: paired posterior spinal arteries (PSA, from vertebral or PICA). ASA territory affected in anterior cord syndrome.",ref:"claude — spinal vascular anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What is the artery of Adamkiewicz and why is it important?",a:"The largest anterior radicular artery, arising usually from left T9–T12 (range T8–L2). Critical supply to the thoracolumbar spinal cord via the ASA. At risk during thoracic aortic surgery and spinal procedures — sacrifice can cause anterior cord syndrome (paraplegia).",ref:"claude — spinal vascular anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{q:"What are the Denis three-column model columns?",a:"Anterior column: anterior longitudinal ligament + anterior 2/3 of vertebral body and disc. Middle column: posterior 1/3 of vertebral body/disc + posterior longitudinal ligament (PLL). Posterior column: pedicles, facets, laminae, posterior ligamentous complex (PLC). Instability = disruption of ≥2 columns.",ref:"Denis 1983"},
],q:[
{stem:"A patient has a stab wound at T10, causing ipsilateral leg weakness + loss of proprioception, and contralateral loss of pain/temperature from T12 down. Which syndrome?",opts:["A. Central cord syndrome","B. Anterior cord syndrome","C. Brown-Séquard syndrome","D. Cauda equina syndrome","E. Conus medullaris syndrome"],ans:2,exp:"Brown-Séquard (hemicord): ipsilateral motor + dorsal column deficit; contralateral spinothalamic (pain/temperature) loss below injury. Best prognosis of incomplete syndromes.",ref:"SCI syndromes"},
{stem:"During thoracic aortic surgery, the patient develops bilateral leg paralysis with preserved light touch but no pain/temperature below T10. Which vessel was most likely compromised?",opts:["A. Posterior spinal artery","B. Anterior spinal artery via artery of Adamkiewicz","C. PICA","D. Vertebral artery","E. Radicular arteries above T8"],ans:1,exp:"Anterior cord syndrome: ASA territory. The artery of Adamkiewicz (T8–L2, usually left) is the major supply to the lower thoracic/lumbar cord via the ASA. Infarction causes anterior cord syndrome — loss of motor and pain/temperature with preserved posterior column function.",ref:"claude — spinal vascular anatomy",src_id:"claude-ai"},
{stem:"Regarding the artery of Adamkiewicz (arteria radicularis magna), which statement is INCORRECT?",opts:["A. It is the dominant blood supply to the anterior thoracolumbar spinal cord","B. It arises from a LEFT-sided intercostal or lumbar vessel in approximately 75% of cases","C. It typically originates at a thoracic level between T9 and T12","D. In approximately 10% of cases it may originate from a lumbar vessel at L1–L2","E. It arises from a RIGHT-sided vessel in the majority of cases (approximately 65%)"],ans:4,exp:"The artery of Adamkiewicz arises from the LEFT side in approximately 75% of cases (right side in only ~25%, not 65%). It typically originates between T9–T12, with L1–L2 origin in ~10%. It enters the spinal canal with a nerve root, joins the anterior spinal artery, and provides the dominant supply to the anterior two-thirds of the cord from T8 downward. Injury during thoracic aortic, thoracolumbar spine, or paravertebral surgery can cause anterior cord syndrome (paraplegia with preserved dorsal column function). Preoperative CTA/MRA identification aids surgical planning.",ref:"Bank, p.4–5",src_id:"k-bank-mcqs",korky:true},
]},
};

